quran[6235]{c,v,t}:
  1,1,All praise is for God‚ÄĒLord of all worlds
  1,2,"the Most Compassionate, Most Merciful"
  1,3,Master of the Day of Judgment
  1,4,You ňĻaloneňļ we worship and You ňĻaloneňļ we ask for help
  1,5,Guide us along the Straight Path
  1,6,"the Path of those You have blessed‚ÄĒnot those You are displeased with, or those who are astray"
  2,1,Alif-L√£m-Mń©m
  2,2,This is the Book! There is no doubt about it‚ÄĒa guide for those mindful ňĻof Godňļ
  2,3,"who believe in the unseen,¬†establish prayer, and donate from what We have provided for them"
  2,4,"and who believe in what has been revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ¬†and what was revealed before you, and have sure faith in the Hereafter"
  2,5,"It is they who are ňĻtrulyňļ guided by their Lord, and it is they who will be successful"
  2,6,"As for those who persist in disbelief, it is the same whether you warn them or not‚ÄĒthey will never believe"
  2,7,"God has sealed their hearts and their hearing, and their sight is covered. They will suffer a tremendous punishment"
  2,8,"And there are some who say, ‚ÄúWe believe in God and the Last Day,‚ÄĚ yet they are not ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  2,9,"They seek to deceive God and the believers, yet they only deceive themselves, but they fail to perceive it"
  2,10,"There is sickness in their hearts, and God ňĻonlyňļ lets their sickness increase. They will suffer a painful punishment for their lies"
  2,11,"When they are told, ‚ÄúDo not spread corruption in the land,‚ÄĚ they reply, ‚ÄúWe are only peace-makers!‚ÄĚ"
  2,12,"Indeed, it is they who are the corruptors, but they fail to perceive it"
  2,13,"And when they are told, ‚ÄúBelieve as others believe,‚ÄĚ they reply, ‚ÄúWill we believe as the fools believe?‚ÄĚ Indeed, it is they who are fools, but they do not know"
  2,14,"When they meet the believers they say, ‚ÄúWe believe.‚ÄĚ But when alone with their evil associates they say, ‚ÄúWe are definitely with you; we were only mocking.‚ÄĚ"
  2,15,"God will throw their mockery back at them, leaving them to continue wandering blindly in their defiance"
  2,16,"They are the ones who trade guidance for misguidance. But this trade is profitless, and they are not ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  2,17,"Their example is that of someone who kindles a fire, but when it lights up all around them, God takes away their light, leaving them in complete darkness‚ÄĒunable to see"
  2,18,"They are ňĻwilfullyňļ deaf, dumb, and blind, so they will never return ňĻto the Right Pathňļ"
  2,19,"Or ňĻthose caught inňļ a rainstorm from the sky with darkness, thunder, and lightning. They press their fingers into their ears at the sound of every thunder-clap for fear of death. And God encompasses the disbelievers ňĻby His mightňļ"
  2,20,"It is as if the lightning were about to snatch away their sight. Whenever lightning strikes, they walk in its light, but when darkness covers them, they stand still. Had God willed, He could have taken away their hearing and sight. Surely God is Most Capable of everything"
  2,21,"O humanity! Worship your Lord, Who created you and those before you, so that you may become mindful ňĻof Himňļ"
  2,22,"ňĻHe is the Oneňļ Who has made the earth a place of settlement for you and the sky a canopy; and sends down rain from the sky, causing fruits to grow as a provision for you. So do not knowingly set up equals to God ňĻin worshipňļ"
  2,23,"And if you are in doubt about what We have revealed to Our servant,¬†then produce a s√Ľrah¬†like it and call your helpers other than God, if what you say is true"
  2,24,"But if you are unable to do so‚ÄĒand you will never be able to do so‚ÄĒthen fear the Fire fuelled with people and stones, which is prepared for the disbelievers"
  2,25,"Give good news ňĻO Prophetňļ to those who believe and do good that they will have Gardens under which rivers flow. Whenever provided with fruit, they will say, ‚ÄúThis is what we were given before,‚ÄĚ for they will be served fruit that looks similar ňĻbut tastes differentňļ. They will have pure spouses,¬†and they will be there forever"
  2,26,"Surely God does not shy away from using the parable of a mosquito or what is even smaller. As for the believers, they know that it is the truth from their Lord. And as for the disbelievers, they argue, ‚ÄúWhat does God mean by such a parable?‚ÄĚ Through this ňĻtestňļ, He leaves many to stray, and guides many. And He leaves none to stray except the rebellious‚ÄĒ"
  2,27,"those who violate God‚Äôs covenant after it has been affirmed, break whatever ňĻtiesňļ God has ordered to be maintained, and spread corruption in the land. It is they who are the ňĻtrueňļ losers"
  2,28,"How can you deny God? You were lifeless and He gave you life, then He will cause you to die and again bring you to life, and then to Him you will ňĻallňļ be returned"
  2,29,"He is the One Who created everything in the earth for you. Then He turned towards the heaven, forming it into seven heavens. And He has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  2,30,"ňĻRememberňļ when your Lord said to the angels, ‚ÄúI am going to place a successive ňĻhumanňļ authority on earth.‚ÄĚ They asked ňĻGodňļ, ‚ÄúWill You place in it someone who will spread corruption there and shed blood while we glorify Your praises and proclaim Your holiness?‚ÄĚ God responded, ‚ÄúI know what you do not know.‚ÄĚ"
  2,31,"He taught Adam the names of all things, then He presented them to the angels and said, ‚ÄúTell Me the names of these, if what you say is true?‚ÄĚ"
  2,32,"They replied, ‚ÄúGlory be to You! We have no knowledge except what You have taught us. You are truly the All-Knowing, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  2,33,"God said, ‚ÄúO Adam! Inform them of their names.‚ÄĚ Then when Adam did, God said, ‚ÄúDid I not tell you that I know the secrets of the heavens and the earth, and I know what you reveal and what you conceal?‚ÄĚ"
  2,34,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We said to the angels, ‚ÄúProstrate before Adam,‚ÄĚ¬†so they all did‚ÄĒbut not Ibl√ģs,¬†who refused and acted arrogantly,¬†becoming unfaithful"
  2,35,"We cautioned, ‚ÄúO Adam! Live with your wife in Paradise and eat as freely as you please, but do not approach this tree, or else you will be wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  2,36,"But Satan deceived them‚ÄĒleading to their fall from the ňĻblissfulňļ state they were in,¬†and We said, ‚ÄúDescend from the heavens ňĻto the earthňļ as enemies to each other.¬†You will find in the earth a residence and provision for your appointed stay.‚ÄĚ"
  2,37,"Then Adam was inspired with words ňĻof prayerňļ by his Lord,¬†so He accepted his repentance. Surely He is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  2,38,"We said, ‚ÄúDescend all of you! Then when guidance comes to you from Me, whoever follows it, there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  2,39,But those who disbelieve and deny Our signs will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever.‚ÄĚ
  2,40,"O children of Israel!¬†Remember My favours upon you. Fulfil your covenant and I will fulfil Mine, and stand in awe of Me ňĻaloneňļ"
  2,41,Believe in My revelations which confirm your Scriptures.¬†Do not be the first to deny them or trade them for a fleeting gain.¬†And be mindful of Me
  2,42,Do not mix truth with falsehood or hide the truth knowingly
  2,43,"Establish prayer, pay alms-tax,¬†and bow down with those who bow down"
  2,44,"Do you preach righteousness and fail to practice it yourselves, although you read the Scripture? Do you not understand"
  2,45,"And seek help through patience and prayer. Indeed, it is a burden except for the humble‚ÄĒ"
  2,46,those who are certain that they will meet their Lord and to Him they will return
  2,47,O Children of Israel! Remember ňĻallňļ the favours I granted you and how I honoured you above the others
  2,48,"Guard yourselves against the Day on which no soul will be of help to another. No intercession¬†will be accepted, no ransom taken, and no help will be given"
  2,49,"ňĻRememberňļ how We delivered you from the people of Pharaoh, who afflicted you with dreadful torment, slaughtering your sons and keeping your women. That was a severe test from your Lord"
  2,50,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We parted the sea, rescued you, and drowned Pharaoh‚Äôs people before your very eyes"
  2,51,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We appointed forty nights for Moses, then you worshipped the calf in his absence, acting wrongfully"
  2,52,Even then We ňĻstillňļ forgave you so perhaps you would be grateful
  2,53,And ňĻrememberňļ when We gave Moses the Scripture‚ÄĒthe standard ňĻto distinguish between right and wrongňļ that perhaps you would be ňĻrightlyňļ guided
  2,54,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Moses said to his people, ‚ÄúO my people! Surely you have wronged yourselves by worshipping the calf, so turn in repentance to your Creator and execute ňĻthe calf-worshippers amongňļ yourselves. That is best for you in the sight of your Creator.‚ÄĚ Then He accepted your repentance. Surely He is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  2,55,"And ňĻrememberňļ when you said, ‚ÄúO Moses! We will never believe you until we see God with our own eyes,‚ÄĚ so a thunderbolt struck you while you were looking on"
  2,56,"Then We brought you back to life after your death, so that perhaps you would be grateful"
  2,57,"And ňĻremember whenňļ We shaded you with clouds and sent down to you manna and quails,¬†ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúEat from the good things We have provided for you.‚ÄĚ The evildoers ňĻcertainlyňļ did not wrong Us, but wronged themselves"
  2,58,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We said, ‚ÄúEnter this city and eat freely from wherever you please; enter the gate with humility, saying, ‚ÄėAbsolve us.‚Äô We will forgive your sins and multiply the reward for the good-doers.‚ÄĚ"
  2,59,But the wrongdoers changed the words they were commanded to say. So We sent down a punishment from the heavens upon them for their rebelliousness
  2,60,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Moses prayed for water for his people, We said, ‚ÄúStrike the rock with your staff.‚ÄĚ Then twelve springs gushed out, ňĻandňļ each tribe knew its drinking place. ňĻWe then said,ňļ ‚ÄúEat and drink of God‚Äôs provisions, and do not go about spreading corruption in the land.‚ÄĚ"
  2,61,"And ňĻrememberňļ when you said, ‚ÄúO Moses! We cannot endure the same meal ňĻevery dayňļ. So ňĻjustňļ call upon your Lord on our behalf, He will bring forth for us some of what the earth produces of herbs, cucumbers, garlic, lentils, and onions.‚ÄĚ Moses scolded ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúDo you exchange what is better for what is worse? ňĻYou canňļ go down to any village and you will find what you have asked for.‚ÄĚ They were stricken with disgrace and misery, and they invited the displeasure of God for rejecting God‚Äôs signs and unjustly killing the prophets. This is ňĻa fair rewardňļ for their disobedience and violations"
  2,62,"Indeed, the believers, Jews, Christians, and Sabians‚ÄĒwhoever ňĻtrulyňļ believes in God and the Last Day and does good will have their reward with their Lord. And there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  2,63,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We took a covenant from you and raised the mountain above you ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúHold firmly to that ňĻScriptureňļ which We have given you and observe its teachings so perhaps you will become mindful ňĻof Godňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  2,64,"Yet you turned away afterwards. Had it not been for God‚Äôs grace and mercy upon you, you would have certainly been of the losers"
  2,65,"You are already aware of those of you who broke the Sabbath. We said to them, ‚ÄúBe disgraced apes!‚ÄĚ"
  2,66,"So We made their fate an example to present and future generations, and a lesson to the God-fearing"
  2,67,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Moses said to his people, ‚ÄúGod commands you to sacrifice a cow.‚ÄĚ¬†They replied, ‚ÄúAre you mocking us?‚ÄĚ Moses responded, ‚ÄúI seek refuge in God from acting foolishly!‚ÄĚ"
  2,68,"They said, ‚ÄúCall upon your Lord to clarify for us what type ňĻof cowňļ it should be!‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúGod says, ‚ÄėThe cow should neither be old nor young but in between. So do as you are commanded!‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  2,69,"They said, ‚ÄúCall upon your Lord to specify for us its colour.‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúGod says, ‚ÄėIt should be a bright yellow cow‚ÄĒpleasant to see.‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  2,70,"Again they said, ‚ÄúCall upon your Lord so that He may make clear to us which cow, for all cows look the same to us. Then, God willing, we will be guided ňĻto the right oneňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  2,71,"He replied, ‚ÄúGod says, ‚ÄėIt should have been used neither to till the soil nor water the fields; wholesome and without blemish.‚Äô‚ÄĚ They said, ‚ÄúNow you have come with the truth.‚ÄĚ Yet they still slaughtered it hesitantly"
  2,72,"ňĻThis isňļ when a man was killed and you disputed who the killer was, but God revealed what you concealed"
  2,73,"So We instructed, ‚ÄúStrike the dead body with a piece of the cow.‚ÄĚ This is how ňĻeasilyňļ God brings the dead to life, showing you His signs so that you may understand"
  2,74,"Even then your hearts became hardened like a rock or even harder, for some rocks gush rivers; others split, spilling water; while others are humbled in awe of God. And God is never unaware of what you do"
  2,75,"Do you ňĻbelievers stillňļ expect them to be true to you, though a group of them would hear the word of God then knowingly corrupt it after understanding it"
  2,76,"When they meet the believers they say, ‚ÄúWe believe.‚ÄĚ But in private they say ňĻto each otherňļ, ‚ÄúWill you disclose to the believers the knowledge God has revealed to you,¬†so that they may use it against you before your Lord? Do you not understand?‚ÄĚ"
  2,77,Do they not know that God is aware of what they conceal and what they reveal
  2,78,"And among them are the illiterate who know nothing about the Scripture except lies, and ňĻsoňļ they ňĻwishfullyňļ speculate"
  2,79,"So woe¬†to those who distort the Scripture with their own hands then say, ‚ÄúThis is from God‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒseeking a fleeting gain! So woe to them for what their hands have written, and woe to them for what they have earned"
  2,80,"ňĻSome ofňļ the Jews claim, ‚ÄúThe Fire will not touch us except for a number of days.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúHave you taken a pledge from God‚ÄĒfor God never breaks His word‚ÄĒor are you ňĻjustňļ saying about God what you do not know?‚ÄĚ"
  2,81,But no! Those who commit evil and are engrossed in sin will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever
  2,82,And those who believe and do good will be the residents of Paradise. They will be there forever
  2,83,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We took a covenant from the children of Israel ňĻstatingňļ, ‚ÄúWorship none but God; be kind to parents, relatives, orphans and the needy; speak kindly to people; establish prayer; and pay alms-tax.‚ÄĚ But you ňĻIsraelitesňļ turned away‚ÄĒexcept for a few of you‚ÄĒand were indifferent"
  2,84,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We took your covenant that you would neither shed each other‚Äôs blood nor expel each other from their homes, you gave your pledge and bore witness"
  2,85,"But here you are, killing each other and expelling some of your people from their homes, aiding one another in sin and aggression; and when those ňĻexpelledňļ come to you as captives, you still ransom them‚ÄĒthough expelling them was unlawful for you.¬†Do you believe in some of the Scripture and reject the rest? Is there any reward for those who do so among you other than disgrace in this worldly life and being subjected to the harshest punishment on the Day of Judgment? For God is never unaware of what you do"
  2,86,"These are the ones who trade the Hereafter for the life of this world. So their punishment will not be reduced, nor will they be helped"
  2,87,"Indeed, We gave Moses the Book and sent after him successive messengers. And We gave Jesus, son of Mary, clear proofs and supported him with the holy spirit.¬†Why is it that every time a messenger comes to you ňĻIsraelitesňļ with something you do not like, you become arrogant, rejecting some and killing others"
  2,88,"They say, ‚ÄúOur hearts are unreceptive!‚ÄĚ¬†In fact, God has condemned them for their disbelief. They have but little faith"
  2,89,"Although they used to pray for victory ňĻby means of the Prophetňļ over the polytheists,¬†when there came to them a Book from God which they recognized,¬†confirming the Scripture they had ňĻin their handsňļ, they rejected it. So may God‚Äôs condemnation be upon the disbelievers"
  2,90,Miserable is the price they have sold their souls for‚ÄĒdenying God‚Äôs revelation and resenting God for granting His grace to whoever He wills of His servants! They have earned wrath upon wrath. And such disbelievers will suffer a humiliating punishment
  2,91,"When it is said to them: ‚ÄúBelieve in what God has revealed,‚ÄĚ they reply, ‚ÄúWe only believe in what was sent down to us,‚ÄĚ and they deny what came afterwards, though it is the truth confirming their own Scriptures! Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúWhy then did you kill God‚Äôs prophets before, if you are ňĻtrulyňļ believers?‚ÄĚ"
  2,92,"Indeed, Moses came to you with clear proofs, then you worshipped the calf in his absence, acting wrongfully"
  2,93,"And when We took your covenant and raised the mountain above you ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúHold firmly to that ňĻScriptureňļ which We have given you and obey,‚ÄĚ they answered, ‚ÄúWe hear and disobey.‚ÄĚ The love of the calf was rooted in their hearts because of their disbelief. Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúHow evil is what your ňĻso-calledňļ belief prompts you to do, if you ňĻactuallyňļ believe ňĻin the Torahňļ!‚ÄĚ"
  2,94,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIf the ňĻeternalňļ Home of the Hereafter with God is exclusively for you ňĻIsraelitesňļ out of all humanity, then wish for death if what you say is true!‚ÄĚ"
  2,95,But they will never wish for that because of what their hands have done.¬†And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of the wrongdoers
  2,96,"You will surely find them clinging to life more eagerly than any other people, even more than polytheists. Each one of them wishes to live a thousand years. But even if they were to live that long, it would not save them from the punishment. And God is All-Seeing of what they do"
  2,97,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWhoever is an enemy of Gabriel should know that he revealed this ňĻQuranňļ to your heart by God‚Äôs Will, confirming what came before it‚ÄĒa guide and good news for the believers.‚ÄĚ"
  2,98,"Whoever is an enemy of God, His angels, His messengers, Gabriel, and Michael, then ňĻlet them know thatňļ God is certainly the enemy of the disbelievers"
  2,99,"Indeed, We have sent down to you ňĻO Prophetňļ clear revelations. ňĻButňļ none will deny them except the rebellious"
  2,100,"Why is it that every time they make a covenant, a group of them casts it aside? In fact, most of them do not believe"
  2,101,"Now, when a messenger from God has come to them‚ÄĒconfirming their own Scriptures‚ÄĒsome of the People of the Book cast the Book of God behind their backs as if they did not know"
  2,102,"They ňĻinsteadňļ followed the magic promoted by the devils during the reign of Solomon. Never did Solomon disbelieve, rather the devils disbelieved. They taught magic to the people, along with what had been revealed to the two angels, H√Ęr√Ľt and M√Ęr√Ľt, in Babylon.¬†The two angels never taught anyone without saying, ‚ÄúWe are only a test ňĻfor youňļ, so do not abandon ňĻyourňļ faith.‚ÄĚ Yet people learned ňĻmagicňļ that caused a rift ňĻevenňļ between husband and wife; although their magic could not harm anyone except by God‚Äôs Will. They learned what harmed them and did not benefit them‚ÄĒalthough they already knew that whoever buys into magic would have no share in the Hereafter. Miserable indeed was the price for which they sold their souls, if only they knew"
  2,103,"If only they were faithful and mindful ňĻof Godňļ, there would have been a better reward from God, if only they knew"
  2,104,"O believers! Do not say, ‚ÄúR√Ę‚Äôina.‚ÄĚ [Herd us!] But say, ‚ÄúUnŠļďurna,‚ÄĚ [Tend to us!] and listen ňĻattentivelyňļ.¬†And the disbelievers will suffer a painful punishment"
  2,105,"The disbelievers from the People of the Book and the polytheists would not want you to receive any blessing from your Lord, but God selects whoever He wills for His mercy. And God is the Lord of infinite bounty"
  2,106,"If We ever abrogate¬†a verse or cause it to be forgotten, We replace it with a better or similar one. Do you not know that God is Most Capable of everything"
  2,107,"Do you not know that the kingdom of the heavens and the earth belongs ňĻonlyňļ to God, and you have no guardian or helper besides God"
  2,108,Or do you ňĻbelieversňļ intend to ask of your Messenger as Moses was asked before?¬†But whoever trades belief for disbelief has truly strayed from the Right Way
  2,109,"Many among the People of the Book wish they could turn you ňĻbelieversňļ back to disbelief because of their envy, after the truth has been made clear to them. Pardon and bear with them until God delivers His decision. Surely God is Most Capable of everything"
  2,110,"Establish prayer, and pay alms-tax. Whatever good you send forth for yourselves, you will ňĻcertainlyňļ find ňĻits rewardňļ with God. Surely God is All-Seeing of what you do"
  2,111,"The Jews and Christians each claim that none will enter Paradise except those of their own faith. These are their desires. Reply, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúShow ňĻmeňļ your proof if what you say is true.‚ÄĚ"
  2,112,"But no! Whoever submits themselves to God and does good will have their reward with their Lord. And there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  2,113,"The Jews say, ‚ÄúThe Christians have nothing to stand on‚ÄĚ and the Christians say, ‚ÄúThe Jews have nothing to stand on,‚ÄĚ although both recite the Scriptures. And those ňĻpagansňļ who have no knowledge say the same ňĻabout people of faithňļ. Surely God will judge between them on the Day of Judgment regarding their dispute"
  2,114,"Who does more wrong than those who prevent God‚Äôs Name from being mentioned in His places of worship and strive to destroy them? Such people have no right to enter these places except with fear.¬†For them is disgrace in this world, and they will suffer a tremendous punishment in the Hereafter"
  2,115,"To God belong the east and the west, so wherever you turn you are facing ňĻtowardsňļ God.¬†Surely God is All-Encompassing,¬†All-Knowing"
  2,116,"They¬†say, ‚ÄúGod has offspring.‚ÄĚ¬†Glory be to Him! In fact, to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth‚ÄĒall are subject to His Will"
  2,117,"ňĻHe isňļ the Originator of the heavens and the earth! When He decrees a matter, He simply tells it, ‚ÄúBe!‚ÄĚ And it is"
  2,118,"Those who have no knowledge say, ‚ÄúIf only God would speak to us or a sign would come to us!‚ÄĚ The same was said by those who came before. Their hearts are all alike. Indeed, We have made the signs clear for people of sure faith"
  2,119,We have surely sent you with the truth ňĻO Prophetňļ as a deliverer of good news and a warner. And you will not be accountable for the residents of the Hellfire
  2,120,"Never will the Jews or Christians be pleased with you, until you follow their faith. Say, ‚ÄúGod‚Äôs guidance is the only ňĻtrueňļ guidance.‚ÄĚ And if you were to follow their desires after ňĻallňļ the knowledge that has come to you, there would be none to protect or help you against God"
  2,121,"Those We have given the Book follow it as it should be followed. It is they who ňĻtrulyňļ believe in it. As for those who reject it, it is they who are the losers"
  2,122,O Children of Israel! Remember My favours upon you and how I honoured you above the others
  2,123,"And guard yourselves against the Day when no soul will be of any help to another. No ransom will be taken, no intercession accepted, and no help will be given"
  2,124,"ňĻRememberňļ when Abraham was tested by his Lord with ňĻcertainňļ commandments, which he fulfilled. God said, ‚ÄúI will certainly make you into a role model for the people.‚ÄĚ Abraham asked, ‚ÄúWhat about my offspring?‚ÄĚ God replied, ‚ÄúMy covenant is not extended to the wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  2,125,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We made the Sacred House¬†a centre and a sanctuary for the people ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúňĻYou mayňļ take the standing-place of Abraham¬†as a site of prayer.‚ÄĚ And We entrusted Abraham and Ishmael to purify My House for those who circle it, who meditate in it, and who bow and prostrate themselves ňĻin prayerňļ"
  2,126,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Abraham said, ‚ÄúMy Lord, make this city ňĻof Meccaňļ secure and provide fruits to its people‚ÄĒthose among them who believe in God and the Last Day.‚ÄĚ He answered, ‚ÄúAs for those who disbelieve, I will let them enjoy themselves for a little while, then I will condemn them to the torment of the Fire. What an evil destination!‚ÄĚ"
  2,127,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Abraham raised the foundation of the House with Ishmael, ňĻboth praying,ňļ ‚ÄúOur Lord! Accept ňĻthisňļ from us. You are indeed the All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  2,128,"Our Lord! Make us both ňĻfullyňļ submit to You¬†and from our descendants a nation that will submit to you. Show us our rituals, and turn to us in grace. You are truly the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  2,129,"Our Lord! Raise from among them a messenger who will recite to them Your revelations, teach them the Book and wisdom, and purify them. Indeed, You ňĻaloneňļ are the Almighty, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  2,130,"And who would reject the faith of Abraham except a fool! We certainly chose him in this life, and in the Hereafter he will surely be among the righteous"
  2,131,"When his Lord ordered him, ‚ÄúSubmit ňĻto My Willňļ,‚ÄĚ he responded, ‚ÄúI submit to the Lord of all worlds.‚ÄĚ"
  2,132,"This was the advice of Abraham‚ÄĒas well as Jacob‚ÄĒto his children, ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúIndeed, God has chosen for you this faith; so do not die except in ňĻa state of fullňļ submission.‚ÄĚ"
  2,133,"Or did you witness when death came to Jacob? He asked his children, ‚ÄúWho will you worship after my passing?‚ÄĚ They replied, ‚ÄúWe will ňĻcontinue toňļ worship your God, the God of your forefathers‚ÄĒAbraham, Ishmael, and Isaac‚ÄĒthe One God. And to Him we ňĻallňļ submit.‚ÄĚ"
  2,134,That was a community that had already gone before. For them is what they earned and for you is what you have earned. And you will not be accountable for what they have done
  2,135,"The Jews and Christians each say, ‚ÄúFollow our faith to be ňĻrightlyňļ guided.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúNo! We follow the faith of Abraham, the upright‚ÄĒwho was not a polytheist.‚ÄĚ"
  2,136,"Say, ňĻO believers,ňļ ‚ÄúWe believe in God and what has been revealed to us; and what was revealed to Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants; and what was given to Moses, Jesus, and other prophets from their Lord. We make no distinction between any of them. And to God we all submit.‚ÄĚ"
  2,137,"So if they believe in what you believe, then they will indeed be ňĻrightlyňļ guided. But if they turn away, they are simply opposed ňĻto the truthňļ. But God will spare you their evil. For He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  2,138,This is the ňĻnaturalňļ Way of God. And who is better than God in ordaining a way? And we worship ňĻnone butňļ Him
  2,139,"Say, ‚ÄúWould you dispute with us about God, while He is our Lord and your Lord? We are accountable for our deeds and you for yours. And we are devoted to Him ňĻaloneňļ"
  2,140,"Do you claim that Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants were all Jews or Christians?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúWho is more knowledgeable: you or God?‚ÄĚ Who does more wrong than those who hide the testimony they received from God? And God is never unaware of what you do"
  2,141,That was a community that had already gone before. For them is what they earned and for you is what you have earned. And you will not be accountable for what they have done
  2,142,"The foolish among the people will ask, ‚ÄúWhy did they turn away from the direction of prayer they used to face?‚ÄĚ¬†Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúThe east and west belong ňĻonlyňļ to God. He guides whoever He wills to the Straight Path.‚ÄĚ"
  2,143,And so We have made you ňĻbelieversňļ an upright¬†community so that you may be witnesses over humanity and that the Messenger may be a witness over you. We assigned your former direction of prayer only to distinguish those who would remain faithful to the Messenger from those who would lose faith. It was certainly a difficult test except for those ňĻrightlyňļ guided by God. And God would never discount your ňĻprevious acts ofňļ faith. Surely God is Ever Gracious and Most Merciful to humanity
  2,144,"Indeed, We see you ňĻO Prophetňļ turning your face towards heaven. Now We will make you turn towards a direction ňĻof prayerňļ that will please you. So turn your face towards the Sacred Mosque ňĻin Meccaňļ‚ÄĒwherever you are, turn your faces towards it. Those who were given the Scripture certainly know this to be the truth from their Lord. And God is never unaware of what they do"
  2,145,"Even if you were to bring every proof to the People of the Book, they would not accept your direction ňĻof prayerňļ, nor would you accept theirs; nor would any of them accept the direction ňĻof prayerňļ of another. And if you were to follow their desires after ňĻallňļ the knowledge that has come to you, then you would certainly be one of the wrongdoers"
  2,146,Those We have given the Scripture recognize this ňĻProphetňļ as they recognize their own children. Yet a group of them hides the truth knowingly
  2,147,"ňĻThis isňļ the truth from your Lord, so do not ever be one of those who doubt"
  2,148,"Everyone turns to their own direction ňĻof prayerňļ. So compete with one another in doing good. Wherever you are, God will bring you all together ňĻfor judgmentňļ. Surely God is Most Capable of everything"
  2,149,"Wherever you are ňĻO Prophetňļ, turn your face towards the Sacred Mosque. This is certainly the truth from your Lord. And God is never unaware of what you ňĻallňļ do"
  2,150,"Wherever you are ňĻO Prophetňļ, turn your face towards the Sacred Mosque. And wherever you ňĻbelieversňļ are, face towards it, so that people will have no argument against you, except the wrongdoers among them. Do not fear them; fear Me, so that I may ňĻcontinue toňļ perfect My favour upon you and so you may be ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  2,151,"Since We have sent you a messenger from among yourselves‚ÄĒreciting to you Our revelations, purifying you, teaching you the Book and wisdom, and teaching you what you never knew‚ÄĒ"
  2,152,"remember Me; I will remember you. And thank Me, and never be ungrateful"
  2,153,O believers! Seek comfort in patience and prayer. God is truly with those who are patient
  2,154,"Never say that those martyred in the cause of God are dead‚ÄĒin fact, they are alive! But you do not perceive it"
  2,155,"We will certainly test you with a touch of fear and famine and loss of property, life, and crops. Give good news to those who patiently endure‚ÄĒ"
  2,156,"who, when faced with a disaster, say, ‚ÄúSurely to God we belong and to Him we will ňĻallňļ return.‚ÄĚ"
  2,157,They are the ones who will receive God‚Äôs blessings and mercy. And it is they who are ňĻrightlyňļ guided
  2,158,"Indeed, ňĻthe hills ofňļ ŠĻĘafa¬†and Marwah¬†are among the symbols of God. So whoever performs the pilgrimage or minor pilgrimage,¬†let them walk between ňĻthe two hillsňļ. And whoever does good willingly, God is truly Appreciative, All-Knowing"
  2,159,Those who hide the clear proofs and guidance that We have revealed‚ÄĒafter We made it clear for humanity in the Book‚ÄĒwill be condemned by God and ňĻallňļ those who condemn
  2,160,"As for those who repent, mend their ways, and let the truth be known, they are the ones to whom I will turn ňĻin forgivenessňļ, for I am the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  2,161,"Surely those who disbelieve and die as disbelievers are condemned by God, the angels, and all of humanity"
  2,162,"They will be in Hell forever. Their punishment will not be lightened, nor will they be delayed ňĻfrom itňļ"
  2,163,"Your God is ňĻonlyňļ One God. There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him‚ÄĒthe Most Compassionate, Most Merciful"
  2,164,"Indeed, in the creation of the heavens and the earth; the alternation of the day and the night; the ships that sail the sea for the benefit of humanity; the rain sent down by God from the skies, reviving the earth after its death; the scattering of all kinds of creatures throughout; the shifting of the winds; and the clouds drifting between the heavens and the earth‚ÄĒňĻin all of thisňļ are surely signs for people of understanding"
  2,165,"Still there are some who take others as God‚Äôs equal‚ÄĒthey love them as they should love God‚ÄĒbut the ňĻtrueňļ believers love God even more. If only the wrongdoers could see the ňĻhorribleňļ punishment ňĻawaiting themňļ, they would certainly realize that all power belongs to God and that God is indeed severe in punishment"
  2,166,ňĻConsider the Dayňļ when those who misled others will disown their followers‚ÄĒwhen they face the torment‚ÄĒand the bonds that united them will be cut off
  2,167,"The ňĻmisledňļ followers will cry, ‚ÄúIf only we could have a second chance, we would disown them as they disowned us.‚ÄĚ And so God will make them remorseful of their misdeeds. And they will never ňĻbe able toňļ leave the Fire"
  2,168,O humanity! Eat from what is lawful and good on the earth and do not follow Satan‚Äôs footsteps. He is truly your sworn enemy
  2,169,"He only incites you to commit evil and indecency, and to claim against God what you do not know"
  2,170,"When it is said to them, ‚ÄúFollow what God has revealed,‚ÄĚ they reply, ‚ÄúNo! We ňĻonlyňļ follow what we found our forefathers practicing.‚ÄĚ ňĻWould they still do so,ňļ even if their forefathers had ňĻabsolutelyňļ no understanding or guidance"
  2,171,"The example of the disbelievers ňĻnot responding to the Messenger‚Äôs warningňļ is like a flock not comprehending the calls and cries of the shepherd. ňĻThey are wilfullyňļ deaf, dumb and blind so they have no understanding"
  2,172,O believers! Eat from the good things We have provided for you. And give thanks to God if you ňĻtrulyňļ worship Him ňĻaloneňļ
  2,173,"He has only forbidden you ňĻto eatňļ carrion, blood, swine,¬†and what is slaughtered in the name of any other than God. But if someone is compelled by necessity‚ÄĒneither driven by desire nor exceeding immediate need‚ÄĒthey will not be sinful. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  2,174,"Indeed, those who hide God‚Äôs revelations, trading them for a fleeting gain consume nothing but fire into their bellies. God will neither speak to them on the Day of Judgment, nor will He purify them. And they will suffer a painful punishment"
  2,175,They are the ones who trade guidance for misguidance and forgiveness for punishment. How persistent are they in pursuit of the Fire
  2,176,That is because God has revealed the Book in truth. And surely those who differ regarding it are totally engrossed in opposition
  2,177,"Righteousness is not in turning your faces towards the east or the west. Rather, the righteous are those who believe in God, the Last Day, the angels, the Books, and the prophets; who give charity out of their cherished wealth to relatives, orphans, the poor, ňĻneedyňļ travellers, beggars, and for freeing captives; who establish prayer, pay alms-tax, and keep the pledges they make; and who are patient in times of suffering, adversity, and in ňĻthe heat ofňļ battle. It is they who are true ňĻin faithňļ, and it is they who are mindful ňĻof Godňļ"
  2,178,"O believers! ňĻThe law ofňļ retaliation is set for you in cases of murder‚ÄĒa free man for a free man, a slave for a slave, and a female for a female.¬†But if the offender is pardoned by the victim‚Äôs guardian,¬†then blood-money should be decided fairly¬†and payment should be made courteously. This is a concession and a mercy from your Lord. But whoever transgresses after that will suffer a painful punishment"
  2,179,"There is ňĻsecurity ofňļ life for you in ňĻthe law ofňļ retaliation, O people of reason, so that you may become mindful ňĻof Godňļ"
  2,180,It is prescribed that when death approaches any of you‚ÄĒif they leave something of value‚ÄĒa will should be made in favour of parents and immediate family with fairness.¬†ňĻThis isňļ an obligation on those who are mindful ňĻof Godňļ
  2,181,"But whoever changes the will after hearing it,¬†the blame will only be on those who made the change. Indeed, God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  2,182,"Whoever suspects an error or an injustice in the will and brings about a ňĻfairňļ settlement among the parties will not be sinful. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  2,183,O believers! Fasting is prescribed for you‚ÄĒas it was for those before you‚ÄĒso perhaps you will become mindful ňĻof Godňļ
  2,184,"ňĻFast aňļ prescribed number of days.¬†But whoever of you is ill or on a journey, then ňĻlet them fastňļ an equal number of days ňĻafter RamaŠłć√Ęnňļ. For those who can only fast with extreme difficulty,¬†compensation can be made by feeding a needy person ňĻfor every day not fastedňļ. But whoever volunteers to give more, it is better for them. And to fast is better for you, if only you knew"
  2,185,"RamaŠłć√Ęn is the month in which the Quran was revealed as a guide for humanity with clear proofs of guidance and the standard ňĻto distinguish between right and wrongňļ. So whoever is present this month, let them fast. But whoever is ill or on a journey, then ňĻlet them fastňļ an equal number of days ňĻafter RamaŠłć√Ęnňļ. God intends ease for you, not hardship, so that you may complete the prescribed period and proclaim the greatness of God for guiding you, and perhaps you will be grateful"
  2,186,"When My servants ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about Me: I am truly near. I respond to one‚Äôs prayer when they call upon Me. So let them respond ňĻwith obedienceňļ to Me and believe in Me, perhaps they will be guided ňĻto the Right Wayňļ"
  2,187,"It has been made permissible for you to be intimate with your wives during the nights preceding the fast. Your spouses are a garment¬†for you as you are for them. God knows that you were deceiving yourselves.¬†So He has accepted your repentance and pardoned you. So now you may be intimate with them and seek what God has prescribed for you.¬†ňĻYou mayňļ eat and drink until you see the light of dawn breaking the darkness of night, then complete the fast until nightfall. Do not be intimate with your spouses while you are meditating in the mosques. These are the limits set by God, so do not exceed them. This is how God makes His revelations clear to people, so they may become mindful ňĻof Himňļ"
  2,188,"Do not consume one another‚Äôs wealth unjustly, nor deliberately bribe authorities in order to devour a portion of others‚Äô property, knowing that it is a sin"
  2,189,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about the phases of the moon. Say, ‚ÄúThey are a means for people to determine time and pilgrimage.‚ÄĚ Righteousness is not in entering your houses from the back doors.¬†Rather, righteousness is to be mindful ňĻof Godňļ. So enter your homes through their ňĻproperňļ doors, and be mindful of God so you may be successful"
  2,190,"Fight in the cause of God ňĻonlyňļ against those who wage war against you, but do not exceed the limits.¬†God does not like transgressors"
  2,191,"Kill them wherever you come upon them¬†and drive them out of the places from which they have driven you out. For persecution¬†is far worse than killing. And do not fight them at the Sacred Mosque unless they attack you there. If they do so, then fight them‚ÄĒthat is the reward of the disbelievers"
  2,192,"But if they cease, then surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  2,193,"Fight against them ňĻif they persecute youňļ until there is no more persecution, and ňĻyourňļ devotion will be to God ňĻaloneňļ. If they stop ňĻpersecuting youňļ, let there be no hostility except against the aggressors"
  2,194,"ňĻThere will be retaliation inňļ a sacred month for ňĻan offence inňļ a sacred month,¬†and all violations will bring about retaliation. So, if anyone attacks you, retaliate in the same manner. ňĻButňļ be mindful of God, and know that God is with those mindful ňĻof Himňļ"
  2,195,"Spend in the cause of God and do not let your own hands throw you into destruction ňĻby withholdingňļ. And do good, for God certainly loves the good-doers"
  2,196,"Complete the pilgrimage and minor pilgrimage for God.¬†But if prevented ňĻfrom proceedingňļ, then ňĻofferňļ whatever sacrificial animals you can afford. And do not shave your heads until the sacrificial animal reaches its destination. But if any of you is ill or has a scalp ailment ňĻrequiring shavingňļ, then compensate either by fasting, charity, or a sacrificial offering. In times of peace, you may combine the pilgrimage and minor pilgrimage then make the sacrificial offering you can afford. Whoever cannot afford that ňĻofferingňļ, let them fast three days during pilgrimage and seven after returning ňĻhomeňļ‚ÄĒcompleting ten. These offerings are for those who do not live near the Sacred House. And be mindful of God, and know that God is severe in punishment"
  2,197,"ňĻCommitment toňļ pilgrimage is made in appointed months.¬†Whoever commits to ňĻperformingňļ pilgrimage, let them stay away from intimate relations, foul language, and arguments during pilgrimage. Whatever good you do, God ňĻfullyňļ knows of it. Take ňĻnecessaryňļ provisions ňĻfor the journeyňļ‚ÄĒsurely the best provision is righteousness. And be mindful of Me, O people of reason"
  2,198,"There is no blame on you for seeking the bounty of your Lord ňĻduring this journeyňļ.¬†When you return from ‚ÄôAraf√Ęt,¬†praise God near the sacred place¬†and praise Him for having guided you, for surely before this ňĻguidanceňļ you were astray"
  2,199,"Then go forth with the rest of the pilgrims. And seek God‚Äôs forgiveness. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  2,200,"When you have fulfilled your sacred rites, praise God as you used to praise your forefathers ňĻbefore Islamňļ, or even more passionately. There are some who say, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Grant us ňĻYour bountiesňļ in this world,‚ÄĚ but they will have no share in the Hereafter"
  2,201,"Yet there are others who say, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Grant us the good of this world and the Hereafter, and protect us from the torment of the Fire.‚ÄĚ"
  2,202,It is they who will receive a ňĻheavenlyňļ reward for the good they have done. Surely God is swift in reckoning
  2,203,"And remember God during ňĻtheseňļ appointed days.¬†Whoever departs swiftly on the second day is not sinful, neither are those who stay behind ňĻtill the third‚ÄĒseeking additional rewardňļ, so long as they are mindful ňĻof their Lordňļ. And be mindful of God, and know that to Him you will ňĻallňļ be gathered"
  2,204,"There are some ňĻhypocritesňļ who impress you with their views regarding worldly affairs and openly call upon God to witness what is in their hearts, yet they are your worst adversaries"
  2,205,"And when they leave ňĻyouňļ,¬†they strive throughout the land to spread mischief in it and destroy crops and cattle. God does not like mischief"
  2,206,"When it is said to them, ‚ÄúFear God,‚ÄĚ pride carries them off to sin. Hell will be their proper place. What an evil place to rest"
  2,207,And there are those who would dedicate their lives to God‚Äôs pleasure. And God is Ever Gracious to ňĻHisňļ servants
  2,208,O believers! Enter into Islam wholeheartedly and do not follow Satan‚Äôs footsteps. Surely he is your sworn enemy
  2,209,"If you falter after receiving the clear proofs, then know that God is indeed Almighty, All-Wise"
  2,210,"Are they waiting for God ňĻHimselfňļ to come to them in the shade of clouds, along with the angels? ňĻIf He didňļ, then the matter would be settled ňĻat onceňļ. And to God ňĻallňļ matters will be returned ňĻfor judgmentňļ"
  2,211,Ask the Children of Israel how many clear signs We have given them. And whoever trades God‚Äôs favour‚ÄĒafter receiving it‚ÄĒňĻfor disbeliefňļ should know that God is indeed severe in punishment
  2,212,"The life of this world has been made appealing to the disbelievers, and they mock the believers. Those who are mindful ňĻof Godňļ will rank above them on the Day of Judgment. And God provides for whoever He wills without limit"
  2,213,"Humanity had once been one community ňĻof believers before they lost faithňļ. Then God raised prophets as deliverers of good news and as warners, and revealed to them the Scriptures in truth to judge among people regarding their disputes. And no one disputed the Scriptures except the very people who received them after clear proofs had come to them‚ÄĒout of jealousy. Then God, by His grace, has guided the believers to the truth regarding those disputes. And God guides whoever He wills to the Straight Path"
  2,214,"Do you think you will be admitted into Paradise without being tested like those before you? They were afflicted with suffering and adversity and were so ňĻviolentlyňļ shaken that ňĻevenňļ the Messenger and the believers with him cried out, ‚ÄúWhen will God‚Äôs help come?‚ÄĚ Indeed, God‚Äôs help is ňĻalwaysňļ near"
  2,215,"They ask you ňĻO Prophet inňļ what ňĻwayňļ they should donate. Say, ‚ÄúWhatever donations you give are for parents, relatives, orphans, the poor, and ňĻneedyňļ travellers. Whatever good you do is certainly well known to God.‚ÄĚ"
  2,216,"Fighting has been made obligatory upon you ňĻbelieversňļ, though you dislike it. Perhaps you dislike something which is good for you and like something which is bad for you. God knows and you do not know"
  2,217,"They¬†ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about fighting in the sacred months.¬†Say, ‚ÄúFighting during these months is a great sin. But hindering ňĻothersňļ from the Path of God, rejecting Him, and expelling the worshippers from the Sacred Mosque is ňĻaňļ greater ňĻsinňļ in the sight of God. For persecution¬†is far worse than killing. And they will not stop fighting you until they turn you away from your faith‚ÄĒif they can. And whoever among you renounces their own faith and dies a disbeliever, their deeds will become void in this life and in the Hereafter. It is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever.‚ÄĚ"
  2,218,"Surely those who have believed, emigrated, and struggled in the Way of God‚ÄĒthey can hope for God‚Äôs mercy. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  2,219,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about intoxicants and gambling. Say, ‚ÄúThere is great evil in both, as well as some benefit for people‚ÄĒbut the evil outweighs the benefit.‚ÄĚ¬†They ňĻalsoňļ ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ what they should donate. Say, ‚ÄúWhatever you can spare.‚ÄĚ This is how God makes His revelations clear to you ňĻbelieversňļ, so perhaps you may reflect"
  2,220,"upon this world and the Hereafter. And they ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ concerning orphans. Say, ‚ÄúImproving their condition is best. And if you partner with them, they are bonded with you ňĻin faithňļ.¬†And God knows who intends harm and who intends good. Had God willed, He could have made it difficult for you.¬†Surely God is Almighty, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  2,221,"Do not marry polytheistic women until they believe; for a believing slave-woman is better than a free polytheist, even though she may look pleasant to you. And do not marry your women to polytheistic men until they believe, for a believing slave-man is better than a free polytheist, even though he may look pleasant to you. They invite ňĻyouňļ to the Fire while God invites ňĻyouňļ to Paradise and forgiveness by His grace.¬†He makes His revelations clear to the people so perhaps they will be mindful"
  2,222,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about menstruation. Say, ‚ÄúBeware of its harm! So keep away, and do not have intercourse with your wives during their monthly cycles until they are purified.¬†When they purify themselves, then you may approach them in the manner specified by God. Surely God loves those who always turn to Him in repentance and those who purify themselves.‚ÄĚ"
  2,223,"Your wives are like farmland for you,¬†so approach them ňĻconsensuallyňļ as you please.¬†And send forth something good for yourselves.¬†Be mindful of God, and know that you will meet Him. And give good news to the believers"
  2,224,"Do not use God‚Äôs Name in your oaths as an excuse for not doing good, not guarding against evil, or not making peace between people. And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  2,225,"God will not hold you accountable for unintentional oaths, but for what you intended in your hearts. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing"
  2,226,"Those who swear not to have intercourse with their wives must wait for four months.¬†If they change their mind, then God is certainly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  2,227,"But if they settle on divorce, then God is indeed All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  2,228,"Divorced women must wait three monthly cycles ňĻbefore they can re-marryňļ. It is not lawful for them to conceal what God has created in their wombs,¬†if they ňĻtrulyňļ believe in God and the Last Day. And their husbands reserve the right to take them back within that period if they desire reconciliation. Women have rights similar to those of men equitably, although men have a degree ňĻof responsibilityňļ above them. And God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  2,229,"Divorce may be retracted twice, then the husband must retain ňĻhis wifeňļ with honour or separate ňĻfrom herňļ with grace.¬†It is not lawful for husbands to take back anything of the dowry given to their wives, unless the couple fears not being able to keep within the limits of God.¬†So if you fear they will not be able to keep within the limits of God, there is no blame if the wife compensates the husband to obtain divorce.¬†These are the limits set by God, so do not transgress them. And whoever transgresses the limits of God, they are the ňĻtrueňļ wrongdoers"
  2,230,"So if a husband divorces his wife ňĻthree timesňļ, then it is not lawful for him to remarry her until after she has married another man and then is divorced. Then it is permissible for them to reunite, as long as they feel they are able to maintain the limits of God. These are the limits set by God, which He makes clear for people of knowledge"
  2,231,"When you divorce women and they have ňĻalmostňļ reached the end of their waiting period, either retain them honourably or let them go honourably. But do not retain them ňĻonlyňļ to harm them ňĻorňļ to take advantage ňĻof themňļ. Whoever does that surely wrongs his own soul. Do not take God‚Äôs revelations lightly. Remember God‚Äôs favours upon you as well as the Book and wisdom¬†He has sent down for your guidance. Be mindful of God, and know that God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  2,232,"When you have divorced women and they have reached the end of their waiting period, do not prevent them from re-marrying their ex-husbands if they come to an honourable agreement. This is enjoined on whoever has faith in God and the Last Day. This is purer and more dignifying for you. God knows and you do not know"
  2,233,"ňĻDivorcedňļ mothers will breastfeed their offspring for two whole years, for those who wish to complete the nursing ňĻof their childňļ. The child‚Äôs father will provide reasonable maintenance and clothing for the mother ňĻduring that periodňļ. No one will be charged with more than they can bear. No mother or father should be made to suffer for their child. The ňĻfather‚Äôsňļ heirs are under the same obligation. But if both sides decide‚ÄĒafter mutual consultation and consent‚ÄĒto wean a child, then there is no blame on them. If you decide to have your children nursed by a wet-nurse, it is permissible as long as you pay fairly. Be mindful of God, and know that God is All-Seeing of what you do"
  2,234,"As for those of you who die and leave widows behind, let them observe a waiting period of four months and ten days. When they have reached the end of this period, then you¬†are not accountable for what they decide for themselves in a reasonable manner. And God is All-Aware of what you do"
  2,235,"There is no blame on you for subtly showing interest in ňĻdivorced or widowedňļ women¬†or for hiding ňĻthe intentionňļ in your hearts. God knows that you are considering them ňĻfor marriageňļ. But do not make a secret commitment with them‚ÄĒyou can only show interest in them appropriately. Do not commit to the bond of marriage until the waiting period expires. Know that God is aware of what is in your hearts, so beware of Him. And know that God is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing"
  2,236,There is no blame if you divorce women before the marriage is consummated or the dowry is settled. But give them a ňĻsuitableňļ compensation‚ÄĒthe rich according to his means and the poor according to his. A reasonable compensation is an obligation on the good-doers
  2,237,"And if you divorce them before consummating the marriage but after deciding on a dowry, pay half of the dowry, unless the wife graciously waives it or the husband graciously pays in full. Graciousness is closer to righteousness. And do not forget kindness among yourselves. Surely God is All-Seeing of what you do"
  2,238,Observe the ňĻfive obligatoryňļ prayers‚ÄĒespecially the middle prayer‚ÄĒand stand in true devotion to God
  2,239,"If you are in danger, pray on foot or while riding. But when you are safe, ňĻtake time toňļ remember God for teaching you what you did not know"
  2,240,"Those of you who die leaving widows should bequeath for them a year‚Äôs maintenance without forcing them out.¬†But if they choose to leave, you are not accountable for what they reasonably decide for themselves. And God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  2,241,Reasonable provisions must be made for divorced women‚ÄĒa duty on those mindful ňĻof Godňļ
  2,242,"This is how God makes His revelations clear to you, so perhaps you will understand"
  2,243,"Have you ňĻO Prophetňļ not seen those who fled their homes in the thousands for fear of death?¬†God said to them, ‚ÄúDie!‚ÄĚ then He gave them life. Surely God is ever Bountiful to humanity, but most people are ungrateful"
  2,244,"Fight in the cause of God, and know that God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  2,245,Who will lend to God a good loan which God will multiply many times over? It is God ňĻaloneňļ who decreases and increases ňĻwealthňļ. And to Him you will ňĻallňļ be returned
  2,246,"Have you not seen those chiefs of the Children of Israel after Moses? They said to one of their prophets, ‚ÄúAppoint for us a king, ňĻandňļ we will fight in the cause of God.‚ÄĚ He said, ‚ÄúAre you not going to cower if ordered to fight?‚ÄĚ They replied, ‚ÄúHow could we refuse to fight in the cause of God, while we were driven out of our homes and ňĻseparated fromňļ our children?‚ÄĚ But when they were ordered to fight, they fled, except for a few of them. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of the wrongdoers"
  2,247,"Their prophet told them, ‚ÄúGod has appointed Saul¬†to be your king.‚ÄĚ They protested, ‚ÄúHow can he be our king when some of us are more deserving of kingship than he, and he has not been blessed with vast riches?‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúGod has chosen him over you and blessed him with knowledge and stature. God grants kingship to whoever He wills. And God is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing.‚ÄĚ"
  2,248,"Their prophet further told them, ‚ÄúThe sign of Saul‚Äôs kingship is that the Ark will come to you‚ÄĒcontaining reassurance¬†from your Lord and relics of the family of Moses and the family of Aaron,¬†which will be carried by the angels. Surely in this is a sign for you, if you ňĻtrulyňļ believe.‚ÄĚ"
  2,249,"When Saul marched forth with his army, he cautioned: ‚ÄúGod will test you with a river. So whoever drinks ňĻhis fillňļ from it is not with me, and whoever does not taste it‚ÄĒexcept a sip from the hollow of his hands‚ÄĒis definitely with me.‚ÄĚ They all drank ňĻtheir fillňļ except for a few! When he and the ňĻremainingňļ faithful with him crossed the river, they said, ‚ÄúNow we are no match for Goliath and his warriors.‚ÄĚ But those ňĻbelieversňļ who were certain they would meet God reasoned, ‚ÄúHow many times has a small force vanquished a mighty army by the Will of God! And God is ňĻalwaysňļ with the steadfast.‚ÄĚ"
  2,250,"When they advanced to face Goliath and his warriors, they prayed, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Shower us with perseverance, make our steps firm, and give us victory over the disbelieving people.‚ÄĚ"
  2,251,"So they defeated them by God‚Äôs Will, and David killed Goliath. And God blessed David with kingship and wisdom and taught him what He willed. Had God not repelled a group of people by ňĻthe might ofňļ another, corruption would have dominated the earth, but God is Gracious to all"
  2,252,These are God‚Äôs revelations which We recite to you ňĻO Prophetňļ in truth. And you are truly one of the messengers
  2,253,"We have chosen some of those messengers above others.¬†God spoke directly to some, and raised some high in rank. To Jesus, son of Mary, We gave clear proofs and supported him with the holy spirit.¬†If God had willed, succeeding generations would not have fought ňĻamong themselvesňļ after receiving the clear proofs. But they differed‚ÄĒsome believed while others disbelieved. Yet if God had willed, they would not have fought one another. But God does what He wills"
  2,254,"O believers! Donate from what We have provided for you before the arrival of a Day when there will be no bargaining,¬†friendship,¬†or intercession. Those who disbelieve are ňĻtrulyňļ the wrongdoers"
  2,255,"God! There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him, the Ever-Living, All-Sustaining. Neither drowsiness nor sleep overtakes Him. To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. Who could possibly intercede with Him without His permission? He ňĻfullyňļ knows what is ahead of them and what is behind them, but no one can grasp any of His knowledge‚ÄĒexcept what He wills ňĻto revealňļ. His Seat¬†encompasses the heavens and the earth, and the preservation of both does not tire Him. For He is the Most High, the Greatest"
  2,256,"Let there be no compulsion in religion, for the truth stands out clearly from falsehood.¬†So whoever renounces false gods and believes in God has certainly grasped the firmest, unfailing hand-hold. And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  2,257,"God is the Guardian of the believers‚ÄĒHe brings them out of darkness and into light. As for the disbelievers, their guardians are false gods who lead them out of light and into darkness. It is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever"
  2,258,"Are you ňĻO Prophetňļ not aware of the one who argued with Abraham about his Lord because God had granted him kingship? ňĻRememberňļ when Abraham said, ‚ÄúMy Lord is the One Who has power to give life and cause death.‚ÄĚ He argued, ‚ÄúI too have the power to give life and cause death.‚ÄĚ Abraham challenged ňĻhimňļ, ‚ÄúGod causes the sun to rise from the east. So make it rise from the west.‚ÄĚ And so the disbeliever was dumbstruck. And God does not guide the wrongdoing people"
  2,259,"Or ňĻare you not aware ofňļ the one who passed by a city which was in ruins. He wondered, ‚ÄúHow could God bring this back to life after its destruction?‚ÄĚ So God caused him to die for a hundred years then brought him back to life. God asked, ‚ÄúHow long have you remained ňĻin this stateňļ?‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúPerhaps a day or part of a day.‚ÄĚ God said, ‚ÄúNo! You have remained here for a hundred years! Just look at your food and drink‚ÄĒthey have not spoiled. ňĻBut nowňļ look at ňĻthe remains ofňļ your donkey! And ňĻsoňļ We have made you into a sign for humanity. And look at the bones ňĻof the donkeyňļ, how We bring them together then clothe them with flesh!‚ÄĚ¬†When this was made clear to him, he declared, ‚ÄúňĻNowňļ I know that God is Most Capable of everything.‚ÄĚ"
  2,260,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Abraham said, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Show me how you give life to the dead.‚ÄĚ God responded, ‚ÄúDo you not believe?‚ÄĚ Abraham replied, ‚ÄúYes I do, but just so my heart can be reassured.‚ÄĚ God said, ‚ÄúThen bring four birds, train them to come to you, ňĻthen cut them into pieces,ňļ and scatter them on different hilltops. Then call them back, they will fly to you in haste. And ňĻso you willňļ know that God is Almighty, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  2,261,"The example of those who spend their wealth in the cause of God is that of a grain that sprouts into seven ears, each bearing one hundred grains. And God multiplies ňĻthe reward even moreňļ to whoever He wills. For God is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing"
  2,262,"Those who spend their wealth in the cause of God and do not follow their charity with reminders of their generosity or hurtful words‚ÄĒthey will get their reward from their Lord, and there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  2,263,"Kind words and forgiveness are better than charity followed by injury. And God is Self-Sufficient, Most Forbearing"
  2,264,"O believers! Do not waste your charity with reminders ňĻof your generosityňļ or hurtful words, like those who donate their wealth just to show off and do not believe in God or the Last Day. Their example is that of a hard barren rock covered with a thin layer of soil hit by a strong rain‚ÄĒleaving it just a bare stone. Such people are unable to preserve the reward of their charity. God does not guide ňĻsuchňļ disbelieving people"
  2,265,"And the example of those who donate their wealth, seeking God‚Äôs pleasure and believing the reward is certain,¬†is that of a garden on a fertile hill: when heavy rain falls, it yields up twice its normal produce. If no heavy rain falls, a drizzle is sufficient. And God is All-Seeing of what you do"
  2,266,"Would any of you wish to have a garden with palm trees, grapevines, and all kinds of fruits with rivers flowing underneath and as they grow very old with dependent children, a fiery whirlwind hits the garden, burning it all up? This is how God makes His revelations clear to you, so perhaps you will reflect"
  2,267,"O believers! Donate from the best of what you have earned and of what We have produced for you from the earth. Do not pick out worthless things for donation, which you yourselves would only accept with closed eyes. And know that God is Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy"
  2,268,"The Devil threatens you with ňĻthe prospect ofňļ poverty and bids you to the shameful deed ňĻof stinginessňļ, while God promises you forgiveness and ňĻgreatňļ bounties from Him. And God is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing"
  2,269,God grants wisdom to whoever He wills. And whoever is granted wisdom is certainly blessed with a great privilege. But none will be mindful ňĻof thisňļ except people of reason
  2,270,Whatever charities you give or vows you make are surely known to God. And the wrongdoers will have no helpers
  2,271,"To give charity publicly is good, but to give to the poor privately is better for you, and will absolve you of your sins. And God is All-Aware of what you do"
  2,272,"You are not responsible for people‚Äôs guidance ňĻO Prophetňļ‚ÄĒit is God Who guides whoever He wills. Whatever you ňĻbelieversňļ spend in charity, it is for your own good‚ÄĒas long as you do so seeking the pleasure of God.¬†Whatever you donate will be paid back to you in full, and you will not be wronged"
  2,273,ňĻCharity isňļ for the needy who are too engaged in the cause of God to move about in the land ňĻfor workňļ. Those unfamiliar with their situation will think they are not in need ňĻof charityňļ because they do not beg. You can recognize them by their appearance. They do not beg people persistently. Whatever you give in charity is certainly well known to God
  2,274,"Those who spend their wealth in charity day and night, secretly and openly‚ÄĒtheir reward is with their Lord, and there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  2,275,"Those who consume interest will stand ňĻon Judgment Dayňļ like those driven to madness by Satan‚Äôs touch. That is because they say, ‚ÄúTrade is no different than interest.‚ÄĚ But God has permitted trading and forbidden interest. Whoever refrains‚ÄĒafter having received warning from their Lord‚ÄĒmay keep their previous gains, and their case is left to God. As for those who persist, it is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever"
  2,276,God has made interest fruitless and charity fruitful. And God does not like any ungrateful evildoer
  2,277,"Indeed, those who believe, do good, establish prayer, and pay alms-tax will receive their reward from their Lord, and there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  2,278,"O believers! Fear God, and give up outstanding interest if you are ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  2,279,"If you do not, then beware of a war with God and His Messenger! But if you repent, you may retain your principal‚ÄĒneither inflicting nor suffering harm"
  2,280,"If it is difficult for someone to repay a debt, postpone it until a time of ease. And if you waive it as an act of charity, it will be better for you, if only you knew"
  2,281,"Be mindful of the Day when you will ňĻallňļ be returned to God, then every soul will be paid in full for what it has done, and none will be wronged"
  2,282,"O believers! When you contract a loan for a fixed period of time, commit it to writing. Let the scribe maintain justice between the parties. The scribe should not refuse to write as God has taught them to write. They will write what the debtor dictates, bearing God in mind and not defrauding the debt. If the debtor is incompetent, weak, or unable to dictate, let their guardian dictate for them with justice. Call upon two of your men to witness. If two men cannot be found, then one man and two women of your choice will witness‚ÄĒso if one of the women forgets the other may remind her.¬†The witnesses must not refuse when they are summoned. You must not be against writing ňĻcontractsňļ for a fixed period‚ÄĒwhether the sum is small or great. This is more just ňĻfor youňļ in the sight of God, and more convenient to establish evidence and remove doubts. However, if you conduct an immediate transaction among yourselves, then there is no need for you to record it, but call upon witnesses when a deal is finalized. Let no harm come to the scribe or witnesses. If you do, then you have gravely exceeded ňĻyour limitsňļ. Be mindful of God, for God ňĻis the One Whoňļ teaches you. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  2,283,"If you are on a journey and a scribe cannot be found, then a security can be taken. If you trust one another, then ňĻthere is no need for a security, butňļ the debtor should honour this trust ňĻby repaying the debtňļ‚ÄĒand let them fear God, their Lord. And do not conceal the testimony, for whoever conceals it, their hearts are indeed sinful. And God ňĻfullyňļ knows what you do"
  2,284,"To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. Whether you reveal what is in your hearts or conceal it, God will call you to account for it. He forgives whoever He wills, and punishes whoever He wills. And God is Most Capable of everything"
  2,285,"The Messenger ňĻfirmlyňļ believes in what has been revealed to him from his Lord, and so do the believers. They ňĻallňļ believe in God, His angels, His Books, and His messengers. ňĻThey proclaim,ňļ ‚ÄúWe make no distinction between any of His messengers.‚ÄĚ And they say, ‚ÄúWe hear and obey. ňĻWe seekňļ Your forgiveness, our Lord! And to You ňĻaloneňļ is the final return.‚ÄĚ"
  2,286,"God does not require of any soul more than what it can afford. All good will be for its own benefit, and all evil will be to its own loss. ňĻThe believers pray,ňļ ‚ÄúOur Lord! Do not punish us if we forget or make a mistake. Our Lord! Do not place a burden on us like the one you placed on those before us. Our Lord! Do not burden us with what we cannot bear. Pardon us, forgive us, and have mercy on us. You are our ňĻonlyňļ Guardian. So grant us victory over the disbelieving people.‚ÄĚ"
  3,1,Alif-L√£m-Mń©m
  3,2,"God! There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him‚ÄĒthe Ever-Living, All-Sustaining"
  3,3,"He has revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ the Book in truth, confirming what came before it, as He revealed the Torah and the Gospel"
  3,4,"previously, as a guide for people, and ňĻalsoňļ revealed the Standard ňĻto distinguish between right and wrongňļ.¬†Surely those who reject God‚Äôs revelations will suffer a severe torment. For God is Almighty, capable of punishment"
  3,5,Surely nothing on earth or in the heavens is hidden from God
  3,6,"He is the One Who shapes you in the wombs of your mothers as He wills. There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him‚ÄĒthe Almighty, All-Wise"
  3,7,"He is the One Who has revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ the Book, of which some verses are precise‚ÄĒthey are the foundation of the Book‚ÄĒwhile others are elusive.¬†Those with deviant hearts follow the elusive verses seeking ňĻto spreadňļ doubt through their ňĻfalseňļ interpretations‚ÄĒbut none grasps their ňĻfullňļ meaning except God. As for those well-grounded in knowledge, they say, ‚ÄúWe believe in this ňĻQuranňļ‚ÄĒit is all from our Lord.‚ÄĚ But none will be mindful ňĻof thisňļ except people of reason"
  3,8,"ňĻThey say,ňļ ‚ÄúOur Lord! Do not let our hearts deviate after you have guided us. Grant us Your mercy. You are indeed the Giver ňĻof all bountiesňļ"
  3,9,Our Lord! You will certainly gather all humanity for the ňĻpromisedňļ Day‚ÄĒabout which there is no doubt. Surely God does not break His promise.‚ÄĚ
  3,10,"Indeed, neither the wealth nor children¬†of the disbelievers will be of any benefit to them against God‚ÄĒand they will be the fuel for the Fire"
  3,11,"Their fate will be like that of the people of Pharaoh and those before them‚ÄĒthey all rejected Our signs, so God seized them for their sins. And God is severe in punishment"
  3,12,"ňĻO Prophet!ňļ Tell the disbelievers, ‚ÄúSoon you will be overpowered and driven to Hell‚ÄĒwhat an evil place to rest!‚ÄĚ"
  3,13,"Indeed, there was a sign for you in the two armies that met in battle‚ÄĒone fighting for the cause of God and the other in denial. The believers saw their enemy twice their number.¬†But God supports with His victory whoever He wills. Surely in this is a lesson for people of insight"
  3,14,"The enjoyment of ňĻworldlyňļ desires‚ÄĒwomen, children,¬†treasures of gold and silver, fine horses, cattle, and fertile land‚ÄĒhas been made appealing to people. These are the pleasures of this worldly life, but with God is the finest destination"
  3,15,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúShall I inform you of what is better than ňĻall ofňļ this? Those mindful ňĻof Godňļ will have Gardens with their Lord under which rivers flow, to stay there forever, and pure spouses,¬†along with God‚Äôs pleasure.‚ÄĚ And God is All-Seeing of ňĻHisňļ servants"
  3,16,"who pray, ‚ÄúOur Lord! We have believed, so forgive our sins and protect us from the torment of the Fire.‚ÄĚ"
  3,17,"ňĻIt is theyňļ who are patient, sincere, obedient, and charitable, and who pray for forgiveness before dawn"
  3,18,"God ňĻHimselfňļ is a Witness that there is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him‚ÄĒand so are the angels and people of knowledge. He is the Maintainer of justice. There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him‚ÄĒthe Almighty, All-Wise"
  3,19,"Certainly, God‚Äôs only Way is Islam.¬†Those who were given the Scripture did not dispute ňĻamong themselvesňļ out of mutual envy until knowledge came to them.¬†Whoever denies God‚Äôs signs, then surely God is swift in reckoning"
  3,20,"So if they argue with you ňĻO Prophetňļ, say, ‚ÄúI have submitted myself to God, and so have my followers.‚ÄĚ And ask those who were given the Scripture and the illiterate ňĻpeopleňļ,¬†‚ÄúHave you submitted yourselves ňĻto Godňļ?‚ÄĚ If they submit, they will be ňĻrightlyňļ guided. But if they turn away, then your duty is only to deliver ňĻthe messageňļ. And God is All-Seeing of ňĻHisňļ servants"
  3,21,"Indeed, those who deny God‚Äôs signs, kill the prophets unjustly, and kill people who stand up for justice‚ÄĒgive them good news of a painful punishment"
  3,22,They are the ones whose deeds are wasted in this world and the Hereafter. And they will have no helpers
  3,23,"Have you not seen those who were given a portion of the Scriptures?¬†Yet when they are invited to the Book of God to settle their disputes, some of them turn away heedlessly"
  3,24,"This is because they say, ‚ÄúThe Fire will not touch us except for a few days.‚ÄĚ They have been deceived in their faith by their wishful lying"
  3,25,"But how ňĻhorribleňļ will it be when We gather them together on the Day about which there is no doubt‚ÄĒwhen every soul will be paid in full for what it has done, and none will be wronged"
  3,26,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO God! Lord over all authorities! You give authority to whoever You please and remove it from who You please; You honour whoever You please and disgrace who You please‚ÄĒall good is in Your Hands. Surely You ňĻaloneňļ are Most Capable of everything"
  3,27,You cause the night to pass into the day and the day into the night. You bring forth the living from the dead and the dead from the living. And You provide for whoever You will without limit.‚ÄĚ
  3,28,Believers should not take disbelievers as guardians instead of the believers‚ÄĒand whoever does so will have nothing to hope for from God‚ÄĒunless it is a precaution against their tyranny. And God warns you about Himself. And to God is the final return
  3,29,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWhether you conceal what is in your hearts or reveal it, it is known to God. For He knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. And God is Most Capable of everything.‚ÄĚ"
  3,30,ňĻWatch forňļ the Day when every soul will be presented with whatever good it has done. And it will wish that its misdeeds were far off. And God warns you about Himself. And God is Ever Gracious to ňĻHisňļ servants
  3,31,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIf you ňĻsincerelyňļ love God, then follow me; God will love you and forgive your sins. For God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  3,32,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúObey God and His Messenger.‚ÄĚ If they still turn away, then truly God does not like the disbelievers"
  3,33,"Indeed, God chose Adam, Noah, the family of Abraham, and the family of ‚ÄôImr√Ęn above all people ňĻof their timeňļ"
  3,34,"They are descendants of one another. And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  3,35,"ňĻRememberňļ when the wife of ‚ÄôImr√Ęn said, ‚ÄúMy Lord! I dedicate what is in my womb entirely to Your service,¬†so accept it from me. You ňĻaloneňļ are truly the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.‚ÄĚ"
  3,36,"When she delivered, she said, ‚ÄúMy Lord! I have given birth to a girl,‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒand God fully knew what she had delivered‚ÄĒ‚Äúand the male is not like the female.¬†I have named her Mary, and I seek Your protection for her and her offspring from Satan, the accursed.‚ÄĚ"
  3,37,"So her Lord accepted her graciously and blessed her with a pleasant upbringing‚ÄĒentrusting her to the care of Zachariah. Whenever Zachariah visited her in the sanctuary, he found her supplied with provisions. He exclaimed, ‚ÄúO Mary! Where did this come from?‚ÄĚ She replied, ‚ÄúIt is from God. Surely God provides for whoever He wills without limit.‚ÄĚ"
  3,38,"Then and there Zachariah prayed to his Lord, saying, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Grant me‚ÄĒby your grace‚ÄĒrighteous offspring. You are certainly the Hearer of ňĻallňļ prayers.‚ÄĚ"
  3,39,"So the angels called out to him while he stood praying in the sanctuary, ‚ÄúGod gives you good news of ňĻthe birth ofňļ John who will confirm the Word of God and will be a great leader, chaste, and a prophet among the righteous.‚ÄĚ"
  3,40,"Zachariah exclaimed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! How can I have a son when I am very old and my wife is barren?‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúSo will it be. God does what He wills.‚ÄĚ"
  3,41,"Zachariah said, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Grant me a sign.‚ÄĚ He said, ‚ÄúYour sign is that you will not ňĻbe able toňļ speak to people for three days except through gestures. Remember your Lord often and glorify ňĻHimňļ morning and evening.‚ÄĚ"
  3,42,"And ňĻrememberňļ when the angels said, ‚ÄúO Mary! Surely God has selected you, purified you, and chosen you over all women of the world"
  3,43,"O Mary! Be devout to your Lord, prostrate yourself ňĻin prayerňļ and bow along with those who bow down.‚ÄĚ"
  3,44,"This is news of the unseen that We reveal to you ňĻO Prophetňļ. You were not with them when they cast lots to decide who would be Mary‚Äôs guardian, nor were you there when they argued ňĻabout itňļ"
  3,45,"ňĻRememberňļ when the angels proclaimed, ‚ÄúO Mary! God gives you good news of a Word¬†from Him, his name will be the Messiah,¬†Jesus, son of Mary; honoured in this world and the Hereafter, and he will be one of those nearest ňĻto Godňļ"
  3,46,And he will speak to people in ňĻhisňļ infancy and adulthood and will be one of the righteous.‚ÄĚ
  3,47,"Mary wondered, ‚ÄúMy Lord! How can I have a child when no man has ever touched me?‚ÄĚ An angel replied, ‚ÄúSo will it be. God creates what He wills. When He decrees a matter, He simply tells it, ‚ÄėBe!‚Äô And it is"
  3,48,"And God will teach him writing and wisdom, the Torah and the Gospel"
  3,49,"and ňĻmake himňļ a messenger to the Children of Israel ňĻto proclaim,ňļ ‚ÄėI have come to you with a sign from your Lord: I will make for you a bird from clay, breathe into it, and it will become a ňĻrealňļ bird‚ÄĒby God‚Äôs Will. I will heal the blind and the leper and raise the dead to life‚ÄĒby God‚Äôs Will. And I will prophesize what you eat and store in your houses. Surely in this is a sign for you if you ňĻtrulyňļ believe"
  3,50,"And I will confirm the Torah revealed before me and legalize some of what had been forbidden to you. I have come to you with a sign from your Lord, so be mindful of God and obey me"
  3,51,Surely God is my Lord and your Lord. So worship Him ňĻaloneňļ. This is the Straight Path.‚Äô‚ÄĚ
  3,52,"When Jesus sensed disbelief from his people, he asked, ‚ÄúWho will stand up with me for God?‚ÄĚ The disciples replied, ‚ÄúWe will stand up for God. We believe in God, so bear witness that we have submitted.‚ÄĚ"
  3,53,"ňĻThey prayed to God,ňļ ‚ÄúOur Lord! We believe in Your revelations and follow the messenger, so count us among those who bear witness.‚ÄĚ"
  3,54,"And the disbelievers made a plan ňĻagainst Jesusňļ, but God also planned‚ÄĒand God is the best of planners"
  3,55,"ňĻRememberňļ when God said, ‚ÄúO Jesus! I will take you¬†and raise you up to Myself. I will deliver you from those who disbelieve, and elevate your followers above the disbelievers until the Day of Judgment. Then to Me you will ňĻallňļ return, and I will settle all your disputes"
  3,56,"As for those who disbelieve, I will subject them to a severe punishment in this life and the Hereafter, and they will have no helpers"
  3,57,"And as for those who believe and do good, they will be rewarded in full. And God does not like the wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  3,58,We recite ňĻallňļ this to you ňĻO Prophetňļ as one of the signs¬†and ňĻasňļ a wise reminder
  3,59,"Indeed, the example of Jesus in the sight of God is like that of Adam. He created him from dust, then said to him, ‚ÄúBe!‚ÄĚ And he was"
  3,60,"This is the truth from your Lord, so do not be one of those who doubt"
  3,61,"Now, whoever disputes with you ňĻO Prophetňļ concerning Jesus after full knowledge has come to you, say, ‚ÄúCome! Let us gather our children and your children, our women and your women, ourselves and yourselves‚ÄĒthen let us sincerely invoke God‚Äôs curse upon the liars.‚ÄĚ"
  3,62,"Certainly, this is the true narrative, and there is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except God. And indeed, God ňĻaloneňļ is the Almighty, All-Wise"
  3,63,"If they turn away, then surely God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of the corruptors"
  3,64,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO People of the Book! Let us come to common terms: that we will worship none but God, associate none with Him, nor take one another as lords instead of God.‚ÄĚ But if they turn away, then say, ‚ÄúBear witness that we have submitted ňĻto God aloneňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  3,65,"O People of the Book! Why do you argue about Abraham, while the Torah and the Gospel were not revealed until long after him? Do you not understand"
  3,66,"Here you are! You disputed about what you have ňĻlittleňļ knowledge of,¬†but why do you now argue about what you have no knowledge of?¬†God knows and you do not know"
  3,67,Abraham was neither a Jew nor a Christian; he submitted in all uprightness¬†and was not a polytheist
  3,68,"Indeed, those who have the best claim to Abraham are his followers, this Prophet,¬†and the believers. And God is the Guardian of those who believe"
  3,69,"Some of the People of the Book wish to mislead you ňĻbelieversňļ. They mislead none but themselves, yet they fail to perceive it"
  3,70,O People of the Book! Why do you reject the signs of God while you bear witness ňĻto their truthňļ
  3,71,O People of the Book! Why do you mix the truth with falsehood and hide the truth knowingly
  3,72,"A group among the People of the Book said ňĻto one anotherňļ, ‚ÄúBelieve in what has been revealed to the believers in the morning and reject it in the evening, so they may abandon their faith"
  3,73,"And only believe those who follow your religion.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúSurely, ňĻthe onlyňļ true guidance is God‚Äôs guidance.‚ÄĚ ňĻThey also said,ňļ ‚ÄúDo not believe that someone will receive ňĻrevealedňļ knowledge similar to yours or argue against you before your Lord.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIndeed, all bounty is in the Hands of God‚ÄĒHe grants it to whoever He wills. And God is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing.‚ÄĚ"
  3,74,He chooses whoever He wills to receive His mercy. And God is the Lord of infinite bounty
  3,75,"There are some among the People of the Book who, if entrusted with a stack of gold, will readily return it. Yet there are others who, if entrusted with a single coin, will not repay it unless you constantly demand it. This is because they say, ‚ÄúWe are not accountable for ňĻexploitingňļ the Gentiles.‚ÄĚ¬†And ňĻsoňļ they attribute lies to God knowingly"
  3,76,Absolutely! Those who honour their trusts and shun evil‚ÄĒsurely God loves those who are mindful ňĻof Himňļ
  3,77,"Indeed, those who trade God‚Äôs covenant and their oaths for a fleeting gain will have no share in the Hereafter. God will neither speak to them, nor look at them, nor purify them on the Day of Judgment. And they will suffer a painful punishment"
  3,78,"There are some among them who distort the Book with their tongues to make you think this ňĻdistortionňļ is from the Book‚ÄĒbut it is not what the Book says. They say, ‚ÄúIt is from God‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒbut it is not from God. And ňĻsoňļ they attribute lies to God knowingly"
  3,79,"It is not appropriate for someone who God has blessed with the Scripture, wisdom, and prophethood to say to people, ‚ÄúWorship me instead of God.‚ÄĚ Rather, he would say, ‚ÄúBe devoted to the worship of your Lord ňĻaloneňļ‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒin accordance with what these prophets read in the Scripture and what they taught"
  3,80,And he would never ask you to take angels and prophets as lords. Would he ask you to disbelieve after you have submitted
  3,81,"ňĻRememberňļ when God made a covenant with the prophets, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúNow that I have given you the Book and wisdom, if there comes to you a messenger¬†confirming what you have, you must believe in him and support him.‚ÄĚ He added, ‚ÄúDo you affirm this covenant and accept this commitment?‚ÄĚ They said, ‚ÄúYes, we do.‚ÄĚ God said, ‚ÄúThen bear witness, and I too am a Witness.‚ÄĚ"
  3,82,"Whoever turns back after this, they will be the rebellious"
  3,83,"Do they desire a way other than God‚Äôs‚ÄĒknowing that all those in the heavens and the earth submit to His Will, willingly or unwillingly, and to Him they will ňĻallňļ be returned"
  3,84,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWe believe in God and what has been revealed to us and what was revealed to Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants; and what was given to Moses, Jesus, and other prophets from their Lord‚ÄĒwe make no distinction between any of them, and to Him we ňĻfullyňļ submit.‚ÄĚ"
  3,85,"Whoever seeks a way other than Islam,¬†it will never be accepted from them, and in the Hereafter they will be among the losers"
  3,86,"How will God guide a people who chose to disbelieve after they had believed, acknowledged the Messenger to be true, and received clear proofs? For God does not guide the wrongdoing people"
  3,87,"Their reward is that they will be condemned by God, the angels, and all of humanity"
  3,88,"They will be in Hell forever. Their punishment will not be lightened, nor will they be delayed ňĻfrom itňļ"
  3,89,"As for those who repent afterwards and mend their ways, then surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  3,90,"Indeed, those who disbelieve after having believed then increase in disbelief, their repentance will never be accepted.¬†It is they who are astray"
  3,91,"Indeed, if each of those who disbelieve then die as disbelievers were to offer a ransom of enough gold to fill the whole world, it would never be accepted from them. It is they who will suffer a painful punishment, and they will have no helpers"
  3,92,You will never achieve righteousness until you donate some of what you cherish. And whatever you give is certainly well known to God
  3,93,"All food was lawful for the children of Israel, except what Israel¬†made unlawful for himself before the Torah was revealed.¬†Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúBring the Torah and read it, if your claims are true.‚ÄĚ"
  3,94,"Then whoever still fabricates lies about God, they will be the ňĻtrueňļ wrongdoers"
  3,95,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod has declared the truth. So follow the Way of Abraham, the upright‚ÄĒwho was not a polytheist.‚ÄĚ"
  3,96,Surely the first House ňĻof worshipňļ established for humanity is the one at Bakkah‚ÄĒa blessed sanctuary and a guide for ňĻallňļ people
  3,97,"In it are clear signs and the standing-place of Abraham. Whoever enters it should be safe. Pilgrimage to this House is an obligation by God upon whoever is able among the people.¬†And whoever disbelieves, then surely God is not in need of ňĻany of Hisňļ creation"
  3,98,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO People of the Book! Why do you deny the revelations of God, when God is a Witness to what you do?‚ÄĚ"
  3,99,"Say, ‚ÄúO People of the Book! Why do you turn the believers away from the Way of God‚ÄĒstriving to make it ňĻappearňļ crooked, while you are witnesses ňĻto its truthňļ? And God is never unaware of what you do.‚ÄĚ"
  3,100,"O believers! If you were to yield to a group of those who were given the Scripture, they would turn you back from belief to disbelief"
  3,101,How can you disbelieve when God‚Äôs revelations are recited to you and His Messenger is in your midst? Whoever holds firmly to God is surely guided to the Straight Path
  3,102,"O believers! Be mindful of God in the way He deserves,¬†and do not die except in ňĻa state of fullňļ submission ňĻto Himňļ"
  3,103,"And hold firmly to the rope of God¬†and do not be divided. Remember God‚Äôs favour upon you when you were enemies, then He united your hearts, so you‚ÄĒby His grace‚ÄĒbecame brothers. And you were at the brink of a fiery pit and He saved you from it. This is how God makes His revelations clear to you, so that you may be ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  3,104,"Let there be a group among you who call ňĻothersňļ to goodness, encourage what is good, and forbid what is evil‚ÄĒit is they who will be successful"
  3,105,And do not be like those who split ňĻinto sectsňļ and differed after clear proofs had come to them. It is they who will suffer a tremendous punishment
  3,106,"On that Day some faces will be bright while others gloomy. To the gloomy-faced it will be said, ‚ÄúDid you disbelieve after having believed? So taste the punishment for your disbelief.‚ÄĚ"
  3,107,"As for the bright-faced, they will be in God‚Äôs mercy, where they will remain forever"
  3,108,These are God‚Äôs revelations We recite to you ňĻO Prophetňļ in truth. And God desires no injustice to ňĻHisňļ creation
  3,109,To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. And to God ňĻallňļ matters will be returned ňĻfor judgmentňļ
  3,110,"You are the best community ever raised for humanity‚ÄĒyou encourage good, forbid evil, and believe in God. Had the People of the Book believed, it would have been better for them. Some of them are faithful, but most are rebellious"
  3,111,"They can never inflict harm on you, except a little annoyance.¬†But if they meet you in battle, they will flee and they will have no helpers"
  3,112,"They will be stricken with disgrace wherever they go, unless they are protected by a covenant with God or a treaty with the people. They have invited the displeasure of God and have been branded with misery for rejecting God‚Äôs revelations and murdering ňĻHisňļ prophets unjustly. This is ňĻa fair rewardňļ for their disobedience and violations"
  3,113,"Yet they are not all alike: there are some among the People of the Book who are upright, who recite God‚Äôs revelations throughout the night, prostrating ňĻin prayerňļ"
  3,114,"They believe in God and the Last Day, encourage good and forbid evil, and race with one another in doing good. They are ňĻtrulyňļ among the righteous"
  3,115,They will never be denied the reward for any good they have done. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of those mindful ňĻof Himňļ
  3,116,"Indeed, neither the wealth nor children of the disbelievers will be of any benefit to them against God. It is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever"
  3,117,"The good they do in this worldly life is like the harvest of an evil people struck by a bitter wind, destroying it ňĻcompletelyňļ. God never wronged them, but they wronged themselves"
  3,118,"O believers! Do not associate closely with others who would not miss a chance to harm you. Their only desire is to see you suffer. Their prejudice has become evident from what they say‚ÄĒand what their hearts hide is far worse. We have made Our revelations clear to you, if only you understood"
  3,119,"Here you are! You love them but they do not love you, and you believe in all Scriptures. When they meet you they say, ‚ÄúWe believe.‚ÄĚ But when alone, they bite their fingertips in rage. Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúňĻMay youňļ die of your rage!‚ÄĚ Surely God knows best what is ňĻhiddenňļ in the heart"
  3,120,"When you ňĻbelieversňļ are touched with good, they grieve; but when you are afflicted with evil, they rejoice. ňĻYet,ňļ if you are patient and mindful ňĻof Godňļ, their schemes will not harm you in the least. Surely God is Fully Aware of what they do"
  3,121,"ňĻRemember, O Prophet,ňļ when you left your home in the early morning to position the believers in the battlefield. And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  3,122,"ňĻRememberňļ when two groups among you ňĻbelieversňļ were about to cower, then God reassured them. So in God let the believers put their trust"
  3,123,"Indeed, God made you victorious at Badr when you were ňĻvastlyňļ outnumbered. So be mindful of God, perhaps you will be grateful"
  3,124,"ňĻRemember, O Prophet,ňļ when you said to the believers, ‚ÄúIs it not enough that your Lord will send down a reinforcement of three thousand angels for your aid?‚ÄĚ"
  3,125,"Most certainly, if you ňĻbelieversňļ are firm and mindful ňĻof Godňļ and the enemy launches a sudden attack on you, God will reinforce you with five thousand angels designated ňĻfor battleňļ"
  3,126,"God ordained this ňĻreinforcementňļ only as good news for you and reassurance for your hearts. And victory comes only from God‚ÄĒthe Almighty, All-Wise‚ÄĒ"
  3,127,"to destroy a group of the disbelievers and humble the rest, causing them to withdraw in disappointment"
  3,128,"You ňĻO Prophetňļ have no say in the matter.¬†It is up to God to turn to them in mercy or punish them, for indeed they are wrongdoers"
  3,129,"To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. He forgives whoever He wills, and punishes whoever He wills. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  3,130,"O believers! Do not consume interest, multiplying it many times over. And be mindful of God, so you may prosper"
  3,131,Guard yourselves against the Fire prepared for the disbelievers
  3,132,"Obey God and the Messenger, so you may be shown mercy"
  3,133,"And hasten towards forgiveness from your Lord and a Paradise as vast as the heavens and the earth, prepared for those mindful ňĻof Godňļ"
  3,134,"ňĻThey areňļ those who donate in prosperity and adversity, control their anger, and pardon others. And God loves the good-doers"
  3,135,"ňĻThey areňļ those who, upon committing an evil deed or wronging themselves, remember God and seek forgiveness and do not knowingly persist in sin‚ÄĒand who forgives sins except God"
  3,136,"Their reward is forgiveness from their Lord and Gardens under which rivers flow, staying there forever. How excellent is the reward for those who work ňĻrighteousnessňļ"
  3,137,"Similar situations came to pass before you, so travel throughout the land and see the fate of the deniers"
  3,138,This¬†is an insight to humanity‚ÄĒa guide and a lesson to the God-fearing
  3,139,"Do not falter or grieve, for you will have the upper hand, if you are ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  3,140,"If you have suffered injuries ňĻat UŠł•udňļ, they suffered similarly ňĻat Badrňļ. We alternate these days ňĻof victory and defeatňļ among people so that God may reveal the ňĻtrueňļ believers, choose martyrs from among you‚ÄĒand God does not like the wrongdoers‚ÄĒ"
  3,141,and distinguish the ňĻtrueňļ believers and destroy the disbelievers
  3,142,Do you think you will enter Paradise without God proving which of you ňĻtrulyňļ struggled ňĻfor His causeňļ and patiently endured
  3,143,"You certainly wished ňĻfor the opportunityňļ for martyrdom before encountering it, now you have seen it with your own eyes"
  3,144,"MuŠł•ammad is no more than a messenger; other messengers have gone before him. If he were to die or to be killed, would you regress into disbelief? Those who do so will not harm God whatsoever. And God will reward those who are grateful"
  3,145,"No soul can ever die without God‚Äôs Will at the destined time. Those who desire worldly gain, We will let them have it, and those who desire heavenly reward, We will grant it to them. And We will reward those who are grateful"
  3,146,"ňĻImagineňļ how many devotees fought along with their prophets and never faltered despite whatever ňĻlossesňļ they suffered in the cause of God, nor did they weaken or give in! God loves those who persevere"
  3,147,"And all they said was, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Forgive our sins and excesses, make our steps firm, and grant us victory over the disbelieving people.‚ÄĚ"
  3,148,So God gave them the reward of this world and the excellent reward of the Hereafter. For God loves the good-doers
  3,149,"O believers! If you yield to the disbelievers, they will drag you back to disbelief‚ÄĒand you will become losers"
  3,150,"But no! God is your Guardian, and He is the best Helper"
  3,151,We will cast horror into the hearts of the disbelievers for associating ňĻfalse godsňļ with God‚ÄĒa practice He has never authorized. The Fire will be their home‚ÄĒwhat an evil place for the wrongdoers to stay
  3,152,"Indeed, God fulfilled His promise to you when you ňĻinitiallyňļ swept them away by His Will, then your courage weakened and you disputed about the command and disobeyed,¬†after God had brought victory within your reach. Some of you were after worldly gain while others desired a heavenly reward. He denied you victory over them as a test, yet He has pardoned you. And God is Gracious to the believers"
  3,153,"ňĻRememberňļ when you were running far away ňĻin panicňļ‚ÄĒnot looking at anyone‚ÄĒwhile the Messenger was calling to you from behind! So God rewarded your disobedience with distress upon distress. Now, do not grieve over the victory you were denied or the injury you suffered. And God is All-Aware of what you do"
  3,154,"Then after distress, He sent down serenity in the form of drowsiness overcoming some of you, while others were disturbed by evil thoughts about God‚ÄĒthe thoughts of ňĻpre-Islamicňļ ignorance. They ask, ‚ÄúDo we have a say in the matter?‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúAll matters are destined by God.‚ÄĚ They conceal in their hearts what they do not reveal to you. They say ňĻto themselvesňļ, ‚ÄúIf we had any say in the matter, none of us would have come to die here.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúEven if you were to remain in your homes, those among you who were destined to be killed would have met the same fate.‚ÄĚ Through this, God tests what is within you and purifies what is in your hearts. And God knows best what is ňĻhiddenňļ in the heart"
  3,155,"Indeed, those ňĻbelieversňļ who fled on the day when the two armies met were made to slip by Satan because of their misdeeds. But God has pardoned them. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing"
  3,156,"O believers! Do not be like the unfaithful¬†who say about their brothers who travel throughout the land or engage in battle, ‚ÄúIf they had stayed with us, they would not have died or been killed.‚ÄĚ God makes such thinking a cause of agony in their hearts. It is God who gives life and causes death. And God is All-Seeing of what you do"
  3,157,"Should you be martyred or die in the cause of God, then His forgiveness and mercy are far better than whatever ňĻwealthňļ those ňĻwho stay behindňļ accumulate"
  3,158,Whether you die or are martyred‚ÄĒall of you will be gathered before God
  3,159,"It is out of God‚Äôs mercy that you ňĻO Prophetňļ have been lenient with them. Had you been cruel or hard-hearted, they would have certainly abandoned you. So pardon them, ask God‚Äôs forgiveness for them, and consult with them in ňĻconductingňļ matters. Once you make a decision, put your trust in God. Surely God loves those who trust in Him"
  3,160,"If God helps you, none can defeat you. But if He denies you help, then who else can help you? So in God let the believers put their trust"
  3,161,"It is not appropriate for a prophet to illegally withhold spoils of war. And whoever does so, it will be held against them on the Day of Judgment. Then every soul will be paid in full for what it has done, and none will be wronged"
  3,162,Are those who seek God‚Äôs pleasure like those who deserve God‚Äôs wrath? Hell is their home. What an evil destination
  3,163,They ňĻeachňļ have varying degrees in the sight of God. And God is All-Seeing of what they do
  3,164,"Indeed, God has done the believers a ňĻgreatňļ favour by raising a messenger from among them‚ÄĒreciting to them His revelations, purifying them, and teaching them the Book and wisdom. For indeed they had previously been clearly astray"
  3,165,"Why is it when you suffered casualties ňĻat UŠł•udňļ‚ÄĒalthough you had made your enemy suffer twice as much ňĻat Badrňļ‚ÄĒyou protested, ‚ÄúHow could this be?‚ÄĚ? Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIt is because of your disobedience.‚ÄĚ Surely God is Most Capable of everything"
  3,166,"So what you suffered on the day the two armies met was by God‚Äôs Will, so that He might distinguish the ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  3,167,"and expose the hypocrites. When it was said to them, ‚ÄúCome fight in the cause of God or ňĻat leastňļ defend yourselves,‚ÄĚ they replied, ‚ÄúIf we had known there was fighting, we would have definitely gone with you.‚ÄĚ They were closer to disbelief than to belief on that day‚ÄĒfor saying with their mouths what was not in their hearts. God is All-Knowing of what they hide"
  3,168,"Those who sat at home, saying about their brothers, ‚ÄúHad they listened to us, they would not have been killed.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúTry not to die¬†if what you say is true!‚ÄĚ"
  3,169,"Never think of those martyred in the cause of God as dead. In fact, they are alive with their Lord, well provided for‚ÄĒ"
  3,170,"rejoicing in God‚Äôs bounties and being delighted for those yet to join them. There will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  3,171,"They are joyful for receiving God‚Äôs grace and bounty, and that God does not deny the reward of the believers"
  3,172,"ňĻAs forňļ those who responded to the call of God and His Messenger after their injury,¬†those of them who did good and were mindful ňĻof Godňļ will have a great reward"
  3,173,"Those who were warned, ‚ÄúYour enemies have mobilized their forces against you, so fear them,‚ÄĚ the warning only made them grow stronger in faith and they replied, ‚ÄúGod ňĻaloneňļ is sufficient ňĻas an aidňļ for us and ňĻHeňļ is the best Protector.‚ÄĚ"
  3,174,"So they returned with God‚Äôs favours and grace, suffering no harm. For they sought to please God. And surely God is ňĻtheňļ Lord of infinite bounty"
  3,175,"That ňĻwarningňļ was only ňĻfromňļ Satan, trying to prompt you to fear his followers.¬†So do not fear them; fear Me if you are ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  3,176,"ňĻO Prophet!ňļ Do not grieve for those who race to disbelieve‚ÄĒsurely they will not harm God in the least. It is God‚Äôs Will to disallow them a share in the Hereafter, and they will suffer a tremendous punishment"
  3,177,"Those who trade belief for disbelief will never harm God in the least, and they will suffer a painful punishment"
  3,178,"Those who disbelieve should not think that living longer is good for them. They are only given more time to increase in sin, and they will suffer a humiliating punishment"
  3,179,"God would not leave the believers in the condition you were in, until He distinguished the good from the evil ňĻamong youňļ. Nor would God ňĻdirectlyňļ reveal to you the unseen,¬†but He chooses whoever He wills as a messenger. So believe in God and His messengers. And if you are faithful and mindful ňĻof Godňļ, you will receive a great reward"
  3,180,"And do not let those who ňĻgreedilyňļ withhold God‚Äôs bounties think it is good for them‚ÄĒin fact, it is bad for them! They will be leashed ňĻby their necksňļ on the Day of Judgment with whatever ňĻwealthňļ they used to withhold. And God is the ňĻsoleňļ inheritor of the heavens and the earth. And God is All-Aware of what you do"
  3,181,"Indeed, God has heard those ňĻamong the Jewsňļ who said, ‚ÄúGod is poor; we are rich!‚ÄĚ We have certainly recorded their slurs and their killing of prophets unjustly. Then We will say, ‚ÄúTaste the torment of burning"
  3,182,This is ňĻthe rewardňļ for what your hands have done. And God is never unjust to ňĻHisňļ creation.‚ÄĚ
  3,183,"Those ňĻare the same peopleňļ who say, ‚ÄúGod has commanded us not to believe in any messenger unless he brings us an offering to be consumed by fire ňĻfrom the skyňļ.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúOther prophets did in fact come to you¬†before me with clear proofs and ňĻevenňļ what you demanded‚ÄĒwhy then did you kill them, if what you say is true?‚ÄĚ"
  3,184,"If you are rejected by them, so too were messengers before you who came with clear proofs, divine Books, and enlightening Scriptures"
  3,185,"Every soul will taste death. And you will only receive your full reward on the Day of Judgment. Whoever is spared from the Fire and is admitted into Paradise will ňĻindeedňļ triumph, whereas the life of this world is no more than the delusion of enjoyment"
  3,186,"You ňĻbelieversňļ will surely be tested in your wealth and yourselves,¬†and you will certainly hear many hurtful words from those who were given the Scripture before you and ňĻfromňļ the polytheists. But if you are patient and mindful ňĻof Godňļ‚ÄĒsurely this is a resolve to aspire to"
  3,187,"ňĻRemember, O Prophet,ňļ when God took the covenant of those who were given the Scripture to make it known to people and not hide it, yet they cast it behind their backs and traded it for a fleeting gain. What a miserable profit"
  3,188,Do not let those who rejoice in their misdeeds and love to take credit for what they have not done think they will escape torment. They will suffer a painful punishment
  3,189,To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth. And God is Most Capable of everything
  3,190,"Indeed, in the creation of the heavens and the earth and the alternation of the day and night there are signs for people of reason"
  3,191,"ňĻThey areňļ those who remember God while standing, sitting, and lying on their sides, and reflect on the creation of the heavens and the earth ňĻand prayňļ, ‚ÄúOur Lord! You have not created ňĻall ofňļ this without purpose. Glory be to You! Protect us from the torment of the Fire"
  3,192,"Our Lord! Indeed, those You commit to the Fire will be ňĻcompletelyňļ disgraced! And the wrongdoers will have no helpers"
  3,193,"Our Lord! We have heard the caller¬†to ňĻtrueňļ belief, ňĻproclaiming,ňļ ‚ÄėBelieve in your Lord ňĻaloneňļ,‚Äô so we believed. Our Lord! Forgive our sins, absolve us of our misdeeds, and allow us ňĻeachňļ to die as one of the virtuous"
  3,194,Our Lord! Grant us what You have promised us through Your messengers and do not put us to shame on Judgment Day‚ÄĒfor certainly You never fail in Your promise.‚ÄĚ
  3,195,"So their Lord responded to them: ‚ÄúI will never deny any of you‚ÄĒmale or female‚ÄĒthe reward of your deeds. Both are equal in reward. Those who migrated or were expelled from their homes, and were persecuted for My sake and fought and ňĻsomeňļ were martyred‚ÄĒI will certainly forgive their sins and admit them into Gardens under which rivers flow, as a reward from God. And with God is the finest reward!‚ÄĚ"
  3,196,Do not be deceived by the prosperity of the disbelievers throughout the land
  3,197,It is only a brief enjoyment. Then Hell will be their home‚ÄĒwhat an evil place to rest
  3,198,"But those who are mindful of their Lord will be in Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there forever‚ÄĒas an accommodation from God. And what is with God is best for the virtuous"
  3,199,"Indeed, there are some among the People of the Book who truly believe in God and what has been revealed to you ňĻbelieversňļ and what was revealed to them. They humble themselves before God‚ÄĒnever trading God‚Äôs revelations for a fleeting gain. Their reward is with their Lord. Surely God is swift in reckoning"
  3,200,"O believers! Patiently endure, persevere, stand on guard,¬†and be mindful of God, so you may be successful"
  4,1,"O humanity! Be mindful of your Lord Who created you from a single soul, and from it He created its mate,¬†and through both He spread countless men and women. And be mindful of God‚ÄĒin Whose Name you appeal to one another‚ÄĒand ňĻhonourňļ family ties. Surely God is ever Watchful over you"
  4,2,"Give orphans their wealth ňĻwhen they reach maturityňļ, and do not exchange your worthless possessions for their valuables, nor cheat them by mixing their wealth with your own. For this would indeed be a great sin"
  4,3,"If you fear you might fail to give orphan women their ňĻdueňļ rights ňĻif you were to marry themňļ, then marry other women of your choice‚ÄĒtwo, three, or four. But if you are afraid you will fail to maintain justice, then ňĻcontent yourselves withňļ one¬†or those ňĻbondwomenňļ in your possession.¬†This way you are less likely to commit injustice"
  4,4,"Give women ňĻyou wedňļ their due dowries graciously. But if they waive some of it willingly, then you may enjoy it freely with a clear conscience"
  4,5,"Do not entrust the incapable ňĻamong your dependantsňļ with your wealth which God has made a means of support for you‚ÄĒbut feed and clothe them from it, and speak to them kindly"
  4,6,"Test ňĻthe competence ofňļ the orphans until they reach a marriageable age. Then if you feel they are capable of sound judgment, return their wealth to them. And do not consume it wastefully and hastily before they grow up ňĻto demand itňļ. If the guardian is well-off, they should not take compensation; but if the guardian is poor, let them take a reasonable provision. When you give orphans back their property, call in witnesses. And sufficient is God as a ňĻvigilantňļ Reckoner"
  4,7,"For men there is a share in what their parents and close relatives leave, and for women there is a share in what their parents and close relatives leave‚ÄĒwhether it is little or much. ňĻThese areňļ obligatory shares"
  4,8,"If ňĻnon-inheritingňļ relatives, orphans,¬†or the needy are present at the time of distribution, offer them a ňĻsmallňļ provision from it and speak to them kindly"
  4,9,Let the guardians be as concerned ňĻfor the orphansňļ as they would if they were to ňĻdie andňļ leave ňĻtheir ownňļ helpless children behind. So let them be mindful of God and speak equitably
  4,10,"Indeed, those who unjustly consume orphans‚Äô wealth ňĻin factňļ consume nothing but fire into their bellies. And they will be burned in a blazing Hell"
  4,11,"God commands you regarding your children: the share of the male will be twice that of the female.¬†If you leave only two ňĻor moreňļ females, their share is two-thirds of the estate. But if there is only one female, her share will be one-half. Each parent is entitled to one-sixth if you leave offspring.¬†But if you are childless and your parents are the only heirs, then your mother will receive one-third.¬†But if you leave siblings, then your mother will receive one-sixth‚ÄĒafter the fulfilment of bequests and debts.¬†ňĻBe fair toňļ your parents and children, as you do not ňĻfullyňļ know who is more beneficial to you.¬†ňĻThis isňļ an obligation from God. Surely God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,12,"You will inherit half of what your wives leave if they are childless. But if they have children, then ňĻyour share isňļ one-fourth of the estate‚ÄĒafter the fulfilment of bequests and debts. And your wives will inherit one-fourth of what you leave if you are childless. But if you have children, then your wives will receive one-eighth of your estate‚ÄĒafter the fulfilment of bequests and debts. And if a man or a woman leaves neither parents nor children but only a brother or a sister ňĻfrom their mother‚Äôs sideňļ, they will each inherit one-sixth, but if they are more than one, they ňĻallňļ will share one-third of the estate‚ÄĒafter the fulfilment of bequests and debts without harm ňĻto the heirsňļ.¬†ňĻThis isňļ a commandment from God. And God is All-Knowing, Most Forbearing"
  4,13,"These ňĻentitlementsňļ are the limits set by God. Whoever obeys God and His Messenger will be admitted into Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there forever. That is the ultimate triumph"
  4,14,"But whoever disobeys God and His Messenger and exceeds their limits will be cast into Hell, to stay there forever. And they will suffer a humiliating punishment"
  4,15,"ňĻAs forňļ those of your women who commit illegal intercourse‚ÄĒcall four witnesses from among yourselves. If they testify, confine the offenders to their homes until they die or God ordains a ňĻdifferentňļ way for them"
  4,16,"And the two among you who commit this sin‚ÄĒdiscipline them. If they repent and mend their ways, relieve them. Surely God is ever Accepting of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  4,17,"God only accepts the repentance of those who commit evil ignorantly ňĻor recklesslyňļ then repent soon after‚ÄĒGod will pardon them. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,18,"However, repentance is not accepted from those who knowingly persist in sin until they start dying, and then cry, ‚ÄúNow I repent!‚ÄĚ nor those who die as disbelievers. For them We have prepared a painful punishment"
  4,19,"O believers! It is not permissible for you to inherit women against their will¬†or mistreat them to make them return some of the dowry ňĻas a ransom for divorceňļ‚ÄĒunless they are found guilty of adultery.¬†Treat them fairly. If you happen to dislike them, you may hate something which God turns into a great blessing"
  4,20,"If you desire to replace a wife with another and you have given the former ňĻevenňļ a stack of gold ňĻas a dowryňļ, do not take any of it back. Would you ňĻstillňļ take it unjustly and very sinfully"
  4,21,And how could you take it back after having enjoyed each other intimately and she has taken from you a firm commitment
  4,22,"Do not marry former wives of your fathers‚ÄĒexcept what was done previously. It was indeed a shameful, despicable, and evil practice"
  4,23,"ňĻAlsoňļ forbidden to you for marriage are your mothers, your daughters, your sisters, your paternal and maternal aunts, your brother‚Äôs daughters, your sister‚Äôs daughters, your foster-mothers, your foster-sisters, your mothers-in-law, your stepdaughters under your guardianship if you have consummated marriage with their mothers‚ÄĒbut if you have not, then you can marry them‚ÄĒnor the wives of your own sons, nor two sisters together at the same time‚ÄĒexcept what was done previously. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,24,"Also ňĻforbidden areňļ married women‚ÄĒexcept ňĻfemaleňļ captives in your possession.¬†This is God‚Äôs commandment to you. Lawful to you are all beyond these‚ÄĒas long as you seek them with your wealth in a legal marriage, not in fornication. Give those you have consummated marriage with their due dowries. It is permissible to be mutually gracious regarding the set dowry. Surely God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,25,"But if any of you cannot afford to marry a free believing woman, then ňĻlet him marryňļ a believing bondwoman possessed by one of you. God knows best ňĻthe state ofňļ your faith ňĻand theirsňļ. You are from one another.¬†So marry them with the permission of their owners,¬†giving them their dowry in fairness, if they are chaste, neither promiscuous nor having secret affairs. If they commit indecency after marriage, they receive half the punishment of free women.¬†This is for those of you who fear falling into sin. But if you are patient, it is better for you. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,26,"It is God‚Äôs Will to make things clear to you, guide you to the ňĻnobleňļ ways of those before you, and turn to you in mercy. For God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,27,"And it is God‚Äôs Will to turn to you in grace, but those who follow their desires wish to see you deviate entirely ňĻfrom God‚Äôs Wayňļ"
  4,28,"And it is God‚Äôs Will to lighten your burdens, for humankind was created weak"
  4,29,"O believers! Do not devour one another‚Äôs wealth illegally, but rather trade by mutual consent. And do not kill ňĻeach other orňļ yourselves. Surely God is ever Merciful to you"
  4,30,"And whoever does this sinfully and unjustly, We will burn them in the Fire. That is easy for God"
  4,31,"If you avoid the major sins forbidden to you, We will absolve you of your ňĻlesserňļ misdeeds and admit you into a place of honour"
  4,32,"And do not crave what God has given some of you over others. Men will be rewarded according to their deeds and women ňĻequallyňļ according to theirs. Rather, ask God for His bounties. Surely God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  4,33,"And We have appointed heirs to what has been left by parents and next of kin. As for those you have made a pledge to, give them their share.¬†Surely God is a Witness over all things"
  4,34,"Men are the caretakers of women, as men have been provisioned by God over women and tasked with supporting them financially. And righteous women are devoutly obedient and, when alone, protective of what God has entrusted them with.¬†And if you sense ill-conduct from your women, advise them ňĻfirstňļ, ňĻif they persist,ňļ do not share their beds, ňĻbut if they still persist,ňļ then discipline them ňĻgentlyňļ.¬†But if they change their ways, do not be unjust to them. Surely God is Most High, All-Great"
  4,35,"If you anticipate a split between them, appoint a mediator from his family and another from hers. If they desire reconciliation, God will restore harmony between them. Surely God is All-Knowing, All-Aware"
  4,36,"Worship God ňĻaloneňļ and associate none with Him. And be kind to parents, relatives, orphans, the poor, near and distant neighbours, close friends, ňĻneedyňļ travellers, and those ňĻbondspeopleňļ in your possession. Surely God does not like whoever is arrogant, boastful‚ÄĒ"
  4,37,"those who are stingy, promote stinginess among people, and withhold God‚Äôs bounties. We have prepared for the disbelievers a humiliating punishment"
  4,38,Likewise for those who spend their wealth to show off and do not believe in God or the Last Day. And whoever takes Satan as an associate‚ÄĒwhat an evil associate they have
  4,39,What harm could have come to them if they had believed in God and the Last Day and donated from what God has provided for them? And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of them
  4,40,"Indeed, God never wrongs ňĻanyoneňļ‚ÄĒeven by an atom‚Äôs weight.¬†And if it is a good deed, He will multiply it many times over and will give a great reward out of His grace"
  4,41,So how will it be when We bring a witness from every faith-community and bring you ňĻO Prophetňļ as a witness against yours
  4,42,"On that Day, those who denied ňĻGodňļ and disobeyed the Messenger will wish they were reduced to dust. And they will never be able to hide anything from God"
  4,43,"O believers! Do not approach prayer while intoxicated¬†until you are aware of what you say, nor in a state of ňĻfullňļ impurity‚ÄĒunless you merely pass through ňĻthe mosqueňļ‚ÄĒuntil you have bathed. But if you are ill, on a journey, or have relieved yourselves, or been intimate with your wives and cannot find water, then purify yourselves with clean earth, wiping your faces and hands.¬†And God is Ever-Pardoning, All-Forgiving"
  4,44,Have you ňĻO Prophetňļ not seen those who were given a portion of the Scriptures yet trade it for misguidance and wish to see you deviate from the ňĻRightňļ Path
  4,45,"God knows best who your enemies are! And God is sufficient as a Guardian, and He is sufficient as a Helper"
  4,46,"Some Jews take words out of context and say, ‚ÄúWe listen and we disobey,‚ÄĚ ‚ÄúHear! May you never hear,‚ÄĚ and ‚ÄúR√Ę‚Äôina!‚ÄĚ [Herd us!]‚ÄĒplaying with words and discrediting the faith. Had they said ňĻcourteouslyňļ, ‚ÄúWe hear and obey,‚ÄĚ ‚ÄúListen to us,‚ÄĚ and ‚ÄúUnŠļďurna,‚ÄĚ [Tend to us!] it would have been better for them and more proper. God has condemned them for their disbelief, so they do not believe except for a few"
  4,47,"O you who were given the Book! Believe in what We have revealed‚ÄĒconfirming your own Scriptures‚ÄĒbefore We wipe out ňĻyourňļ faces, turning them backwards, or We condemn the defiant as We did to the Sabbath-breakers.¬†And God‚Äôs command is always executed"
  4,48,"Indeed, God does not forgive associating others with Him ňĻin worshipňļ,¬†but forgives anything else of whoever He wills. And whoever associates others with God has indeed committed a grave sin"
  4,49,Have you ňĻO Prophetňļ not seen those who ňĻfalselyňļ elevate themselves? It is God who elevates whoever He wills. And none will be wronged ňĻeven by the width ofňļ the thread of a date stone
  4,50,See how they fabricate lies against God‚ÄĒthis alone is a blatant sin
  4,51,Have you ňĻO Prophetňļ not seen those who were given a portion of the Scriptures yet believe in idols and false gods and reassure the disbelievers¬†that they are better guided than the believers
  4,52,It is they who have been condemned by God. And whoever is condemned by God will have no helper
  4,53,"Do they have control over shares of the kingdom? If so, they would not have given anyone so much as the speck on a date stone"
  4,54,"Or do they envy the people for God‚Äôs bounties? Indeed, We have given the descendants of Abraham the Book and wisdom, along with great authority"
  4,55,Yet some believed in him while others turned away from him.¬†Hell is sufficient as a torment
  4,56,"Surely those who reject Our signs, We will cast them into the Fire. Whenever their skin is burnt completely, We will replace it so they will ňĻconstantlyňļ taste the punishment. Indeed, God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  4,57,"As for those who believe and do good, We will admit them into Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there for ever and ever. There they will have pure spouses,¬†and We will place them under a vast shade"
  4,58,"Indeed, God commands you to return trusts to their rightful owners;¬†and when you judge between people, judge with fairness. What a noble commandment from God to you! Surely God is All-Hearing, All-Seeing"
  4,59,"O believers! Obey God and obey the Messenger and those in authority among you. Should you disagree on anything, then refer it to God and His Messenger, if you ňĻtrulyňļ believe in God and the Last Day. This is the best and fairest resolution"
  4,60,"Have you ňĻO Prophetňļ not seen those who claim they believe in what has been revealed to you and what was revealed before you? They seek the judgment of false judges, which they were commanded to reject. And Satan ňĻonlyňļ desires to lead them farther away"
  4,61,"When it is said to them, ‚ÄúCome to God‚Äôs revelations and to the Messenger,‚ÄĚ you see the hypocrites turn away from you stubbornly"
  4,62,"How ňĻhorribleňļ will it be if a disaster strikes them because of what their hands have done, then they come to you swearing by God, ‚ÄúWe intended nothing but goodwill and reconciliation.‚ÄĚ"
  4,63,"ňĻOnlyňļ God knows what is in their hearts. So turn away from them, caution them, and give them advice that will shake their very souls"
  4,64,"We only sent messengers to be obeyed by God‚Äôs Will. If only those ňĻhypocritesňļ came to you ňĻO Prophetňļ‚ÄĒafter wronging themselves‚ÄĒseeking God‚Äôs forgiveness and the Messenger prayed for their forgiveness, they would have certainly found God ever Accepting of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  4,65,"But no! By your Lord, they will never be ňĻtrueňļ believers until they accept you ňĻO Prophetňļ as the judge in their disputes, and find no resistance within themselves against your decision and submit wholeheartedly"
  4,66,"If We had commanded them to sacrifice themselves or abandon their homes, none would have obeyed except for a few. Had they done what they were advised to do,¬†it would have certainly been far better for them and more reassuring"
  4,67,and We would have granted them a great reward by Our grace
  4,68,and guided them to the Straight Path
  4,69,"And whoever obeys God and the Messenger will be in the company of those blessed by God: the prophets, the people of truth, the martyrs, and the righteous‚ÄĒwhat honourable company"
  4,70,"This is God‚Äôs favour, and God fully knows ňĻwho deserves itňļ"
  4,71,O believers! Take your precautions and go forth either in groups or together
  4,72,"There will be some among you who will lag behind so that if you face a disaster, they will say, ‚ÄúGod has blessed us for not being there among them.‚ÄĚ"
  4,73,"But if you return with God‚Äôs bounties, they will say‚ÄĒas if there had been no bond between you‚ÄĒ‚ÄúWe wish we had been there with them to share the great gain!‚ÄĚ"
  4,74,Let those who would sacrifice this life for the Hereafter fight in the cause of God. And whoever fights in God‚Äôs cause‚ÄĒwhether they achieve martyrdom or victory‚ÄĒWe will honour them with a great reward
  4,75,"And what is it with you? You do not fight in the cause of God and for oppressed men, women, and children who cry out, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Deliver us from this land of oppressors! Appoint for us a saviour; appoint for us a helper‚ÄĒall by Your grace.‚ÄĚ"
  4,76,"Believers fight for the cause of God, whereas disbelievers fight for the cause of the Devil. So fight against Satan‚Äôs ňĻevilňļ forces. Indeed, Satan‚Äôs schemes are ever weak"
  4,77,"Have you ňĻO Prophetňļ not seen those who had been told, ‚ÄúDo not fight! Rather, establish prayer and pay alms-tax.‚ÄĚ? Then once the order came to fight, a group of them feared those ňĻhostileňļ people as God should be feared‚ÄĒor even more. They said, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Why have You ordered us to fight? If only You had delayed ňĻthe order forňļ us for a little while!‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúThe enjoyment of this world is so little, whereas the Hereafter is far better for those mindful ňĻof Godňļ. And none of you will be wronged ňĻeven by the width ofňļ the thread of a date stone"
  4,78,"Wherever you may be, death will overcome you‚ÄĒeven if you were in fortified towers.‚ÄĚ When something good befalls them, they say, ‚ÄúThis is from God,‚ÄĚ but when something evil befalls them, they say, ‚ÄúThis is from you.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúBoth have been destined by God.‚ÄĚ So what is the matter with these people? They can hardly comprehend anything"
  4,79,Whatever good befalls you is from God and whatever evil befalls you is from yourself.¬†We have sent you ňĻO Prophetňļ as a messenger to ňĻallňļ people. And God is sufficient as a Witness
  4,80,"Whoever obeys the Messenger has truly obeyed God. But whoever turns away, then ňĻknow thatňļ We have not sent you ňĻO Prophetňļ as a keeper over them"
  4,81,"And they say, ‚ÄúWe obey,‚ÄĚ but when they leave you, a group of them would spend the night contradicting what they said. God records all their schemes. So turn away from them, and put your trust in God. And God is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs"
  4,82,"Do they not then reflect on the Quran? Had it been from anyone other than God, they would have certainly found in it many inconsistencies"
  4,83,"And when they hear news of security or fear,¬†they publicize it. Had they referred it to the Messenger or their authorities, those with sound judgment among them would have validated it. Had it not been for God‚Äôs grace and mercy, you would have followed Satan‚ÄĒexcept for a few"
  4,84,"So fight in the cause of God ňĻO Prophetňļ. You are accountable for none but yourself. And motivate the believers ňĻto fightňļ, so perhaps God will curb the disbelievers‚Äô might. And God is far superior in might and in punishment"
  4,85,"Whoever intercedes for a good cause will have a share in the reward, and whoever intercedes for an evil cause will have a share in the burden. And God is Watchful over all things"
  4,86,"And when you are greeted, respond with a better greeting or at least similarly. Surely God is a ňĻvigilantňļ Reckoner of all things"
  4,87,"God, there is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. He will certainly gather ňĻall ofňļ you together on the Day of Judgment‚ÄĒabout which there is no doubt. And whose word is more truthful than God‚Äôs"
  4,88,"Why are you ňĻbelieversňļ divided into two groups regarding the hypocrites while God allowed them to regress ňĻto disbeliefňļ because of their misdeeds? Do you wish to guide those left by God to stray? And whoever God leaves to stray, you will never find for them a way"
  4,89,"They wish you would disbelieve as they have disbelieved, so you may all be alike. So do not take them as allies unless they emigrate in the cause of God. But if they turn away, then seize them and kill them wherever you find them, and do not take any of them as allies or helpers"
  4,90,"except those who are allies of a people you are bound with in a treaty or those wholeheartedly opposed to fighting either you or their own people. If God had willed, He would have empowered them to fight you. So if they refrain from fighting you and offer you peace, then God does not permit you to harm them"
  4,91,"You will find others who wish to be safe from you and their own people. Yet they cannot resist the temptation ňĻof disbelief or hostilityňļ. If they do not keep away, offer you peace, or refrain from attacking you, then seize them and kill them wherever you find them. We have given you full permission over such people"
  4,92,"It is not lawful for a believer to kill another except by mistake. And whoever kills a believer unintentionally must free a believing slave and pay blood-money to the victim‚Äôs family‚ÄĒunless they waive it charitably. But if the victim is a believer from a hostile people, then a believing slave must be freed. And if the victim is from a people bound with you in a treaty, then blood-money must be paid to the family along with freeing a believing slave. Those who are unable, let them fast two consecutive months‚ÄĒas a means of repentance to God. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,93,"And whoever kills a believer intentionally, their reward will be Hell‚ÄĒwhere they will stay indefinitely.¬†God will be displeased with them, condemn them, and will prepare for them a tremendous punishment"
  4,94,"O believers! When you struggle in the cause of God, be sure of who you fight. And do not say to those who offer you ňĻgreetings ofňļ peace, ‚ÄúYou are no believer!‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒseeking a fleeting worldly gain.¬†Instead, God has infinite bounties ňĻin storeňļ. You were initially like them then God blessed you ňĻwith Islamňļ. So be sure! Indeed, God is All-Aware of what you do"
  4,95,"Those who stay at home‚ÄĒexcept those with valid excuses‚ÄĒare not equal to those who strive in the cause of God with their wealth and their lives. God has elevated in rank those who strive with their wealth and their lives above those who stay behind ňĻwith valid excusesňļ. God has promised each a fine reward, but those who strive will receive a far better reward than others‚ÄĒ"
  4,96,"far superior ranks, forgiveness, and mercy from Him. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,97,"When the angels seize the souls of those who have wronged themselves‚ÄĒscolding them, ‚ÄúWhat do you think you were doing?‚ÄĚ they will reply, ‚ÄúWe were oppressed in the land.‚ÄĚ The angels will respond, ‚ÄúWas God‚Äôs earth not spacious enough for you to emigrate?‚ÄĚ It is they who will have Hell as their home‚ÄĒwhat an evil destination"
  4,98,"Except helpless men, women, and children who cannot afford a way out‚ÄĒ"
  4,99,"it is right to hope that God will pardon them. For God is Ever-Pardoning, All-Forgiving"
  4,100,"Whoever emigrates in the cause of God will find many safe havens and bountiful resources throughout the earth. Those who leave their homes and die while emigrating to God and His Messenger‚ÄĒtheir reward has already been secured with God. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,101,"When you travel through the land, it is permissible for you to shorten the prayer‚ÄĒňĻespeciallyňļ if you fear an attack by the disbelievers. Indeed, the disbelievers are your sworn enemies"
  4,102,"When you ňĻO Prophetňļ are ňĻcampaigningňļ with them and you lead them in prayer, let one group of them pray with you‚ÄĒwhile armed. When they prostrate themselves, let the other group stand guard behind them. Then the group that has not yet prayed will then join you in prayer‚ÄĒand let them be vigilant and armed.¬†The disbelievers would wish to see you neglect your weapons and belongings, so they could launch a sweeping assault on you. But there is no blame if you lay aside your weapons when overcome by heavy rain or illness‚ÄĒbut take precaution. Indeed, God has prepared a humiliating punishment for the disbelievers"
  4,103,"When the prayers are over, remember God‚ÄĒwhether you are standing, sitting, or lying down. But when you are secure, establish regular prayers. Indeed, performing prayers is a duty on the believers at the appointed times"
  4,104,"Do not falter in pursuit of the enemy‚ÄĒif you are suffering, they too are suffering. But you can hope to receive from God what they can never hope for. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,105,"Indeed, We have sent down the Book to you ňĻO Prophetňļ in truth to judge between people by means of what God has shown you. So do not be an advocate for the deceitful"
  4,106,"And seek God‚Äôs forgiveness‚ÄĒindeed, God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,107,"Do not advocate for those who wrong themselves.¬†Surely God does not like those who are deceitful, sinful"
  4,108,"They try to hide ňĻtheir deceptionňļ from people, but they can never hide it from God‚ÄĒin Whose presence they plot by night what is displeasing to Him. And God is Fully Aware of what they do"
  4,109,"Here you are! You ňĻbelieversňļ are advocating for them in this life, but who will ňĻdare toňļ advocate for them before God on the Day of Judgment? Or who will come to their defence"
  4,110,"Whoever commits evil or wrongs themselves then seeks God‚Äôs forgiveness will certainly find God All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,111,"And whoever commits a sin‚ÄĒit is only to their own loss. God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,112,"And whoever commits an evil or sinful deed then blames it on an innocent person, they will definitely bear the guilt of slander and blatant sin"
  4,113,"Had it not been for God‚Äôs grace and mercy, a group of them would have sought to deceive you ňĻO Prophetňļ. Yet they would deceive none but themselves, nor can they harm you in the least. God has revealed to you the Book and wisdom and taught you what you never knew. Great ňĻindeedňļ is God‚Äôs favour upon you"
  4,114,"There is no good in most of their secret talks‚ÄĒexcept those encouraging charity, kindness, or reconciliation between people. And whoever does this seeking God‚Äôs pleasure, We will grant them a great reward"
  4,115,"And whoever defies the Messenger after guidance has become clear to them and follows a path other than that of the believers, We will let them pursue what they have chosen, then burn them in Hell‚ÄĒwhat an evil end"
  4,116,"Surely God does not forgive associating ňĻothersňļ with Him ňĻin worshipňļ,¬†but forgives anything else of whoever He wills. Indeed, whoever associates ňĻothersňļ with God has clearly gone far astray"
  4,117,"Instead of God, they only invoke female gods¬†and they ňĻactuallyňļ invoke none but a rebellious Satan‚ÄĒ"
  4,118,"cursed by God‚ÄĒwho said, ‚ÄúI will surely take hold of a certain number of Your servants"
  4,119,"I will certainly mislead them and delude them with empty hopes. Also, I will order them and they will slit the ears of cattle¬†and alter God‚Äôs creation.‚ÄĚ And whoever takes Satan as a guardian instead of God has certainly suffered a tremendous loss"
  4,120,Satan only makes them ňĻfalseňļ promises and deludes them with ňĻemptyňļ hopes. Truly Satan promises them nothing but delusion
  4,121,"It is they who will have Hell as their home, and they will find no escape from it"
  4,122,"And those who believe and do good, We will soon admit them into Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there for ever and ever. God‚Äôs promise is ňĻalwaysňļ true. And whose word is more truthful than God‚Äôs"
  4,123,"ňĻDivine grace isňļ neither by your wishes nor those of the People of the Book! Whoever commits evil will be rewarded accordingly, and they will find no protector or helper besides God"
  4,124,But those who do good‚ÄĒwhether male or female‚ÄĒand have faith will enter Paradise and will never be wronged ňĻeven as much asňļ the speck on a date stone
  4,125,"And who is better in faith than those who ňĻfullyňļ submit themselves to God, do good, and follow the Way of Abraham, the upright? God chose Abraham as a close friend"
  4,126,To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. And God is Fully Aware of everything
  4,127,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ regarding women. Say, ‚ÄúIt is God Who instructs you regarding them. Instruction has ňĻalreadyňļ been revealed in the Book¬†concerning the orphan women you deprive of their due rights¬†but still wish to marry, also helpless children, as well as standing up for orphans‚Äô rights. And whatever good you do is certainly well known to God.‚ÄĚ"
  4,128,"If a woman fears indifference or neglect from her husband, there is no blame on either of them if they seek ňĻfairňļ settlement, which is best. Humans are ever inclined to selfishness.¬†But if you are gracious and mindful ňĻof Godňļ, surely God is All-Aware of what you do"
  4,129,"You will never be able to maintain ňĻemotionalňļ justice between your wives‚ÄĒno matter how keen you are. So do not totally incline towards one leaving the other in suspense.¬†And if you do what is right and are mindful ňĻof Godňļ, surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,130,"But if they choose to separate, God will enrich both of them from His bounties. And God is Ever-Bountiful, All-Wise"
  4,131,"To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. Indeed, We have commanded those given the Scripture before you, as well as you, to be mindful of God. But if you disobey, then ňĻknow thatňļ to God belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth. And God is Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy"
  4,132,To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. And God is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs
  4,133,"If it is His Will, He can remove you altogether, O humanity, and replace you with others. And God is Most Capable to do so"
  4,134,"Whoever desires the reward of this world, then ňĻlet them know thatňļ with God are the rewards of this world and the Hereafter. And God is All-Hearing, All-Seeing"
  4,135,"O believers! Stand firm for justice as witnesses for God even if it is against yourselves, your parents, or close relatives. Be they rich or poor, God is best to ensure their interests. So do not let your desires cause you to deviate ňĻfrom justiceňļ. If you distort the testimony or refuse to give it, then ňĻknow thatňļ God is certainly All-Aware of what you do"
  4,136,"O believers! Have faith in God, His Messenger, the Book He has revealed to His Messenger, and the Scriptures He revealed before. Indeed, whoever denies God, His angels, His Books, His messengers, and the Last Day has clearly gone far astray"
  4,137,"Indeed, those who believed then disbelieved, then believed and again disbelieved‚ÄĒňĻonlyňļ increasing in disbelief‚ÄĒGod will neither forgive them nor guide them to the ňĻRightňļ Way"
  4,138,Give good news of a painful punishment to hypocrites
  4,139,who choose disbelievers as allies instead of the believers. Do they seek honour and power through that company? Surely all honour and power belongs to God
  4,140,"He has already revealed to you in the Book that when you hear God‚Äôs revelations being denied or ridiculed, then do not sit in that company unless they engage in a different topic, or else you will be like them.¬†Surely God will gather the hypocrites and disbelievers all together in Hell"
  4,141,"ňĻThe hypocrites areňļ those who wait to see what happens to you. So if God grants you victory, they say ňĻto youňļ, ‚ÄúWere we not on your side?‚ÄĚ But if the disbelievers have a share ňĻof victoryňļ, they say ňĻto themňļ, ‚ÄúDid we not have the advantage over you, yet we protected you from the believers?‚ÄĚ God will judge between ňĻall ofňļ you on the Day of Judgment. And God will never grant the disbelievers a way over the believers"
  4,142,"Surely the hypocrites seek to deceive God, but He outwits them. When they stand up for prayer, they do it half-heartedly only to be seen by people‚ÄĒhardly remembering God at all"
  4,143,"Torn between belief and disbelief‚ÄĒbelonging neither to these ňĻbelieversňļ nor those ňĻdisbelieversňļ. And whoever God leaves to stray, you will never find for them a way"
  4,144,O believers! Do not take disbelievers as allies instead of the believers. Would you like to give God solid proof against yourselves
  4,145,Surely the hypocrites will be in the lowest depths of the Fire‚ÄĒand you will never find for them any helper‚ÄĒ
  4,146,"except those who repent, mend their ways, hold fast to God, and are sincere in their devotion to God; they will be with the believers. And God will grant the believers a great reward"
  4,147,"Why should God punish you if you are grateful and faithful? God is ever Appreciative, All-Knowing"
  4,148,"God does not like negative thoughts to be voiced‚ÄĒexcept by those who have been wronged.¬†God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  4,149,"Whether you reveal or conceal a good or pardon an evil‚ÄĒsurely God is Ever-Pardoning, Most Capable"
  4,150,"Surely those who deny God and His messengers and wish to make a distinction between God and His messengers,¬†saying, ‚ÄúWe believe in some and disbelieve in others,‚ÄĚ desiring to forge a compromise"
  4,151,they are indeed the true disbelievers. And We have prepared for the disbelievers a humiliating punishment
  4,152,"As for those who believe in God and His messengers‚ÄĒaccepting all; rejecting none‚ÄĒHe will surely give them their rewards. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  4,153,"The People of the Book demand that you ňĻO Prophetňļ bring down for them a revelation in writing from heaven.¬†They demanded what is even greater than this from Moses, saying, ‚ÄúMake God visible to us!‚ÄĚ So a thunderbolt struck them for their wrongdoing. Then they took the calf for worship after receiving clear signs. Still We forgave them for that ňĻafter their repentanceňļ and gave Moses compelling proof"
  4,154,"We raised the Mount over them ňĻas a warningňļ for ňĻbreakingňļ their covenant and said, ‚ÄúEnter the gate ňĻof Jerusalemňļ with humility.‚ÄĚ We also warned them, ‚ÄúDo not break the Sabbath,‚ÄĚ and took from them a firm covenant"
  4,155,"ňĻThey were condemnedňļ for breaking their covenant, rejecting God‚Äôs signs, killing the prophets unjustly, and for saying, ‚ÄúOur hearts are unreceptive!‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒit is God Who has sealed their hearts for their disbelief, so they do not believe except for a few‚ÄĒ"
  4,156,and for their denial and outrageous accusation against Mary
  4,157,"and for boasting, ‚ÄúWe killed the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, the messenger of God.‚ÄĚ But they neither killed nor crucified him‚ÄĒit was only made to appear so.¬†Even those who argue for this ňĻcrucifixionňļ are in doubt. They have no knowledge whatsoever‚ÄĒonly making¬†assumptions. They certainly did not kill him"
  4,158,"Rather, God raised him up to Himself. And God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  4,159,Every one of the People of the Book will definitely believe in him before his death.¬†And on the Day of Judgment Jesus will be a witness against them
  4,160,"We forbade the Jews certain foods that had been lawful to them for their wrongdoing, and for hindering many from the Way of God"
  4,161,"taking interest despite its prohibition, and consuming people‚Äôs wealth unjustly. We have prepared for the disbelievers among them a painful punishment"
  4,162,"But those of them well-grounded in knowledge, the faithful ňĻwhoňļ believe in what has been revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ and what was revealed before you‚ÄĒňĻespeciallyňļ those who establish prayer‚ÄĒand those who pay alms-tax and believe in God and the Last Day, to these ňĻpeopleňļ We will grant a great reward"
  4,163,"Indeed, We have sent revelation to you ňĻO Prophetňļ as We sent revelation to Noah and the prophets after him. We also sent revelation to Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants, ňĻas well asňļ Jesus, Job, Jonah, Aaron, and Solomon. And to David We gave the Psalms"
  4,164,There are messengers whose stories We have told you already and others We have not. And to Moses God spoke directly
  4,165,"ňĻAll wereňļ messengers delivering good news and warnings so humanity should have no excuse before God after ňĻthe coming ofňļ the messengers. And God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  4,166,"Yet ňĻif you are denied, O Prophet,ňļ God bears witness to what He has sent down to you‚ÄĒHe has sent it with His knowledge. The angels too bear witness. And God ňĻaloneňļ is sufficient as a Witness"
  4,167,Those who disbelieve and hinder ňĻothersňļ from the Way of God have certainly strayed far away
  4,168,Those who disbelieve and wrong themselves‚ÄĒsurely God will neither forgive them nor guide them to any path
  4,169,"except that of Hell, to stay there for ever and ever. And that is easy for God"
  4,170,"O humanity! The Messenger has certainly come to you with the truth from your Lord, so believe for your own good. But if you disbelieve, then ňĻknow thatňļ to God belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  4,171,"O People of the Book! Do not go to extremes regarding your faith; say nothing about God except the truth.¬†The Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, was no more than a messenger of God and the fulfilment of His Word through Mary and a spirit ňĻcreated by a commandňļ from Him.¬†So believe in God and His messengers and do not say, ‚ÄúTrinity.‚ÄĚ Stop!‚ÄĒfor your own good. God is only One God. Glory be to Him! He is far above having a son! To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. And God is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs"
  4,172,"The Messiah would never be too proud to be a servant of God, nor would the angels nearest to God. Those who are too proud and arrogant to worship Him will be brought before Him all together"
  4,173,"As for those who believe and do good, He will reward them in full and increase them out of His grace. But those who are too proud and arrogant, He will subject them to a painful punishment. And besides God they will find no protector or helper"
  4,174,O humanity! There has come to you conclusive evidence from your Lord. And We have sent down to you a brilliant light
  4,175,"As for those who believe in God and hold fast to Him, He will admit them into His mercy and grace and guide them to Himself through the Straight Path"
  4,176,"They ask you ňĻfor a ruling, O Prophetňļ. Say, ‚ÄúGod gives you a ruling regarding those who die without children or parents.‚ÄĚ If a man dies childless and leaves behind a sister, she will inherit one-half of his estate, whereas her brother will inherit all of her estate if she dies childless. If this person leaves behind two sisters, they together will inherit two-thirds of the estate. But if the deceased leaves male and female siblings, a male‚Äôs share will be equal to that of two females. God makes ňĻthisňļ clear to you so you do not go astray. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  5,1,"O believers! Honour your obligations. All grazing livestock has been made lawful to you‚ÄĒexcept what is hereby announced to you and hunting while on pilgrimage. Indeed, God commands what He wills"
  5,2,"O believers! Do not violate God‚Äôs rituals ňĻof pilgrimageňļ, the sacred months, the sacrificial animals, the ňĻofferings decorated withňļ garlands, nor those ňĻpilgrimsňļ on their way to the Sacred House seeking their Lord‚Äôs bounty and pleasure. When pilgrimage has ended, you are allowed to hunt. Do not let the hatred of a people who once barred you from the Sacred Mosque provoke you to transgress. Cooperate with one another in goodness and righteousness, and do not cooperate in sin and transgression. And be mindful of God. Surely God is severe in punishment"
  5,3,"Forbidden to you are carrion, blood, and swine; what is slaughtered in the name of any other than God; what is killed by strangling, beating, a fall, or by being gored to death; what is partly eaten by a predator unless you slaughter it; and what is sacrificed on altars. You are also forbidden to draw lots for decisions.¬†This is all evil. Today the disbelievers have given up all hope of ňĻunderminingňļ your faith. So do not fear them; fear Me! Today I have perfected your faith for you, completed My favour upon you, and chosen Islam as your way. But whoever is compelled by extreme hunger‚ÄĒnot intending to sin‚ÄĒthen surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  5,4,"They ask you, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ what is permissible for them ňĻto eatňļ. Say, ‚ÄúWhat is good and lawful. Also what is caught by your hunting animals and birds of prey which you have trained as instructed by God. So eat what they catch for you, but mention the Name of God over it ňĻfirstňļ.‚ÄĚ And be mindful of God. Surely God is swift in reckoning"
  5,5,"Today all good, pure foods have been made lawful for you. Similarly, the food of the People of the Book¬†is permissible for you and yours is permissible for them. And ňĻpermissible for you in marriageňļ are chaste believing women as well as chaste women of those given the Scripture before you‚ÄĒas long as you pay them their dowries in wedlock, neither fornicating nor taking them as mistresses. And whoever rejects the faith, all their good deeds will be void ňĻin this lifeňļ and in the Hereafter they will be among the losers"
  5,6,"O believers! When you rise up for prayer, wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows, wipe your heads, and wash your feet to the ankles. And if you are in a state of ňĻfullňļ impurity,¬†then take a full bath. But if you are ill, on a journey, or have relieved yourselves, or have been intimate with your wives and cannot find water, then purify yourselves with clean earth by wiping your faces and hands.¬†It is not God‚Äôs Will to burden you, but to purify you and complete His favour upon you, so perhaps you will be grateful"
  5,7,"Remember God‚Äôs favour upon you and the covenant He made with you when you said, ‚ÄúWe hear and obey.‚ÄĚ And be mindful of God. Surely God knows best what is ňĻhiddenňļ in the heart"
  5,8,O believers! Stand firm for God and bear true testimony. Do not let the hatred of a people lead you to injustice. Be just! That is closer to righteousness. And be mindful of God. Surely God is All-Aware of what you do
  5,9,God has promised those who believe and do good ňĻHisňļ forgiveness and a great reward
  5,10,"As for those who disbelieve and deny Our signs, they are the residents of the Hellfire"
  5,11,"O believers! Remember God‚Äôs favour upon you: when a people sought to harm you, but He held their hands back from you. Be mindful of God. And in God let the believers put their trust"
  5,12,"God made a covenant with the Children of Israel and appointed twelve leaders from among them and ňĻthenňļ said, ‚ÄúI am truly with you. If you establish prayer, pay alms-tax, believe in My messengers, support them, and lend to God a good loan, I will certainly forgive your sins and admit you into Gardens under which rivers flow. And whoever among you disbelieves afterwards has truly strayed from the Right Way.‚ÄĚ"
  5,13,"But for breaking their covenant We condemned them and hardened their hearts. They distorted the words of the Scripture and neglected a portion of what they had been commanded to uphold. You ňĻO Prophetňļ will always find deceit on their part, except for a few. But pardon them and bear with them. Indeed, God loves the good-doers"
  5,14,"And from those who say, ‚ÄúWe are Christians,‚ÄĚ We took their covenant, but they neglected a portion of what they had been commanded to uphold. So We let hostility and enmity arise between them until the Day of Judgment, and soon God will inform them of all they have done"
  5,15,"O People of the Book! Now Our Messenger has come to you, revealing much of what you have hidden of the Scriptures and disregarding much. There certainly has come to you from God a light and a clear Book"
  5,16,"through which God guides those who seek His pleasure to the ways of peace, brings them out of darkness and into light by His Will, and guides them to the Straight Path"
  5,17,"Indeed, those who say, ‚ÄúGod is the Messiah, son of Mary,‚ÄĚ have fallen into disbelief. Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWho has the power to prevent God if He chose to destroy the Messiah, son of Mary, his mother, and everyone in the world all together?‚ÄĚ To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth and everything in between. He creates whatever He wills. And God is Most Capable of everything"
  5,18,"The Jews and the Christians each say, ‚ÄúWe are the children of God and His most beloved!‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWhy then does He punish you for your sins? No! You are only humans like others of His Own making. He forgives whoever He wills and punishes whoever He wills. To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth and everything in between. And to Him is the final return.‚ÄĚ"
  5,19,"O People of the Book! Our Messenger has indeed come to you, making things clear to you after an interval between the messengers so you do not say, ‚ÄúThere has never come to us a deliverer of good news or a warner.‚ÄĚ Now there has come to you a deliverer of good news and a warner. And God is Most Capable of everything"
  5,20,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Moses said to his people, ‚ÄúO my people! Remember God‚Äôs favours upon you when He raised prophets from among you, made you sovereign,¬†and gave you what He had never given anyone in the world"
  5,21,O my people! Enter the Holy Land which God has destined for you ňĻto enterňļ. And do not turn back or else you will become losers.‚ÄĚ
  5,22,"They replied, ‚ÄúO Moses! There is an enormously powerful people there, so we will never ňĻbe able toňļ enter it until they leave. If they do, then we will enter!‚ÄĚ"
  5,23,"Two God-fearing men‚ÄĒwho had been blessed by God‚ÄĒsaid, ‚ÄúSurprise them through the gate. If you do, you will certainly prevail. Put your trust in God if you are ňĻtrulyňļ believers.‚ÄĚ"
  5,24,"ňĻYetňļ they said, ‚ÄúO Moses! ňĻStillňļ we will never enter as long as they remain there. So go‚ÄĒboth you and your Lord‚ÄĒand fight; we are staying right here!‚ÄĚ"
  5,25,"Moses pleaded, ‚ÄúMy Lord! I have no control over anyone except myself and my brother. So set us apart from the rebellious people.‚ÄĚ"
  5,26,"God replied, ‚ÄúThen this land is forbidden to them for forty years, during which they will wander through the land. So do not grieve for the rebellious people.‚ÄĚ"
  5,27,"Relate to them in truth ňĻO Prophetňļ the story of Adam‚Äôs two sons‚ÄĒhow each offered a sacrifice: Abel‚Äôs offering was accepted while Cain‚Äôs was not. So Cain threatened, ‚ÄúI will kill you!‚ÄĚ His brother replied, ‚ÄúGod only accepts ňĻthe offeringňļ of the sincerely devout"
  5,28,"If you raise your hand to kill me, I will not raise mine to kill you, because I fear God‚ÄĒthe Lord of all worlds"
  5,29,"I want to let you bear your sin against me along with your other sins, then you will be one of those destined to the Fire. And that is the reward of the wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  5,30,"Yet Cain convinced himself to kill his brother, so he killed him‚ÄĒbecoming a loser"
  5,31,"Then God sent a crow digging ňĻa graveňļ in the ground ňĻfor a dead crowňļ, in order to show him how to bury the corpse of his brother. He cried, ‚ÄúAlas! Have I ňĻevenňļ failed to be like this crow and bury the corpse of my brother?‚ÄĚ So he became regretful"
  5,32,"That is why We ordained for the Children of Israel that whoever takes a life‚ÄĒunless as a punishment for murder or mischief in the land‚ÄĒit will be as if they killed all of humanity; and whoever saves a life, it will be as if they saved all of humanity.¬†ňĻAlthoughňļ Our messengers already came to them with clear proofs, many of them still transgressed afterwards through the land"
  5,33,"Indeed, the penalty for those who wage war against God and His Messenger and spread mischief in the land is death, crucifixion, cutting off their hands and feet on opposite sides, or exile from the land. This ňĻpenaltyňļ is a disgrace for them in this world, and they will suffer a tremendous punishment in the Hereafter"
  5,34,"As for those who repent before you seize them, then know that God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  5,35,"O believers! Be mindful of God and seek what brings you closer to Him and struggle in His Way, so you may be successful"
  5,36,"As for the disbelievers, even if they were to possess everything in the world twice over ňĻand offer it allňļ to ransom themselves from the punishment of the Day of Judgment, it would never be accepted from them. And they will suffer a painful punishment"
  5,37,They will be desperate to get out of the Fire but they will never be able to. And they will suffer an everlasting punishment
  5,38,"As for male and female thieves, cut off their hands for what they have done‚ÄĒa deterrent from God. And God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  5,39,"But whoever repents after their wrongdoing and mends their ways, God will surely turn to them in forgiveness. Indeed, God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  5,40,Do you not know that the kingdom of the heavens and the earth belongs to God ňĻaloneňļ? He punishes whoever He wills and forgives whoever He wills. And God is Most Capable of everything
  5,41,"O Messenger! Do not grieve for those who race to disbelieve‚ÄĒthose who say, ‚ÄúWe believe‚ÄĚ with their tongues, but their hearts are in disbelief. Nor those among the Jews who eagerly listen to lies, attentive to those who are too arrogant to come to you. They distort the Scripture, taking rulings out of context, then say, ‚ÄúIf this is the ruling you get ňĻfrom MuŠł•ammadňļ, accept it. If not, beware!‚ÄĚ Whoever God allows to be deluded, you can never be of any help to them against God. It is not God‚Äôs Will to purify their hearts. For them is disgrace in this world, and they will suffer a tremendous punishment in the Hereafter"
  5,42,"They eagerly listen to falsehood and consume forbidden gain.¬†So if they come to you ňĻO Prophetňļ, either judge between them or turn away from them. If you turn away from them, they cannot harm you whatsoever. But if you judge between them, then do so with justice. Surely God loves those who are just"
  5,43,"But why do they come to you for judgment when they ňĻalreadyňļ have the Torah containing God‚Äôs judgment, then they turn away after all? They are not ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  5,44,"Indeed, We revealed the Torah, containing guidance and light, by which the prophets, who submitted themselves to God, made judgments for Jews. So too did the rabbis and scholars judge according to God‚Äôs Book, with which they were entrusted and of which they were made keepers. So do not fear the people; fear Me! Nor trade my revelations for a fleeting gain. And those who do not judge by what God has revealed are ňĻtrulyňļ the disbelievers"
  5,45,"We ordained for them in the Torah, ‚ÄúA life for a life, an eye for an eye, a nose for a nose, an ear for an ear, a tooth for a tooth‚ÄĒand for wounds equal retaliation.‚ÄĚ But whoever waives it charitably, it will be atonement for them. And those who do not judge by what God has revealed are ňĻtrulyňļ the wrongdoers"
  5,46,"Then in the footsteps of the prophets, We sent Jesus, son of Mary, confirming the Torah revealed before him. And We gave him the Gospel containing guidance and light and confirming what was revealed in the Torah‚ÄĒa guide and a lesson to the God-fearing"
  5,47,So let the people of the Gospel judge by what God has revealed in it. And those who do not judge by what God has revealed are ňĻtrulyňļ the rebellious
  5,48,"We have revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ this Book with the truth, as a confirmation of previous Scriptures and a supreme authority on them. So judge between them by what God has revealed, and do not follow their desires over the truth that has come to you. To each of you We have ordained a code of law and a way of life. If God had willed, He would have made you one community, but His Will is to test you with what He has given ňĻeach ofňļ you. So compete with one another in doing good. To God you will all return, then He will inform you ňĻof the truthňļ regarding your differences"
  5,49,"And judge between them ňĻO Prophetňļ by what God has revealed, and do not follow their desires. And beware, so they do not lure you away from some of what God has revealed to you. If they turn away ňĻfrom God‚Äôs judgmentňļ, then know that it is God‚Äôs Will to repay them for some of their sins, and that many people are indeed rebellious"
  5,50,Is it the judgment of ňĻpre-Islamicňļ ignorance they seek? Who could be a better judge than God for people of sure faith
  5,51,O believers! Take neither Jews nor Christians as guardians‚ÄĒthey are guardians of each other.¬†Whoever does so will be counted as one of them. Surely God does not guide the wrongdoing people
  5,52,"You see those with sickness in their hearts racing for their guardianship, saying ňĻin justificationňļ, ‚ÄúWe fear a turn of fortune will strike us.‚ÄĚ But perhaps God will bring about ňĻyourňļ victory or another favour by His command, and they will regret what they have hidden in their hearts"
  5,53,"ňĻOnly then,ňļ the believers will ask ňĻone anotherňļ, ‚ÄúAre these the ones who swore solemn oaths by God that they were with you?‚ÄĚ Their deeds have been in vain, so they have become losers"
  5,54,"O believers! Whoever among you abandons their faith, God will replace them with others who love Him and are loved by Him. They will be humble with the believers but firm towards the disbelievers, struggling in the Way of God; fearing no blame from anyone. This is the favour of God. He grants it to whoever He wills. And God is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing"
  5,55,"Your only guardians are God, His Messenger, and fellow believers‚ÄĒwho establish prayer and pay alms-tax¬†with humility"
  5,56,"Whoever allies themselves with God, His Messenger, and fellow believers, then it is certainly God‚Äôs party that will prevail"
  5,57,O believers! Do not seek the guardianship of those given the Scripture before you and the disbelievers who have made your faith a mockery and amusement. And be mindful of God if you are ňĻtrulyňļ believers
  5,58,"When you call to prayer, they mock it in amusement. This is because they are a people without understanding"
  5,59,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO People of the Book! Do you resent us only because we believe in God and what has been revealed to us and what was revealed before‚ÄĒwhile most of you are rebellious?‚ÄĚ"
  5,60,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúShall I inform you of those who deserve a worse punishment from God ňĻthan the rebelliousňļ? It is those who earned God‚Äôs condemnation and displeasure‚ÄĒsome being reduced to apes and pigs¬†and worshippers of false gods. These are far worse in rank and farther astray from the Right Way.‚ÄĚ"
  5,61,"When they come to you ňĻbelieversňļ they say, ‚ÄúWe believe.‚ÄĚ But they are committed to disbelief when they enter and when they leave. And God knows what they hide"
  5,62,"You see many of them racing towards sin, transgression, and consumption of forbidden gain. Evil indeed are their actions"
  5,63,Why do their rabbis and scholars not forbid them from saying what is sinful and consuming what is unlawful? Evil indeed is their inaction
  5,64,"ňĻSome amongňļ the Jews said, ‚ÄúGod is tight-fisted.‚ÄĚ¬†May their fists be tied and they be condemned for what they said. Rather, He is open-handed, giving freely as He pleases. That which has been revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ from your Lord will only cause many of them to increase in wickedness and disbelief. We have stirred among them hostility and hatred until the Day of Judgment. Whenever they kindle the fire of war, God puts it out. And they strive to spread corruption in the land. And God does not like corruptors"
  5,65,"Had the People of the Book only been faithful and mindful ňĻof Godňļ, We would have certainly absolved them of their sins and admitted them into the Gardens of Bliss"
  5,66,"And had they observed the Torah, the Gospel, and what has been revealed to them from their Lord, they would have been overwhelmed with provisions from above and below. Some among them are upright, yet many do nothing but evil"
  5,67,"O Messenger! Convey everything revealed to you from your Lord. If you do not, then you have not delivered His message. God will ňĻcertainlyňļ protect you from the people. Indeed, God does not guide the people who disbelieve"
  5,68,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO People of the Book! You have nothing to stand on unless you observe the Torah, the Gospel, and what has been revealed to you from your Lord.‚ÄĚ And your Lord‚Äôs revelation to you ňĻO Prophetňļ will only cause many of them to increase in wickedness and disbelief. So do not grieve for the people who disbelieve"
  5,69,"Indeed, the believers, Jews, Sabians¬†and Christians‚ÄĒwhoever ňĻtrulyňļ believes in God and the Last Day and does good, there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  5,70,"Indeed, We took a covenant from the Children of Israel and sent them messengers. Whenever a messenger came to them with what they did not desire, they denied some and killed others"
  5,71,"They thought there would be no consequences, so they turned a blind eye and a deaf ear. Yet God turned to them in forgiveness ňĻafter their repentanceňļ, but again many became blind and deaf. And God is All-Seeing of what they do"
  5,72,"Those who say, ‚ÄúGod is the Messiah, son of Mary,‚ÄĚ have certainly fallen into disbelief. The Messiah ňĻhimselfňļ said, ‚ÄúO Children of Israel! Worship God‚ÄĒmy Lord and your Lord.‚ÄĚ Whoever associates others with God ňĻin worshipňļ will surely be forbidden Paradise by God. Their home will be the Fire. And the wrongdoers will have no helpers"
  5,73,"Those who say, ‚ÄúGod is one in a Trinity,‚ÄĚ have certainly fallen into disbelief. There is only One God. If they do not stop saying this, those who disbelieve among them will be afflicted with a painful punishment"
  5,74,"Will they not turn to God in repentance and seek His forgiveness? And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  5,75,"The Messiah, son of Mary, was no more than a messenger. ňĻManyňļ messengers had ňĻcome andňļ gone before him. His mother was a woman of truth. They both ate food.¬†See how We make the signs clear to them, yet see how they are deluded ňĻfrom the truthňļ"
  5,76,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúHow can you worship besides God those who can neither harm nor benefit you? And God ňĻaloneňļ is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.‚ÄĚ"
  5,77,"Say, ‚ÄúO People of the Book! Do not go to extremes in your faith beyond the truth, nor follow the vain desires of those who went astray before ňĻyouňļ. They misled many and strayed from the Right Way.‚ÄĚ"
  5,78,"The disbelievers among the Children of Israel were condemned in the revelations of David and Jesus, son of Mary. That was for their disobedience and violations"
  5,79,They did not forbid one another from doing evil. Evil indeed was what they did
  5,80,"You see many of them taking the disbelievers¬†as allies. Truly wicked are their misdeeds, which have earned them God‚Äôs wrath. And they will be in everlasting torment"
  5,81,"Had they believed in God, the Prophet, and what has been revealed to him, they would have never taken those ňĻpagansňļ as allies. But most of them are rebellious"
  5,82,You will surely find the most bitter towards the believers to be the Jews and polytheists and the most gracious to be those who call themselves Christian. That is because there are priests and monks among them and because they are not arrogant
  5,83,"When they listen to what has been revealed to the Messenger, you see their eyes overflowing with tears for recognizing the truth. They say, ‚ÄúOur Lord! We believe, so count us among the witnesses"
  5,84,Why should we not believe in God and the truth that has come to us? And we long for our Lord to include us in the company of the righteous.‚ÄĚ
  5,85,"So God will reward them for what they said with Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there forever. And that is the reward of the good-doers"
  5,86,"As for those who disbelieve and reject Our signs, they will be the residents of the Hellfire"
  5,87,"O believers! Do not forbid the good things which God has made lawful for you, and do not transgress. Indeed, God does not like transgressors"
  5,88,"Eat of the good, lawful things provided to you by God. And be mindful of God in Whom you believe"
  5,89,"God will not call you to account for your thoughtless oaths, but He will hold you accountable for deliberate oaths. The penalty for a broken oath is to feed ten poor people from what you normally feed your own family, or to clothe them, or to free a bondsperson. But if none of this is affordable, then you must fast three days. This is the penalty for breaking your oaths. So be mindful of your oaths. This is how God makes things clear to you, so perhaps you will be grateful"
  5,90,"O believers! Intoxicants, gambling, idols, and drawing lots for decisions¬†are all evil of Satan‚Äôs handiwork. So shun them so you may be successful"
  5,91,Satan‚Äôs plan is to stir up hostility and hatred between you with intoxicants and gambling and to prevent you from remembering God and praying. Will you not then abstain
  5,92,"Obey God and obey the Messenger and beware! But if you turn away, then know that Our Messenger‚Äôs duty is only to deliver ňĻthe messageňļ clearly"
  5,93,"There is no blame on those who believe and do good for what they had consumed before ňĻthe prohibitionňļ, as long as they fear God, have faith, and do what is good; then they believe and act virtuously, then become fully mindful ňĻof Godňļ and do righteous deeds. For God loves the good-doers"
  5,94,O believers! God will surely test you with game within the reach of your hands and spears to distinguish those who fear Him in secret. Whoever transgresses from now on will suffer a painful punishment
  5,95,"O believers! Do not kill game while on pilgrimage. Whoever kills game intentionally must compensate by offering its equivalence‚ÄĒas judged by two just men among you‚ÄĒto be offered at the Sacred House, or by feeding the needy, or by fasting so that they may taste the consequences of their violations. God has forgiven what has been done. But those who persist will be punished by God. And God is Almighty, capable of punishment"
  5,96,"It is lawful for you to hunt and eat seafood, as a provision for you and for travellers. But hunting on land is forbidden to you while on pilgrimage. Be mindful of God to Whom you all will be gathered"
  5,97,"God has made the Ka‚Äôbah‚ÄĒthe Sacred House‚ÄĒa sanctuary of well-being for all people, along with the sacred months, the sacrificial animals, and the ňĻofferings decorated withňļ garlands. All this so you may know that God knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth, and that He has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of everything"
  5,98,"Know that God is severe in punishment and that He is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  5,99,The Messenger‚Äôs duty is only to deliver ňĻthe messageňļ. And God ňĻfullyňļ knows what you reveal and what you conceal
  5,100,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGood and evil are not equal, though you may be dazzled by the abundance of evil. So be mindful of God, O people of reason, so you may be successful.‚ÄĚ"
  5,101,"O believers! Do not ask about any matter which, if made clear to you, may disturb you. But if you inquire about what is being revealed in the Quran, it will be made clear to you. God has forgiven what was done ňĻin the pastňļ.¬†And God is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing"
  5,102,Some people before you asked such questions then denied their answers
  5,103,"God has never ordained the ňĻso-calledňļ baŠł•√ģrah, s√Ę'ibah, waŠĻ£√ģlah, and Šł•√Ęm¬†camels.¬†But the disbelievers¬†just fabricate lies about God, and most of them lack understanding"
  5,104,"When it is said to them, ‚ÄúCome to God‚Äôs revelations and to the Messenger,‚ÄĚ they reply, ‚ÄúWhat we found our forefathers practicing is good enough for us.‚ÄĚ ňĻWould they still do so,ňļ even if their forefathers had absolutely no knowledge or guidance"
  5,105,"O believers! You are accountable only for yourselves.¬†It will not harm you if someone chooses to deviate‚ÄĒas long as you are ňĻrightlyňļ guided. To God you will all return, and He will inform you of what you used to do"
  5,106,"O believers! When death approaches any of you, call upon two just Muslim men to witness as you make a bequest; otherwise, two non-Muslims if you are afflicted with death while on a journey.¬†If you doubt ňĻtheir testimonyňļ, keep them after prayer and let them testify under oath ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúBy God! We would never sell our testimony for any price, even in favour of a close relative, nor withhold the testimony of God. Otherwise, we would surely be sinful.‚ÄĚ"
  5,107,"If they are found guilty ňĻof false testimonyňļ, let the deceased‚Äôs two closest heirs affected by the bequest replace the witnesses and testify under oath ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúBy God! Our testimony is truer than theirs. We have not transgressed. Otherwise, we would surely be wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  5,108,In this way it is more likely that witnesses will give true testimony or else fear that their oaths could be refuted by those of the heirs. Be mindful of God and obey. For God does not guide the rebellious people
  5,109,"ňĻConsiderňļ the Day God will gather the messengers and say, ‚ÄúWhat response did you receive?‚ÄĚ They will reply, ‚ÄúWe have no knowledge ňĻcompared to Youňļ! You ňĻaloneňļ are indeed the Knower of all unseen.‚ÄĚ"
  5,110,"And ňĻon Judgment Dayňļ God will say, ‚ÄúO Jesus, son of Mary! Remember My favour upon you and your mother: how I supported you with the holy spirit¬†so you spoke to people in ňĻyourňļ infancy and adulthood. How I taught you writing, wisdom, the Torah, and the Gospel. How you moulded a bird from clay‚ÄĒby My Will‚ÄĒand breathed into it and it became a ňĻrealňļ bird‚ÄĒby My Will. How you healed the blind and the lepers‚ÄĒby My Will. How you brought the dead to life‚ÄĒby My Will. How I prevented the Children of Israel from harming you when you came to them with clear proofs and the disbelievers among them said, ‚ÄúThis is nothing but pure magic.‚ÄĚ"
  5,111,"And how I inspired the disciples, ‚ÄúBelieve in Me and My messenger!‚ÄĚ They declared, ‚ÄúWe believe and bear witness that we fully submit ňĻto Godňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  5,112,"ňĻRememberňļ when the disciples asked, ‚ÄúO Jesus, son of Mary! Would your Lord be willing to send down to us a table spread with food from heaven?‚ÄĚ Jesus answered, ‚ÄúFear God if you are ňĻtrulyňļ believers.‚ÄĚ"
  5,113,"They said, ‚ÄúWe ňĻonlyňļ wish to eat from it to reassure our hearts, to verify you are indeed truthful to us, and to become its witnesses.‚ÄĚ"
  5,114,"Jesus, son of Mary, prayed, ‚ÄúO God, our Lord! Send us from heaven a table spread with food as a feast for us‚ÄĒthe first and last of us‚ÄĒand as a sign from You. Provide for us! You are indeed the Best Provider.‚ÄĚ"
  5,115,"God answered, ‚ÄúI am sending it down to you. But whoever among you denies afterwards will be subjected to a torment I have never inflicted on anyone of My creation.‚ÄĚ"
  5,116,"And ňĻon Judgment Dayňļ God will say, ‚ÄúO Jesus, son of Mary! Did you ever ask the people to worship you and your mother as gods besides God?‚ÄĚ He will answer, ‚ÄúGlory be to You! How could I ever say what I had no right to say? If I had said such a thing, you would have certainly known it. You know what is ňĻhiddenňļ within me, but I do not know what is within You. Indeed, You ňĻaloneňļ are the Knower of all unseen"
  5,117,"I never told them anything except what You ordered me to say: ‚ÄúWorship God‚ÄĒmy Lord and your Lord!‚ÄĚ And I was witness over them as long as I remained among them. But when You took me,¬†You were the Witness over them‚ÄĒand You are a Witness over all things"
  5,118,"If You punish them, they belong to You after all.¬†But if You forgive them, You are surely the Almighty, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  5,119,"God will declare, ‚ÄúThis is the Day when ňĻonlyňļ the faithful will benefit from their faithfulness. Theirs are Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there for ever and ever. God is pleased with them and they are pleased with Him. That is the ultimate triumph.‚ÄĚ"
  5,120,To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth and everything within. And He is Most Capable of everything
  6,1,All praise is for God Who created the heavens and the earth and made darkness and light.¬†Yet the disbelievers set up equals to their Lord ňĻin worshipňļ
  6,2,"He is the One Who created you from clay,¬†then appointed a term ňĻfor your deathňļ and another known only to Him ňĻfor your resurrectionňļ‚ÄĒyet you continue to doubt"
  6,3,"He is the Only True God in the heavens and the earth. He knows whatever you conceal and whatever you reveal, and knows whatever you do"
  6,4,"Whenever a sign comes to them from their Lord, they turn away from it"
  6,5,"They have indeed rejected the truth when it came to them, so they will soon face the consequences of their ridicule"
  6,6,Have they not seen how many ňĻdisbelievingňļ peoples¬†We destroyed before them? We had made them more established in the land than you. We sent down abundant rain for them and made rivers flow at their feet. Then We destroyed them for their sins and replaced them with other peoples
  6,7,"Had We sent down to you ňĻO Prophetňļ a revelation in writing and they were to touch it with their own hands, the disbelievers would still have said, ‚ÄúThis is nothing but pure magic!‚ÄĚ"
  6,8,"They say, ‚ÄúWhy has no ňĻvisibleňļ angel come with him?‚ÄĚ Had We sent down an angel, the matter would have certainly been settled ňĻat onceňļ,¬†and they would have never been given more time ňĻto repentňļ"
  6,9,"And if We had sent an angel, We would have certainly made it ňĻassume the form ofňļ a man‚ÄĒleaving them more confused than they already are"
  6,10,"ňĻOtherňļ messengers had already been ridiculed before you ňĻO Prophetňļ, but those who mocked them were overtaken by what they used to ridicule"
  6,11,"Say, ‚ÄúTravel throughout the land and see the fate of the deniers.‚ÄĚ"
  6,12,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúTo whom belongs everything in the heavens and the earth?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúTo God!‚ÄĚ He has taken upon Himself to be Merciful. He will certainly gather ňĻall ofňļ you together for the Day of Judgment‚ÄĒabout which there is no doubt. But those who have ruined themselves will never believe"
  6,13,"To Him belongs whatever exists in the day and night. And He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  6,14,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWill I take any guardian other than God, the Originator of the heavens and the earth, Who provides for all and is not in need of provision?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúI have been commanded to be the first to submit and not be one of the polytheists.‚ÄĚ"
  6,15,"Say, ‚ÄúI truly fear‚ÄĒif I were to disobey my Lord‚ÄĒthe torment of a tremendous Day.‚ÄĚ"
  6,16,Whoever is spared the torment of that Day will have certainly been shown God‚Äôs mercy. And that is the absolute triumph
  6,17,"If God touches you with harm, none can undo it except Him. And if He touches you with a blessing, He is Most Capable of everything"
  6,18,"He reigns supreme over His creation. And He is the All-Wise, All-Aware"
  6,19,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúWho is the best witness?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúGod is! He is a Witness between me and you. And this Quran has been revealed to me so that, with it, I may warn you and whoever it reaches. Do you ňĻpagansňļ testify that there are other gods besides God?‚ÄĚ ňĻThenňļ say, ‚ÄúI will never testify ňĻto thisňļ!‚ÄĚ ňĻAndňļ say, ‚ÄúThere is only One God. And I totally reject whatever ňĻidolsňļ you associate with Him.‚ÄĚ"
  6,20,Those to whom We gave the Scripture recognize him ňĻto be a true prophetňļ as they recognize their own children. Those who have ruined themselves will never believe
  6,21,"Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against God or deny His signs? Indeed, the wrongdoers will never succeed"
  6,22,"ňĻConsiderňļ the Day We will gather them all together then ask those who associated others ňĻwith God in worshipňļ, ‚ÄúWhere are those gods you used to claim?‚ÄĚ"
  6,23,"Their only argument will be: ‚ÄúBy God, our Lord! We were never polytheists.‚ÄĚ"
  6,24,See how they will lie about themselves and how those ňĻgodsňļ they fabricated will fail them
  6,25,"There are some of them who ňĻpretend toňļ listen to your recitation ňĻof the Quranňļ, but We have cast veils over their hearts‚ÄĒleaving them unable to comprehend it‚ÄĒand deafness in their ears. Even if they were to see every sign, they still would not believe in them. The disbelievers would ňĻevenňļ come to argue with you, saying, ‚ÄúThis ňĻQuranňļ is nothing but ancient fables!‚ÄĚ"
  6,26,"They turn others away from the Prophet and distance themselves as well. They ruin none but themselves, yet they fail to perceive it"
  6,27,"If only you could see when they will be detained before the Fire! They will cry, ‚ÄúOh! If only we could be sent back, we would never deny the signs of our Lord and we would ňĻsurelyňļ be of the believers.‚ÄĚ"
  6,28,"But no! ňĻThey only say thisňļ because the truth they used to hide will become all too clear to them. Even if they were to be sent back, they would certainly revert to what they were forbidden. Indeed they are liars"
  6,29,"They insisted, ‚ÄúThere is nothing beyond this worldly life and we will never be resurrected.‚ÄĚ"
  6,30,"But if only you could see when they will be detained before their Lord! He will ask ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúIs this ňĻHereafterňļ not the truth?‚ÄĚ They will cry, ‚ÄúAbsolutely, by our Lord!‚ÄĚ He will say, ‚ÄúThen taste the punishment for your disbelief.‚ÄĚ"
  6,31,"Losers indeed are those who deny the meeting with God until the Hour takes them by surprise, then they will cry, ‚ÄúWoe to us for having ignored this!‚ÄĚ They will bear ňĻthe burden ofňļ their sins on their backs. Evil indeed is their burden"
  6,32,"This worldly life is no more than play and amusement, but far better is the ňĻeternalňļ Home of the Hereafter for those mindful ňĻof Godňļ. Will you not then understand"
  6,33,We certainly know that what they say grieves you ňĻO Prophetňļ. It is not your honesty they question‚ÄĒit is God‚Äôs signs that the wrongdoers deny
  6,34,"Indeed, messengers before you were rejected but patiently endured rejection and persecution until Our help came to them. And God‚Äôs promise ňĻto helpňļ is never broken. And you have already received some of the narratives of these messengers"
  6,35,"If you find their denial unbearable, then build‚ÄĒif you can‚ÄĒa tunnel through the earth or stairs to the sky to bring them a ňĻmore compellingňļ sign. Had God so willed, He could have guided them all. So do not be one of those ignorant ňĻof this factňļ"
  6,36,"Only the attentive will respond ňĻto your callňļ. As for the dead, God will raise them up, then to Him they will ňĻallňļ be returned"
  6,37,"They ask, ‚ÄúWhy has no ňĻotherňļ sign been sent down to him from his Lord?‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod certainly has the power to send down a sign‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒthough most of them do not know"
  6,38,All living beings roaming the earth and winged birds soaring in the sky are communities like yourselves.¬†We have left nothing out of the Record.¬†Then to their Lord they will be gathered all together
  6,39,Those who deny Our signs are ňĻwilfullyňļ deaf and dumb‚ÄĒlost in darkness. God leaves whoever He wills to stray and guides whoever He wills to the Straight Way
  6,40,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúImagine if you were overwhelmed by God‚Äôs torment or the Hour‚ÄĒwould you call upon any other than God ňĻfor helpňļ? ňĻAnswer meňļ if your claims are true"
  6,41,"No! He is the only One you would call. And if He willed, He could remove the affliction that made you invoke Him. Only then will you forget whatever you associate with Him ňĻin worshipňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  6,42,"Indeed, We have sent messengers before you ňĻO Prophetňļ to other people who We put through suffering and adversity ňĻfor their denialňļ, so perhaps they would be humbled"
  6,43,"Why did they not humble themselves when We made them suffer? Instead, their hearts were hardened, and Satan made their misdeeds appealing to them"
  6,44,"When they became oblivious to warnings, We showered them with everything they desired. But just as they became prideful of what they were given, We seized them by surprise, then they instantly fell into despair"
  6,45,So the wrongdoers were utterly uprooted. And all praise is for God‚ÄĒLord of all worlds
  6,46,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúImagine if God were to take away your hearing or sight, or seal your hearts‚ÄĒwho else other than God could restore it?‚ÄĚ See ňĻO Prophetňļ how We vary the signs, yet they still turn away"
  6,47,"Ask, ‚ÄúImagine if God‚Äôs punishment were to overwhelm you with or without warning‚ÄĒwho would be destroyed other than the wrongdoers?‚ÄĚ"
  6,48,"We have sent messengers only as deliverers of good news and as warners. Whoever believes and does good, there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  6,49,But those who deny Our signs will be afflicted with punishment for their rebelliousness
  6,50,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúI do not say to you that I possess God‚Äôs treasuries or know the unseen, nor do I claim to be an angel. I only follow what is revealed to me.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúAre those blind ňĻto the truthňļ equal to those who can see? Will you not then reflect?‚ÄĚ"
  6,51,Warn with this ňĻQuranňļ those who are awed by the prospect of being gathered before their Lord‚ÄĒwhen they will have no protector or intercessor besides Him‚ÄĒso perhaps they will be mindful ňĻof Himňļ
  6,52,"ňĻO Prophet!ňļ Do not dismiss those ňĻpoor believersňļ who invoke their Lord morning and evening, seeking His pleasure.¬†You are not accountable for them whatsoever, nor are they accountable for you. So do not dismiss them, or you will be one of the wrongdoers"
  6,53,"In this way We have tested some by means of others, so those ňĻdisbelieversňļ may say, ‚ÄúHas God favoured these ňĻpoor believersňļ out of all of us?‚ÄĚ Does God not best recognize the grateful"
  6,54,"When the believers in Our revelations come to you, say, ‚ÄúPeace be upon you! Your Lord has taken upon Himself to be Merciful. Whoever among you commits evil ignorantly ňĻor recklesslyňļ then repents afterwards and mends their ways, then God is truly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  6,55,"This is how We make Our signs clear, so the way of the wicked may become distinct"
  6,56,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúI have been forbidden to worship those you invoke besides God.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúI will not follow your desires, for I then would certainly be astray and not one of those ňĻrightlyňļ guided.‚ÄĚ"
  6,57,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIndeed, I stand on a clear proof from my Lord‚ÄĒyet you have denied it. That ňĻtormentňļ you seek to hasten is not within my power. It is only God Who decides ňĻits timeňļ. He declares the truth. And He is the Best of Judges.‚ÄĚ"
  6,58,"Say ňĻalsoňļ, ‚ÄúIf what you seek to hasten were within my power, the matter between us would have already been settled. But God knows the wrongdoers best.‚ÄĚ"
  6,59,"With Him are the keys of the unseen‚ÄĒno one knows them except Him.¬†And He knows what is in the land and sea. Not even a leaf falls without His knowledge, nor a grain in the darkness of the earth or anything‚ÄĒgreen or dry‚ÄĒbut is ňĻwrittenňļ in a perfect Record"
  6,60,"He is the One Who calls back your souls by night and knows what you do by day, then revives you daily to complete your appointed term. To Him is your ňĻultimateňļ return, then He will inform you of what you used to do"
  6,61,"He reigns supreme over all of His creation, and sends recording-angels, watching over you. When death comes to any of you, Our angels take their soul, never neglecting this duty"
  6,62,Then they are ňĻallňļ returned to God‚ÄĒtheir True Master. Judgment is His ňĻaloneňļ. And He is the Swiftest Reckoner
  6,63,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWho rescues you from the darkest times on land and at sea? He ňĻaloneňļ you call upon with humility, openly and secretly: ‚ÄúIf You rescue us from this, we will be ever grateful.‚ÄĚ"
  6,64,"Say, ‚ÄúňĻOnlyňļ God rescues you from this and any other distress, yet you associate others with Him ňĻin worshipňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  6,65,"Say, ‚ÄúHe ňĻaloneňļ has the power to unleash upon you a torment from above or below you or split you into ňĻconflictingňļ factions and make you taste the violence of one another.‚ÄĚ See how We vary the signs, so perhaps they will comprehend"
  6,66,"Still your people ňĻO Prophetňļ have rejected this ňĻQuranňļ, although it is the truth. Say, ‚ÄúI am not a keeper over you.‚ÄĚ"
  6,67,Every ňĻdestinedňļ matter has a ňĻsetňļ time to transpire. And you will soon come to know
  6,68,"And when you come across those who ridicule Our revelations, do not sit with them unless they engage in a different topic. Should Satan make you forget, then once you remember, do not ňĻcontinue toňļ sit with the wrongdoing people"
  6,69,"Those mindful ňĻof Godňļ will not be accountable for those ňĻwho ridicule itňļ whatsoever‚ÄĒtheir duty is to advise, so perhaps the ridiculers will abstain"
  6,70,"And leave those who take this¬†faith ňĻof Islamňļ as mere play and amusement and are deluded by ňĻtheirňļ worldly life. Yet remind them by this ňĻQuranňļ, so no one should be ruined for their misdeeds. They will have no protector or intercessor other than God. Even if they were to offer every ňĻpossibleňļ ransom, none will be accepted from them. Those are the ones who will be ruined for their misdeeds. They will have a boiling drink and painful punishment for their disbelief"
  6,71,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúShould we invoke, other than God, those ňĻidolsňļ which cannot benefit or harm us, and turn back to disbelief after God has guided us? ňĻIf we do so, we will beňļ like those disoriented by devils in the wilderness, while their companions call them to guidance, ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄėCome to us!‚Äô Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod‚Äôs guidance is the ňĻonlyňļ true guidance. And we are commanded to submit to the Lord of all worlds"
  6,72,"establish prayer, and be mindful of Him. To Him you will all be gathered together"
  6,73,"He is the One Who created the heavens and the earth in truth. On the Day ňĻof Judgmentňļ He will say, ‚ÄėBe!‚Äô And there will be! His command is truth. All authority is His ňĻaloneňļ¬†on the Day the Trumpet will be blown.¬†He is the Knower of all‚ÄĒseen or unseen. And He is the All-Wise, All-Aware.‚ÄĚ"
  6,74,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Abraham said to his father, »āzar, ‚ÄúDo you take idols as gods? It is clear to me that you and your people are entirely misguided.‚ÄĚ"
  6,75,"We also showed Abraham the wonders of the heavens and the earth, so he would be sure in faith"
  6,76,"When the night grew dark upon him, he saw a star and said, ‚ÄúThis is my Lord!‚ÄĚ But when it set, he said, ‚ÄúI do not love things that set.‚ÄĚ"
  6,77,"Then when he saw the moon rising, he said, ‚ÄúThis one is my Lord!‚ÄĚ But when it disappeared, he said, ‚ÄúIf my Lord does not guide me, I will certainly be one of the misguided people.‚ÄĚ"
  6,78,"Then when he saw the sun shining, he said, ‚ÄúThis must be my Lord‚ÄĒit is the greatest!‚ÄĚ But again when it set, he declared, ‚ÄúO my people! I totally reject whatever you associate ňĻwith God in worshipňļ"
  6,79,I have turned my face towards the One Who has originated the heavens and the earth‚ÄĒbeing upright‚ÄĒand I am not one of the polytheists.‚ÄĚ
  6,80,"And his people argued with him. He responded, ‚ÄúAre you arguing with me about God, while He has guided me? I am not afraid of whatever ňĻidolsňļ you associate with Him‚ÄĒňĻnone can harm me,ňļ unless my Lord so wills. My Lord encompasses everything in ňĻHisňļ knowledge. Will you not be mindful"
  6,81,"And how should I fear your associate-gods, while you have no fear in associating ňĻothersňļ with God‚ÄĒa practice He has never authorized? Which side has more right to security? ňĻTell meňļ if you really know!‚ÄĚ"
  6,82,It is ňĻonlyňļ those who are faithful and do not tarnish their faith with falsehood¬†who are guaranteed security and are ňĻrightlyňļ guided
  6,83,"This was the argument We gave Abraham against his people. We elevate in rank whoever We please. Surely your Lord is All-Wise, All-Knowing"
  6,84,"And We blessed him with Isaac and Jacob. We guided them all as We previously guided Noah and those among his descendants: David, Solomon, Job, Joseph, Moses, and Aaron. This is how We reward the good-doers"
  6,85,"Likewise, ňĻWe guidedňļ Zachariah, John, Jesus, and Elias, who were all of the righteous"
  6,86,"ňĻWe also guidedňļ Ishmael, Elisha, Jonah, and Lot, favouring each over other people ňĻof their timeňļ"
  6,87,"And ňĻWe favouredňļ some of their forefathers, their descendants, and their brothers. We chose them and guided them to the Straight Path"
  6,88,"This is God‚Äôs guidance with which He guides whoever He wills of His servants. Had they associated others with Him ňĻin worshipňļ, their ňĻgoodňļ deeds would have been wasted"
  6,89,"Those were the ones to whom We gave the Scripture, wisdom, and prophethood. But if these ňĻpagansňļ disbelieve in this ňĻmessageňļ, then We have already entrusted it to a people who will never disbelieve in it"
  6,90,"These ňĻprophetsňļ were ňĻrightlyňļ guided by God, so follow their guidance. Say, ‚ÄúI ask no reward of you for this ňĻQuranňļ‚ÄĒit is a reminder to the whole world.‚ÄĚ"
  6,91,"And they¬†have not shown God His proper reverence when they said, ‚ÄúGod has revealed nothing to any human being.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWho then revealed the Book brought forth by Moses as a light and guidance for people, which you split into separate sheets‚ÄĒrevealing some and hiding much? You have been taught ňĻthrough this Quranňļ what neither you nor your forefathers knew.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod ňĻrevealed itňļ!‚ÄĚ Then leave them to amuse themselves with falsehood"
  6,92,This is a blessed Book which We have revealed‚ÄĒconfirming what came before it‚ÄĒso you may warn the Mother of Cities¬†and everyone around it. Those who believe in the Hereafter ňĻtrulyňļ believe in it and guard their prayers
  6,93,"Who does more wrong than the one who fabricates lies against God or claims, ‚ÄúI have received revelations!‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒalthough nothing was revealed to them‚ÄĒor the one who says, ‚ÄúI can reveal the like of God‚Äôs revelations!‚ÄĚ? If you ňĻO Prophetňļ could only see the wrongdoers in the throes of death while the angels are stretching out their hands ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúGive up your souls! Today you will be rewarded with the torment of disgrace for telling lies about God and for being arrogant towards His revelations!‚ÄĚ"
  6,94,ňĻTodayňļ you have come back to Us all alone as We created you the first time‚ÄĒleaving behind everything We have provided you with. We do not see your intercessors with you‚ÄĒthose you claimed were God‚Äôs partners ňĻin worshipňļ. All your ties have been broken and all your claims have let you down.‚ÄĚ
  6,95,"Indeed, God is the One Who causes seeds and fruit stones to sprout. He brings forth the living from the dead and the dead from the living. That is God! How can you then be deluded ňĻfrom the truthňļ"
  6,96,"He causes the dawn to break, and has made the night for rest and ňĻmadeňļ the sun and the moon ňĻto travelňļ with precision. That is the design of the Almighty, All-Knowing"
  6,97,And He is the One Who has made the stars as your guide through the darkness of land and sea. We have already made the signs clear for people who know
  6,98,"And He is the One Who originated you all from a single soul,¬†then assigned you a place to live and another to ňĻbe laid toňļ rest. We have already made the signs clear for people who comprehend"
  6,99,"And He is the One Who sends down rain from the sky‚ÄĒcausing all kinds of plants to grow‚ÄĒproducing green stalks from which We bring forth clustered grain. And from palm trees come clusters of dates hanging within reach. ňĻThere areňļ also gardens of grapevines, olives, and pomegranates, similar ňĻin shapeňļ but dissimilar ňĻin tasteňļ. Look at their fruit as it yields and ripens! Indeed, in these are signs for people who believe"
  6,100,"Yet they associate the jinn¬†with God ňĻin worshipňļ, even though He created them, and they falsely attribute to Him sons¬†and daughters¬†out of ignorance. Glorified and Exalted is He above what they claim"
  6,101,ňĻHe isňļ the Originator of the heavens and earth. How could He have children when He has no mate? He created all things and has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of everything
  6,102,"That is God‚ÄĒyour Lord! There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. ňĻHe isňļ the Creator of all things, so worship Him ňĻaloneňļ. And He is the Maintainer of everything"
  6,103,"No vision can encompass Him, but He encompasses all vision. For He is the Most Subtle, All-Aware"
  6,104,"Indeed, there have come to you insights from your Lord. So whoever chooses to see, it is for their own good. But whoever chooses to be blind, it is to their own loss. And I am not a keeper over you"
  6,105,"And so We vary our signs to the extent that they will say, ‚ÄúYou have studied ňĻprevious scripturesňļ,‚ÄĚ¬†and We make this ňĻQuranňļ clear for people who know"
  6,106,ňĻO Prophet!ňļ Follow what is revealed to you from your Lord‚ÄĒthere is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him‚ÄĒand turn away from the polytheists
  6,107,"Had God willed, they would not have been polytheists. We have not appointed you as their keeper, nor are you their maintainer"
  6,108,"ňĻO believers!ňļ Do not insult what they invoke besides God or they will insult God spitefully out of ignorance. This is how We have made each people‚Äôs deeds appealing to them. Then to their Lord is their return, and He will inform them of what they used to do"
  6,109,"They swear by God their most solemn oaths that if a sign were to come to them, they would certainly believe in it. Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúSigns are only with God.‚ÄĚ What will make you ňĻbelieversňļ realize that even if a sign were to come to them, they still would not believe"
  6,110,"We turn their hearts and eyes away ňĻfrom the truthňļ as they refused to believe at first, leaving them to wander blindly in their defiance"
  6,111,"Even if We had sent them the angels, made the dead speak to them, and assembled before their own eyes every sign ňĻthey demandedňļ, they still would not have believed‚ÄĒunless God so willed. But most of them are ignorant ňĻof thisňļ"
  6,112,"And so We have made for every prophet enemies‚ÄĒdevilish humans and jinn‚ÄĒwhispering to one another with elegant words of deception. Had it been your Lord‚Äôs Will, they would not have done such a thing. So leave them and their deceit"
  6,113,"so that the hearts of those who disbelieve in the Hereafter may be receptive to it, be pleased with it, and be persistent in their evil pursuits"
  6,114,"ňĻSay, O Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúShould I seek a judge other than God while He is the One Who has revealed for you the Book ňĻwith the truthňļ perfectly explained?‚ÄĚ Those who were given the Scripture know that it has been revealed ňĻto youňļ from your Lord in truth. So do not be one of those who doubt"
  6,115,"The Word of your Lord has been perfected in truth and justice. None can change His Words. And He is the All-Hearing, All- Knowing"
  6,116,"ňĻO Prophet!ňļ If you were to obey most of those on earth, they would lead you away from God‚Äôs Way. They follow nothing but assumptions and do nothing but lie"
  6,117,"Indeed, your Lord knows best who has strayed from His Way and who is ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  6,118,So eat only of what is slaughtered in God‚Äôs Name if you truly believe in His revelations
  6,119,Why should you not eat of what is slaughtered in God‚Äôs Name when He has already explained to you what He has forbidden to you‚ÄĒexcept when compelled by necessity? Many ňĻdeviantsňļ certainly mislead others by their whims out of ignorance. Surely your Lord knows the transgressors best
  6,120,"Shun all sin‚ÄĒopen and secret. Indeed, those who commit sin will be punished for what they earn"
  6,121,"Do not eat of what is not slaughtered in God‚Äôs Name. For that would certainly be ňĻan act ofňļ disobedience. Surely the devils whisper to their ňĻhumanňļ associates to argue with you.¬†If you were to obey them, then you ňĻtooňļ would be polytheists"
  6,122,"Can those who had been dead, to whom We gave life and a light with which they can walk among people, be compared to those in complete darkness from which they can never emerge?¬†That is how the misdeeds of the disbelievers have been made appealing to them"
  6,123,"And so We have placed in every society the most wicked to conspire in it. Yet they plot only against themselves, but they fail to perceive it"
  6,124,"Whenever a sign comes to them, they say, ‚ÄúWe will never believe until we receive what God‚Äôs messengers received.‚ÄĚ God knows best where to place His message. The wicked will soon be overwhelmed by humiliation from God and a severe punishment for their evil plots"
  6,125,"Whoever God wills to guide, He opens their heart to Islam.¬†But whoever He wills to leave astray, He makes their chest tight and constricted as if they were climbing up into the sky. This is how God dooms those who disbelieve"
  6,126,That is your Lord‚Äôs Path‚ÄĒperfectly straight. We have already made the signs clear to those who are mindful
  6,127,"They will have the Home of Peace with their Lord, Who will be their Guardian because of what they used to do"
  6,128,"ňĻConsiderňļ the Day He will gather them ňĻallňļ together and say, ‚ÄúO assembly of jinn! You misled humans in great numbers.‚ÄĚ And their human associates will say, ‚ÄúOur Lord! We benefited from each other‚Äôs company,¬†but now we have reached the term which You appointed for us.‚ÄĚ ňĻThenňļ He will say, ‚ÄúThe Fire is your home, yours to stay in forever, except whoever God wills to spare.‚ÄĚ¬†Surely your Lord is All-Wise, All-Knowing"
  6,129,This is how We make the wrongdoers ňĻdestructiveňļ allies of one another because of their misdeeds
  6,130,"ňĻGod will ask,ňļ ‚ÄúO assembly of jinn and humans! Did messengers not come from among you, proclaiming My revelations and warning you of the coming of this Day of yours?‚ÄĚ They will say, ‚ÄúWe confess against ourselves!‚ÄĚ For they have been deluded by ňĻtheirňļ worldly life. And they will testify against themselves that they were disbelievers"
  6,131,This ňĻsending of the messengersňļ is because your Lord would never destroy a society for their wrongdoing while its people are unaware ňĻof the truthňļ
  6,132,They will each be assigned ranks according to their deeds. And your Lord is not unaware of what they do
  6,133,"Your Lord is the Self-Sufficient, Full of Mercy. If He wills, He can do away with you and replace you with whoever He wills, just as He produced you from the offspring of other people"
  6,134,"Indeed, what you have been promised will certainly come to pass. And you will have no escape"
  6,135,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO my people! Persist in your ways, for I ňĻtooňļ will persist in mine. You will soon know who will fare best in the end. Indeed, the wrongdoers will never succeed.‚ÄĚ"
  6,136,"The pagans set aside for God a share of the crops and cattle He created, saying, ‚ÄúThis ňĻportionňļ is for God,‚ÄĚ so they claim, ‚Äúand this ňĻoneňļ for our associate-gods.‚ÄĚ Yet the portion of their associate-gods is not shared with God while God‚Äôs portion is shared with their associate-gods. What unfair judgment"
  6,137,"Likewise, the pagans‚Äô evil associates have made it appealing to them to kill their own children‚ÄĒonly leading to their destruction as well as confusion in their faith. Had it been God‚Äôs Will, they would not have done such a thing. So leave them and their falsehood"
  6,138,"They say, ‚ÄúThese cattle and crops are reserved‚ÄĒnone may eat them except those we permit,‚ÄĚ so they claim. Some other cattle are exempted from labour and others are not slaughtered in God‚Äôs Name‚ÄĒfalsely attributing lies to Him. He will repay them for their lies"
  6,139,"They ňĻalsoňļ say, ‚ÄúThe offspring of this cattle is reserved for our males and forbidden to our females; but if it is stillborn, they may all share it.‚ÄĚ He will repay them for their falsehood. Surely He is All-Wise, All-Knowing"
  6,140,Lost indeed are those who have murdered their own children foolishly out of ignorance and have forbidden what God has provided for them‚ÄĒfalsely attributing lies to God. They have certainly strayed and are not ňĻrightlyňļ guided
  6,141,"He is the One Who produces gardens‚ÄĒboth cultivated and wild‚ÄĒand palm trees, crops of different flavours, olives, and pomegranates‚ÄĒsimilar ňĻin shapeňļ, but dissimilar ňĻin tasteňļ. Eat of the fruit they bear and pay the dues at harvest, but do not waste. Surely He does not like the wasteful"
  6,142,"Some cattle are fit for labour, others are too small.¬†Eat of what God has provided for you and do not follow Satan‚Äôs footsteps. Certainly, he is your sworn enemy"
  6,143,"ňĻGod has createdňļ four pairs: a pair of sheep and a pair of goats‚ÄĒask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúHas He forbidden ňĻto youňļ the two males or the two females or what is in the wombs of the two females? Tell me with knowledge, if what you say is true.‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒ"
  6,144,"and a pair of camels and a pair of oxen. Ask ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúHas He forbidden ňĻto youňļ the two males or the two females or what is in the wombs of the two females? Or were you present when God gave you this commandment?‚ÄĚ Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against God to mislead others without ňĻanyňļ knowledge? Surely God does not guide the wrongdoing people"
  6,145,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúI do not find in what has been revealed to me anything forbidden to eat except carrion, running blood, swine‚ÄĒwhich is impure‚ÄĒor a sinful offering in the name of any other than God. But if someone is compelled by necessity‚ÄĒneither driven by desire nor exceeding immediate need‚ÄĒthen surely your Lord is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  6,146,"For those who are Jewish, We forbade every animal with undivided hoofs and the fat of oxen and sheep except what is joined to their backs or intestines or mixed with bone. In this way We rewarded them for their violations. And We are certainly truthful"
  6,147,"But if they deny you ňĻO Prophetňļ, say, ‚ÄúYour Lord is infinite in mercy, yet His punishment will not be averted from the wicked people.‚ÄĚ"
  6,148,"The polytheists will argue, ‚ÄúHad it been God‚Äôs Will, neither we nor our forefathers would have associated others with Him ňĻin worshipňļ or made anything unlawful.‚ÄĚ Likewise, those before them rejected the truth until they tasted Our punishment. Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúDo you have any knowledge that you can produce for us? Surely you follow nothing but ňĻfalseňļ assumptions and you do nothing but lie.‚ÄĚ"
  6,149,"Say, ‚ÄúGod has the most conclusive argument. Had it been His Will, He would have easily imposed guidance upon all of you.‚ÄĚ"
  6,150,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúBring your witnesses who can testify that God has forbidden this.‚ÄĚ If they ňĻfalselyňļ testify, do not testify with them. And do not follow the desires of those who deny Our proofs, disbelieve in the Hereafter, and set up equals with their Lord"
  6,151,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúCome! Let me recite to you what your Lord has forbidden to you: do not associate others with Him ňĻin worshipňļ. ňĻDo not fail toňļ honour your parents. Do not kill your children for fear of poverty. We provide for you and for them. Do not come near indecencies, openly or secretly. Do not take a ňĻhumanňļ life‚ÄĒmade sacred by God‚ÄĒexcept with ňĻlegalňļ right.¬†This is what He has commanded you, so perhaps you will understand"
  6,152,"And do not come near the wealth of the orphan‚ÄĒunless intending to enhance it‚ÄĒuntil they attain maturity. Give full measure and weigh with justice. We never require of any soul more than what it can afford. Whenever you speak,¬†maintain justice‚ÄĒeven regarding a close relative. And fulfil your covenant with God. This is what He has commanded you, so perhaps you will be mindful"
  6,153,"Indeed, that is My Path‚ÄĒperfectly straight. So follow it and do not follow other ways, for they will lead you away from His Way. This is what He has commanded you, so perhaps you will be conscious ňĻof Godňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  6,154,"Additionally, We gave Moses the Scripture, completing the favour upon those who do good, detailing everything, and as a guide and a mercy, so perhaps they would be certain of the meeting with their Lord"
  6,155,"This is a blessed Book We have revealed. So follow it and be mindful ňĻof Godňļ, so you may be shown mercy"
  6,156,"You ňĻpagansňļ can no longer say, ‚ÄúScriptures were only revealed to two groups before us and we were unaware of their teachings.‚ÄĚ"
  6,157,"Nor can you say, ‚ÄúIf only the Scriptures had been revealed to us, we would have been better guided than they.‚ÄĚ Now there has come to you from your Lord a clear proof‚ÄĒa guide and mercy. Who then does more wrong than those who deny God‚Äôs revelations and turn away from them? We will reward those who turn away from Our revelations with a dreadful punishment for turning away"
  6,158,"Are they awaiting the coming of the angels, or your Lord ňĻHimselfňļ, or some of your Lord‚Äôs ňĻmajorňļ signs? On the Day your Lord‚Äôs signs arrive, belief will not benefit those who did not believe earlier or those who did no good through their faith.¬†Say, ‚ÄúKeep waiting! We too are waiting.‚ÄĚ"
  6,159,"Indeed, you ňĻO Prophetňļ are not responsible whatsoever for those who have divided their faith and split into sects. Their judgment rests only with God. And He will inform them of what they used to do"
  6,160,Whoever comes with a good deed will be rewarded tenfold. But whoever comes with a bad deed will be punished for only one. None will be wronged
  6,161,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúSurely my Lord has guided me to the Straight Path, a perfect way, the faith of Abraham, the upright, who was not one of the polytheists.‚ÄĚ"
  6,162,"Say, ‚ÄúSurely my prayer, my worship, my life, and my death are all for God‚ÄĒLord of all worlds"
  6,163,"He has no partner. So I am commanded, and so I am the first to submit.‚ÄĚ"
  6,164,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúShould I seek a lord other than God while He is the Lord of everything?‚ÄĚ No one will reap except what they sow. No soul burdened with sin will bear the burden of another. Then to your Lord is your return, and He will inform you of your differences"
  6,165,"He is the One Who has placed you as successors on earth and elevated some of you in rank over others, so He may test you with what He has given you. Surely your Lord is swift in punishment, but He is certainly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  7,1,Alif-L√£m-Mń©m-ŠĻĘ√£d
  7,2,"ňĻThis isňļ a Book sent down to you ňĻO Prophetňļ‚ÄĒdo not let anxiety into your heart regarding it‚ÄĒso with it you may warn ňĻthe disbelieversňļ, and as a reminder to the believers"
  7,3,"Follow what has been sent down to you from your Lord, and do not take others as guardians besides Him. How seldom are you mindful"
  7,4,ňĻImagineňļ how many societies We have destroyed! Our torment took them by surprise ňĻwhile sleepingňļ at night or midday
  7,5,"Their only cry‚ÄĒwhen overwhelmed by Our torment‚ÄĒwas, ‚ÄúWe have indeed been wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  7,6,We will surely question those who received messengers and We will question the messengers ňĻthemselvesňļ
  7,7,Then We will give them a full account with sure knowledge‚ÄĒfor We were never absent
  7,8,"The weighing on that Day will be just. As for those whose scale will be heavy ňĻwith good deedsňļ, ňĻonlyňļ they will be successful"
  7,9,"But those whose scale is light, they have doomed themselves for wrongfully denying Our signs"
  7,10,We have indeed established you on earth and provided you with a means of livelihood. ňĻYetňļ you seldom give any thanks
  7,11,"Surely We created you,¬†then shaped you, then said to the angels, ‚ÄúProstrate before Adam,‚ÄĚ so they all did‚ÄĒbut not Ibl√ģs,¬†who refused to prostrate with the others"
  7,12,"God asked, ‚ÄúWhat prevented you from prostrating when I commanded you?‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúI am better than he is: You created me from fire and him from clay.‚ÄĚ"
  7,13,"God said, ‚ÄúThen get down from Paradise! It is not for you to be arrogant here. So get out! You are truly one of the disgraced.‚ÄĚ"
  7,14,"He appealed, ‚ÄúThen delay my end until the Day of their resurrection.‚ÄĚ"
  7,15,"God said, ‚ÄúYou are delayed ňĻuntil the appointed Dayňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  7,16,"He said, ‚ÄúFor leaving me to stray I will lie in ambush for them on Your Straight Path"
  7,17,"I will approach them from their front, their back, their right, their left, and then You will find most of them ungrateful.‚ÄĚ"
  7,18,"God said, ‚ÄúGet out of Paradise! You are disgraced and rejected! I will certainly fill up Hell with you and your followers all together.‚ÄĚ"
  7,19,"ňĻGod said,ňļ ‚ÄúO Adam! Live with your wife in Paradise and eat from wherever you please, but do not approach this tree, or else you will be wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  7,20,"Then Satan tempted them in order to expose what was hidden of their nakedness. He said, ‚ÄúYour Lord has forbidden this tree to you only to prevent you from becoming angels or immortals.‚ÄĚ"
  7,21,"And he swore to them, ‚ÄúI am truly your sincere advisor.‚ÄĚ"
  7,22,"So he brought about their fall through deception. And when they tasted of the tree, their nakedness was exposed to them, prompting them to cover themselves with leaves from Paradise. Then their Lord called out to them, ‚ÄúDid I not forbid you from that tree and ňĻdid I notňļ tell you that Satan is your sworn enemy?‚ÄĚ"
  7,23,"They replied, ‚ÄúOur Lord! We have wronged ourselves. If You do not forgive us and have mercy on us, we will certainly be losers.‚ÄĚ"
  7,24,"God said, ‚ÄúDescend as enemies to each other.¬†You will find in the earth a residence and provision for your appointed stay.‚ÄĚ"
  7,25,"He added, ‚ÄúThere you will live, there you will die, and from there you will be resurrected.‚ÄĚ"
  7,26,"O children of Adam! We have provided for you clothing to cover your nakedness and as an adornment. However, the best clothing is righteousness. This is one of God‚Äôs bounties, so perhaps you will be mindful"
  7,27,O children of Adam! Do not let Satan deceive you as he tempted your parents out of Paradise and caused their cover to be removed in order to expose their nakedness. Surely he and his soldiers watch you from where you cannot see them. We have made the devils allies of those who disbelieve
  7,28,"Whenever they commit a shameful deed,¬†they say, ‚ÄúWe found our forefathers doing it and God has commanded us to do it.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúNo! God never commands what is shameful. How can you attribute to God what you do not know?‚ÄĚ"
  7,29,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúMy Lord has commanded uprightness and dedication ňĻto Him aloneňļ in worship, calling upon Him with sincere devotion. Just as He first brought you into being, you will be brought to life again.‚ÄĚ"
  7,30,"He has guided some, while others are destined to stray. They have taken devils as their masters instead of God‚ÄĒthinking they are ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  7,31,"O Children of Adam! Dress properly whenever you are at worship. Eat and drink, but do not waste. Surely He does not like the wasteful"
  7,32,"Ask, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWho has forbidden the adornments and lawful provisions God has brought forth for His servants?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúThey are for the enjoyment of the believers in this worldly life, but they will be exclusively theirs on the Day of Judgment.¬†This is how We make Our revelations clear for people of knowledge.‚ÄĚ"
  7,33,"Say, ‚ÄúMy Lord has only forbidden open and secret indecencies, sinfulness, unjust aggression, associating ňĻothersňļ with God ňĻin worshipňļ‚ÄĒa practice He has never authorized‚ÄĒand attributing to God what you do not know.‚ÄĚ"
  7,34,"For each community there is an appointed term. When their time arrives, they can neither delay it for a moment, nor could they advance it"
  7,35,"O children of Adam! When messengers from among yourselves come to you reciting My revelations‚ÄĒwhoever shuns evil and mends their ways, there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve"
  7,36,But those who receive Our revelations with denial and arrogance will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever
  7,37,"Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against God or deny His revelations? They will receive what is destined for them,¬†until Our messenger-angels arrive to take their souls, asking them, ‚ÄúWhere are those ňĻfalse godsňļ you used to invoke besides God?‚ÄĚ They will cry, ‚ÄúThey have failed us,‚ÄĚ and they will confess against themselves that they were indeed disbelievers"
  7,38,"God will say, ‚ÄúEnter the Fire along with the ňĻevilňļ groups of jinn and humans that preceded you.‚ÄĚ Whenever a group enters Hell, it will curse the preceding one until they are all gathered inside, the followers will say about their leaders, ‚ÄúOur Lord! They have misled us, so multiply their torment in the Fire.‚ÄĚ He will answer, ‚ÄúIt has already been multiplied for all, but you do not know.‚ÄĚ"
  7,39,"Then the leaders will say to their followers, ‚ÄúYou were no better than us! So taste the torment for what you used to commit.‚ÄĚ"
  7,40,"Surely those who receive our revelations with denial and arrogance, the gates of heaven will not be opened for them, nor will they enter Paradise until a camel passes through the eye of a needle. This is how We reward the wicked"
  7,41,Hell will be their bed; flames will be their cover. This is how We reward the wrongdoers
  7,42,As for those who believe and do good‚ÄĒWe never require of any soul more than what it can afford‚ÄĒit is they who will be the residents of Paradise. They will be there forever
  7,43,"We will remove whatever bitterness they had in their hearts.¬†Rivers will flow under their feet. And they will say, ‚ÄúPraise be to God for guiding us to this. We would have never been guided if God had not guided us. The messengers of our Lord had certainly come with the truth.‚ÄĚ It will be announced to them, ‚ÄúThis is Paradise awarded to you for what you used to do.‚ÄĚ"
  7,44,"The residents of Paradise will call out to the residents of the Fire, ‚ÄúWe have certainly found our Lord‚Äôs promise to be true. Have you too found your Lord‚Äôs promise to be true?‚ÄĚ They will reply, ‚ÄúYes, we have!‚ÄĚ Then a caller will announce to both, ‚ÄúMay God‚Äôs condemnation be upon the wrongdoers"
  7,45,"those who hindered ňĻothersňļ from God‚Äôs Way, strived to make it ňĻappearňļ crooked, and disbelieved in the Hereafter.‚ÄĚ"
  7,46,"There will be a barrier between Paradise and Hell. And on the heights ňĻof that barrierňļ will be people¬†who will recognize ňĻthe residents ofňļ both by their appearance.¬†They will call out to the residents of Paradise, ‚ÄúPeace be upon you!‚ÄĚ They will have not yet entered Paradise, but eagerly hope to"
  7,47,"When their eyes will turn towards the residents of Hell, they will pray, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Do not join us with the wrongdoing people.‚ÄĚ"
  7,48,"Those on the heights will call out to some ňĻtyrants in the Fireňļ, who they will recognize by their appearance, saying, ‚ÄúYour large numbers and arrogance are of no use ňĻtodayňļ"
  7,49,"Are these ňĻhumble believersňļ the ones you swore would never be shown God‚Äôs mercy?‚ÄĚ ňĻFinally, those on the heights will be told:ňļ ‚ÄúEnter Paradise! There will be no fear for you, nor will you grieve.‚ÄĚ"
  7,50,"The residents of the Fire will then cry out to the residents of Paradise, ‚ÄúAid us with some water or any provision God has granted you.‚ÄĚ They will reply, ‚ÄúGod has forbidden both to the disbelievers"
  7,51,"those who took this¬†faith ňĻof Islamňļ as mere amusement and play and were deluded by ňĻtheirňļ worldly life.‚ÄĚ ňĻGod will say,ňļ ‚ÄúToday We will ignore them just as they ignored the coming of this Day of theirs and for rejecting Our revelations.‚ÄĚ"
  7,52,We have certainly brought them a Book which We explained with knowledge‚ÄĒa guide and mercy for those who believe
  7,53,"Do they only await the fulfilment ňĻof its warningňļ? The Day it will be fulfilled, those who ignored it before will say, ‚ÄúThe messengers of our Lord certainly came with the truth. Are there any intercessors who can plead on our behalf? Or can we be sent back so we may do ňĻgood,ňļ unlike what we used to do?‚ÄĚ They will have certainly ruined themselves, and whatever ňĻgodsňļ they fabricated will fail them"
  7,54,"Indeed your Lord is God Who created the heavens and the earth in six Days,¬†then established Himself on the Throne. He makes the day and night overlap in rapid succession. He created the sun, the moon, and the stars‚ÄĒall subjected by His command. The creation and the command belong to Him ňĻaloneňļ. Blessed is God‚ÄĒLord of all worlds"
  7,55,Call upon your Lord humbly and secretly. Surely He does not like the transgressors
  7,56,"Do not spread corruption in the land after it has been set in order. And call upon Him with hope and fear. Indeed, God‚Äôs mercy is always close to the good-doers"
  7,57,"He is the One Who sends the winds ushering in His mercy. When they bear heavy clouds, We drive them to a lifeless land and then cause rain to fall, producing every type of fruit. Similarly, We will bring the dead to life, so perhaps you will be mindful"
  7,58,"The fertile land produces abundantly by the Will of its Lord, whereas the infertile land hardly produces anything. This is how We vary ňĻOurňļ lessons to those who are thankful"
  7,59,"Indeed, We sent Noah to his people. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God‚ÄĒyou have no other god except Him. I truly fear for you the torment of a tremendous Day.‚ÄĚ"
  7,60,"But the chiefs of his people said, ‚ÄúWe surely see that you are clearly misguided.‚ÄĚ"
  7,61,"He replied, ‚ÄúO my people! I am not misguided! But I am a messenger from the Lord of all worlds"
  7,62,conveying to you my Lord‚Äôs messages and giving you ňĻsincereňļ advice. And I know from God what you do not know
  7,63,"Do you find it astonishing that a reminder should come to you from your Lord through one of your own, warning you, so you may beware and perhaps be shown mercy?‚ÄĚ"
  7,64,"But they rejected him, so We saved him and those with him in the Ark, and drowned those who rejected Our signs. They were certainly a blind people"
  7,65,"And to the people of ‚Äô√ād We sent their brother H√Ľd. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God‚ÄĒyou have no other god except Him. Will you not then fear Him?‚ÄĚ"
  7,66,"The disbelieving chiefs of his people responded, ‚ÄúWe surely see you as a fool, and we certainly think you are a liar.‚ÄĚ"
  7,67,"H√Ľd replied, ‚ÄúO my people! I am no fool! But I am a messenger from the Lord of all worlds"
  7,68,conveying to you my Lord‚Äôs messages. And I am your sincere advisor
  7,69,"Do you find it astonishing that a reminder should come to you from your Lord through one of your own so he may warn you? Remember that He made you successors after the people of Noah and increased you greatly in stature. So remember God‚Äôs favours, so you may be successful.‚ÄĚ"
  7,70,"They said, ‚ÄúHave you come to us so that we would worship God alone and abandon what our forefathers used to worship? Then bring us what you threaten us with, if what you say is true!‚ÄĚ"
  7,71,"He said, ‚ÄúYou will certainly be subjected to your Lord‚Äôs torment and wrath. Do you dispute with me regarding the so-called gods which you and your forefathers have made up‚ÄĒa practice God has never authorized? Then wait! I too am waiting with you.‚ÄĚ"
  7,72,So We saved him and those with him by Our mercy and uprooted those who denied Our signs. They were not believers
  7,73,"And to the people of Tham√Ľd We sent their brother ŠĻĘ√ĘliŠł•. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God‚ÄĒyou have no other god except Him. A clear proof has come to you from your Lord: this is God‚Äôs she-camel as a sign to you. So leave her to graze ňĻfreelyňļ on God‚Äôs land and do not harm her, or else you will be overcome by a painful punishment"
  7,74,"Remember when He made you successors after ‚Äô√ād and established you in the land‚ÄĒňĻandňļ you built palaces on its plains and carved homes into mountains. So remember God‚Äôs favours, and do not go about spreading corruption in the land.‚ÄĚ"
  7,75,"The arrogant chiefs of his people asked the lowly who believed among them, ‚ÄúAre you certain that ŠĻĘ√ĘliŠł• has been sent by his Lord?‚ÄĚ They replied, ‚ÄúWe certainly believe in what he has been sent with.‚ÄĚ"
  7,76,"The arrogant said, ‚ÄúWe surely reject what you believe in.‚ÄĚ"
  7,77,"Then they killed the she-camel‚ÄĒdefying their Lord‚Äôs command‚ÄĒand challenged ňĻŠĻĘ√ĘliŠł•ňļ, ‚ÄúBring us what you threaten us with, if you are ňĻtrulyňļ one of the messengers.‚ÄĚ"
  7,78,"Then an ňĻoverwhelmingňļ earthquake struck them, and they fell lifeless in their homes"
  7,79,"So he turned away from them, saying, ‚ÄúO my people! Surely I conveyed to you my Lord‚Äôs message and gave you ňĻsincereňļ advice, but you do not like ňĻsincereňļ advisors.‚ÄĚ"
  7,80,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Lot scolded ňĻthe men ofňļ his people, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúDo you commit a shameful deed that no man has ever done before"
  7,81,You lust after men instead of women! You are certainly transgressors.‚ÄĚ
  7,82,"But his people‚Äôs only response was to say, ‚ÄúExpel them from your land! They are a people who wish to remain chaste!‚ÄĚ"
  7,83,"So We saved him and his family except his wife, who was one of the doomed"
  7,84,We poured upon them a rain ňĻof brimstoneňļ. See what was the end of the wicked
  7,85,"And to the people of Midian We sent their brother Shu‚Äôaib. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God‚ÄĒyou have no other god except Him. A clear proof has already come to you from your Lord. So give just measure and weight, do not defraud people of their property, nor spread corruption in the land after it has been set in order. This is for your own good, if you are ňĻtrulyňļ believers"
  7,86,"And do not lie in ambush on every road‚ÄĒthreatening and hindering those who believe in God from His Path and striving to make it ňĻappearňļ crooked. Remember when you were few, then He increased you in number. And consider the fate of the corruptors"
  7,87,"If some of you do believe in what I have been sent with while others do not, then be patient until God judges between us. He is the Best of Judges.‚ÄĚ"
  7,88,"The arrogant chiefs of his people threatened, ‚ÄúO Shu‚Äôaib! We will certainly expel you and your fellow believers from our land, unless you return to our faith.‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúEven if we hate it"
  7,89,"We would surely be fabricating a lie against God if we were to return to your faith after God has saved us from it. It does not befit us to return to it unless it is the Will of God, our Lord. Our Lord has encompassed everything in ňĻHisňļ knowledge. In God we trust. Our Lord! Judge between us and our people with truth. You are the best of those who judge.‚ÄĚ"
  7,90,"The disbelieving chiefs of his people threatened, ‚ÄúIf you follow Shu‚Äôaib, you will surely be losers!‚ÄĚ"
  7,91,Then an ňĻoverwhelmingňļ earthquake struck them and they fell lifeless in their homes
  7,92,Those who rejected Shu‚Äôaib were ňĻwiped outňļ as if they had never lived there. Those who rejected Shu‚Äôaib were the true losers
  7,93,"He turned away from them, saying, ‚ÄúO my people! Indeed, I have delivered to you the messages of my Lord and gave you ňĻsincereňļ advice. How can I then grieve for those who chose to disbelieve?‚ÄĚ"
  7,94,"Whenever We sent a prophet to a society, We afflicted its ňĻdisbelievingňļ people with suffering and adversity, so perhaps they would be humbled"
  7,95,"Then We changed their adversity to prosperity until they flourished and argued ňĻfalselyňļ, ‚ÄúOur forefathers ňĻtooňļ had been visited by adversity and prosperity.‚ÄĚ¬†So We seized them by surprise, while they were unaware"
  7,96,"Had the people of those societies been faithful and mindful ňĻof Godňļ, We would have overwhelmed them with blessings from heaven and earth. But they disbelieved, so We seized them for what they used to commit"
  7,97,Did the people of those societies feel secure that Our punishment would not come upon them by night while they were asleep
  7,98,Or did they feel secure that Our punishment would not come upon them by day while they were at play
  7,99,Did they feel secure against God‚Äôs planning? None would feel secure from God‚Äôs planning except the losers
  7,100,Is it not clear to those who take over the land after ňĻthe destruction ofňļ its former residents that‚ÄĒif We will‚ÄĒWe can punish them ňĻtooňļ for their sins and seal their hearts so they will not hear ňĻthe truthňļ
  7,101,"We have narrated to you ňĻO Prophetňļ some of the stories of those societies. Surely, their messengers came to them with clear proofs, but still they would not believe in what they had already denied. This is how God seals the hearts of the disbelievers"
  7,102,"We did not find most of them true to their covenant. Rather, We found most of them truly rebellious"
  7,103,"Then after them We sent Moses with Our signs to Pharaoh and his chiefs, but they wrongfully rejected them. See what was the end of the corruptors"
  7,104,"And Moses said, ‚ÄúO Pharaoh! I am truly a messenger from the Lord of all worlds"
  7,105,"obliged to say nothing about God except the truth. Indeed, I have come to you with clear proof from your Lord, so let the children of Israel go with me.‚ÄĚ"
  7,106,"Pharaoh said, ‚ÄúIf you have come with a sign, then bring it if what you say is true.‚ÄĚ"
  7,107,So Moses threw down his staff and‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒit became a real snake
  7,108,Then he drew his hand ňĻout of his collarňļ and it was ňĻshiningňļ white for all to see
  7,109,"The chiefs of Pharaoh‚Äôs people said, ‚ÄúHe is indeed a skilled magician"
  7,110,"who seeks to drive you from your land.‚ÄĚ ňĻSo Pharaoh asked,ňļ ‚ÄúWhat do you propose?‚ÄĚ"
  7,111,"They replied, ‚ÄúLet him and his brother wait and send mobilizers to all cities"
  7,112,to bring you every clever magician.‚ÄĚ
  7,113,"The magicians came to Pharaoh, saying, ‚ÄúShall we receive a ňĻsuitableňļ reward if we prevail?‚ÄĚ"
  7,114,"He replied, ‚ÄúYes, and you will certainly be among those closest to me.‚ÄĚ"
  7,115,"They asked, ‚ÄúO Moses! Will you cast, or shall we be the first to cast?‚ÄĚ"
  7,116,"Moses said, ‚ÄúYou first.‚ÄĚ So when they did, they deceived the eyes of the people, stunned them, and made a great display of magic"
  7,117,"Then We inspired Moses, ‚ÄúThrow down your staff,‚ÄĚ and‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒit devoured the objects of their illusion"
  7,118,So the truth prevailed and their illusions failed
  7,119,So Pharaoh and his people were defeated right there and put to shame
  7,120,"And the magicians fell down, prostrating"
  7,121,"They declared, ‚ÄúWe ňĻnowňļ believe in the Lord of all worlds‚ÄĒ"
  7,122,the Lord of Moses and Aaron.‚ÄĚ
  7,123,"Pharaoh threatened, ‚ÄúHow dare you believe in him before I give you permission? This must be a conspiracy you devised in the city to drive out its people, but soon you will see"
  7,124,"I will certainly cut off your hands and feet on opposite sides, then crucify you all.‚ÄĚ"
  7,125,"They responded, ‚ÄúSurely to our Lord we will ňĻallňļ return"
  7,126,"Your rage towards us is only because we believed in the signs of our Lord when they came to us. Our Lord! Shower us with perseverance, and let us die while submitting ňĻto Youňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  7,127,"The chiefs of Pharaoh‚Äôs people protested, ‚ÄúAre you going to leave Moses and his people free to spread corruption in the land and abandon you and your gods?‚ÄĚ He responded, ‚ÄúWe will kill their sons and keep their women.¬†We will completely dominate them.‚ÄĚ"
  7,128,"Moses reassured his people, ‚ÄúSeek God‚Äôs help and be patient. Indeed, the earth belongs to God ňĻaloneňļ. He grants it to whoever He chooses of His servants. The ultimate outcome belongs ňĻonlyňļ to the righteous.‚ÄĚ"
  7,129,"They complained, ‚ÄúWe have always been oppressed‚ÄĒbefore and after you came to us ňĻwith the messageňļ.‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúPerhaps your Lord will destroy your enemy and make you successors in the land to see what you will do.‚ÄĚ"
  7,130,"Indeed, We afflicted Pharaoh‚Äôs people with famine and shortage of crops so they might come back ňĻto their sensesňļ"
  7,131,"In times of prosperity, they said, ‚ÄúThis is what we deserve,‚ÄĚ but in adversity, they blamed it on Moses and those with him.¬†Surely all is destined by God. Yet most of them did not know"
  7,132,"They said, ‚ÄúNo matter what sign you may bring to deceive us, we will never believe in you.‚ÄĚ"
  7,133,"So We plagued them with floods, locusts, lice, frogs, and blood‚ÄĒall as clear signs, but they persisted in arrogance and were a wicked people"
  7,134,"When tormented, they pleaded, ‚ÄúO Moses! Pray to your Lord on our behalf, by virtue of the covenant He made with you. If you help remove this torment from us, we will certainly believe in you and let the Children of Israel go with you.‚ÄĚ"
  7,135,But as soon as We removed the torment from them‚ÄĒuntil they met their inevitable fate‚ÄĒthey broke their promise
  7,136,"So We inflicted punishment upon them, drowning them in the sea for denying Our signs and being heedless of them"
  7,137,"And ňĻsoňļ We made the oppressed people successors of the eastern and western lands, which We had showered with blessings. ňĻIn this wayňļ the noble Word of your Lord was fulfilled for the Children of Israel for what they had endured. And We destroyed what Pharaoh and his people constructed and what they established"
  7,138,"We brought the Children of Israel across the sea and they came upon a people devoted to idols. They demanded, ‚ÄúO Moses! Make for us a god like their gods.‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúIndeed, you are a people acting ignorantly"
  7,139,What they follow is certainly doomed to destruction and their deeds are in vain.‚ÄĚ
  7,140,"He added, ‚ÄúShall I seek for you a god other than God, while He has honoured you above the others?‚ÄĚ"
  7,141,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We rescued you from the people of Pharaoh, who afflicted you with dreadful torment‚ÄĒkilling your sons and keeping your women. That was a severe test from your Lord"
  7,142,"We appointed for Moses thirty nights then added another ten‚ÄĒcompleting his Lord‚Äôs term of forty nights. Moses commanded his brother Aaron, ‚ÄúTake my place among my people, do what is right, and do not follow the way of the corruptors.‚ÄĚ"
  7,143,"When Moses came at the appointed time and his Lord spoke to him, he asked, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Reveal Yourself to me so I may see You.‚ÄĚ God answered, ‚ÄúYou cannot see Me! But look at the mountain. If it remains firm in its place, only then will you see Me.‚ÄĚ When his Lord appeared to the mountain, He levelled it to dust and Moses collapsed unconscious. When he recovered, he cried, ‚ÄúGlory be to You! I turn to You in repentance and I am the first of the believers.‚ÄĚ"
  7,144,"God said, ‚ÄúO Moses! I have ňĻalreadyňļ elevated you above all others by My messages and speech.¬†So hold firmly to what I have given you and be grateful.‚ÄĚ"
  7,145,"We wrote for him on the Tablets ňĻthe fundamentalsňļ of everything; commandments and explanations of all things. ňĻWe commanded,ňļ ‚ÄúHold to this firmly and ask your people to take the best of it.¬†I will soon show ňĻall ofňļ you the home of the rebellious"
  7,146,"I will turn away from My signs those who act unjustly with arrogance in the land. And even if they were to see every sign, they still would not believe in them. If they see the Right Path, they will not take it. But if they see a crooked path, they will follow it. This is because they denied Our signs and were heedless of them"
  7,147,The deeds of those who deny Our signs and the meeting ňĻwith Godňļ in the Hereafter will be in vain. Will they be rewarded except for what they have done?‚ÄĚ
  7,148,"In the absence of Moses, his people made from their ňĻgoldenňļ jewellery an idol of a calf that made a lowing sound. Did they not see that it could neither speak to them nor guide them to the ňĻRightňļ Path? Still they took it as a god and were wrongdoers"
  7,149,"Later, when they were filled with remorse and realized they had gone astray, they cried, ‚ÄúIf our Lord does not have mercy on us and forgive us, we will certainly be losers.‚ÄĚ"
  7,150,"Upon Moses‚Äô return to his people, ňĻtotallyňļ furious and sorrowful, he said, ‚ÄúWhat an evil thing you committed in my absence! Did you want to hasten your Lord‚Äôs torment?‚ÄĚ Then he threw down the Tablets and grabbed his brother by the hair, dragging him closer. Aaron pleaded, ‚ÄúO son of my mother! The people overpowered me and were about to kill me. So do not ňĻhumiliate me andňļ make my enemies rejoice, nor count me among the wrongdoing people.‚ÄĚ"
  7,151,"Moses prayed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Forgive me and my brother! And admit us into Your mercy. You are the Most Merciful of the merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  7,152,Those who worshipped the calf will certainly be afflicted with God‚Äôs wrath as well as disgrace in the life of this world. This is how We reward those who invent falsehood
  7,153,"But those who commit evil, then repent and become ňĻtrueňļ believers, your Lord will certainly be All-Forgiving, Most-Merciful"
  7,154,"When Moses‚Äô anger subsided, he took up the Tablets whose text contained guidance and mercy for those who stand in awe of their Lord"
  7,155,"Moses chose seventy men from among his people for Our appointment and, when they were seized by an earthquake,¬†he cried, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Had You willed, You could have destroyed them long ago, and me as well. Will You destroy us for what the foolish among us have done? This is only a test from You‚ÄĒby which You allow whoever you will to stray and guide whoever You will. You are our Guardian. So forgive us and have mercy on us. You are the best forgiver"
  7,156,"Ordain for us what is good in this life and the next. Indeed, we have turned to You ňĻin repentanceňļ.‚ÄĚ God replied, ‚ÄúI will inflict My torment on whoever I will. But My mercy encompasses everything. I will ordain mercy for those who shun evil, pay alms-tax, and believe in Our revelations"
  7,157,"‚ÄúňĻThey areňļ the ones who follow the Messenger, the unlettered Prophet, whose description they find in their Torah and the Gospel.¬†He commands them to do good and forbids them from evil, permits for them what is lawful and forbids to them what is impure, and relieves them from their burdens and the shackles that bound them. ňĻOnlyňļ those who believe in him, honour and support him, and follow the light sent down to him will be successful.‚ÄĚ"
  7,158,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO humanity! I am God‚Äôs Messenger to you all. To Him ňĻaloneňļ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth. There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. He gives life and causes death.‚ÄĚ So believe in God and His Messenger, the unlettered Prophet, who believes in God and His revelations. And follow him, so you may be ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  7,159,There are some among the people of Moses who guide with the truth and establish justice accordingly
  7,160,"We divided them into twelve tribes‚ÄĒeach as a community. And We revealed to Moses, when his people asked for water, ‚ÄúStrike the rock with your staff.‚ÄĚ Then twelve springs gushed out. Each tribe knew its drinking place. We shaded them with clouds and sent down to them manna and quails,¬†ňĻsayingňļ, ‚ÄúEat from the good things We have provided for you.‚ÄĚ They ňĻcertainlyňļ did not wrong Us, but wronged themselves"
  7,161,"And ňĻrememberňļ when it was said to them, ‚ÄúEnter this city ňĻof Jerusalemňļ and eat from wherever you please. Say, ‚ÄėAbsolve us,‚Äô and enter the gate with humility. We will forgive your sins, ňĻandňļ We will multiply the reward for the good-doers.‚ÄĚ"
  7,162,But the wrongdoers among them changed the words they were commanded to say. So We sent down a punishment from the heavens upon them for their wrongdoing
  7,163,"Ask them ňĻO Prophetňļ about ňĻthe people ofňļ the town which was by the sea, who broke the Sabbath.¬†During the Sabbath, ňĻabundantňļ fish would come to them clearly visible, but on other days the fish were never seen. In this way We tested them for their rebelliousness"
  7,164,"When some of ňĻthe righteous amongňļ them questioned ňĻtheir fellow Sabbath-keepersňļ, ‚ÄúWhy do you ňĻbother toňļ warn those ňĻSabbath-breakersňļ who will either be destroyed or severely punished by God?‚ÄĚ They replied, ‚ÄúJust to be free from your Lord‚Äôs blame, and so perhaps they may abstain.‚ÄĚ"
  7,165,"When they ignored the warning they were given, We rescued those who used to warn against evil and overtook the wrongdoers with a dreadful punishment for their rebelliousness"
  7,166,"But when they stubbornly persisted in violation, We said to them, ‚ÄúBe disgraced apes!‚ÄĚ"
  7,167,"And ňĻremember, O Prophet,ňļ when your Lord declared that He would send against them others who would make them suffer terribly until the Day of Judgment. Indeed, your Lord is swift in punishment, but He is certainly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  7,168,"We dispersed them through the land in groups‚ÄĒsome were righteous, others were less so. We tested them with prosperity and adversity, so perhaps they would return ňĻto the Right Pathňļ"
  7,169,"Then they were succeeded by other generations who inherited the Scripture. They indulged in unlawful gains, claiming, ‚ÄúWe will be forgiven ňĻafter allňļ.‚ÄĚ And if similar gain came their way, they would seize it. Was a covenant not taken from them in the Scripture that they would not say anything about God except the truth? And they were already well-versed in its teachings. But the ňĻeternalňļ Home of the Hereafter is far better for those mindful ňĻof Godňļ. Will you not then understand"
  7,170,As for those who firmly abide by the Scripture and establish prayer‚ÄĒsurely We never discount the reward of those acting righteously
  7,171,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a cloud and they thought it would fall on them.¬†ňĻWe said,ňļ ‚ÄúHold firmly to that ňĻScriptureňļ which¬†We have given you and observe its teachings so perhaps you will become mindful ňĻof Godňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  7,172,"And ňĻrememberňļ when your Lord brought forth from the loins of the children of Adam their descendants and had them testify regarding themselves. ňĻGod asked,ňļ ‚ÄúAm I not your Lord?‚ÄĚ They replied, ‚ÄúYes, You are! We testify.‚ÄĚ ňĻHe cautioned,ňļ ‚ÄúNow you have no right to say on Judgment Day, ‚ÄėWe were not aware of this.‚Äô"
  7,173,"Nor say, ‚ÄėIt was our forefathers who had associated others ňĻwith God in worshipňļ and we, as their descendants, followed in their footsteps. Will you then destroy us for the falsehood they invented?‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  7,174,"This is how We make our signs clear, so perhaps they will return ňĻto the Right Pathňļ"
  7,175,"And relate to them ňĻO Prophetňļ the story of the one to whom We gave Our signs, but he abandoned them, so Satan took hold of him, and he became a deviant"
  7,176,"If We had willed, We would have elevated him with Our signs, but he clung to this life‚ÄĒfollowing his evil desires. His example is that of a dog: if you chase it away, it pants, and if you leave it, it ňĻstillňļ pants. This is the example of the people who deny Our signs.¬†So narrate ňĻto themňļ stories ňĻof the pastňļ, so perhaps they will reflect"
  7,177,What an evil example of those who denied Our signs! They ňĻonlyňļ wronged their own souls
  7,178,"Whoever God guides is truly guided. And whoever He leaves to stray, they are the ňĻtrueňļ losers"
  7,179,"Indeed, We have destined many jinn and humans for Hell. They have hearts they do not understand with, eyes they do not see with, and ears they do not hear with. They are like cattle. In fact, they are even less guided! Such ňĻpeopleňļ are ňĻentirelyňļ heedless"
  7,180,"God has the Most Beautiful Names. So call upon Him by them, and keep away from those who abuse His Names.¬†They will be punished for what they used to do"
  7,181,And among those We created is a group that guides with the truth and establishes justice accordingly
  7,182,"As for those who deny Our signs, We will gradually draw them to destruction in ways they cannot comprehend"
  7,183,"I ňĻonlyňļ delay their end for a while, but My planning is flawless"
  7,184,Have they not ever given it a thought? Their fellow man¬†is not insane. He is only sent with a clear warning
  7,185,"Have they ever reflected on the wonders of the heavens and the earth, and everything God has created, and that perhaps their end is near? So what message after this ňĻQuranňļ would they believe in"
  7,186,"Whoever God allows to stray, none can guide, leaving them to wander blindly in their defiance"
  7,187,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ regarding the Hour, ‚ÄúWhen will it be?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúThat knowledge is only with my Lord. He alone will reveal it when the time comes. It is too tremendous for the heavens and the earth and will only take you by surprise.‚ÄĚ They ask you as if you had full knowledge of it. Say, ‚ÄúThat knowledge is only with God, but most people do not know.‚ÄĚ"
  7,188,"Say, ‚ÄúI have no power to benefit or protect myself, except by the Will of God. If I had known the unknown, I would have benefited myself enormously, and no harm would have ever touched me. I am only a warner and deliverer of good news for those who believe.‚ÄĚ"
  7,189,"He is the One Who created you from a single soul, then from it made its spouse so he may find comfort in her. After he had been united with her, she carried a light burden that developed gradually. When it grew heavy, they prayed to God, their Lord, ‚ÄúIf you grant us good offspring, we will certainly be grateful.‚ÄĚ"
  7,190,"But when He granted their descendants good offspring, they associated false gods in what He has given them. Exalted is God above what they associate ňĻwith Himňļ"
  7,191,"Do they associate ňĻwith Godňļ those ňĻidolsňļ which cannot create anything, but are in fact created"
  7,192,"which cannot help them, or even help themselves"
  7,193,"And if you ňĻidolatersňļ call upon them for guidance, they cannot respond to you. It is all the same whether you call them or remain silent"
  7,194,"Those ňĻidolsňļ you invoke besides God are created beings like yourselves. So call upon them and see if they will answer you, if your claims are true"
  7,195,"Do they have feet to walk with? Or hands to hold with? Or eyes to see with? Or ears to hear with? Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúCall upon your associate-gods and conspire against me without delay"
  7,196,"‚ÄúIndeed, my Protector is God Who has revealed this Book. For He ňĻaloneňļ protects the righteous"
  7,197,But those ňĻfalse godsňļ you call besides Him can neither help you nor even themselves.‚ÄĚ
  7,198,"If you ňĻidolatersňļ call them to guidance, they cannot hear. And you ňĻO Prophetňļ may see them facing towards you, but they cannot see"
  7,199,"Be gracious, enjoin what is right, and turn away from those who act ignorantly"
  7,200,"If you are tempted by Satan, then seek refuge with God. Surely He is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  7,201,"Indeed, when Satan whispers to those mindful ňĻof Godňļ, they remember ňĻtheir Lordňļ then they start to see ňĻthingsňļ clearly"
  7,202,"But the devils persistently plunge their ňĻhumanňļ associates¬†deeper into wickedness, sparing no effort"
  7,203,"If you ňĻO Prophetňļ do not bring them a sign ňĻwhich they demandedňļ, they ask, ‚ÄúWhy do you not make it yourself?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúI only follow what is revealed to me from my Lord. This ňĻQuranňļ is an insight from your Lord‚ÄĒa guide and a mercy for those who believe.‚ÄĚ"
  7,204,"When the Quran is recited, listen to it attentively and be silent, so you may be shown mercy"
  7,205,"Remember your Lord inwardly with humility and reverence and in a moderate tone of voice, both morning and evening. And do not be one of the heedless"
  7,206,Surely those ňĻangelsňļ nearest to your Lord are not too proud to worship Him. They glorify Him. And to Him they prostrate
  8,1,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ regarding the spoils of war. Say, ‚ÄúTheir distribution is decided by God and His Messenger. So be mindful of God, settle your affairs, and obey God and His Messenger if you are ňĻtrueňļ believers.‚ÄĚ"
  8,2,"The ňĻtrueňļ believers are only those whose hearts tremble at the remembrance of God, whose faith increases when His revelations are recited to them, and who put their trust in their Lord"
  8,3,ňĻThey areňļ those who establish prayer and donate from what We have provided for them
  8,4,"It is they who are the true believers. They will have elevated ranks, forgiveness, and an honourable provision from their Lord"
  8,5,"Similarly, when your Lord brought you ňĻO Prophetňļ out of your home for a just cause, a group of believers was totally against it"
  8,6,"They disputed with you about the truth after it had been made clear, as if they were being driven to death with their eyes wide open"
  8,7,"ňĻRemember, O believers,ňļ when God promised ňĻto giveňļ you the upper hand over either target, you wished to capture the unarmed party.¬†But it was God‚Äôs Will¬†to establish the truth by His Words and uproot the disbelievers"
  8,8,to firmly establish the truth and wipe out falsehood‚ÄĒeven to the dismay of the wicked
  8,9,"ňĻRememberňļ when you cried out to your Lord for help, He answered, ‚ÄúI will reinforce you with a thousand angels‚ÄĒfollowed by many others.‚ÄĚ"
  8,10,"And God made this a sign of victory and reassurance to your hearts. Victory comes only from God. Surely God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  8,11,"ňĻRememberňļ when He caused drowsiness to overcome you, giving you serenity.¬†And He sent down rain from the sky to purify you, free you from Satan‚Äôs whispers, strengthen your hearts, and make ňĻyourňļ steps firm"
  8,12,"ňĻRemember, O Prophet,ňļ when your Lord revealed to the angels, ‚ÄúI am with you. So make the believers stand firm. I will cast horror into the hearts of the disbelievers. So strike their necks and strike their fingertips.‚ÄĚ"
  8,13,"This is because they defied God and His Messenger. And whoever defies God and His Messenger, then ňĻknow thatňļ God is surely severe in punishment"
  8,14,"That ňĻworldly punishmentňļ is yours, so taste it! Then the disbelievers will suffer the torment of the Fire"
  8,15,"O believers! When you face the disbelievers in battle, never turn your backs to them"
  8,16,"And whoever does so on such an occasion‚ÄĒunless it is a manoeuvre or to join their own troops‚ÄĒwill earn the displeasure of God, and their home will be Hell. What an evil destination"
  8,17,"It was not you ňĻbelieversňļ who killed them, but it was God Who did so. Nor was it you ňĻO Prophetňļ who threw ňĻa handful of sand at the disbelieversňļ,¬†but it was God Who did so, rendering the believers a great favour. Surely God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  8,18,"As such, God frustrates the evil plans of the disbelievers"
  8,19,"If you ňĻMeccansňļ sought judgment, now it has come to you. And if you cease, it will be for your own good. But if you persist, We will persist. And your forces‚ÄĒno matter how numerous they might be‚ÄĒwill not benefit you whatsoever. For God is certainly with the believers"
  8,20,O believers! Obey God and His Messenger and do not turn away from him while you hear ňĻhis callňļ
  8,21,"Do not be like those who say, ‚ÄúWe hear,‚ÄĚ but in fact they are not listening"
  8,22,"Indeed, the worst of all beings in the sight of God are the ňĻwilfullyňļ deaf and dumb, who do not understand"
  8,23,"Had God known any goodness in them, He would have certainly made them hear. ňĻButňļ even if He had made them hear, they would have surely turned away heedlessly"
  8,24,"O believers! Respond to God and His Messenger when he calls you to that which gives you life. And know that God stands between a person and their heart, and that to Him you will all be gathered"
  8,25,Beware of a trial that will not only affect the wrongdoers among you. And know that God is severe in punishment
  8,26,"Remember when you had been vastly outnumbered and oppressed in the land,¬†constantly in fear of attacks by your enemy, then He sheltered you, strengthened you with His help, and provided you with good things so perhaps you would be thankful"
  8,27,"O believers! Do not betray God and the Messenger, nor betray your trusts knowingly"
  8,28,And know that your wealth and your children are only a test and that with God is a great reward
  8,29,"O believers! If you are mindful of God, He will grant you a standard ňĻto distinguish between right and wrongňļ, absolve you of your sins, and forgive you. And God is the Lord of infinite bounty"
  8,30,"And ňĻremember, O Prophet,ňļ when the disbelievers conspired to capture, kill, or exile you. They planned, but God also planned. And God is the best of planners"
  8,31,"Whenever Our revelations are recited to them, they challenge ňĻyouňļ, ‚ÄúWe have already heard ňĻthe recitationňļ. If we wanted, we could have easily produced something similar. This ňĻQuranňļ is nothing but ancient fables!‚ÄĚ"
  8,32,"And ňĻrememberňļ when they prayed, ‚ÄúO God! If this is indeed the truth from You, then rain down stones upon us from the sky or overcome us with a painful punishment.‚ÄĚ"
  8,33,But God would never punish them while you ňĻO Prophetňļ were in their midst. Nor would He ever punish them if they prayed for forgiveness
  8,34,"And why should God not punish them while they hinder pilgrims from the Sacred Mosque, claiming to be its rightful guardians? None has the right to guardianship except those mindful ňĻof Godňļ, but most pagans do not know"
  8,35,Their prayer at the Sacred House was nothing but whistling and clapping. So taste the punishment for your disbelief
  8,36,Surely the disbelievers spend their wealth to hinder others from the Path of God. They will continue to spend to the point of regret. Then they will be defeated and the disbelievers will be driven into Hell
  8,37,so God may separate the evil from the good. He will pile up the evil ones all together and then cast them into Hell. They are the ňĻtrueňļ losers
  8,38,"Tell the disbelievers that if they desist, their past will be forgiven. But if they persist, then they have an example in those destroyed before them"
  8,39,"Fight against them until there is no more persecution‚ÄĒand ňĻyourňļ devotion will be entirely to God. But if they desist, then surely God is All-Seeing of what they do"
  8,40,"And if they do not comply, then know that God is your Protector. What an excellent Protector, and what an excellent Helper"
  8,41,"Know that whatever spoils you take, one-fifth is for God and the Messenger, his close relatives, orphans, the poor, and ňĻneedyňļ travellers, if you ňĻtrulyňļ believe in God and what We revealed to Our servant on that decisive day when the two armies met ňĻat Badrňļ. And God is Most Capable of everything"
  8,42,"ňĻRememberňļ when you were on the near side of the valley, your enemy on the far side, and the caravan was below you. Even if the two armies had made an appointment ňĻto meetňļ, both would have certainly missed it.¬†Still it transpired so God may establish what He had destined‚ÄĒthat those who were to perish and those who were to survive might do so after the truth had been made clear to both. Surely God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  8,43,"ňĻRemember, O Prophet,ňļ when God showed them in your dream as few in number. Had He shown them to you as many, you ňĻbelieversňļ would have certainly faltered and disputed in the matter. But God spared you ňĻfrom thatňļ. Surely He knows best what is ňĻhiddenňļ in the heart"
  8,44,"Then when your armies met, God made them appear as few in your eyes, and made you appear as few in theirs, so God may establish what He had destined. And to God ňĻallňļ matters will be returned ňĻfor judgmentňļ"
  8,45,"O believers! When you face an enemy, stand firm and remember God often so you may triumph"
  8,46,"Obey God and His Messenger and do not dispute with one another, or you would be discouraged and weakened. Persevere! Surely God is with those who persevere"
  8,47,"Do not be like those ňĻpagansňļ who left their homes arrogantly, only to be seen by people and to hinder others from God‚Äôs Path. And God is Fully Aware of what they do"
  8,48,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Satan made their ňĻevilňļ deeds appealing to them, and said, ‚ÄúNo one can overcome you today. I am surely by your side.‚ÄĚ But when the two forces faced off, he cowered and said, ‚ÄúI have absolutely nothing to do with you. I certainly see what you do not see. I truly fear God, for God is severe in punishment.‚ÄĚ"
  8,49,"ňĻRememberňļ when the hypocrites and those with sickness in their hearts said, ‚ÄúThese ňĻbelieversňļ are deluded by their faith.‚ÄĚ But whoever puts their trust in God, surely God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  8,50,"If only you could see when the angels take the souls of the disbelievers, beating their faces and backs, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúTaste the torment of burning"
  8,51,This is ňĻthe rewardňļ for what your hands have done. And God is never unjust to ňĻHisňļ creation.‚ÄĚ
  8,52,"Their fate is that of the people of Pharaoh and those before them‚ÄĒthey all disbelieved in God‚Äôs signs, so God seized them for their sins. Indeed, God is All-Powerful, severe in punishment"
  8,53,"This is because God would never discontinue His favour to a people until they discontinue their faith. Surely God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  8,54,"That was the case with Pharaoh‚Äôs people and those before them‚ÄĒthey all rejected the signs of their Lord, so We destroyed them for their sins and drowned Pharaoh‚Äôs people. They were all wrongdoers"
  8,55,"Indeed, the worst of all beings in the sight of God are those who persist in disbelief, never to have faith‚ÄĒ"
  8,56,"ňĻnamelyňļ those with whom you ňĻO Prophetňļ have entered into treaties, but they violate them every time, not fearing the consequences"
  8,57,"If you ever encounter them in battle, make a fearsome example of them, so perhaps those who would follow them may be deterred"
  8,58,"And if you ňĻO Prophetňļ see signs of betrayal by a people, respond by openly terminating your treaty with them. Surely God does not like those who betray"
  8,59,Do not let those disbelievers¬†think they are not within reach. They will have no escape
  8,60,Prepare against them what you ňĻbelieversňļ can of ňĻmilitaryňļ power and cavalry to deter God‚Äôs enemies and your enemies as well as other enemies unknown to you but known to God. Whatever you spend in the cause of God will be paid to you in full and you will not be wronged
  8,61,"If the enemy is inclined towards peace, make peace with them. And put your trust in God. Indeed, He ňĻaloneňļ is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  8,62,"But if their intention is only to deceive you, then God is certainly sufficient for you. He is the One Who has supported you with His help and with the believers"
  8,63,"He brought their hearts together. Had you spent all the riches in the earth, you could not have united their hearts. But God has united them. Indeed, He is Almighty, All-Wise"
  8,64,O Prophet! God is sufficient for you and for the believers who follow you
  8,65,"O Prophet! Motivate the believers to fight. If there are twenty steadfast among you, they will overcome two hundred. And if there are one hundred of you, they will overcome one thousand of the disbelievers, for they are a people who do not comprehend"
  8,66,"Now God has lightened your burden, for He knows that there is weakness in you. So if there are a hundred steadfast among you, they will overcome two hundred. And if there be one thousand, they will overcome two thousand, by God‚Äôs Will. And God is with the steadfast"
  8,67,"It is not fit for a prophet that he should take captives until he has thoroughly subdued the land. You ňĻbelieversňļ settled with the fleeting gains of this world,¬†while God‚Äôs aim ňĻfor youňļ is the Hereafter. God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  8,68,"Had it not been for a prior decree from God,¬†you would have certainly been disciplined with a tremendous punishment for whatever ňĻransomňļ you have taken"
  8,69,"Now enjoy what you have taken, for it is lawful and good. And be mindful of God. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  8,70,"O Prophet! Tell the captives in your custody, ‚ÄúIf God finds goodness in your hearts, He will give you better than what has been taken from you, and forgive you. For God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  8,71,"But if their intention is only to betray you ňĻO Prophetňļ, they sought to betray God before. But He gave you power over them. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  8,72,"Those who believed, emigrated, and strived with their wealth and lives in the cause of God, as well as those who gave them shelter and help‚ÄĒthey are truly guardians of one another. As for those who believed but did not emigrate, you have no obligations to them until they emigrate. But if they seek your help ňĻagainst persecutionňļ in faith, it is your obligation to help them, except against people bound with you in a treaty. God is All-Seeing of what you do"
  8,73,"As for the disbelievers, they are guardians of one another. And unless you ňĻbelieversňļ act likewise, there will be great oppression and corruption in the land"
  8,74,"Those who believed, migrated, and struggled in the cause of God, and those who gave ňĻthemňļ shelter and help, they are the true believers. They will have forgiveness and an honourable provision"
  8,75,"And those who later believed, migrated, and struggled alongside you, they are also with you. But only blood relatives are now entitled to inherit from one another,¬†as ordained by God. Surely God has ňĻfullňļ knowledge of everything"
  9,1,"ňĻThis isňļ a discharge from all obligations,¬†by God and His Messenger, to the polytheists you ňĻbelieversňļ have entered into treaties with"
  9,2,"‚ÄúYou ňĻpolytheistsňļ may travel freely through the land for four months, but know that you will have no escape from God, and that God will disgrace the disbelievers.‚ÄĚ"
  9,3,"A declaration from God and His Messenger ňĻis madeňļ to all people on the day of the greater pilgrimage¬†that God and His Messenger are free of the polytheists. So if you ňĻpagansňļ repent, it will be better for you. But if you turn away, then know that you will have no escape from God. And give good news ňĻO Prophetňļ to the disbelievers of a painful punishment"
  9,4,"As for the polytheists who have honoured every term of their treaty with you and have not supported an enemy against you, honour your treaty with them until the end of its term. Surely God loves those who are mindful ňĻof Himňļ"
  9,5,"But once the Sacred Months have passed, kill the polytheists ňĻwho violated their treatiesňļ wherever you find them,¬†capture them, besiege them, and lie in wait for them on every way. But if they repent, perform prayers, and pay alms-tax, then set them free. Indeed, God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  9,6,"And if anyone from the polytheists asks for your protection ňĻO Prophetňļ, grant it to them so they may hear the Word of God, then escort them to a place of safety, for they are a people who have no knowledge"
  9,7,"How can such polytheists have a treaty with God and His Messenger, except those you have made a treaty with at the Sacred Mosque?¬†So, as long as they are true to you, be true to them. Indeed God loves those who are mindful ňĻof Himňļ"
  9,8,"How ňĻcan they have a treatyňļ? If they were to have the upper hand over you, they would have no respect for kinship or treaty. They only flatter you with their tongues, but their hearts are in denial, and most of them are rebellious"
  9,9,"They chose a fleeting gain over God‚Äôs revelations, hindering ňĻothersňļ from His Way. Evil indeed is what they have done"
  9,10,They do not honour the bonds of kinship or treaties with the believers. It is they who are the transgressors
  9,11,"But if they repent, perform prayer, and pay alms-tax, then they are your brothers in faith. This is how We make the revelations clear for people of knowledge"
  9,12,"But if they break their oaths after making a pledge and attack your faith, then fight the champions of disbelief‚ÄĒwho never honour their oaths‚ÄĒso perhaps they will desist"
  9,13,"Will you not fight those who have broken their oaths, conspired to expel the Messenger ňĻfrom Meccaňļ, and attacked you first? Do you fear them? God is more deserving of your fear, if you are ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  9,14,"ňĻSoňļ fight them and God will punish them at your hands, put them to shame, help you overcome them, and soothe the hearts of the believers‚ÄĒ"
  9,15,"removing rage from their hearts. And God pardons whoever He wills. For God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  9,16,"Do you ňĻbelieversňļ think that you will be left without God proving who among you ňĻtrulyňļ struggles ňĻin His causeňļ and never takes trusted allies other than God, His Messenger, or the believers? And God is All-Aware of what you do"
  9,17,"It is not for the polytheists to maintain the mosques of God while they openly profess disbelief. Their deeds are void, and they will be in the Fire forever"
  9,18,"The mosques of God should only be maintained by those who believe in God and the Last Day, establish prayer, pay alms-tax, and fear none but God. It is right to hope that they will be among the ňĻtrulyňļ guided"
  9,19,Do you ňĻpagansňļ consider providing the pilgrims with water and maintaining the Sacred Mosque as equal to believing in God and the Last Day and struggling in the cause of God? They are not equal in God‚Äôs sight. And God does not guide the wrongdoing people
  9,20,"Those who have believed, emigrated, and strived in the cause of God with their wealth and their lives are greater in rank in the sight of God. It is they who will triumph"
  9,21,"Their Lord gives them good news of His mercy, pleasure, and Gardens with everlasting bliss"
  9,22,to stay there for ever and ever. Surely with God is a great reward
  9,23,"O believers! Do not take your parents and siblings as trusted allies if they choose disbelief over belief. And whoever of you does so, they are the ňĻtrueňļ wrongdoers"
  9,24,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIf your parents and children and siblings and spouses and extended family and the wealth you have acquired and the trade you fear will decline and the homes you cherish‚ÄĒňĻif all theseňļ are more beloved to you than God and His Messenger and struggling in His Way, then wait until God brings about His Will. God does not guide the rebellious people.‚ÄĚ"
  9,25,"Indeed God has given you ňĻbelieversňļ victory on many battlefields, even at the Battle of Šł§unain¬†when you took pride in your great numbers, but they proved of no advantage to you. The earth, despite its vastness, seemed to close in on you, then you turned back in retreat"
  9,26,"Then God sent down His reassurance¬†upon His Messenger and the believers, and sent down forces¬†you could not see, and punished those who disbelieved. Such was the reward of the disbelievers"
  9,27,"Then afterwards God will turn in grace to whoever He wills.¬†And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  9,28,"O believers! Indeed, the polytheists are ňĻspirituallyňļ impure,¬†so they should not approach the Sacred Mosque after this year.¬†If you fear poverty, God will enrich you out of His bounty, if He wills. Surely, God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  9,29,"Fight those who do not believe in God and the Last Day, nor comply with what God and His Messenger have forbidden, nor embrace the religion of truth from among those who were given the Scripture,¬†until they pay the tax,¬†willingly submitting, fully humbled"
  9,30,"The Jews say, ‚ÄúEzra is the son of God,‚ÄĚ while the Christians say, ‚ÄúThe Messiah is the son of God.‚ÄĚ Such are their baseless assertions, only parroting the words of earlier disbelievers. May God condemn them! How can they be deluded ňĻfrom the truthňļ"
  9,31,"They have taken their rabbis and monks as well as the Messiah, son of Mary, as lords besides God,¬†even though they were commanded to worship none but One God. There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. Glorified is He above what they associate ňĻwith Himňļ"
  9,32,"They wish to extinguish God‚Äôs light¬†with their mouths, but God will only allow His light to be perfected, even to the dismay of the disbelievers"
  9,33,"He is the One Who has sent His Messenger with ňĻtrueňļ guidance and the religion of truth, making it prevail over all others, even to the dismay of the polytheists"
  9,34,"O believers! Indeed, many rabbis and monks consume people‚Äôs wealth wrongfully and hinder ňĻothersňļ from the Way of God. Give good news of a painful torment to those who hoard gold and silver and do not spend it in God‚Äôs cause"
  9,35,"The Day ňĻwill comeňļ when their treasure will be heated up in the Fire of Hell, and their foreheads, sides, and backs branded with it. ňĻIt will be said to them,ňļ ‚ÄúThis is the treasure you hoarded for yourselves. Now taste what you hoarded!‚ÄĚ"
  9,36,"Indeed, the number of months ordained by God is twelve‚ÄĒin God‚Äôs Record¬†since the day He created the heavens and the earth‚ÄĒof which four are sacred. That is the Right Way. So do not wrong one another during these months. And together fight the polytheists as they fight against you together. And know that God is with those mindful ňĻof Himňļ"
  9,37,"Reallocating the sanctity of ňĻtheseňļ months¬†is an increase in disbelief, by which the disbelievers are led ňĻfarňļ astray. They adjust the sanctity one year and uphold it in another, only to maintain the number of months sanctified by God, violating the very months God has made sacred. Their evil deeds have been made appealing to them. And God does not guide the disbelieving people"
  9,38,"O believers! What is the matter with you that when you are asked to march forth in the cause of God, you cling firmly to ňĻyourňļ land?¬†Do you prefer the life of this world over the Hereafter? The enjoyment of this worldly life is insignificant compared to that of the Hereafter"
  9,39,"If you do not march forth, He will afflict you with a painful torment and replace you with other people. You are not harming Him in the least. And God is Most Capable of everything"
  9,40,"ňĻIt does not matterňļ if you ňĻbelieversňļ do not support him, for God did in fact support him when the disbelievers drove him out ňĻof Meccaňļ and he was only one of two. While they both were in the cave, he reassured his companion,¬†‚ÄúDo not worry; God is certainly with us.‚ÄĚ So God sent down His serenity upon the Prophet, supported him with forces you ňĻbelieversňļ did not see, and made the word of the disbelievers lowest, while the Word of God is supreme. And God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  9,41,"ňĻO believers!ňļ March forth whether it is easy or difficult for you, and strive with your wealth and your lives in the cause of God. That is best for you, if only you knew"
  9,42,"Had the gain been within reach and the journey shorter, they would have followed you, but the distance seemed too long for them. And they will swear by God, ‚ÄúHad we been able, we would have certainly joined you.‚ÄĚ They are ruining themselves. And God knows that they are surely lying"
  9,43,May God pardon you ňĻO Prophetňļ! Why did you give them permission ňĻto stay behindňļ before those who told the truth were distinguished from those who were lying
  9,44,Those who believe in God and the Last Day do not ask for exemption from striving with their wealth and their lives. And God has perfect knowledge of those who are mindful ňĻof Himňļ
  9,45,"No one would ask for exemption except those who have no faith in God or the Last Day, and whose hearts are in doubt, so they are torn by their doubts"
  9,46,"Had they ňĻreallyňļ intended to march forth, they would have made preparations for it. But God disliked that they should go, so He let them lag behind, and it was said ňĻto themňļ, ‚ÄúStay with those ňĻhelplessňļ who remain behind.‚ÄĚ"
  9,47,"Had they gone forth with you ňĻbelieversňļ, they would have been nothing but trouble for you, and would have scrambled around, seeking to spread discord in your midst. And some of you would have eagerly listened to them. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of the wrongdoers"
  9,48,"They had already sought to spread discord before¬†and devised every ňĻpossibleňļ plot against you ňĻO Prophetňļ, until the truth came and God‚Äôs Will prevailed‚ÄĒmuch to their dismay"
  9,49,"There are some of them who say, ‚ÄúExempt me and do not expose me to temptation.‚ÄĚ¬†They have already fallen into temptation. And Hell will surely engulf the disbelievers"
  9,50,"If a blessing befalls you ňĻO Prophetňļ, they grieve, but if a disaster befalls you, they say, ‚ÄúWe took our precaution in advance,‚ÄĚ and turn away, rejoicing"
  9,51,"Say, ‚ÄúNothing will ever befall us except what God has destined for us. He is our Protector.‚ÄĚ So in God let the believers put their trust"
  9,52,"Say, ‚ÄúAre you awaiting anything to befall us except one of the two best things: ňĻvictory or martyrdomňļ? But¬†We are awaiting God to afflict you with torment either from Him or at our hands. So keep waiting! We too are waiting with you.‚ÄĚ"
  9,53,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúňĻWhether youňļ donate willingly or unwillingly, it will never be accepted from you, for you have been a rebellious people.‚ÄĚ"
  9,54,"And what prevented their donations from being accepted is that they have lost faith in God and His Messenger, they never come to prayer except half-heartedly, and they never donate except resentfully"
  9,55,"So let neither their wealth nor children impress you ňĻO Prophetňļ. God only intends to torment them through these things in this worldly life, then their souls will depart while they are disbelievers"
  9,56,"They swear by God that they are part of you, but they are not. They only say so out of fear"
  9,57,"If only they could find a refuge, or a cave, or any hiding-place, they would rush headlong towards it"
  9,58,"There are some of them who are critical of your distribution of alms ňĻO Prophetňļ. If they are given some of it they are pleased, but if not they are enraged"
  9,59,"If only they had been content with what God and His Messenger had given them and said, ‚ÄúGod is sufficient for us! God will grant us out of His bounty, and so will His Messenger. To God ňĻaloneňļ we turn with hope.‚ÄĚ"
  9,60,"Alms-tax is only for the poor and the needy, for those employed to administer it, for those whose hearts are attracted ňĻto the faithňļ, for ňĻfreeingňļ slaves, for those in debt, for God‚Äôs cause, and for ňĻneedyňļ travellers. ňĻThis isňļ an obligation from God. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  9,61,"And there are others who hurt the Prophet by saying, ‚ÄúHe listens to anyone.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúHe listens to what is best for you. He believes in God, has faith in the believers, and is a mercy for those who believe among you.‚ÄĚ Those who hurt God‚Äôs Messenger will suffer a painful punishment"
  9,62,"They swear by God to you ňĻbelieversňļ in order to please you, while it is the pleasure of God and His Messenger they should seek, if they are ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  9,63,Do they not know that whoever opposes God and His Messenger will be in the Fire of Hell forever? That is the ultimate disgrace
  9,64,"The hypocrites fear that a s√Ľrah¬†should be revealed about them, exposing what is in their hearts. Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúKeep mocking! God will definitely bring to light what you fear.‚ÄĚ"
  9,65,"If you question them, they will certainly say, ‚ÄúWe were only talking idly and joking around.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúWas it God, His revelations, and His Messenger that you ridiculed?‚ÄĚ"
  9,66,"Make no excuses! You have lost faith after your belief. If We pardon a group of you,¬†We will punish others for their wickedness"
  9,67,"The hypocrites, both men and women, are all alike: they encourage what is evil, forbid what is good, and withhold ňĻwhat is inňļ their hands. They neglected God, so He neglected them. Surely the hypocrites are the rebellious"
  9,68,"God has promised the hypocrites, both men and women, and the disbelievers an everlasting stay in the Fire of Hell‚ÄĒit is sufficient for them. God has condemned them, and they will suffer a never-ending punishment"
  9,69,"ňĻYou hypocrites areňļ like those ňĻdisbelieversňļ before you. They were far superior to you in might and more abundant in wealth and children. They enjoyed their share in this life. You have enjoyed your share, just as they did. And you have engaged in idle talk, just as they did. Their deeds have become void in this world and the Hereafter. And it is they who are the ňĻtrueňļ losers"
  9,70,"Have they not received the stories of those ňĻdestroyedňļ before them: the people of Noah, ‚Äô√ād, and Tham√Ľd, the people of Abraham, the residents of Midian, and the overturned cities ňĻof Lotňļ?¬†Their messengers came to them with clear proofs. God would have never wronged them, but it was they who wronged themselves"
  9,71,"The believers, both men and women, are guardians of one another. They encourage good and forbid evil, establish prayer and pay alms-tax, and obey God and His Messenger. It is they who will be shown God‚Äôs mercy. Surely God is Almighty, All-Wise"
  9,72,"God has promised the believers, both men and women, Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there forever, and splendid homes in the Gardens of Eternity, and‚ÄĒabove all‚ÄĒthe pleasure of God. That is ňĻtrulyňļ the ultimate triumph"
  9,73,"O Prophet! Struggle against the disbelievers and the hypocrites, and be firm with them. Hell will be their home. What an evil destination"
  9,74,"They swear by God that they never said anything ňĻblasphemousňļ, while they did in fact utter a blasphemy, lost faith after accepting Islam, and plotted what they could not carry out.¬†It is only through resentment that they pay God and His Messenger back for enriching them out of His bounty! If they repent, it will be better for them. But if they turn away, God will torment them with a painful punishment in this world and the Hereafter, and they will have no one on earth to protect or help them"
  9,75,"And there are some who had made a vow to God: ‚ÄúIf He gives us from His bounty, we will surely spend in charity and be of the righteous.‚ÄĚ"
  9,76,"But when He gave them out of His bounty, they withheld it and turned away indifferently"
  9,77,"So He caused hypocrisy to plague their hearts until the Day they will meet Him, for breaking their promise to God and for their lies"
  9,78,"Do they not know that God ňĻfullyňļ knows their ňĻevilňļ thoughts and secret talks, and that God is the Knower of all unseen"
  9,79,"ňĻThere areňļ those who slander ňĻsome ofňļ the believers for donating liberally and mock others for giving only the little they can afford. God will throw their mockery back at them, and they will suffer a painful punishment"
  9,80,"ňĻIt does not matterňļ whether you ňĻO Prophetňļ pray for them to be forgiven or not. Even if you pray for their forgiveness seventy times, God will never forgive them. That is because they have lost faith in God and His Messenger. And God does not guide the rebellious people"
  9,81,"Those ňĻhypocritesňļ who remained behind rejoiced for doing so in defiance of the Messenger of God and hated ňĻthe prospect ofňļ striving with their wealth and their lives in the cause of God. They said ňĻto one anotherňļ, ‚ÄúDo not march forth in the heat.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúThe Fire of Hell is far hotter!‚ÄĚ If only they could comprehend"
  9,82,So let them laugh a little‚ÄĒthey will weep much as a reward for what they have committed
  9,83,"If God returns you ňĻO Prophetňļ to a group of them and they ask to go forth with you, say, ‚ÄúYou will not ever go forth or fight an enemy along with me. You preferred to stay behind the first time, so stay with those ňĻhelplessňļ who remain behind.‚ÄĚ"
  9,84,"And do not ever offer ňĻfuneralňļ prayers for any of their dead, nor stand by their grave ňĻat burialňļ, for they have lost faith in God and His Messenger and died rebellious"
  9,85,"And let neither their wealth nor children impress you ňĻO Prophetňļ. God only intends to torment them through these things in this world, and ňĻthenňļ their souls will depart while they are disbelievers"
  9,86,"Whenever a s√Ľrah¬†is revealed stating, ‚ÄúBelieve in God and struggle along with His Messenger,‚ÄĚ the rich among them would ask to be exempt, saying, ‚ÄúLeave us with those who remain behind.‚ÄĚ"
  9,87,"They preferred to stay behind with the helpless, and their hearts have been sealed so they do not comprehend"
  9,88,"But the Messenger and the believers with him strived with their wealth and their lives. They will have all the best, and it is they who will be successful"
  9,89,"God has prepared for them Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there forever. That is the ultimate triumph"
  9,90,"Some nomadic Arabs ňĻalsoňļ came with excuses, seeking exemption. And those who were untrue to God and His Messenger remained behind ňĻwith no excuseňļ. The unfaithful among them will be afflicted with a painful punishment"
  9,91,"There is no blame on the weak, the sick, or those lacking the means ňĻif they stay behindňļ, as long as they are true to God and His Messenger. There is no blame on the good-doers. And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  9,92,"Nor ňĻis there any blame onňļ those who came to you ňĻO Prophetňļ for mounts, then when you said, ‚ÄúI can find no mounts for you,‚ÄĚ they left with eyes overflowing with tears out of grief that they had nothing to contribute"
  9,93,"Blame is only on those who seek exemption from you although they have the means. They preferred to stay behind with the helpless, and God has sealed their hearts so they do not realize ňĻthe consequencesňļ"
  9,94,"They will make excuses to you ňĻbelieversňļ when you return to them. Say, ‚ÄúMake no excuses, ňĻforňļ we will not believe you. God has already informed us about your ňĻtrueňļ state ňĻof faithňļ. Your ňĻfutureňļ deeds will be observed by God and His Messenger as well. And you will be returned to the Knower of the seen and unseen, then He will inform you of what you used to do.‚ÄĚ"
  9,95,"When you return, they will swear to you by God so that you may leave them alone. So leave them alone‚ÄĒthey are truly evil. Hell will be their home as a reward for what they have committed"
  9,96,"They will swear to you in order to please you. And even if you are pleased with them, God will never be pleased with the rebellious people"
  9,97,"The nomadic Arabs ňĻaround Medinaňļ are far worse in disbelief and hypocrisy, and less likely to know the laws revealed by God to His Messenger. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  9,98,"And among the nomads are those who consider what they donate to be a loss and await your misfortune. May ill-fortune befall them! And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  9,99,"However, among the nomadic Arabs are those who believe in God and the Last Day, and consider what they donate as a means of coming closer to God and ňĻreceivingňļ the prayers of the Messenger. It will certainly bring them closer. God will admit them into His mercy. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  9,100,"As for the foremost‚ÄĒthe first of the Emigrants¬†and the Helpers‚ÄĒand those who follow them in goodness, God is pleased with them and they are pleased with Him. And He has prepared for them Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there for ever and ever. That is the ultimate triumph"
  9,101,"Some of the nomads around you ňĻbelieversňļ are hypocrites, as are some of the people of Medina. They have mastered hypocrisy. They are not known to you ňĻO Prophetňļ; they are known to Us. We will punish them twice ňĻin this worldňļ,¬†then they will be brought back ňĻto their Lordňļ for a tremendous punishment"
  9,102,"Some others have confessed their wrongdoing: they have mixed goodness with evil.¬†It is right to hope that God will turn to them in mercy. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  9,103,"Take from their wealth ňĻO Prophetňļ charity to purify and bless them, and pray for them‚ÄĒsurely your prayer is a source of comfort for them. And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  9,104,"Do they not know that God alone accepts the repentance of His servants and receives ňĻtheirňļ charity, and that God alone is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  9,105,"Tell ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúDo as you will. Your deeds will be observed by God, His Messenger, and the believers. And you will be returned to the Knower of the seen and unseen, then He will inform you of what you used to do.‚ÄĚ"
  9,106,"And some others are left for God‚Äôs decision, either to punish them or turn to them in mercy.¬†And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  9,107,"There are also those ňĻhypocritesňļ who set up a mosque ňĻonlyňļ to cause harm, promote disbelief, divide the believers, and as a base for those who had previously fought against God and His Messenger.¬†They will definitely swear, ‚ÄúWe intended nothing but good,‚ÄĚ but God bears witness that they are surely liars"
  9,108,"Do not ňĻO Prophetňļ ever pray in it. Certainly, a mosque founded on righteousness from the first day is more worthy of your prayers. In it are men who love to be purified.¬†And God loves those who purify themselves"
  9,109,"Which is better: those who laid the foundation of their building on the fear and pleasure of God, or those who did so on the edge of a crumbling cliff that tumbled down with them into the Fire of Hell? And God does not guide the wrongdoing people"
  9,110,"The building which they erected will never cease to fuel hypocrisy in their hearts until their hearts are torn apart. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  9,111,"God has indeed purchased from the believers their lives and wealth in exchange for Paradise. They fight in the cause of God and kill or are killed. This is a true promise binding on Him in the Torah, the Gospel, and the Quran. And whose promise is truer than God‚Äôs? So rejoice in the exchange you have made with Him. That is ňĻtrulyňļ the ultimate triumph"
  9,112,"ňĻIt is the believersňļ who repent, who are devoted to worship, who praise ňĻtheir Lordňļ, who fast, who bow down and prostrate themselves, who encourage good and forbid evil, and who observe the limits set by God. And give good news to the believers"
  9,113,"It is not ňĻproperňļ for the Prophet and the believers to seek forgiveness for the polytheists, even if they were close relatives, after it has become clear to the believers that they are bound for the Hellfire"
  9,114,"As for Abraham‚Äôs prayer for his father‚Äôs forgiveness, it was only in fulfilment of a promise he had made to him. But when it became clear to Abraham that his father was an enemy of God, he broke ties with him.¬†Abraham was truly tender-hearted, forbearing"
  9,115,"God would never consider a people deviant after He has guided them, until He makes clear to them what they must avoid. Surely God has ňĻfullňļ knowledge of everything"
  9,116,"Indeed, to God ňĻaloneňļ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth. He gives life and causes death. And besides God you have no guardian or helper"
  9,117,"God has certainly turned in mercy to the Prophet¬†as well as the Emigrants and the Helpers who stood by him in the time of hardship, after the hearts of a group of them had almost faltered. He then accepted their repentance. Surely He is Ever Gracious and Most Merciful to them"
  9,118,"And ňĻGod has also turned in mercy toňļ the three who had remained behind, ňĻwhose guilt distressed themňļ until the earth, despite its vastness, seemed to close in on them, and their souls were torn in anguish. They knew there was no refuge from God except in Him. Then He turned to them in mercy so that they might repent. Surely God ňĻaloneňļ is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful"
  9,119,O believers! Be mindful of God and be with the truthful
  9,120,"It was not ňĻproperňļ for the people of Medina and the nomadic Arabs around them to avoid marching with the Messenger of God or to prefer their own lives above his. That is because whenever they suffer from thirst, fatigue, or hunger in the cause of God; or tread on a territory, unnerving the disbelievers; or inflict any loss on an enemy‚ÄĒit is written to their credit as a good deed. Surely God never discounts the reward of the good-doers"
  9,121,"And whenever they make a donation, small or large, or cross a valley ňĻin God‚Äôs causeňļ‚ÄĒit is written to their credit, so that God may grant them the best reward for what they used to do"
  9,122,"ňĻHowever,ňļ it is not necessary for the believers to march forth all at once. Only a party from each group should march forth, leaving the rest to gain religious knowledge then enlighten their people when they return to them, so that they ňĻtooňļ may beware ňĻof evilňļ"
  9,123,O believers! Fight the disbelievers around you and let them find firmness in you. And know that God is with those mindful ňĻof Himňļ
  9,124,"Whenever a s√Ľrah¬†is revealed, some of them ask ňĻmockinglyňļ, ‚ÄúWhich of you has this increased in faith?‚ÄĚ As for the believers, it has increased them in faith and they rejoice"
  9,125,"But as for those with sickness in their hearts,¬†it has increased them only in wickedness upon their wickedness, and they die as disbelievers"
  9,126,Do they not see that they are tried once or twice every year?¬†Yet they neither repent nor do they learn a lesson
  9,127,"Whenever a s√Ľrah¬†is revealed, they look at one another, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúIs anyone watching you?‚ÄĚ Then they slip away. ňĻIt isňļ God ňĻWhoňļ has turned their hearts away because they are a people who do not comprehend"
  9,128,"There certainly has come to you a messenger from among yourselves. He is concerned by your suffering, anxious for your well-being, and gracious and merciful to the believers"
  9,129,"But if they turn away, then say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod is sufficient for me. There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. In Him I put my trust. And He is the Lord of the Mighty Throne.‚ÄĚ"
  10,1,"Alif-L√£m-Ra. These are the verses of the Book, rich in wisdom"
  10,2,"Is it astonishing to people that We have sent revelation to a man from among themselves, ňĻinstructing him,ňļ ‚ÄúWarn humanity and give good news to the believers that they will have an honourable status with their Lord.‚ÄĚ? Yet the disbelievers said, ‚ÄúIndeed, this ňĻmanňļ is clearly a magician!‚ÄĚ"
  10,3,"Surely your Lord is God Who created the heavens and the earth in six Days,¬†then established Himself on the Throne, conducting every affair. None can intercede except by His permission. That is God‚ÄĒyour Lord, so worship Him ňĻaloneňļ. Will you not then be mindful"
  10,4,"To Him is your return all together. God‚Äôs promise is ňĻalwaysňļ true. Indeed, He originates the creation then resurrects it so that He may justly reward those who believe and do good. But those who disbelieve will have a boiling drink and a painful punishment for their disbelief"
  10,5,"He is the One Who made the sun a radiant source and the moon a reflected light, with precisely ordained phases, so that you may know the number of years and calculation ňĻof timeňļ. God did not create all this except for a purpose. He makes the signs clear for people of knowledge"
  10,6,"Surely in the alternation of the day and the night, and in all that God has created in the heavens and the earth, there are truly signs for those mindful ňĻof Himňļ"
  10,7,"Indeed, those who do not expect to meet Us, being pleased and content with this worldly life, and who are heedless of Our signs"
  10,8,they will have the Fire as a home because of what they have committed
  10,9,"Surely those who believe and do good, their Lord will guide them ňĻto Paradiseňļ through their faith, rivers will flow under their feet in the Gardens of Bliss"
  10,10,"in which their prayer will be, ‚ÄúGlory be to You, O God!‚ÄĚ and their greeting will be, ‚ÄúPeace!‚ÄĚ and their closing prayer will be, ‚ÄúAll praise is for God‚ÄĒLord of all worlds!‚ÄĚ"
  10,11,"If God were to hasten evil for people¬†as they wish to hasten good, they would have certainly been doomed. But We leave those who do not expect to meet Us to wander blindly in their defiance"
  10,12,"Whenever someone is touched by hardship, they cry out to Us, whether lying on their side, sitting, or standing. But when We relieve their hardship, they return to their old ways as if they had never cried to Us to remove any hardship! This is how the misdeeds of the transgressors have been made appealing to them"
  10,13,"We surely destroyed ňĻotherňļ peoples before you when they did wrong, and their messengers came to them with clear proofs but they would not believe! This is how We reward the wicked people"
  10,14,Then We made you their successors in the land to see how you would act
  10,15,"When Our clear revelations are recited to them, those who do not expect to meet Us say ňĻto the Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúBring us a different Quran or make some changes in it.‚ÄĚ Say ňĻto themňļ, ‚ÄúIt is not for me to change it on my own. I only follow what is revealed to me. I fear, if I were to disobey my Lord, the punishment of a tremendous Day.‚ÄĚ"
  10,16,"Say, ‚ÄúHad God willed, I would not have recited it to you, nor would He have made it known to you. I had lived my whole life among you before this ňĻrevelationňļ. Do you not understand?‚ÄĚ"
  10,17,"Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against God or deny His revelations? Indeed, the wicked will never succeed"
  10,18,"They worship besides God others who can neither harm nor benefit them, and say, ‚ÄúThese are our intercessors with God.‚ÄĚ Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúAre you informing God of something He does not know in the heavens or the earth? Glorified and Exalted is He above what they associate ňĻwith Himňļ!‚ÄĚ"
  10,19,"Humanity was once nothing but a single community ňĻof believersňļ, but then they differed.¬†Had it not been for a prior decree from your Lord,¬†their differences would have been settled ňĻat onceňļ"
  10,20,"They ask, ‚ÄúWhy has no ňĻotherňļ sign been sent down to him from his Lord?‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúňĻThe knowledge ofňļ the unseen is with God alone. So wait! I too am waiting with you.‚ÄĚ"
  10,21,"When We give people a taste of mercy after being afflicted with a hardship, they swiftly devise plots against Our revelations! Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod is swifter in devising ňĻpunishmentňļ. Surely Our messenger-angels record whatever you devise.‚ÄĚ"
  10,22,"He is the One Who enables you to travel through land and sea. And it so happens that you are on ships, sailing with a favourable wind, to the passengers‚Äô delight. Suddenly, the ships are overcome by a gale wind and those on board are overwhelmed by waves from every side, and they assume they are doomed. They cry out to God ňĻaloneňļ in sincere devotion, ‚ÄúIf You save us from this, we will certainly be grateful.‚ÄĚ"
  10,23,"But as soon as He rescues them, they transgress in the land unjustly. O humanity! Your transgression is only against your own souls. ňĻThere is onlyňļ brief enjoyment in this worldly life, then to Us is your return, and then We will inform you of what you used to do"
  10,24,"The life of this world is just like rain We send down from the sky, producing a mixture of plants which humans and animals consume. Then just as the earth looks its best, perfectly beautified, and its people think they have full control over it, there comes to it Our command by night or by day, so We mow it down as if it never flourished yesterday! This is how We make the signs clear for people who reflect"
  10,25,And God invites ňĻallňļ to the Home of Peace and guides whoever He wills to the Straight Path
  10,26,Those who do good will have the finest reward¬†and ňĻevenňļ more.¬†Neither gloom nor disgrace will cover their faces. It is they who will be the residents of Paradise. They will be there forever
  10,27,"As for those who commit evil, the reward of an evil deed is its equivalent. Humiliation will cover them‚ÄĒwith no one to protect them from God‚ÄĒas if their faces were covered with patches of the night‚Äôs deep darkness. It is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever"
  10,28,"ňĻConsiderňļ the Day We will gather them all together then say to those who associated others ňĻwith God in worshipňļ, ‚ÄúStay in your places‚ÄĒyou and your associate-gods.‚ÄĚ We will separate them from each other, and their associate-gods will say, ‚ÄúIt was not us that you worshipped"
  10,29,God is sufficient as a Witness between each of us that we were totally unaware of your worship.‚ÄĚ
  10,30,Then and there every soul will face ňĻthe consequences ofňļ what it had done. They all will be returned to God‚ÄĒtheir True Master. And whatever ňĻgodsňļ they fabricated will fail them
  10,31,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúWho provides for you from heaven and earth? Who owns ňĻyourňļ hearing and sight? Who brings forth the living from the dead and the dead from the living? And who conducts every affair?‚ÄĚ They will ňĻsurelyňļ say, ‚ÄúGod.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúWill you not then fear ňĻHimňļ"
  10,32,That is God‚ÄĒyour True Lord. So what is beyond the truth except falsehood? How can you then be turned away?‚ÄĚ
  10,33,And so your Lord‚Äôs decree has been proven true against the rebellious‚ÄĒthat they will never believe
  10,34,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúCan any of your associate-gods originate creation and then resurrect it?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúňĻOnlyňļ God originates creation and then resurrects it. How can you then be deluded ňĻfrom the truthňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  10,35,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúCan any of your associate-gods guide to the truth?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúňĻOnlyňļ God guides to the truth.‚ÄĚ Who then is more worthy to be followed: the One Who guides to the truth or those who cannot find the way unless guided? What is the matter with you? How do you judge"
  10,36,Most of them follow nothing but ňĻinheritedňļ assumptions. ňĻAndňļ surely assumptions can in no way replace the truth. God is indeed All-Knowing of what they do
  10,37,"It is not ňĻpossibleňļ for this Quran to have been produced by anyone other than God. In fact, it is a confirmation of what came before, and an explanation of the Scripture. It is, without a doubt, from the Lord of all worlds"
  10,38,"Or do they claim, ‚ÄúHe¬†made it up!‚ÄĚ? Tell them ňĻO Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúProduce one s√Ľrah¬†like it then, and seek help from whoever you can‚ÄĒother than God‚ÄĒif what you say is true!‚ÄĚ"
  10,39,"In fact, they ňĻhastilyňļ rejected the Book without comprehending it and before the fulfilment of its warnings. Similarly, those before them were in denial. See then what was the end of the wrongdoers"
  10,40,Some of them will ňĻeventuallyňļ believe in it; others will not. And your Lord knows best the corruptors
  10,41,"If they deny you, then say, ‚ÄúMy deeds are mine and your deeds are yours. You are free of what I do and I am free of what you do!‚ÄĚ"
  10,42,"Some of them listen to what you say, but can you make the deaf hear even though they do not understand"
  10,43,"And some of them look at you, but can you guide the blind even though they cannot see"
  10,44,"Indeed, God does not wrong people in the least, but it is people who wrong themselves"
  10,45,"On the Day He will gather them, it will be as if they had not stayed ňĻin the worldňļ except for an hour of a day,¬†ňĻas though they were onlyňļ getting to know one another. Lost indeed will be those who denied the meeting with God, and were not ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  10,46,"Whether We show you ňĻO Prophetňļ some of what We threaten them with, or cause you to die ňĻbefore thatňļ, to Us is their return and God is a Witness over what they do"
  10,47,"And for every community there is a messenger. After their messenger has come,¬†judgment is passed on them in all fairness, and they are not wronged"
  10,48,"They ask ňĻthe believersňļ, ‚ÄúWhen will this threat come to pass if what you say is true?‚ÄĚ"
  10,49,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúI have no power to benefit or protect myself, except by the Will of God.‚ÄĚ For each community there is an appointed term. When their time arrives, they cannot delay it for a moment, nor could they advance it"
  10,50,"Tell them ňĻO Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúImagine if His torment were to overcome you by night or day‚ÄĒdo the wicked realize what they are ňĻreallyňļ asking Him to hasten"
  10,51,Will you believe in it only after it has overtaken you? Now? But you always wanted to hasten it!‚ÄĚ
  10,52,"Then the wrongdoers will be told, ‚ÄúTaste the torment of eternity! Are you not rewarded except for what you used to commit?‚ÄĚ"
  10,53,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúIs this true?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúYes, by my Lord! Most certainly it is true! And you will have no escape.‚ÄĚ"
  10,54,"If every wrongdoer were to possess everything in the world, they would surely ransom themselves with it. They will hide ňĻtheirňļ remorse when they see the torment. And they will be judged in all fairness, and none will be wronged"
  10,55,"Surely to God belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth. Surely God‚Äôs promise is ňĻalwaysňļ true, but most of them do not know"
  10,56,"He ňĻis the One Whoňļ gives life and causes death, and to Him you will ňĻallňļ be returned"
  10,57,"O humanity! Indeed, there has come to you a warning from your Lord, a cure for what is in the hearts, a guide, and a mercy for the believers"
  10,58,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIn God‚Äôs grace and mercy let them rejoice. That is far better than whatever ňĻwealthňļ they amass.‚ÄĚ"
  10,59,"Ask ňĻthe pagans, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúHave you seen that which God has sent down for you as a provision, of which you have made some lawful and some unlawful?‚ÄĚ¬†Say, ‚ÄúHas God given you authorization, or are you fabricating lies against God?‚ÄĚ"
  10,60,"What do those who fabricate lies against God expect on Judgment Day? Surely God is ever Bountiful to humanity,¬†but most of them are ungrateful"
  10,61,"There is no activity you may be engaged in ňĻO Prophetňļ or portion of the Quran you may be reciting, nor any deed you ňĻallňļ may be doing except that We are a Witness over you while doing it. Not ňĻevenňļ an atom‚Äôs weight is hidden from your Lord on earth or in heaven; nor anything smaller or larger than that, but is ňĻwrittenňļ in a perfect Record"
  10,62,"There will certainly be no fear for the close servants of God, nor will they grieve"
  10,63,ňĻThey areňļ those who are faithful and are mindful ňĻof Himňļ
  10,64,For them is good news in this worldly life and the Hereafter. There is no change in the promise of God. That is ňĻtrulyňļ the ultimate triumph
  10,65,"Do not let their words grieve you ňĻO Prophetňļ. Surely all honour and power belongs to God. He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  10,66,Certainly to God ňĻaloneňļ belong all those in the heavens and all those on the earth. And what do those who associate others with God really follow? They follow nothing but assumptions and do nothing but lie
  10,67,He is the One Who has made the night for you to rest in and the day bright. Surely in this are signs for people who listen
  10,68,"They¬†say, ‚ÄúGod has offspring.‚ÄĚ¬†Glory be to Him! He is the Self-Sufficient. To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. You have no proof of this! Do you say about God what you do not know"
  10,69,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIndeed, those who fabricate lies against God will never succeed.‚ÄĚ"
  10,70,"ňĻIt is onlyňļ a brief enjoyment in this world, then to Us is their return, then We will make them taste the severe punishment for their disbelief"
  10,71,"Relate to them ňĻO Prophetňļ the story of Noah when he said to his people, ‚ÄúO my People! If my presence and my reminders to you of God‚Äôs signs are unbearable to you, then ňĻknow thatňļ I have put my trust in God. So devise a plot along with your associate-gods‚ÄĒand you do not have to be secretive about your plot‚ÄĒthen carry it out against me without delay"
  10,72,"And if you turn away, ňĻrememberňļ I have never demanded a reward from you ňĻfor delivering the messageňļ. My reward is only from God. And I have been commanded to be one of those who submit ňĻto Godňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  10,73,"But they still rejected him, so We saved him and those with him in the Ark and made them successors, and drowned those who rejected Our signs. See then what was the end of those who had been warned"
  10,74,Then after him We sent ňĻotherňļ messengers to their ňĻownňļ people and they came to them with clear proofs. But they would not believe in what they had rejected before. This is how We seal the hearts of the transgressors
  10,75,Then after these ňĻmessengersňļ We sent Moses and Aaron to Pharaoh and his chiefs with Our signs. But they behaved arrogantly and were a wicked people
  10,76,"When the truth came to them from Us, they said, ‚ÄúThis is certainly pure magic!‚ÄĚ"
  10,77,"Moses responded, ‚ÄúIs this what you say about the truth when it has come to you? Is this magic? Magicians will never succeed.‚ÄĚ"
  10,78,"They argued, ‚ÄúHave you come to turn us away from the faith of our forefathers so that the two of you may become supreme in the land? We will never believe in you!‚ÄĚ"
  10,79,"Pharaoh demanded, ‚ÄúBring me every skilled magician.‚ÄĚ"
  10,80,"When the magicians came, Moses said to them, ‚ÄúCast whatever you wish to cast!‚ÄĚ"
  10,81,"When they did, Moses said, ‚ÄúWhat you have produced is mere magic, God will surely make it useless, for God certainly does not set right the work of the corruptors"
  10,82,And God establishes the truth by His Words‚ÄĒeven to the dismay of the wicked.‚ÄĚ
  10,83,"But no one believed in Moses except a few youths of his people, while fearing that Pharaoh and their own chiefs might persecute them. And certainly Pharaoh was a tyrant in the land, and he was truly a transgressor"
  10,84,"Moses said, ‚ÄúO my people! If you do believe in God and submit ňĻto His Willňļ, then put your trust in Him.‚ÄĚ"
  10,85,"They replied, ‚ÄúIn God we trust. Our Lord! Do not subject us to the persecution of the oppressive people"
  10,86,and deliver us by Your mercy from the disbelieving people.‚ÄĚ
  10,87,"We revealed to Moses and his brother, ‚ÄúAppoint houses for your people in Egypt. Turn these houses into places of worship, establish prayer, and give good news to the believers!‚ÄĚ"
  10,88,"Moses prayed, ‚ÄúOur Lord! You have granted Pharaoh and his chiefs luxuries and riches in this worldly life, ňĻwhich they abusedňļ to lead people astray from Your Way! Our Lord, destroy their riches and harden their hearts so that they will not believe until they see the painful punishment.‚ÄĚ"
  10,89,"God responded ňĻto Moses and Aaronňļ,¬†‚ÄúYour prayer is answered! So be steadfast and do not follow the way of those who do not know.‚ÄĚ"
  10,90,"We brought the Children of Israel across the sea. Then Pharaoh and his soldiers pursued them unjustly and oppressively. But as Pharaoh was drowning, he cried out, ‚ÄúI believe that there is no god except that in whom the Children of Israel believe, and I am ňĻnowňļ one of those who submit.‚ÄĚ"
  10,91,"ňĻHe was told,ňļ ‚ÄúNow ňĻyou believeňļ? But you always disobeyed and were one of the corruptors"
  10,92,Today We will preserve your corpse so that you may become an example¬†for those who come after you. And surely most people are heedless of Our examples!‚ÄĚ
  10,93,"Indeed, We settled the Children of Israel in a blessed land,¬†and granted them good, lawful provisions. They did not differ until knowledge came to them.¬†Surely your Lord will judge between them on the Day of Judgment regarding their differences"
  10,94,"If you ňĻO Prophetňļ are in doubt about ňĻthese storiesňļ that We have revealed to you, then ask those who read the Scripture before you. The truth has certainly come to you from your Lord, so do not be one of those who doubt"
  10,95,and do not be one of those who deny God‚Äôs signs or you will be one of the losers
  10,96,"Indeed, those against whom God‚Äôs decree ňĻof tormentňļ is justified will not believe‚ÄĒ"
  10,97,even if every sign were to come to them‚ÄĒuntil they see the painful punishment
  10,98,"If only there had been a society which believed ňĻbefore seeing the tormentňļ and, therefore, benefited from its belief, like the people of Jonah.¬†When they believed, We lifted from them the torment of disgrace in this world and allowed them enjoyment for a while"
  10,99,"Had your Lord so willed ňĻO Prophetňļ, all ňĻpeopleňļ on earth would have certainly believed, every single one of them! Would you then force people to become believers"
  10,100,"It is not for any soul to believe except by God‚Äôs leave, and He will bring His wrath upon those who are unmindful"
  10,101,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúConsider all that is in the heavens and the earth!‚ÄĚ Yet neither signs nor warners are of any benefit to those who refuse to believe"
  10,102,"Are they waiting for ňĻanythingňļ except the same torments that befell those before them? Say, ‚ÄúKeep waiting then! I too am waiting with you.‚ÄĚ"
  10,103,Then We saved Our messengers and those who believed. For it is Our duty to save the believers
  10,104,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO humanity! If you are in doubt of my faith, then ňĻknow thatňļ I do not worship those ňĻidolsňļ you worship instead of God. But I worship God, Who has the power to cause your death. And I have been commanded, ‚ÄėBe one of the believers,‚Äô"
  10,105,"and, ‚ÄėBe steadfast in faith in all uprightness, and do not be one of the polytheists,‚Äô"
  10,106,"and ‚ÄėDo not invoke, instead of God, what can neither benefit nor harm you‚ÄĒfor if you do, then you will certainly be one of the wrongdoers,‚Äô"
  10,107,"and ‚ÄėIf God touches you with harm, none can undo it except Him. And if He intends good for you, none can withhold His bounty. He grants it to whoever He wills of His servants. And He is the All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  10,108,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO humanity! The truth has surely come to you from your Lord. So whoever chooses to be guided, it is only for their own good. And whoever chooses to stray, it is only to their own loss. And I am not a keeper over you.‚ÄĚ"
  10,109,"And follow what is revealed to you, and be patient until God passes His judgment. For He is the Best of Judges"
  11,1,"Alif-L√£m-Ra. ňĻThis isňļ a Book whose verses are well perfected and then fully explained. ňĻIt isňļ from the One ňĻWho isňļ All-Wise, All-Aware"
  11,2,"ňĻTell them, O Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWorship none but God. Surely I am a warner and deliverer of good news to you from Him"
  11,3,"And seek your Lord‚Äôs forgiveness and turn to Him in repentance. He will grant you a good provision for an appointed term and graciously reward the doers of good. But if you turn away, then I truly fear for you the torment of a formidable Day"
  11,4,To God is your return. And He is Most Capable of everything.‚ÄĚ
  11,5,"Indeed, they¬†enfold ňĻwhat is inňļ their hearts, ňĻtryingňļ to hide it from Him! But even when they cover themselves with their clothes, He knows what they conceal and what they reveal. Surely He knows best what is ňĻhiddenňļ in the heart"
  11,6,There is no moving creature on earth whose provision is not guaranteed by God. And He knows where it lives and where it is laid to rest. All is ňĻwrittenňļ in a perfect Record
  11,7,"He is the One Who created the heavens and the earth in six Days‚ÄĒand His Throne was upon the waters‚ÄĒin order to test which of you is best in deeds. And if you ňĻO Prophetňļ say, ‚ÄúSurely you will ňĻallňļ be raised up after death,‚ÄĚ the disbelievers will certainly say, ‚ÄúThat is nothing but pure magic!‚ÄĚ"
  11,8,"And if We delay their punishment until an appointed time, they will definitely say, ‚ÄúWhat is holding it back?‚ÄĚ Indeed, on the Day it overtakes them, it will not be averted from them, and they will be overwhelmed by what they used to ridicule"
  11,9,"If We give people a taste of Our mercy then take it away from them, they become utterly desperate, ungrateful"
  11,10,"But if We give them a taste of prosperity after being touched with adversity, they say, ‚ÄúMy ills are gone,‚ÄĚ and become totally prideful and boastful"
  11,11,except those who patiently endure and do good. It is they who will have forgiveness and a mighty reward
  11,12,"Perhaps you ňĻO Prophetňļ may wish to give up some of what is revealed to you and may be distressed by it because they say, ‚ÄúIf only a treasure had been sent down to him, or an angel had come with him!‚ÄĚ You are only a warner, and God is the Trustee of All Affairs"
  11,13,"Or do they say, ‚ÄúHe¬†has fabricated this ňĻQuranňļ!‚ÄĚ? Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúProduce ten fabricated s√Ľrahs like it and seek help from whoever you can‚ÄĒother than God‚ÄĒif what you say is true!‚ÄĚ"
  11,14,"But if your helpers fail you, then know that it has been revealed with the knowledge of God, and that there is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him! Will you ňĻnotňļ then submit ňĻto Godňļ"
  11,15,"Whoever desires ňĻonlyňļ this worldly life and its luxuries, We will pay them in full for their deeds in this life‚ÄĒnothing will be left out"
  11,16,It is they who will have nothing in the Hereafter except the Fire. Their efforts in this life will be fruitless and their deeds will be useless
  11,17,"ňĻCan these people be compared toňļ those ňĻbelieversňļ who stand on clear proof from their Lord, backed by ňĻthe Quran asňļ a witness from Him, and preceded by the Book of Moses ňĻwhich was revealedňļ as a guide and mercy? It is those ňĻbelieversňļ who have faith in it. But whoever from the ňĻdisbelievingňļ groups¬†rejects it, the Fire will be their destiny. So do not be in doubt of it. It is certainly the truth from your Lord, but most people do not believe"
  11,18,"Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against God? They will be brought before their Lord, and the witnesses¬†will say, ‚ÄúThese are the ones who lied against their Lord.‚ÄĚ Surely God‚Äôs condemnation is upon the wrongdoers"
  11,19,"who hinder ňĻothersňļ from God‚Äôs Path, striving to make it ňĻappearňļ crooked, and disbelieve in the Hereafter"
  11,20,"They will never frustrate God on earth, and they will have no protector besides God. Their punishment will be multiplied, for they failed to hear or see ňĻthe truthňļ"
  11,21,"It is they who have ruined themselves, and whatever ňĻgodsňļ they fabricated will fail them"
  11,22,"Without a doubt, they will be the worst losers in the Hereafter"
  11,23,"Surely those who believe, do good, and humble themselves before their Lord will be the residents of Paradise. They will be there forever"
  11,24,"The example of these two parties is that of the blind and the deaf, compared to the seeing and the hearing. Can the two be equal? Will you not then be mindful"
  11,25,"Surely We sent Noah to his people. ňĻHe said,ňļ ‚ÄúIndeed, I am sent to you with a clear warning"
  11,26,that you should worship none but God. I truly fear for you the torment of a painful Day.‚ÄĚ
  11,27,"The disbelieving chiefs of his people said, ‚ÄúWe see you only as a human being like ourselves, and we see that no one follows you except the lowliest among us, who do so ňĻhastilyňļ without thinking.¬†We do not see anything that makes ňĻall ofňļ you any better than us. In fact, we think you are liars.‚ÄĚ"
  11,28,"He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Consider if I stand on a clear proof from my Lord and He has blessed me with a mercy from Himself,¬†which you fail to see. Should we ňĻthenňļ force it on you against your will"
  11,29,"O my people! I do not ask you for a payment for this ňĻmessageňļ. My reward is only from God. And I will never dismiss the believers, for they will surely meet their Lord. But I can see that you are a people acting ignorantly"
  11,30,O my people! Who would protect me from God if I were to dismiss them? Will you not then be mindful
  11,31,"I do not say to you that I possess God‚Äôs treasuries or know the unseen, nor do I claim to be an angel, nor do I say that God will never grant goodness to those you look down upon. God knows best what is ňĻhiddenňļ within them. ňĻIf I did,ňļ then I would truly be one of the wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  11,32,"They protested, ‚ÄúO Noah! You have argued with us far too much, so bring upon us what you threaten us with, if what you say is true.‚ÄĚ"
  11,33,"He responded, ‚ÄúIt is God Who can bring it upon you if He wills, and then you will have no escape"
  11,34,"My advice will not benefit you‚ÄĒno matter how hard I try‚ÄĒif God wills ňĻforňļ you to stray. He is your Lord, and to Him you will ňĻallňļ be returned.‚ÄĚ"
  11,35,"Or do they say, ‚ÄúHe¬†has fabricated this ňĻQuranňļ!‚ÄĚ? Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIf I have done so, then I bear the burden of that sin! But I am free from your sinful accusation.‚ÄĚ"
  11,36,"And it was revealed to Noah, ‚ÄúNone of your people will believe except those who already have. So do not be distressed by what they have been doing"
  11,37,"And build the Ark under Our ňĻwatchfulňļ Eyes and directions, and do not plead with Me for those who have done wrong, for they will surely be drowned.‚ÄĚ"
  11,38,"So he began to build the Ark, and whenever some of the chiefs of his people passed by, they mocked him. He said, ‚ÄúIf you laugh at us, we will ňĻsoonňļ laugh at you similarly"
  11,39,You will soon come to know who will be visited by a humiliating torment ňĻin this lifeňļ and overwhelmed by an everlasting punishment ňĻin the nextňļ.‚ÄĚ
  11,40,"And when Our command came and the oven burst ňĻwith waterňļ,¬†We said ňĻto Noahňļ, ‚ÄúTake into the Ark a pair from every species along with your family‚ÄĒexcept those against whom the decree ňĻto drownňļ has already been passed‚ÄĒand those who believe.‚ÄĚ But none believed with him except for a few"
  11,41,"And he said, ‚ÄúBoard it! In the Name of God it will sail and cast anchor. Surely my Lord is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  11,42,"And ňĻsoňļ the Ark sailed with them through waves like mountains. Noah called out to his son, who stood apart, ‚ÄúO my dear son! Come aboard with us and do not be with the disbelievers.‚ÄĚ"
  11,43,"He replied, ‚ÄúI will take refuge on a mountain, which will protect me from the water.‚ÄĚ Noah cried, ‚ÄúToday no one is protected from God‚Äôs decree except those to whom He shows mercy!‚ÄĚ And the waves came between them, and his son was among the drowned"
  11,44,"And it was said, ‚ÄúO earth! Swallow up your water. And O sky! Withhold ňĻyour rainňļ.‚ÄĚ The floodwater receded and the decree was carried out. The Ark rested on Mount Judi, and it was said, ‚ÄúAway with the wrongdoing people!‚ÄĚ"
  11,45,"Noah called out to his Lord, saying, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Certainly my son is ňĻalsoňļ of my family, Your promise is surely true, and You are the most just of all judges!‚ÄĚ"
  11,46,"God replied, ‚ÄúO Noah! He is certainly not of your family‚ÄĒhe was entirely of unrighteous conduct. So do not ask Me about what you have no knowledge of! I warn you so you do not fall into ignorance.‚ÄĚ"
  11,47,"Noah pleaded, ‚ÄúMy Lord, I seek refuge in You from asking You about what I have no knowledge of, and unless You forgive me and have mercy on me, I will be one of the losers.‚ÄĚ"
  11,48,"It was said, ‚ÄúO Noah! Disembark with Our peace and blessings on you and some of the descendants of those with you. As for the others, We will allow them ňĻa briefňļ enjoyment, then they will be touched with a painful punishment from Us.‚ÄĚ"
  11,49,"This is one of the stories of the unseen, which we reveal to you ňĻO Prophetňļ. Neither you nor your people knew it before this. So be patient! Surely the ultimate outcome belongs ňĻonlyňļ to the righteous"
  11,50,"And to the people of ‚Äô√ād We sent their brother H√Ľd. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God. You have no god other than Him. You do nothing but fabricate lies ňĻagainst Godňļ"
  11,51,O my people! I do not ask you for any reward for this ňĻmessageňļ. My reward is only from the One Who created me. Will you not then understand
  11,52,"And O my people! Seek your Lord‚Äôs forgiveness and turn to Him in repentance. He will shower you with rain in abundance, and add strength to your strength. So do not turn away, persisting in wickedness.‚ÄĚ"
  11,53,"They argued, ‚ÄúO H√Ľd! You have not given us any clear proof, and we will never abandon our gods upon your word, nor will we believe in you"
  11,54,"All we can say is that some of our gods have possessed you with evil.‚ÄĚ He said, ‚ÄúI call God to witness, and you too bear witness, that I ňĻtotallyňļ reject whatever you associate"
  11,55,with Him ňĻin worshipňļ. So let all of you plot against me without delay
  11,56,I have put my trust in God‚ÄĒmy Lord and your Lord. There is no living creature that is not completely under His control.¬†Surely my Lord‚Äôs Way is perfect justice
  11,57,"But if you turn away, I have already delivered to you what I have been sent with. My Lord will replace you with others. You are not harming Him in the least. Indeed, my Lord is a ňĻvigilantňļ Keeper over all things.‚ÄĚ"
  11,58,"When Our command came, We rescued H√Ľd and those who believed with him by a mercy from Us, saving them from a harsh torment"
  11,59,"That was ‚Äô√ād. They denied the signs of their Lord, disobeyed His messengers, and followed the command of every stubborn tyrant"
  11,60,"They were followed by a curse in this world, as they will be on the Day of Judgment. Surely ‚Äô√ād denied their Lord. So away with ‚Äô√ād, the people of H√Ľd"
  11,61,"And to the people of Tham√Ľd We sent their brother ŠĻĘ√ĘliŠł•. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God. You have no god other than Him. He ňĻis the One Whoňļ produced you from the earth and settled you on it. So seek His forgiveness and turn to Him in repentance. Surely my Lord is Ever Near, All-Responsive ňĻto prayersňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  11,62,"They argued, ‚ÄúO ŠĻĘ√ĘliŠł•! We truly had high hopes in you before this.¬†How dare you forbid us to worship what our forefathers had worshipped? We are certainly in alarming doubt about what you are inviting us to.‚ÄĚ"
  11,63,"He responded, ‚ÄúO my people! Consider if I stand on a clear proof from my Lord and He has blessed me with a mercy from Him. Who could help me against God if I were to disobey Him? You would only contribute to my doom"
  11,64,"And O my people! This she-camel of God is a sign for you.¬†So leave her to graze ňĻfreelyňļ on God‚Äôs earth and do her no harm, or a swift punishment will overtake you!‚ÄĚ"
  11,65,"But they killed her, so he warned ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúYou have ňĻonlyňļ three ňĻmoreňļ days to enjoy life in your homes‚ÄĒthis is an unfailing promise!‚ÄĚ"
  11,66,"When Our command came, We saved ŠĻĘ√ĘliŠł• and those who believed with him by a mercy from Us and spared them the disgrace of that Day. Surely your Lord ňĻaloneňļ is the All-Powerful, Almighty"
  11,67,"And the ňĻmightyňļ blast overtook the wrongdoers, so they fell lifeless in their homes"
  11,68,"as if they had never lived there. Surely Tham√Ľd denied their Lord, so away with Tham√Ľd"
  11,69,"And surely Our messenger-angels came to Abraham with good news ňĻof a sonňļ. They greeted ňĻhim withňļ, ‚ÄúPeace!‚ÄĚ And he replied, ‚ÄúPeace ňĻbe upon youňļ!‚ÄĚ Then it was not long before he brought ňĻthemňļ a ňĻfat,ňļ roasted calf"
  11,70,"And when he saw that their hands did not reach for the food, he became suspicious and fearful of them.¬†They reassured ňĻhimňļ, ‚ÄúDo not be afraid! We are ňĻangelsňļ sent ňĻonlyňļ against the people of Lot.‚ÄĚ"
  11,71,"And his wife was standing by, so she laughed,¬†then We gave her good news of ňĻthe birth ofňļ Isaac, and, after him, Jacob"
  11,72,"She wondered, ‚ÄúOh, my! How can I have a child in this old age, and my husband here is an old man? This is truly an astonishing thing!‚ÄĚ"
  11,73,"They responded, ‚ÄúAre you astonished by God‚Äôs decree? May God‚Äôs mercy and blessings be upon you, O people of this house. Indeed, He is Praiseworthy, All-Glorious.‚ÄĚ"
  11,74,"Then after the fear had left Abraham, and the good news had reached him, he began to plead with Us for the people of Lot"
  11,75,"Truly, Abraham was forbearing, tender-hearted, and ever turning ňĻto his Lordňļ"
  11,76,"ňĻThe angels said,ňļ ‚ÄúO Abraham! Plead no more! Your Lord‚Äôs decree has already come, and they will certainly be afflicted with a punishment that cannot be averted!‚ÄĚ"
  11,77,"When Our messenger-angels came to Lot, he was distressed and worried by their arrival.¬†He said, ‚ÄúThis is a terrible day.‚ÄĚ"
  11,78,"And ňĻthe men ofňļ his people‚ÄĒwho were used to shameful deeds‚ÄĒcame to him rushing. He pleaded, ‚ÄúO my people! Here are my daughters¬†ňĻfor marriageňļ‚ÄĒthey are pure for you. So fear God, and do not humiliate me by disrespecting my guests. Is there not ňĻevenňļ a single right-minded man among you?‚ÄĚ"
  11,79,"They argued, ‚ÄúYou certainly know that we have no need for your daughters. You already know what we desire!‚ÄĚ"
  11,80,"He responded, ‚ÄúIf only I had the strength ňĻto resist youňļ or could rely on a strong supporter.‚ÄĚ"
  11,81,"The angels said, ‚ÄúO Lot! We are the messengers of your Lord. They will never reach you. So travel with your family in the dark of night, and do not let any of you look back, except your wife. She will certainly suffer the fate of the others.¬†Their appointed time is the morning. Is the morning not near?‚ÄĚ"
  11,82,"When Our command came, We turned the cities upside down and rained down on them clustered stones of baked clay"
  11,83,marked by your Lord ňĻO Prophetňļ. And these stones are not far from the ňĻpaganňļ wrongdoers
  11,84,"And to the people of Midian We sent their brother Shu‚Äôaib. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God. You have no god other than Him. And do not give short measure and weight. I do see you in prosperity now, but I truly fear for you the torment of an overwhelming Day"
  11,85,"O my people! Give full measure and weigh with justice. Do not defraud people of their property, nor go about spreading corruption in the land"
  11,86,What is left ňĻas a lawful gainňļ by God is far better for you if you are ňĻtrulyňļ believers. And I am not a keeper over you.‚ÄĚ
  11,87,"They asked ňĻsarcasticallyňļ, ‚ÄúO Shu‚Äôaib! Does your prayer command you that we should abandon what our forefathers worshipped or give up managing our wealth as we please? Indeed, you are such a tolerant, sensible man!‚ÄĚ"
  11,88,"He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Consider if I stand on a clear proof from my Lord and He has blessed me with a good provision from Him. I do not want to do what I am forbidding you from. I only intend reform to the best of my ability. My success comes only through God. In Him I trust and to Him I turn"
  11,89,"O my people! Do not let your opposition to me lead you to a fate similar to that of the people of Noah, or H√Ľd, or ŠĻĘ√ĘliŠł•. And the people of Lot are not far from you"
  11,90,"So seek your Lord‚Äôs forgiveness and turn to Him in repentance. Surely my Lord is Most Merciful, All-Loving.‚ÄĚ"
  11,91,"They threatened, ‚ÄúO Shu‚Äôaib! We do not comprehend much of what you say, and surely we see you powerless among us. Were it not for your clan, we would have certainly stoned you, for you are nothing to us.‚ÄĚ"
  11,92,"He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Do you have more regard for my clan than for God, turning your back on Him entirely? Surely my Lord is Fully Aware of what you do"
  11,93,"O my people! Persist in your ways, for I ňĻtooňļ will persist in mine. You will soon come to know who will be visited by a humiliating torment and is a liar! And watch! I too am watching with you!‚ÄĚ"
  11,94,"When Our command came, We saved Shu‚Äôaib and those who believed with him by a mercy from Us. And the ňĻmightyňļ blast overtook the wrongdoers, so they fell lifeless in their homes"
  11,95,as if they had never lived there. So away with Midian as it was with Tham√Ľd
  11,96,"Indeed, We sent Moses with Our signs and compelling proof"
  11,97,"to Pharaoh and his chiefs, but they followed the command of Pharaoh, and Pharaoh‚Äôs command was not well guided"
  11,98,He will be before his people on the Day of Judgment and will lead them into the Fire. What an evil place to be led into
  11,99,They were followed by a curse in this ňĻlifeňļ and ňĻwill receive anotherňļ on the Day of Judgment. What an evil gift to receive
  11,100,"These are accounts, We relate to you ňĻO Prophetňļ, of the ňĻdestroyedňļ cities. Some are still standing ňĻbarrenňļ, while others have been mowed down"
  11,101,"We did not wrong them, rather they wronged themselves. The gods they invoked beside God were of no help at all when the command of your Lord came, and only contributed to their ruin"
  11,102,"Such is the ňĻcrushingňļ grip of your Lord when He seizes the societies entrenched in wrongdoing. Indeed, His grip is ňĻterriblyňļ painful and severe"
  11,103,Surely in this is a sign for those who fear the torment of the Hereafter. That is a Day for which humanity will be gathered and a Day ňĻthat will beňļ witnessed ňĻby allňļ
  11,104,We only delay it for a fixed term
  11,105,"When that Day arrives, no one will dare speak except with His permission. Some of them will be miserable, others joyful"
  11,106,"As for those bound for misery, they will be in the Fire, where they will be sighing and gasping"
  11,107,"staying there forever, as long as the heavens and the earth will endure, except what your Lord wills.¬†Surely your Lord does what He intends"
  11,108,"And as for those destined to joy, they will be in Paradise, staying there forever, as long as the heavens and the earth will endure, except what your Lord wills‚ÄĒa ňĻgenerousňļ giving, without end"
  11,109,"So do not be in doubt ňĻO Prophetňļ about what those ňĻpagansňļ worship. They worship nothing except what their forefathers worshipped before ňĻthemňļ. And We will certainly give them their share ňĻof punishmentňļ in full, without any reduction"
  11,110,"Indeed, We had given Moses the Scripture, but differences arose regarding it. Had it not been for a prior decree from your Lord,¬†their differences would have been settled ňĻat onceňļ. They are truly in alarming doubt about it"
  11,111,And surely your Lord will fully pay all for their deeds. He is certainly All-Aware of what they do
  11,112,"So be steadfast as you are commanded ňĻO Prophetňļ, along with those who turn ňĻin submission to Godňļ with you. And do not transgress. Surely He is All-Seeing of what you ňĻbelieversňļ do"
  11,113,"And do not be inclined to the wrongdoers or you will be touched by the Fire. For then you would have no protectors other than God, nor would you be helped"
  11,114,Establish prayer ňĻO Prophetňļ at both ends of the day and in the early part of the night.¬†Surely good deeds wipe out evil deeds. That is a reminder for the mindful
  11,115,And be patient! Certainly God does not discount the reward of the good-doers
  11,116,"If only there had been among the ňĻdestroyedňļ peoples before you, ňĻO believers,ňļ virtuous individuals who forbade corruption in the land‚ÄĒother than the few We had saved ňĻfrom the tormentňļ. But the wrongdoers ňĻonlyňļ pursued their ňĻworldlyňļ pleasures, becoming wicked"
  11,117,And your Lord ňĻO Prophetňļ would never destroy a society unjustly while its people were acting rightly
  11,118,"Had your Lord so willed, He would have certainly made humanity one single community ňĻof believersňļ, but they will always ňĻchoose toňļ differ‚ÄĒ"
  11,119,"except those shown mercy by your Lord‚ÄĒand so He created them ňĻto choose freelyňļ. And so the Word of your Lord will be fulfilled: ‚ÄúI will surely fill up Hell with jinn and humans all together.‚ÄĚ"
  11,120,"And We relate to you ňĻO Prophetňļ the stories of the messengers to reassure your heart. And there has come to you in this ňĻs√Ľrahňļ the truth, a warning ňĻto the disbelieversňļ, and a reminder to the believers"
  11,121,"Say to those who disbelieve, ‚ÄúPersist in your ways; we will certainly persist in ours"
  11,122,And wait! Surely we ňĻtooňļ are waiting.‚ÄĚ
  11,123,To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs the knowledge of what is hidden in the heavens and the earth. And to Him all matters are returned. So worship Him and put your trust in Him. And your Lord is never unaware of what you do
  12,1,Alif-L√£m-Ra. These are the verses of the clear Book
  12,2,"Indeed, We have sent it down as an Arabic Quran¬†so that you may understand"
  12,3,"We relate to you ňĻO Prophetňļ the best of stories through Our revelation of this Quran, though before this you were totally unaware ňĻof themňļ"
  12,4,"ňĻRememberňļ when Joseph said to his father, ‚ÄúO my dear father! Indeed I dreamt of eleven stars, and the sun, and the moon‚ÄĒI saw them prostrating to me!‚ÄĚ"
  12,5,"He replied, ‚ÄúO my dear son! Do not relate your vision to your brothers, or they will devise a plot against you. Surely Satan is a sworn enemy to humankind"
  12,6,"And so will your Lord choose you ňĻO Josephňļ, and teach you the interpretation of dreams, and perfect His favour upon you and the descendants of Jacob‚ÄĒňĻjustňļ as He once perfected it upon your forefathers, Abraham and Isaac. Surely your Lord is All-Knowing, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  12,7,"Indeed, in the story of Joseph and his brothers there are lessons for all who ask"
  12,8,"ňĻRememberňļ when they said ňĻto one anotherňļ, ‚ÄúSurely Joseph and his brother ňĻBenjaminňļ are more beloved to our father than we, even though we are a group of so many.¬†Indeed, our father is clearly mistaken"
  12,9,"Kill Joseph or cast him out to some ňĻdistantňļ land so that our father‚Äôs attention will be only ours, then after that you may ňĻrepent andňļ become righteous people!‚ÄĚ"
  12,10,"One of them said, ‚ÄúDo not kill Joseph. But if you must do something, throw him into the bottom of a well so perhaps he may be picked up by some travellers.‚ÄĚ"
  12,11,"They said, ‚ÄúO our father! Why do you not trust us with Joseph, although we truly wish him well"
  12,12,Send him out with us tomorrow so that he may enjoy himself and play. And we will really watch over him.‚ÄĚ
  12,13,"He responded, ‚ÄúIt would truly sadden me if you took him away with you, and I fear that a wolf may devour him while you are negligent of him.‚ÄĚ"
  12,14,"They said, ‚ÄúIf a wolf were to devour him, despite our strong group, then we would certainly be losers!‚ÄĚ"
  12,15,"And so, when they took him away and decided to throw him into the bottom of the well, We inspired him: ‚ÄúňĻOne dayňļ you will remind them of this deed of theirs while they are unaware ňĻof who you areňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  12,16,"Then they returned to their father in the evening, weeping"
  12,17,"They cried, ‚ÄúOur father! We went racing and left Joseph with our belongings, and a wolf devoured him! But you will not believe us, no matter how truthful we are.‚ÄĚ"
  12,18,"And they brought his shirt, stained with false blood.¬†He responded, ‚ÄúNo! Your souls must have tempted you to do something ňĻevilňļ. So ňĻI can only endure withňļ beautiful patience!¬†It is God‚Äôs help that I seek to bear your claims.‚ÄĚ"
  12,19,"And there came some travellers, and they sent their water-boy who let down his bucket into the well. He cried out, ‚ÄúOh, what a great find! Here is a boy!‚ÄĚ And they took him secretly ňĻto be soldňļ as merchandise, but God is All-Knowing of what they did"
  12,20,"They ňĻlaterňļ sold him for a cheap price, just a few silver coins‚ÄĒonly wanting to get rid of him"
  12,21,"The man from Egypt¬†who bought him said to his wife, ‚ÄúTake good care of him, perhaps he may be useful to us or we may adopt him as a son.‚ÄĚ This is how We established Joseph in the land, so that We might teach him the interpretation of dreams. God‚Äôs Will always prevails, but most people do not know"
  12,22,"And when he reached maturity, We gave him wisdom and knowledge. This is how We reward the good-doers"
  12,23,"And the lady, in whose house he lived, tried to seduce him. She locked the doors ňĻfirmlyňļ and said, ‚ÄúCome to me!‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúGod is my refuge! It is ňĻnot right to betrayňļ my master, who has taken good care of me. Indeed, the wrongdoers never succeed.‚ÄĚ"
  12,24,"She advanced towards him, and he would have done likewise, had he not seen a sign from his Lord.¬†This is how We kept evil and indecency away from him, for he was truly one of Our chosen servants"
  12,25,"They raced for the door and she tore his shirt from the back, only to find her husband at the door. She cried, ‚ÄúWhat is the penalty for someone who tried to violate your wife, except imprisonment or a painful punishment?‚ÄĚ"
  12,26,"Joseph responded, ‚ÄúIt was she who tried to seduce me.‚ÄĚ And a witness from her own family testified: ‚ÄúIf his shirt is torn from the front, then she has told the truth and he is a liar"
  12,27,"But if it is torn from the back, then she has lied and he is truthful.‚ÄĚ"
  12,28,"So when her husband saw that Joseph‚Äôs shirt was torn from the back, he said ňĻto herňļ, ‚ÄúThis must be ňĻan exampleňļ of the cunning of you ňĻwomenňļ! Indeed, your cunning is so shrewd"
  12,29,O Joseph! Forget about this. And you ňĻO wifeňļ! Seek forgiveness for your sin.¬†It certainly has been your fault.‚ÄĚ
  12,30,"Some women of the city gossiped, ‚ÄúThe Chief Minister‚Äôs wife is trying to seduce her slave-boy. Love for him has plagued her heart. Indeed, we see that she is clearly mistaken.‚ÄĚ"
  12,31,"When she heard about their gossip,¬†she invited them and set a banquet for them. She gave each one a knife, then said ňĻto Josephňļ, ‚ÄúCome out before them.‚ÄĚ When they saw him, they were so stunned ňĻby his beautyňļ that they cut their hands,¬†and exclaimed, ‚ÄúGood God! This cannot be human; this must be a noble angel!‚ÄĚ"
  12,32,"She said, ‚ÄúThis is the one for whose love you criticized me! I did try to seduce him but he ňĻfirmlyňļ refused. And if he does not do what I order him to, he will certainly be imprisoned and ňĻfullyňļ disgraced.‚ÄĚ"
  12,33,"Joseph prayed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! I would rather be in jail than do what they invite me to. And if You do not turn their cunning away from me, I might yield to them and fall into ignorance.‚ÄĚ"
  12,34,"So his Lord responded to him, turning their cunning away from him. Surely He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  12,35,"And so it occurred to those in charge, despite seeing all the proofs ňĻof his innocenceňļ, that he should be imprisoned for a while"
  12,36,"And two other servants went to jail with Joseph. One of them said, ‚ÄúI dreamt I was pressing wine.‚ÄĚ The other said, ‚ÄúI dreamt I was carrying ňĻsomeňļ bread on my head, from which birds were eating.‚ÄĚ ňĻThen both said,ňļ ‚ÄúTell us their interpretation, for we surely see you as one of the good-doers.‚ÄĚ"
  12,37,"Joseph replied, ‚ÄúI can even tell you what kind of meal you will be served before you receive it. This ňĻknowledgeňļ is from what my Lord has taught me. I have shunned the faith of a people who disbelieve in God and deny the Hereafter"
  12,38,"I follow the faith of my fathers: Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. It is not ňĻrightňļ for us to associate anything with God ňĻin worshipňļ. This is part of God‚Äôs grace upon us and humanity, but most people are not grateful"
  12,39,"O my fellow-prisoners! Which is far better: many different lords or God‚ÄĒthe One, the Supreme"
  12,40,"Whatever ňĻidolsňļ you worship instead of Him are mere names which you and your forefathers have made up‚ÄĒa practice God has never authorized. It is only God Who decides. He has commanded that you worship none but Him. That is the upright faith, but most people do not know"
  12,41,"‚ÄúO my fellow-prisoners! ňĻThe firstňļ one of you will serve wine to his master, and the other will be crucified and the birds will eat from his head. The matter about which you inquired has been decided.‚ÄĚ"
  12,42,"Then he said to the one he knew would survive, ‚ÄúMention me in the presence of your master.‚ÄĚ But Satan made him forget to mention Joseph to his master, so he remained in prison for several years"
  12,43,"And ňĻone dayňļ the King¬†said, ‚ÄúI dreamt of seven fat cows eaten up by seven skinny ones; and seven green ears of grain and ňĻsevenňļ others dry. O chiefs! Tell me the meaning of my dream if you can interpret dreams.‚ÄĚ"
  12,44,"They replied, ‚ÄúThese are confused visions and we do not know the interpretation of such dreams.‚ÄĚ"
  12,45,"ňĻFinally,ňļ the surviving ex-prisoner remembered ňĻJosephňļ after a long time and said, ‚ÄúI will tell you its interpretation, so send me forth ňĻto Josephňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  12,46,"ňĻHe said,ňļ ‚ÄúJoseph, O man of truth! Interpret for us ňĻthe dream ofňļ seven fat cows eaten up by seven skinny ones; and seven green ears of grain and ňĻsevenňļ others dry, so that I may return to the people and let them know.‚ÄĚ"
  12,47,"Joseph replied, ‚ÄúYou will plant ňĻgrainňļ for seven consecutive years, leaving in the ear whatever you will harvest, except for the little you will eat"
  12,48,"Then after that will come seven years of great hardship which will consume whatever you have saved, except the little you will store ňĻfor seedňļ"
  12,49,Then after that will come a year in which people will receive abundant rain and they will press ňĻoil and wineňļ.‚ÄĚ
  12,50,"The King ňĻthenňļ said, ‚ÄúBring him to me.‚ÄĚ When the messenger came to him, Joseph said, ‚ÄúGo back to your master and ask him about the case of the women who cut their hands. Surely my Lord has ňĻfullňļ knowledge of their cunning.‚ÄĚ"
  12,51,"The King asked ňĻthe womenňļ, ‚ÄúWhat did you get when you tried to seduce Joseph?‚ÄĚ They replied, ‚ÄúGod forbid! We know nothing indecent about him.‚ÄĚ Then the Chief Minister‚Äôs wife admitted, ‚ÄúNow the truth has come to light. It was I who tried to seduce him, and he is surely truthful"
  12,52,"From this, Joseph should know that I did not speak dishonestly about him in his absence, for God certainly does not guide the scheming of the dishonest"
  12,53,"And I do not seek to free myself from blame, for indeed the soul is ever inclined to evil, except those shown mercy by my Lord. Surely my Lord is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  12,54,"The King said, ‚ÄúBring him to me. I will employ him exclusively in my service.‚ÄĚ And when Joseph spoke to him, the King said, ‚ÄúToday you are highly esteemed and fully trusted by us.‚ÄĚ"
  12,55,"Joseph proposed, ‚ÄúPut me in charge of the store-houses of the land, for I am truly reliable and adept.‚ÄĚ"
  12,56,"This is how We established Joseph in the land to settle wherever he pleased. We shower Our mercy on whoever We will, and We never discount the reward of the good-doers"
  12,57,And the reward of the Hereafter is far better for those who are faithful and are mindful ňĻof Godňļ
  12,58,And Joseph‚Äôs brothers came and entered his presence. He recognized them but they were unaware of who he really was
  12,59,"When he had provided them with their supplies, he demanded, ‚ÄúBring me your brother on your father‚Äôs side.¬†Do you not see that I give full measure and I am the best of hosts"
  12,60,"But if you do not bring him to me ňĻnext timeňļ, I will have no grain for you, nor will you ever come close to me again.‚ÄĚ"
  12,61,"They promised, ‚ÄúWe will try to convince his father to let him come. We will certainly do ňĻour bestňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  12,62,Joseph ordered his servants to put his brothers‚Äô money back into their saddlebags so that they would find it when they returned to their family and perhaps they would come back
  12,63,"When Joseph‚Äôs brothers returned to their father, they pleaded, ‚ÄúO our father! We have been denied ňĻfurtherňļ supplies. So send our brother with us so that we may receive our measure, and we will definitely watch over him.‚ÄĚ"
  12,64,"He responded, ‚ÄúShould I trust you with him as I once trusted you with his brother ňĻJosephňļ? But ňĻonlyňļ God is the best Protector, and He is the Most Merciful of the merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  12,65,"When they opened their bags, they discovered that their money had been returned to them. They argued, ‚ÄúO our father! What more can we ask for? Here is our money, fully returned to us. Now we can buy more food for our family. We will watch over our brother, and obtain an extra camel-load of grain. That load can be easily secured.‚ÄĚ"
  12,66,"Jacob insisted, ‚ÄúI will not send him with you until you give me a solemn oath by God that you will certainly bring him back to me, unless you are totally overpowered.‚ÄĚ Then after they had given him their oaths, he concluded, ‚ÄúGod is a Witness to what we have said.‚ÄĚ"
  12,67,"He then instructed ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúO my sons! Do not enter ňĻthe cityňļ all through one gate, but through separate gates.¬†I cannot help you against ňĻwhat is destined byňļ God in the least. It is only God Who decides. In Him I put my trust. And in Him let the faithful put their trust.‚ÄĚ"
  12,68,"Then when they entered as their father had instructed them, this did not help them against ňĻthe Will ofňļ God whatsoever. It was just a desire in Jacob‚Äôs heart which he satisfied. He was truly blessed with ňĻgreatňļ knowledge because of what We had taught him, but most people have no knowledge"
  12,69,"When they entered Joseph‚Äôs presence, he called his brother ňĻBenjaminňļ aside, and confided ňĻto himňļ, ‚ÄúI am indeed your brother ňĻJosephňļ! So do not feel distressed about what they have been doing.‚ÄĚ"
  12,70,"When Joseph had provided them with supplies, he slipped the royal cup into his brother‚Äôs bag. Then a herald cried, ‚ÄúO people of the caravan! You must be thieves!‚ÄĚ"
  12,71,"They asked, turning back, ‚ÄúWhat have you lost?‚ÄĚ"
  12,72,"The herald ňĻalong with the guardsňļ replied, ‚ÄúWe have lost the King‚Äôs measuring cup. And whoever brings it will be awarded a camel-load ňĻof grainňļ. I guarantee it.‚ÄĚ"
  12,73,"Joseph‚Äôs brothers replied, ‚ÄúBy God! You know well that we did not come to cause trouble in the land, nor are we thieves.‚ÄĚ"
  12,74,"Joseph‚Äôs men asked, ‚ÄúWhat should be the price for theft, if you are lying?‚ÄĚ"
  12,75,"Joseph‚Äôs brothers responded, ‚ÄúThe price will be ňĻthe enslavement ofňļ the one in whose bag the cup is found. That is how we punish the wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  12,76,"Joseph began searching their bags before that of his brother ňĻBenjaminňļ, then brought it out of Benjamin‚Äôs bag. This is how We inspired Joseph to plan. He could not have taken his brother under the King‚Äôs law, but God had so willed. We elevate in rank whoever We will. But above those ranking in knowledge is the One All-Knowing"
  12,77,"ňĻTo distance themselves,ňļ Joseph‚Äôs brothers argued, ‚ÄúIf he has stolen, so did his ňĻfullňļ brother before.‚ÄĚ¬†But Joseph suppressed his outrage‚ÄĒrevealing nothing to them‚ÄĒand said ňĻto himselfňļ, ‚ÄúYou are in such an evil position,¬†and God knows best ňĻthe truth ofňļ what you claim.‚ÄĚ"
  12,78,"They appealed, ‚ÄúO Chief Minister! He has a very old father, so take one of us instead. We surely see you as one of the good-doers.‚ÄĚ"
  12,79,"Joseph responded, ‚ÄúGod forbid that we should take other than the one with whom we found our property. Otherwise, we would surely be unjust.‚ÄĚ"
  12,80,"When they lost all hope in him, they spoke privately. The eldest of them said, ‚ÄúDo you not know that your father had taken a solemn oath by God from you, nor how you failed him regarding Joseph before? So I am not leaving this land until my father allows me to, or God decides for me. For He is the Best of Judges"
  12,81,"Return to your father and say, ‚ÄėO our father! Your son committed theft. We testify only to what we know. We could not guard against the unforeseen"
  12,82,Ask ňĻthe people ofňļ the land where we were and the caravan we travelled with. We are certainly telling the truth.‚Äô‚ÄĚ
  12,83,"He cried, ‚ÄúNo! Your souls must have tempted you to do something ňĻevilňļ. So ňĻI am left with nothing butňļ beautiful patience!¬†I trust God will return them all to me. Surely He ňĻaloneňļ is the All-Knowing, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  12,84,"He turned away from them, lamenting, ‚ÄúAlas, poor Joseph!‚ÄĚ And his eyes turned white out of the grief he suppressed"
  12,85,"They said, ‚ÄúBy God! You will not cease to remember Joseph until you lose your health or ňĻevenňļ your life.‚ÄĚ"
  12,86,"He replied, ‚ÄúI complain of my anguish and sorrow only to God, and I know from God what you do not know"
  12,87,"O my sons! Go and search ňĻdiligentlyňļ for Joseph and his brother. And do not lose hope in the mercy of God, for no one loses hope in God‚Äôs mercy except those with no faith.‚ÄĚ"
  12,88,"When they entered Joseph‚Äôs presence, they pleaded, ‚ÄúO Chief Minister! We and our family have been touched with hardship, and we have brought only a few worthless coins, but ňĻpleaseňļ give us our supplies in full and be charitable to us. Indeed, God rewards the charitable.‚ÄĚ"
  12,89,"He asked, ‚ÄúDo you remember what you did to Joseph and his brother in your ignorance?‚ÄĚ"
  12,90,"They replied ňĻin shockňļ, ‚ÄúAre you really Joseph?‚ÄĚ He said, ‚ÄúI am Joseph, and here is my brother ňĻBenjaminňļ! God has truly been gracious to us. Surely whoever is mindful ňĻof Godňļ and patient, then certainly God never discounts the reward of the good-doers.‚ÄĚ"
  12,91,"They admitted, ‚ÄúBy God! God has truly preferred you over us, and we have surely been sinful.‚ÄĚ"
  12,92,"Joseph said, ‚ÄúThere is no blame on you today. May God forgive you! He is the Most Merciful of the merciful"
  12,93,"Go with this shirt of mine and cast it over my father‚Äôs face, and he will regain his sight. Then come back to me with your whole family.‚ÄĚ"
  12,94,"When the caravan departed ňĻfrom Egyptňļ, their father said ňĻto those around himňļ, ‚ÄúYou may think I am senile, but I certainly sense the smell of Joseph.‚ÄĚ"
  12,95,"They replied, ‚ÄúBy God! You are definitely still in your old delusion.‚ÄĚ"
  12,96,"But when the bearer of the good news arrived, he cast the shirt over Jacob‚Äôs face, so he regained his sight. Jacob then said ňĻto his childrenňļ, ‚ÄúDid I not tell you that I truly know from God what you do not know?‚ÄĚ"
  12,97,"They begged, ‚ÄúO our father! Pray for the forgiveness of our sins. We have certainly been sinful.‚ÄĚ"
  12,98,"He said, ‚ÄúI will pray to my Lord for your forgiveness.¬†He ňĻaloneňļ is indeed the All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  12,99,"When they entered Joseph‚Äôs presence, he received his parents ňĻgraciouslyňļ and said, ‚ÄúEnter Egypt, God willing, in security.‚ÄĚ"
  12,100,"Then he raised his parents to the throne, and they all fell down in prostration to Joseph,¬†who then said, ‚ÄúO my dear father! This is the interpretation of my old dream. My Lord has made it come true. He was truly kind to me when He freed me from prison, and brought you all from the desert after Satan had ignited rivalry between me and my siblings.¬†Indeed my Lord is subtle in fulfilling what He wills. Surely He ňĻaloneňļ is the All-Knowing, All-Wise.‚ÄĚ"
  12,101,‚ÄúMy Lord! You have surely granted me authority and taught me the interpretation of dreams. ňĻOňļ Originator of the heavens and the earth! You are my Guardian in this world and the Hereafter. Allow me to die as one who submits¬†and join me with the righteous.‚ÄĚ
  12,102,"That is from the stories of the unseen which We reveal to you ňĻO Prophetňļ. You were not present when they ňĻallňļ¬†made up their minds, and when they plotted ňĻagainst Josephňļ"
  12,103,And most people will not believe‚ÄĒno matter how keen you are‚ÄĒ
  12,104,even though you are not asking them for a reward for this ňĻQuranňļ. It is only a reminder to the whole world
  12,105,How many signs in the heavens and the earth do they pass by with indifference
  12,106,And most of them do not believe in God without associating others with Him ňĻin worshipňļ
  12,107,"Do they feel secure that an overwhelming torment from God will not overtake them, or that the Hour will not take them by surprise when they least expect ňĻitňļ"
  12,108,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúThis is my way. I invite to God with insight‚ÄĒI and those who follow me. Glory be to God, and I am not one of the polytheists.‚ÄĚ"
  12,109,We only sent before you ňĻO Prophetňļ men inspired by Us from among the people of each society. Have the deniers not travelled through the land to see what was the end of those ňĻdestroyedňļ before them? And surely the ňĻeternalňļ Home of the Hereafter is far better for those mindful ňĻof Godňļ. Will you not then understand
  12,110,"And when the messengers despaired and their people thought the messengers had been denied help, Our help came to them ňĻat lastňļ. We then saved whoever We willed, and Our punishment is never averted from the wicked people"
  12,111,"In their stories there is truly a lesson for people of reason. This message cannot be a fabrication, rather ňĻit isňļ a confirmation of previous revelation, a detailed explanation of all things, a guide, and a mercy for people of faith"
  13,1,"Alif-L√£m-Mń©m-Ra. These are the verses of the Book. What has been revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ from your Lord is the truth, but most people do not believe"
  13,2,"It is God Who has raised the heavens without pillars‚ÄĒas you can see‚ÄĒthen established Himself on the Throne. He has subjected the sun and the moon, each orbiting for an appointed term. He conducts the whole affair. He makes the signs clear so that you may be certain of the meeting with your Lord"
  13,3,"And He is the One Who spread out the earth and placed firm mountains and rivers upon it, and created fruits of every kind in pairs.¬†He covers the day with night. Surely in this are signs for those who reflect"
  13,4,"And on the earth there are ňĻdifferentňļ neighbouring tracts, gardens of grapevines, ňĻvariousňļ crops, palm trees‚ÄĒsome stemming from the same root, others standing alone. They are all irrigated with the same water, yet We make some taste better than others. Surely in this are signs for those who understand"
  13,5,"ňĻNow,ňļ if anything should amaze you ňĻO Prophetňļ, then it is their question: ‚ÄúWhen we are reduced to dust, will we really be raised as a new creation?‚ÄĚ It is they who have disbelieved in their Lord. It is they who will have shackles around their necks. And it is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever"
  13,6,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ to hasten the torment rather than grace, though there have ňĻalreadyňļ been ňĻmanyňļ torments before them. Surely your Lord is full of forgiveness for people, despite their wrongdoing, and your Lord is truly severe in punishment"
  13,7,"The disbelievers say, ‚ÄúIf only a sign could be sent down to him from his Lord.‚ÄĚ You ňĻO Prophetňļ are only a warner. And every people had a guide"
  13,8,God knows what every female bears and what increases and decreases in the wombs.¬†And with Him everything is determined with precision
  13,9,"ňĻHe is theňļ Knower of the seen and the unseen‚ÄĒthe All-Great, Most Exalted"
  13,10,"It is the same ňĻto Himňļ whether any of you speaks secretly or openly, whether one hides in the darkness of night or goes about in broad daylight"
  13,11,"For each one there are successive angels before and behind, protecting them by God‚Äôs command. Indeed, God would never change a people‚Äôs state ňĻof favourňļ until they change their own state ňĻof faithňļ. And if it is God‚Äôs Will to torment a people, it can never be averted, nor can they find a protector other than Him"
  13,12,"He is the One Who shows you lightning, inspiring ňĻyou withňļ hope and fear,¬†and produces heavy clouds"
  13,13,"The thunder glorifies His praises, as do the angels in awe of Him. He sends thunderbolts, striking with them whoever He wills. Yet they dispute about God. And He is tremendous in might"
  13,14,"Calling upon Him ňĻaloneňļ is the truth. But those ňĻidolsňļ the pagans invoke besides Him ňĻcanňļ never respond to them in any way. ňĻIt isňļ just like someone who stretches out their hands to water, ňĻasking itňļ to reach their mouths, but it can never do so. The calls of the disbelievers are only in vain"
  13,15,"To God ňĻaloneňļ bow down ňĻin submissionňļ¬†all those in the heavens and the earth‚ÄĒwillingly or unwillingly‚ÄĒas do their shadows, morning and evening"
  13,16,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúWho is the Lord of the heavens and the earth?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúGod!‚ÄĚ Ask ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúWhy ňĻthenňļ have you taken besides Him lords who cannot even benefit or protect themselves?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúCan the blind and the sighted be equal? Or can darkness and light be equal?‚ÄĚ¬†Or have they associated with God partners who ňĻsupposedlyňļ produced a creation like His, leaving them confused between the two creations? Say, ‚ÄúGod is the Creator of all things, and He is the One, the Supreme.‚ÄĚ"
  13,17,"He sends down rain from the sky, causing the valleys to flow, each according to its capacity. The currents then carry along rising foam, similar to the slag produced from metal that people melt in the fire for ornaments or tools. This is how God compares truth to falsehood. The ňĻworthlessňļ residue is then cast away, but what benefits people remains on the earth. This is how God sets forth parables"
  13,18,"Those who respond to ňĻthe call ofňļ their Lord will have the finest reward. As for those who do not respond to Him, even if they were to possess everything in the world twice over, they would certainly offer it to ransom themselves. They will face strict judgment, and Hell will be their home. What an evil place to rest"
  13,19,Can the one who knows that your Lord‚Äôs revelation to you ňĻO Prophetňļ is the truth be like the one who is blind? None will be mindful ňĻof thisňļ except people of reason
  13,20,"ňĻThey areňļ those who honour God‚Äôs covenant, never breaking the pledge"
  13,21,"and those who maintain whatever ňĻtiesňļ God has ordered to be maintained, stand in awe of their Lord, and fear strict judgment"
  13,22,"And ňĻthey areňļ those who endure patiently, seeking their Lord‚Äôs pleasure,¬†establish prayer, donate from what We have provided for them‚ÄĒsecretly and openly‚ÄĒand respond to evil with good. It is they who will have the ultimate abode"
  13,23,"the Gardens of Eternity, which they will enter along with the righteous among their parents, spouses, and descendants. And the angels will enter upon them from every gate, ňĻsaying,ňļ"
  13,24,‚ÄúPeace be upon you for your perseverance. How excellent is the ultimate abode!‚ÄĚ
  13,25,"And those who violate God‚Äôs covenant after it has been affirmed, break whatever ňĻtiesňļ God has ordered to be maintained, and spread corruption in the land‚ÄĒit is they who will be condemned and will have the worst abode"
  13,26,"God gives abundant or limited provisions to whoever He wills. And the disbelievers become prideful of ňĻthe pleasures ofňļ this worldly life. But the life of this world, compared to the Hereafter, is nothing but a fleeting enjoyment"
  13,27,"The disbelievers say, ‚ÄúIf only a sign could be sent down to him from his Lord.‚ÄĚ¬†Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIndeed, God leaves to stray whoever He wills, and guides to Himself whoever turns to Him‚ÄĒ"
  13,28,those who believe and whose hearts find comfort in the remembrance of God. Surely in the remembrance of God do hearts find comfort
  13,29,"Those who believe and do good, for them will be bliss and an honourable destination.‚ÄĚ"
  13,30,"And so We have sent you ňĻO Prophetňļ to a community, like ňĻWe did withňļ earlier communities, so that you may recite to them what We have revealed to you. Yet they deny the Most Compassionate.¬†Say, ‚ÄúHe is my Lord! There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. In Him I put my trust, and to Him I turn ňĻin repentanceňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  13,31,"If there were a recitation that could cause mountains to move, or the earth to split, or the dead to speak, ňĻit would have been this Quranňļ. But all matters are by God‚Äôs Will. Have the believers not yet realized that had God willed, He could have guided all of humanity? And disasters will continue to afflict the disbelievers or strike close to their homes for their misdeeds, until God‚Äôs promise comes to pass. Surely God never fails in His promise"
  13,32,"Other messengers had already been ridiculed before you, but I delayed the disbelievers ňĻfor a whileňļ then seized them. And how ňĻhorribleňļ was My punishment"
  13,33,"Is ňĻthere any equal toňļ the Vigilant One Who knows what every soul commits? Yet the pagans have associated others with God ňĻin worshipňļ. Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúName them! Or do you ňĻmean toňļ inform Him of something He does not know on the earth? Or are these ňĻgodsňļ just empty words?‚ÄĚ In fact, the disbelievers‚Äô falsehood has been made so appealing to them that they have been turned away from the Path. And whoever God leaves to stray will be left with no guide"
  13,34,"For them is punishment in this worldly life, but the punishment of the Hereafter is truly far worse. And none can shield them from God"
  13,35,The description of the Paradise promised to the righteous is that under it rivers flow; eternal is its fruit as well as its shade. That is the ňĻultimateňļ outcome for the righteous. But the outcome for the disbelievers is the Fire
  13,36,"ňĻThe believers amongňļ those who were given the Scripture rejoice at what has been revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ, while some ňĻdisbelievingňļ factions deny a portion of it. Say, ‚ÄúI have only been commanded to worship God, associating none with Him ňĻin worshipňļ. To Him I invite ňĻallňļ, and to Him is my return.‚ÄĚ"
  13,37,"And so We have revealed it as an authority in Arabic. And if you were to follow their desires after ňĻallňļ the knowledge that has come to you, there would be none to protect or shield you from God"
  13,38,We have certainly sent messengers before you ňĻO Prophetňļ and blessed them with wives and offspring. It was not for any messenger to bring a sign without God‚Äôs permission. Every destined matter has a ňĻsetňļ time
  13,39,"God eliminates and confirms what He wills, and with Him is the Master Record"
  13,40,"Whether We show you ňĻO Prophetňļ some of what We threaten them with, or cause you to die ňĻbefore thatňļ, your duty is only to deliver ňĻthe messageňļ. Judgment is for Us"
  13,41,Do they not see that We gradually reduce their land from its borders? God decides‚ÄĒnone can reverse His decision. And He is swift in reckoning
  13,42,"Those ňĻdisbelieversňļ before them ňĻsecretlyňļ planned, but God has the ultimate plan. He knows what every soul commits. And the disbelievers will soon know who will have the ultimate outcome"
  13,43,"The disbelievers say, ‚ÄúYou ňĻMuŠł•ammadňļ are no messenger.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod is sufficient as a Witness between me and you, as is whoever has knowledge of the Scripture.‚ÄĚ"
  14,1,"Alif-L√£m-Ra. ňĻThis isňļ a Book which We have revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ so that you may lead people out of darkness and into light, by the Will of their Lord, to the Path of the Almighty, the Praiseworthy‚ÄĒ"
  14,2,"God, to Whom belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. And woe to the disbelievers because of a severe torment"
  14,3,"ňĻThey areňļ the ones who favour the life of this world over the Hereafter and hinder ňĻothersňļ from the Way of God, striving to make it ňĻappearňļ crooked. It is they who have gone far astray"
  14,4,"We have not sent a messenger except in the language of his people to clarify ňĻthe messageňļ for them. Then God leaves whoever He wills to stray and guides whoever He wills. And He is the Almighty, All-Wise"
  14,5,"Indeed, We sent Moses with Our signs, ňĻordering him,ňļ ‚ÄúLead your people out of darkness and into light, and remind them of God‚Äôs days ňĻof favourňļ.‚ÄĚ Surely in this are signs for whoever is steadfast, grateful"
  14,6,"ňĻConsiderňļ when Moses said to his people, ‚ÄúRemember God‚Äôs favour upon you when He rescued you from the people of Pharaoh, who afflicted you with dreadful torment‚ÄĒslaughtering your sons and keeping your women. That was a severe test from your Lord"
  14,7,"And ňĻrememberňļ when your Lord proclaimed, ‚ÄėIf you are grateful, I will certainly give you more. But if you are ungrateful, surely My punishment is severe.‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  14,8,"Moses added, ‚ÄúIf you along with everyone on earth were to be ungrateful, then ňĻknow thatňļ God is indeed Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy.‚ÄĚ"
  14,9,"Have you not ňĻalreadyňļ received the stories of those who were before you: the people of Noah, ‚Äô√ād, Tham√Ľd, and those after them? Only God knows how many they were. Their messengers came to them with clear proofs, but they put their hands over their mouths¬†and said, ‚ÄúWe totally reject what you have been sent with, and we are certainly in alarming doubt about what you are inviting us to.‚ÄĚ"
  14,10,"Their messengers asked ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúIs there any doubt about God, the Originator of the heavens and the earth? He is inviting you in order to forgive your sins, and delay your end until your appointed term.‚ÄĚ¬†They argued, ‚ÄúYou are no more than humans like us! You ňĻonlyňļ wish to turn us away from what our forefathers worshipped. So bring us some compelling proof.‚ÄĚ"
  14,11,"Their messengers said to them, ‚ÄúWe are ňĻindeedňļ only humans like you, but God favours whoever He chooses of His servants. It is not for us to bring you any proof without God‚Äôs permission. And in God let the believers put their trust"
  14,12,"Why should we not put our trust in God, when He has truly guided us to ňĻthe very best ofňļ ways? Indeed, we will patiently endure whatever harm you may cause us. And in God let the faithful put their trust.‚ÄĚ"
  14,13,"The disbelievers then threatened their messengers, ‚ÄúWe will certainly expel you from our land, unless you return to our faith.‚ÄĚ So their Lord revealed to them, ‚ÄúWe will surely destroy the wrongdoers"
  14,14,and make you reside in the land after them. This is for whoever is in awe of standing before Me and fears My warning.‚ÄĚ
  14,15,"And both sides called for judgment, so every stubborn tyrant was doomed"
  14,16,"Awaiting them is Hell, and they will be left to drink oozing pus"
  14,17,"which they will sip with difficulty, and can hardly swallow. Death will overwhelm them from every side, yet they will not ňĻbe able toňļ die. Awaiting them still is harsher torment"
  14,18,The parable of the deeds of those who disbelieve in their Lord is that of ashes fiercely blown away by wind on a stormy day. They will gain nothing from what they have earned. That is ňĻtrulyňļ the farthest one can stray
  14,19,"Have you not seen that God created the heavens and the earth for a reason? If He wills, He can eliminate you and produce a new creation"
  14,20,And that is not difficult for God ňĻat allňļ
  14,21,"They will all appear before God, and the lowly ňĻfollowersňļ will appeal to the arrogant ňĻleadersňļ, ‚ÄúWe were your ňĻdedicatedňļ followers, so will you ňĻthenňļ protect us from God‚Äôs torment in any way?‚ÄĚ They will reply, ‚ÄúHad God guided us, we would have guided you. ňĻNowňļ it is all the same for us whether we suffer patiently or impatiently, there is no escape for us.‚ÄĚ"
  14,22,"And Satan will say ňĻto his followersňļ after the judgment has been passed, ‚ÄúIndeed, God has made you a true promise.¬†I too made you a promise, but I failed you. I did not have any authority over you. I only called you, and you responded to me. So do not blame me; blame yourselves. I cannot save you, nor can you save me. Indeed, I denounce your previous association of me with God ňĻin loyaltyňļ. Surely the wrongdoers will suffer a painful punishment.‚ÄĚ"
  14,23,"Those who believe and do good will be admitted into Gardens, under which rivers flow‚ÄĒto stay there forever by the Will of their Lord‚ÄĒwhere they will be greeted with ‚ÄúPeace!‚ÄĚ"
  14,24,Do you not see how God compares a good word to a good tree? Its root is firm and its branches reach the sky
  14,25,"ňĻalwaysňļ yielding its fruit in every season by the Will of its Lord. This is how God sets forth parables for the people, so perhaps they will be mindful"
  14,26,"And the parable of an evil word is that of an evil tree, uprooted from the earth, having no stability"
  14,27,God makes the believers steadfast with the firm Word ňĻof faithňļ¬†in this worldly life and the Hereafter. And God leaves the wrongdoers to stray. For God does what He wills
  14,28,Have you not seen those ňĻdisbelieversňļ who meet God‚Äôs favours with ingratitude and lead their own people to their doom
  14,29,In Hell they will burn. What an evil place for settlement
  14,30,"They set up equals to God to mislead ňĻothersňļ from His Way. Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúEnjoy yourselves! Surely your destination is the Fire.‚ÄĚ"
  14,31,Tell My believing servants to establish prayer and donate from what We have provided for them‚ÄĒopenly and secretly‚ÄĒbefore the arrival of a Day in which there will be no ransom or friendly connections
  14,32,"It is God Who created the heavens and the earth and sends down rain from the sky, causing fruits to grow as a provision for you. He has subjected the ships for your service, sailing through the sea by His command, and has subjected the rivers for you"
  14,33,"He has ňĻalsoňļ subjected for you the sun and the moon, both constantly orbiting, and has subjected the day and night for you"
  14,34,"And He has granted you all that you asked Him for. If you tried to count God‚Äôs blessings, you would never be able to number them. Indeed humankind is truly unfair, ňĻtotallyňļ ungrateful"
  14,35,"ňĻRememberňļ when Abraham prayed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Make this city ňĻof Meccaňļ secure, and keep me and my children away from the worship of idols"
  14,36,"My Lord! They have caused many people to go astray. So whoever follows me is with me, and whoever disobeys me‚ÄĒthen surely You are ňĻstillňļ All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  14,37,"Our Lord! I have settled some of my offspring in a barren valley, near Your Sacred House, our Lord, so that they may establish prayer. So make the hearts of ňĻbelievingňļ people incline towards them and provide them with fruits, so perhaps they will be thankful"
  14,38,Our Lord! You certainly know what we conceal and what we reveal. Nothing on earth or in heaven is hidden from God
  14,39,All praise is for God who has blessed me with Ishmael and Isaac in my old age. My Lord is indeed the Hearer of ňĻallňļ prayers
  14,40,My Lord! Make me and those ňĻbelieversňļ of my descendants keep up prayer. Our Lord! Accept my prayers
  14,41,"Our Lord! Forgive me, my parents, and the believers on the Day when the judgment will come to pass.‚ÄĚ"
  14,42,Do not think ňĻO Prophetňļ that God is unaware of what the wrongdoers do. He only delays them until a Day when ňĻtheirňļ eyes will stare in horror‚ÄĒ
  14,43,"rushing forth, heads raised, never blinking, hearts void"
  14,44,"And warn the people of the Day when the punishment will overtake ňĻthe wicked amongňļ them, and the wrongdoers will cry, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Delay us for a little while. We will respond to Your call and follow the messengers!‚ÄĚ ňĻIt will be said,ňļ ‚ÄúDid you not swear before that you would never be removed ňĻto the next lifeňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  14,45,"You passed by the ruins of those ňĻdestroyed peoplesňļ who had wronged themselves.¬†It was made clear to you how We dealt with them, and We gave you ňĻmanyňļ examples"
  14,46,"They devised every plot, which was fully known to God, but their plotting was not enough to ňĻevenňļ overpower mountains ňĻlet alone Godňļ"
  14,47,"So do not think ňĻO Prophetňļ that God will fail to keep His promise to His messengers. God is indeed Almighty, capable of punishment"
  14,48,"ňĻWatch forňļ the Day ňĻwhenňļ the earth will be changed into a different earth and the heavens as well, and all will appear before God‚ÄĒthe One, the Supreme"
  14,49,On that Day you will see the wicked bound together in chains
  14,50,"with garments of tar, and their faces covered with flames"
  14,51,"As such, God will reward every soul for what it has committed. Surely God is swift in reckoning"
  14,52,"This ňĻQuranňļ is a ňĻsufficientňļ message for humanity so that they may take it as a warning and know that there is only One God, and so that people of reason may be mindful"
  15,1,Alif-L√£m-Ra. These are the verses of the Book; the clear Quran
  15,2,ňĻThe day will come whenňļ the disbelievers will certainly wish they had submitted ňĻto Godňļ
  15,3,"ňĻSoňļ let them eat and enjoy themselves and be diverted by ňĻfalseňļ hope, for they will soon know"
  15,4,We have never destroyed a society without a destined term
  15,5,"No people can advance their doom, nor can they delay it"
  15,6,"They say, ‚ÄúO you to whom the Reminder¬†is revealed! You must be insane"
  15,7,"Why do you not bring us the angels, if what you say is true?‚ÄĚ"
  15,8,"We do not send the angels down except for a just cause, and then ňĻthe end ofňļ the disbelievers will not be delayed"
  15,9,"It is certainly We Who have revealed the Reminder, and it is certainly We Who will preserve it"
  15,10,"Indeed, We sent messengers before you ňĻO Prophetňļ among the groups of early peoples"
  15,11,but no messenger ever came to them without being mocked
  15,12,This is how We allow disbelief ňĻto steepňļ into the hearts of the wicked
  15,13,They would not believe in this ňĻQuranňļ despite the ňĻmanyňļ examples of those ňĻdestroyedňļ before
  15,14,"And even if We opened for them a gate to heaven, through which they continued to ascend"
  15,15,"still they would say, ‚ÄúOur eyes have truly been dazzled! In fact, we must have been bewitched.‚ÄĚ"
  15,16,"Indeed, We have placed constellations in the sky, and adorned it for all to see"
  15,17,And We protected it from every accursed devil
  15,18,"except the one eavesdropping, who is then pursued by a visible flare"
  15,19,"As for the earth, We spread it out and placed upon it firm mountains, and caused everything to grow there in perfect balance"
  15,20,"And We made in it means of sustenance for you and others, who you do not provide for"
  15,21,"There is not any means ňĻof sustenanceňļ whose reserves We do not hold, only bringing it forth in precise measure"
  15,22,"We send fertilizing winds, and bring down rain from the sky for you to drink. It is not you who hold its reserves"
  15,23,Surely it is We Who give life and cause death. And We are the ňĻEternalňļ Successor
  15,24,We certainly know those who have gone before you and those who will come after ňĻyouňļ
  15,25,"Surely your Lord ňĻaloneňļ will gather them together ňĻfor judgmentňļ. He is truly All-Wise, All-Knowing"
  15,26,"Indeed, We created man from sounding clay moulded from black mud"
  15,27,"As for the jinn, We created them earlier from smokeless fire"
  15,28,"ňĻRemember, O Prophetňļ when your Lord said to the angels, ‚ÄúI am going to create a human being from sounding clay moulded from black mud"
  15,29,"So when I have fashioned him and had a spirit of My Own ňĻcreationňļ breathed into him, fall down in prostration to him.‚ÄĚ"
  15,30,So the angels prostrated all together‚ÄĒ
  15,31,"but not Ibl√ģs,¬†who refused to prostrate with the others"
  15,32,"God asked, ‚ÄúO Ibl√ģs! What is the matter with you that you did not join others in prostration?‚ÄĚ"
  15,33,"He replied, ‚ÄúIt is not for me to prostrate to a human You created from sounding clay moulded from black mud.‚ÄĚ"
  15,34,"God commanded, ‚ÄúThen get out of Paradise, for you are truly cursed"
  15,35,And surely upon you is condemnation until the Day of Judgment.‚ÄĚ
  15,36,"Satan appealed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Then delay my end until the Day of their resurrection.‚ÄĚ"
  15,37,"God said, ‚ÄúYou will be delayed"
  15,38,until the appointed Day.‚ÄĚ
  15,39,"Satan responded, ‚ÄúMy Lord! For allowing me to stray I will surely tempt them on earth and mislead them all together"
  15,40,except Your chosen servants among them.‚ÄĚ
  15,41,"God said, ‚ÄúThis is the Way, binding on Me"
  15,42,"you will certainly have no authority over My servants, except the deviant who follow you"
  15,43,"and surely Hell is their destined place, all together"
  15,44,"It has seven gates, to each a group of them is designated.‚ÄĚ"
  15,45,"Indeed, the righteous will be amid Gardens and springs"
  15,46,"ňĻIt will be said to them,ňļ ‚ÄúEnter in peace and security.‚ÄĚ"
  15,47,"We will remove whatever bitterness they had in their hearts.¬†In a friendly manner, they will be on thrones, facing one another"
  15,48,"No fatigue will touch them there, nor will they ever be asked to leave"
  15,49,"Inform My servants ňĻO Prophetňļ that I am truly the All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  15,50,and that My torment is indeed the most painful
  15,51,And inform them ňĻO Prophetňļ about Abraham‚Äôs guests
  15,52,"who entered upon him and greeted ňĻhim withňļ, ‚ÄúPeace!‚ÄĚ He ňĻlaterňļ said, ‚ÄúSurely we are afraid of you.‚ÄĚ"
  15,53,"They reassured ňĻhimňļ, ‚ÄúDo not be afraid! Surely we give you good news of a knowledgeable son.‚ÄĚ"
  15,54,"He wondered, ‚ÄúDo you give me good news despite my old age? What unlikely news!‚ÄĚ"
  15,55,"They responded, ‚ÄúWe give you good news in all truth, so do not be one of those who despair.‚ÄĚ"
  15,56,"He exclaimed, ‚ÄúWho would despair of the mercy of their Lord except the misguided?‚ÄĚ"
  15,57,"He ňĻthenňļ added, ‚ÄúWhat is your mission, O messenger-angels?‚ÄĚ"
  15,58,"They replied, ‚ÄúWe have actually been sent to a wicked people"
  15,59,"As for the family of Lot, we will certainly deliver them all"
  15,60,except his wife. We have determined that she will be one of the doomed.‚ÄĚ
  15,61,So when the messengers came to the family of Lot
  15,62,"he said, ‚ÄúYou are surely an unfamiliar people!‚ÄĚ"
  15,63,"They responded, ‚ÄúWe have come to you with that ňĻtormentňļ which they have doubted"
  15,64,"We come to you with the truth, and we are certainly truthful"
  15,65,"So travel with your family in the dark of night, and follow ňĻcloselyňļ behind them. Do not let any of you look back, and go where you are commanded.‚ÄĚ"
  15,66,"We revealed to him this decree: ‚ÄúThose ňĻsinnersňļ will be uprooted in the morning.‚ÄĚ"
  15,67,"And there came the men of the city, rejoicing"
  15,68,"Lot pleaded, ‚ÄúIndeed, these are my guests, so do not embarrass me"
  15,69,Fear God and do not humiliate me.‚ÄĚ
  15,70,"They responded, ‚ÄúHave we not forbidden you from protecting anyone?‚ÄĚ"
  15,71,"He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Here are my daughters¬†ňĻso marry themňļ if you wish to do so.‚ÄĚ"
  15,72,"By your life ňĻO Prophetňļ,¬†they certainly wandered blindly, intoxicated ňĻby lustňļ"
  15,73,So the ňĻmightyňļ blast overtook them at sunrise
  15,74,And We turned the cities ňĻof Sodom and Gomorrahňļ upside down and rained upon them stones of baked clay
  15,75,Surely in this are signs for those who contemplate
  15,76,Their ruins still lie along a known route
  15,77,Surely in this is a sign for those who believe
  15,78,And the residents of the Forest were truly wrongdoers
  15,79,so We inflicted punishment upon them. The ruins of both nations still lie on a well-known road
  15,80,"Indeed, the residents of the Stone Valley also denied the messengers"
  15,81,"We gave them Our signs, but they turned away from them"
  15,82,"They carved their homes in the mountains, feeling secure"
  15,83,But the ňĻmightyňļ blast overtook them in the morning
  15,84,and all they achieved was of no help to them
  15,85,"We have not created the heavens and the earth and everything in between except for a purpose. And the Hour is certain to come, so forgive graciously"
  15,86,"Surely your Lord is the Master Creator, All-Knowing"
  15,87,We have certainly granted you the seven often-repeated verses¬†and the great Quran
  15,88,"Do not let your eyes crave the ňĻfleetingňļ pleasures We have provided for some of the disbelievers, nor grieve for them. And be gracious to the believers"
  15,89,"And say, ‚ÄúI am truly sent with a clear warning‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒ"
  15,90,ňĻa warningňļ similar to what We sent to those who divided ňĻthe Scripturesňļ
  15,91,"who ňĻnowňļ accept parts of the Quran, rejecting others"
  15,92,So by your Lord! We will certainly question them all
  15,93,about what they used to do
  15,94,"So proclaim what you have been commanded, and turn away from the polytheists"
  15,95,Surely We will be sufficient for you against the mockers
  15,96,who set up ňĻotherňļ gods with God. They will soon come to know
  15,97,We certainly know that your heart is truly distressed by what they say
  15,98,So glorify the praises of your Lord and be one of those who ňĻalwaysňļ pray
  15,99,and worship your Lord until the inevitable¬†comes your way
  16,1,"The command of God is at hand, so do not hasten it. Glorified and Exalted is He above what they associate ňĻwith Him in worshipňļ"
  16,2,"He sends down the angels with revelation by His command to whoever He wills of His servants, ňĻstating:ňļ ‚ÄúWarn ňĻhumanityňļ that there is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Me, so be mindful of Me ňĻaloneňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  16,3,He created the heavens and the earth for a purpose. Exalted is He above what they associate with Him ňĻin worshipňļ
  16,4,"He created humans from a sperm-drop, then‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒthey openly challenge ňĻHimňļ"
  16,5,"And He created the cattle for you as a source of warmth, food, and ňĻmany otherňļ benefits"
  16,6,They are also pleasing to you when you bring them home and when you take them out to graze
  16,7,"And they carry your loads to ňĻdistantňļ lands which you could not otherwise reach without great hardship. Surely your Lord is Ever Gracious, Most Merciful"
  16,8,"ňĻHe also createdňļ horses, mules, and donkeys for your transportation and adornment. And He creates what you do not know"
  16,9,"It is upon God ňĻaloneňļ to ňĻclearlyňļ show the Straight Way. Other ways are deviant. Had He willed, He would have easily imposed guidance upon all of you"
  16,10,"He is the One Who sends down rain from the sky, from which you drink and by which plants grow for your cattle to graze"
  16,11,"With it He produces for you ňĻvariousňļ crops, olives, palm trees, grapevines, and every type of fruit. Surely in this is a sign for those who reflect"
  16,12,"And He has subjected for your benefit the day and the night, the sun and the moon. And the stars have been subjected by His command. Surely in this are signs for those who understand"
  16,13,And ňĻHe subjectedňļ for you whatever He has created on earth of varying colours.¬†Surely in this is a sign for those who are mindful
  16,14,"And He is the One Who has subjected the sea, so from it you may eat tender seafood and extract ornaments to wear. And you see the ships ploughing their way through it, so you may seek His bounty and give thanks ňĻto Himňļ"
  16,15,"He has placed into the earth firm mountains, so it does not shake with you, as well as rivers, and pathways so you may find your way"
  16,16,Also by landmarks and stars do people find their way
  16,17,Can the One Who creates be equal to those who do not? Will you not then be mindful
  16,18,"If you tried to count God‚Äôs blessings, you would never be able to number them. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  16,19,And God knows what you conceal and what you reveal
  16,20,But those ňĻidolsňļ they invoke besides God cannot create anything‚ÄĒthey themselves are created
  16,21,"They are dead, not alive‚ÄĒnot even knowing when their followers will be resurrected"
  16,22,"Your God is ňĻonlyňļ One God. As for those who do not believe in the Hereafter, their hearts are in denial, and they are too proud"
  16,23,"Without a doubt, God knows what they conceal and what they reveal. He certainly does not like those who are too proud"
  16,24,"And when it is said to them, ‚ÄúWhat has your Lord revealed?‚ÄĚ They say, ‚ÄúAncient fables!‚ÄĚ"
  16,25,Let them bear their burdens in full on the Day of Judgment as well as some of the burdens of those they mislead without knowledge. Evil indeed is what they will bear
  16,26,"Indeed, those before them had plotted, but God struck at the ňĻveryňļ foundation of their structure, so the roof collapsed on top of them, and the torment came upon them from where they did not expect"
  16,27,"Then on the Day of Judgment He will humiliate them and say, ‚ÄúWhere are My ňĻso-calledňļ associate-gods for whose sake you used to oppose ňĻthe believersňļ?‚ÄĚ Those gifted with knowledge will say, ‚ÄúSurely disgrace and misery today are upon the disbelievers.‚ÄĚ"
  16,28,"Those whose souls the angels seize while they wrong themselves will then offer ňĻfullňļ submission ňĻand say falsely,ňļ ‚ÄúWe did not do any evil.‚ÄĚ ňĻThe angels will say,ňļ ‚ÄúNo! Surely God fully knows what you used to do"
  16,29,"So enter the gates of Hell, to stay there forever. Indeed, what an evil home for the arrogant!‚ÄĚ"
  16,30,"And ňĻwhenňļ it is said to those mindful ňĻof Godňļ, ‚ÄúWhat has your Lord revealed?‚ÄĚ They say, ‚ÄúAll the best!‚ÄĚ For those who do good in this world, there is goodness. But far better is the ňĻeternalňļ Home of the Hereafter. How excellent indeed is the home of the righteous"
  16,31,"the Gardens of Eternity which they will enter, under which rivers flow. In it they will have whatever they desire. This is how God rewards the righteous‚ÄĒ"
  16,32,"those whose souls the angels take while they are virtuous, saying ňĻto themňļ, ‚ÄúPeace be upon you! Enter Paradise for what you used to do.‚ÄĚ"
  16,33,"Are they only awaiting the coming of the angels or the command of your Lord ňĻO Prophetňļ? So were those before them. And God never wronged them, but it was they who wronged themselves"
  16,34,"Then the evil ňĻconsequencesňļ of their deeds overtook them, and they were overwhelmed by what they used to ridicule"
  16,35,"The polytheists argue, ‚ÄúHad God willed, neither we nor our forefathers would have worshipped anything other than Him, nor prohibited anything without His command.‚ÄĚ So did those before them. Is not the messengers‚Äô duty only to deliver ňĻthe messageňļ clearly"
  16,36,"We surely sent a messenger to every community, saying, ‚ÄúWorship God and shun false gods.‚ÄĚ But some of them were guided by God, while others were destined to stray. So travel throughout the land and see the fate of the deniers"
  16,37,"Even though you ňĻO Prophetňļ are keen on their guidance, God certainly does not guide those He leaves to stray, and they will have no helpers"
  16,38,"They swear by God their most solemn oaths that God will never raise the dead to life. Yes ňĻHe willňļ! It is a true promise binding on Him, but most people do not know"
  16,39,"ňĻHe will do thatňļ to make clear to them what they disagreed on, and for the disbelievers to know that they were liars"
  16,40,"If We ever will something ňĻto existňļ, all We say is: ‚ÄúBe!‚ÄĚ And it is"
  16,41,"As for those who emigrated in ňĻthe cause ofňļ God after being persecuted, We will surely bless them with a good home in this world. But the reward of the Hereafter is far better, if only they knew"
  16,42,"ňĻIt isňļ they who have patiently endured, and in their Lord they put their trust"
  16,43,"We did not send ňĻmessengersňļ before you ňĻO Prophetňļ except mere men inspired by Us. If you ňĻpolytheistsňļ do not know ňĻthis alreadyňļ, then ask those who have knowledge ňĻof the Scripturesňļ"
  16,44,"ňĻWe sent themňļ with clear proofs and divine Books. And We have sent down to you ňĻO Prophetňļ the Reminder, so that you may explain to people what has been revealed for them, and perhaps they will reflect"
  16,45,Do those who devise evil plots feel secure that God will not cause the earth to swallow them? Or that the torment will not come upon them in ways they cannot comprehend
  16,46,"Or that He will not seize them while they go about ňĻtheir dayňļ, for then they will have no escape"
  16,47,"Or that He will not destroy them gradually? But your Lord is truly Ever Gracious, Most Merciful"
  16,48,"Have they not considered how the shadows of everything God has created incline to the right and the left ňĻas the sun movesňļ, totally submitting to God in all humility"
  16,49,"And to God ňĻaloneňļ bows down ňĻin submissionňļ¬†whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth of living creatures, as do the angels‚ÄĒwho are not too proud ňĻto do soňļ"
  16,50,"They¬†fear their Lord above them, and do whatever they are commanded"
  16,51,"And God has said, ‚ÄúDo not take two gods. There is only One God. So be in awe of Me ňĻaloneňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  16,52,"To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and to Him ňĻaloneňļ is the everlasting devotion. Will you then fear any other than God"
  16,53,"Whatever blessings you have are from God. Then whenever hardship touches you, to Him ňĻaloneňļ you cry ňĻfor helpňļ"
  16,54,"Then as soon as He removes the hardship from you, a group of you associates ňĻothersňļ with their Lord ňĻin worshipňļ"
  16,55,"only returning Our favours with ingratitude. So enjoy yourselves, for you will soon know"
  16,56,And they ňĻevenňļ assign to those ňĻidolsňļ‚ÄĒwho know nothing‚ÄĒa share of what We have provided for them. By God! You will certainly be questioned about whatever ňĻliesňļ you used to fabricate ňĻagainst Godňļ
  16,57,And they attribute ňĻangels asňļ daughters to God‚ÄĒglory be to Him!‚ÄĒthe opposite of what they desire for themselves
  16,58,"Whenever one of them is given the good news of a baby girl, his face grows gloomy, as he suppresses his rage"
  16,59,"He hides himself from the people because of the bad news he has received. Should he keep her in disgrace, or bury her ňĻaliveňļ in the ground? Evil indeed is their judgment"
  16,60,"To those who disbelieve in the Hereafter belong all evil qualities, whereas to God belong the finest attributes. And He is the Almighty, All-Wise"
  16,61,"If God were to punish people ňĻimmediatelyňļ for their wrongdoing, He would not have left a single living being on earth. But He delays them for an appointed term. And when their time arrives, they cannot delay it for a moment, nor could they advance it"
  16,62,"They attribute to God what they hate ňĻfor themselvesňļ,¬†and their tongues utter the lie that they will have the finest reward. Without a doubt, for them is the Fire, where they will be abandoned"
  16,63,"By God! We have surely sent messengers to communities before you ňĻO Prophetňļ, but Satan made their misdeeds appealing to them. So he is their patron today, and they will suffer a painful punishment"
  16,64,"We have revealed to you the Book only to clarify for them what they differed about, and as a guide and mercy for those who believe"
  16,65,"And God sends down rain from the sky, giving life to the earth after its death. Surely in this is a sign for those who listen"
  16,66,"And there is certainly a lesson for you in cattle: We give you to drink of what is in their bellies, from between digested food and blood: pure milk, pleasant to drink"
  16,67,And from the fruits of palm trees and grapevines you derive intoxicants¬†as well as wholesome provision. Surely in this is a sign for those who understand
  16,68,"And your Lord inspired the bees: ‚ÄúMake ňĻyourňļ homes in the mountains, the trees, and in what people construct"
  16,69,"and feed from ňĻthe flower ofňļ any fruit ňĻyou pleaseňļ and follow the ways your Lord has made easy for you.‚ÄĚ From their bellies comes forth liquid of varying colours, in which there is healing for people. Surely in this is a sign for those who reflect"
  16,70,"God has created you, and then causes you to die. And some of you are left to reach the most feeble stage of life so that they may know nothing after having known much. Indeed, God is All-Knowing, Most Capable"
  16,71,"And God has favoured some of you over others in provision. But those who have been much favoured would not share their wealth with those ňĻbondspeopleňļ in their possession, making them their equals.¬†Do they then deny God‚Äôs favours"
  16,72,"And God has made for you spouses of your own kind, and given you through your spouses children and grandchildren.¬†And He has granted you good, lawful provisions. Are they then faithful to falsehood and ungrateful for God‚Äôs favours"
  16,73,"Yet they worship besides God those ňĻidolsňļ who do not afford them any provision from the heavens and the earth, nor do they have the power to"
  16,74,"So do not set up equals to God, for God certainly knows and you do not know"
  16,75,"God sets forth a parable: a slave who lacks all means, compared to a ňĻfreeňļ man to whom We granted a good provision, of which he donates ňĻfreely,ňļ openly and secretly. Are they equal? Praise be to God. In fact, most of them do not know"
  16,76,"And God sets forth a parable of two men: one of them is dumb, incapable of anything. He is a burden on his master. Wherever he is sent, he brings no good. Can such a person be equal to the one who commands justice and is on the Straight Path"
  16,77,"To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs ňĻthe knowledge ofňļ the unseen in the heavens and the earth. Bringing about the Hour would only take the blink of an eye, or even less. Surely God is Most Capable of everything"
  16,78,"And God brought you out of the wombs of your mothers while you knew nothing, and gave you hearing, sight, and intellect so perhaps you would be thankful"
  16,79,Have they not seen the birds glide in the open sky? None holds them up except God. Surely in this are signs for those who believe
  16,80,"And God has made your homes a place to rest, and has given you tents from the hide of animals, light to handle when you travel and when you camp. And out of their wool, fur, and hair He has given you furnishings and goods for a while"
  16,81,"And God has provided you shade out of what He created, and has given you shelter in the mountains. He has also provided you with clothes protecting you from the heat ňĻand coldňļ, and armour shielding you in battle. This is how He perfects His favour upon you, so perhaps you will ňĻfullyňļ submit ňĻto Himňļ"
  16,82,"But if they turn away, then your duty ňĻO Prophetňļ is only to deliver ňĻthe messageňļ clearly"
  16,83,"They are aware of God‚Äôs favours, but still deny them. And most of them are ňĻtrulyňļ ungrateful"
  16,84,"ňĻConsider, O Prophet,ňļ the Day We will call ňĻa prophet asňļ a witness from every faith-community. Then the disbelievers will neither be allowed to plead nor appease ňĻtheir Lordňļ"
  16,85,"And when the wrongdoers face the punishment, it will not be lightened for them, nor will they be delayed ňĻfrom itňļ"
  16,86,"And when the polytheists see their associate-gods, they will say, ‚ÄúOur Lord! These are our associate-gods that we used to invoke besides You.‚ÄĚ Their gods will throw a rebuttal at them, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúYou are definitely liars.‚ÄĚ"
  16,87,"They will offer ňĻfullňļ submission to God on that Day, and whatever ňĻgodsňļ they fabricated will fail them"
  16,88,"For those who disbelieve and hinder ňĻothersňļ from the Way of God, We will add more punishment to their punishment for all the corruption they spread"
  16,89,"ňĻConsider, O Prophet,ňļ the Day We will call against every faith-community a witness of their own. And We will call you to be a witness against these ňĻpeople of yoursňļ. We have revealed to you the Book as an explanation of all things, a guide, a mercy, and good news for those who ňĻfullyňļ submit"
  16,90,"Indeed, God commands justice, grace, as well as courtesy to close relatives. He forbids indecency, wickedness, and aggression. He instructs you so perhaps you will be mindful"
  16,91,"Honour God‚Äôs covenant when you make a pledge, and do not break your oaths after confirming them, having made God your guarantor. Surely God knows all you do"
  16,92,"Do not be like the woman who ňĻfoolishlyňļ unravels her yarn after it is firmly spun, by taking your oaths as a means of deceiving one another in favour of a stronger group. Surely God tests you through this. And on the Day of Judgment He will certainly make your differences clear to you"
  16,93,"Had God willed, He could have easily made you one community ňĻof believersňļ, but He leaves to stray whoever He wills and guides whoever He wills.¬†And you will certainly be questioned about what you used to do"
  16,94,"And do not take your oaths as a means of deceiving one another or your feet will slip after they have been firm. Then you will taste the evil ňĻconsequencesňļ of hindering ňĻothersňļ from the Way of God, and you will suffer a tremendous punishment"
  16,95,"And do not trade God‚Äôs covenant for a fleeting gain. What is with God is certainly far better for you, if only you knew"
  16,96,"Whatever you have will end, but whatever God has is everlasting. And We will certainly reward the steadfast according to the best of their deeds"
  16,97,"Whoever does good, whether male or female, and is a believer, We will surely bless them with a good life, and We will certainly reward them according to the best of their deeds"
  16,98,"When you recite the Quran, seek refuge with God from Satan, the accursed"
  16,99,He certainly has no authority over those who believe and put their trust in their Lord
  16,100,His authority is only over those who take him as a patron and who‚ÄĒunder his influence‚ÄĒassociate ňĻothersňļ with God ňĻin worshipňļ
  16,101,"When We replace a verse with another‚ÄĒand God knows best what He reveals‚ÄĒthey say, ‚ÄúYou ňĻMuŠł•ammadňļ are just a fabricator.‚ÄĚ In fact, most of them do not know"
  16,102,"Say, ‚ÄúThe holy spirit¬†has brought it down from your Lord with the truth to reassure the believers, and as a guide and good news for those who submit ňĻto Godňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  16,103,"And We surely know that they say, ‚ÄúNo one is teaching him except a human.‚ÄĚ But the man they refer to speaks a foreign tongue, whereas this ňĻQuranňļ is ňĻinňļ eloquent Arabic"
  16,104,"Surely those who do not believe in God‚Äôs revelations will never be guided by God, and they will suffer a painful punishment"
  16,105,"No one fabricates lies except those who disbelieve in God‚Äôs revelations, and it is they who are the ňĻtrueňļ liars"
  16,106,"Whoever disbelieves in God after their belief‚ÄĒnot those who are forced while their hearts are firm in faith,¬†but those who embrace disbelief wholeheartedly‚ÄĒthey will be condemned by God and suffer a tremendous punishment"
  16,107,This is because they prefer the life of this world over the Hereafter. Surely God never guides those who ňĻchoose toňļ disbelieve
  16,108,"They are the ones whose hearts, ears, and eyes are sealed by God, and it is they who are ňĻtrulyňļ heedless"
  16,109,"Without a doubt, they will be the losers in the Hereafter"
  16,110,"As for those who emigrated after being compelled ňĻto renounce Islamňļ, then struggled ňĻin God‚Äôs causeňļ, and persevered, your Lord ňĻO Prophetňļ is truly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful after all"
  16,111,"ňĻConsiderňļ the Day ňĻwhenňļ every soul will come pleading for itself, and each will be paid in full for what it did, and none will be wronged"
  16,112,"And God sets forth the example of a society which was safe and at ease, receiving its provision in abundance from all directions. But its people met God‚Äôs favours with ingratitude, so God made them taste the clutches of hunger and fear for their misdeeds"
  16,113,"A messenger of their own actually did come to them, but they denied him. So the torment overtook them while they persisted in wrongdoing"
  16,114,"So eat from the good, lawful things which God has provided for you, and be grateful for God‚Äôs favours, if you ňĻtrulyňļ worship Him ňĻaloneňļ"
  16,115,"He has only forbidden you ňĻto eatňļ carrion, blood, swine,¬†and what is slaughtered in the name of any other than God. But if someone is compelled by necessity‚ÄĒneither driven by desire nor exceeding immediate need‚ÄĒthen surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  16,116,"Do not falsely declare with your tongues, ‚ÄúThis is lawful, and that is unlawful,‚ÄĚ ňĻonlyňļ fabricating lies against God. Indeed, those who fabricate lies against God will never succeed"
  16,117,"ňĻIt is onlyňļ a brief enjoyment, then they will suffer a painful punishment"
  16,118,"To the Jews, We have forbidden what We related to you before.¬†We did not wrong them, but it was they who wronged themselves"
  16,119,"As for those who commit evil ignorantly ňĻor recklesslyňļ, then repent afterwards and mend their ways, then your Lord is surely All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  16,120,"Indeed, Abraham was a model of excellence: devoted to God, ňĻperfectlyňļ upright‚ÄĒnot a polytheist‚ÄĒ"
  16,121,ňĻutterlyňļ grateful for God‚Äôs favours. ňĻSoňļ He chose him and guided him to the Straight Path
  16,122,"We blessed him with all goodness in this world,¬†and in the Hereafter he will certainly be among the righteous"
  16,123,"Then We revealed to you ňĻO Prophet, sayingňļ: ‚ÄúFollow the faith of Abraham, the upright, who was not one of the polytheists.‚ÄĚ"
  16,124,ňĻHonouringňļ the Sabbath was ordained only for those who disputed about Abraham.¬†And surely your Lord will judge between them on the Day of Judgment regarding their disputes
  16,125,"Invite ňĻallňļ to the Way of your Lord with wisdom and kind advice, and only debate with them in the best manner. Surely your Lord ňĻaloneňļ knows best who has strayed from His Way and who is ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  16,126,"If you retaliate, then let it be equivalent to what you have suffered. But if you patiently endure, it is certainly best for those who are patient"
  16,127,"Be patient ňĻO Prophetňļ, for your patience is only with God‚Äôs help. Do not grieve over those ňĻwho disbelieveňļ, nor be distressed by their schemes"
  16,128,Surely God is with those who shun evil and who do good ňĻdeedsňļ
  17,1,"Glory be to the One Who took His servant ňĻMuŠł•ammadňļ by night from the Sacred Mosque to the Farthest Mosque whose surroundings We have blessed, so that We may show him some of Our signs.¬†Indeed, He¬†alone is the All-Hearing, All-Seeing"
  17,2,"And We gave Moses the Scripture and made it a guide for the Children of Israel, ňĻstating:ňļ ‚ÄúDo not take besides Me any other Trustee of Affairs"
  17,3,ňĻOňļ descendants of those We carried with Noah ňĻin the Arkňļ! He was indeed a grateful servant.‚ÄĚ
  17,4,"And We warned the Children of Israel in the Scripture, ‚ÄúYou will certainly cause corruption in the land twice, and you will become extremely arrogant"
  17,5,"When the first of the two warnings would come to pass, We would send against you some of Our servants of great might, who would ravage your homes. This would be a warning fulfilled"
  17,6,"Then ňĻafter your repentanceňļ We would give you the upper hand over them and aid you with wealth and offspring, causing you to outnumber them"
  17,7,"If you act rightly, it is for your own good, but if you do wrong, it is to your own loss. ‚ÄúAnd when the second warning would come to pass, your enemies would ňĻbe left toňļ totally disgrace you and enter the Temple ňĻof Jerusalemňļ as they entered it the first time, and utterly destroy whatever would fall into their hands"
  17,8,"Perhaps your Lord will have mercy on you ňĻif you repentňļ, but if you return ňĻto sinňļ, We will return ňĻto punishmentňļ. And We have made Hell a ňĻpermanentňļ confinement for the disbelievers.‚ÄĚ"
  17,9,"Surely this Quran guides to what is most upright, and gives good news to the believers‚ÄĒwho do good‚ÄĒthat they will have a mighty reward"
  17,10,And ňĻit warnsňļ those who do not believe in the Hereafter ňĻthatňļ We have prepared for them a painful punishment
  17,11,And humans ňĻswiftlyňļ pray for evil¬†as they pray for good. For humankind is ever hasty
  17,12,"We made the day and night as two signs. So We made the sign of the night devoid of light, and We made the sign of the day ňĻperfectlyňļ bright, so that you may seek the bounty of your Lord and know the number of years and calculation ňĻof timeňļ. And We have explained everything in detail"
  17,13,We have bound every human‚Äôs destiny to their neck.¬†And on the Day of Judgment We will bring forth to each ňĻpersonňļ a record which they will find laid open
  17,14,"ňĻAnd it will be said,ňļ ‚ÄúRead your record. You ňĻaloneňļ are sufficient this Day to take account of yourself.‚ÄĚ"
  17,15,"Whoever chooses to be guided, it is only for their own good. And whoever chooses to stray, it is only to their own loss. No soul burdened with sin will bear the burden of another. And We would never punish ňĻa peopleňļ until We have sent a messenger ňĻto warn themňļ"
  17,16,"Whenever We intend to destroy a society, We command its elite ňĻto obey Godňļ but they act rebelliously in it. So the decree ňĻof punishmentňļ is justified, and We destroy it utterly"
  17,17,ňĻImagineňļ how many peoples We have destroyed after Noah! And sufficient is your Lord as All-Aware and All-Seeing of the sins of His servants
  17,18,"Whoever desires this fleeting world ňĻaloneňļ, We hasten in it whatever We please to whoever We will; then We destine them for Hell, where they will burn, condemned and rejected"
  17,19,"But whoever desires the Hereafter and strives for it accordingly, and is a ňĻtrueňļ believer, it is they whose striving will be appreciated"
  17,20,We provide both the former and the latter from the bounty of your Lord. And the bounty of your Lord can never be withheld
  17,21,"See how We have favoured some over others ňĻin this lifeňļ, but the Hereafter is certainly far greater in rank and in favour"
  17,22,"Do not set up any other god with God, or you will end up condemned, abandoned"
  17,23,"For your Lord has decreed that you worship none but Him. And honour your parents. If one or both of them reach old age in your care, never say to them ňĻevenňļ ‚Äėugh,‚Äô nor yell at them. Rather, address them respectfully"
  17,24,"And be humble with them out of mercy, and pray, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Be merciful to them as they raised me when I was young.‚ÄĚ"
  17,25,"Your Lord knows best what is within yourselves. If you are righteous, He is certainly All-Forgiving to those who ňĻconstantlyňļ turn to Him"
  17,26,"Give to close relatives their due, as well as the poor and ňĻneedyňļ travellers. And do not spend wastefully"
  17,27,Surely the wasteful are ňĻlikeňļ brothers to the devils. And the Devil is ever ungrateful to his Lord
  17,28,But if you must turn them down ňĻbecause you lack the means to giveňļ‚ÄĒwhile hoping to receive your Lord‚Äôs bounty‚ÄĒthen ňĻat leastňļ give them a kind word
  17,29,"Do not be so tight-fisted, for you will be blameworthy; nor so open-handed, for you will end up in poverty"
  17,30,"Surely your Lord gives abundant or limited provisions to whoever He wills. He is certainly All-Aware, All-Seeing of His servants"
  17,31,Do not kill your children for fear of poverty. We provide for them and for you. Surely killing them is a heinous sin
  17,32,Do not go near adultery. It is truly a shameful deed and an evil way
  17,33,"Do not take a ňĻhumanňļ life‚ÄĒmade sacred by God‚ÄĒexcept with ňĻlegalňļ right.¬†If anyone is killed unjustly, We have given their heirs¬†the authority, but do not let them exceed limits in retaliation,¬†for they are already supported ňĻby lawňļ"
  17,34,"Do not come near the wealth of the orphan‚ÄĒunless intending to enhance it‚ÄĒuntil they attain maturity. Honour ňĻyourňļ pledges, for you will surely be accountable for them"
  17,35,"Give in full when you measure, and weigh with an even balance. That is fairest and best in the end"
  17,36,"Do not follow what you have no ňĻsureňļ knowledge of. Indeed, all will be called to account for ňĻtheirňļ hearing, sight, and intellect"
  17,37,And do not walk on the earth arrogantly. Surely you can neither crack the earth nor stretch to the height of the mountains
  17,38,The violation of any of these ňĻcommandmentsňļ is detestable to your Lord
  17,39,"This is part of the wisdom which your Lord has revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ. And do not set up any other god with God ňĻO humanityňļ, or you will be cast into Hell, blameworthy, rejected"
  17,40,Has your Lord favoured you ňĻpagansňļ with sons and taken angels as ňĻHisňļ daughters?¬†You are truly making an outrageous claim
  17,41,"We have surely varied ňĻthe signsňļ in this Quran so perhaps they may be mindful, but it only drives them farther away"
  17,42,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúHad there been other gods besides Him‚ÄĒas they claim‚ÄĒthen they would have certainly sought a way to ňĻchallengeňļ the Lord of the Throne.‚ÄĚ"
  17,43,Glorified and Highly Exalted is He above what they claim
  17,44,"The seven heavens, the earth, and all those in them glorify Him. There is not a single thing that does not glorify His praises‚ÄĒbut you ňĻsimplyňļ cannot comprehend their glorification. He is indeed Most Forbearing, All-Forgiving"
  17,45,"When you ňĻO Prophetňļ recite the Quran, We put a hidden barrier between you and those who do not believe in the Hereafter"
  17,46,"We have cast veils over their hearts‚ÄĒleaving them unable to comprehend it‚ÄĒand deafness in their ears. And when you mention your Lord alone in the Quran, they turn their backs in aversion"
  17,47,"We know best how they listen to your recitation and what they say privately‚ÄĒwhen the wrongdoers say, ‚ÄúYou would only be following a bewitched man.‚ÄĚ"
  17,48,See how they call you names ňĻO Prophetňļ!¬†So they have gone so ňĻfarňļ astray that they cannot find the ňĻRightňļ Way
  17,49,"And they say ňĻmockinglyňļ, ‚ÄúWhen we are reduced to bones and ashes, will we really be raised as a new creation?‚ÄĚ"
  17,50,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúňĻYes, even ifňļ you become stones, or iron"
  17,51,"or whatever you think is harder to bring to life!‚ÄĚ Then they will ask ňĻyouňļ, ‚ÄúWho will bring us back ňĻto lifeňļ?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúThe One Who created you the first time.‚ÄĚ They will then shake their heads at you and ask, ‚ÄúWhen will that be?‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúPerhaps it is soon!‚ÄĚ"
  17,52,"On the Day He will call you, you will ňĻinstantlyňļ respond by praising Him,¬†thinking you had remained ňĻin the worldňļ only for a little while"
  17,53,Tell My ňĻbelievingňļ servants to say only what is best. Satan certainly seeks to sow discord among them. Satan is indeed a sworn enemy to humankind
  17,54,"Your Lord knows you best. He may have mercy on you if He wills, or punish you if He wills. We have not sent you ňĻO Prophetňļ as a keeper over them"
  17,55,"Your Lord knows best all those in the heavens and the earth. And We have surely favoured some prophets above others, and to David We gave the Psalms"
  17,56,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúInvoke those you claim ňĻto be divineňļ¬†besides Him‚ÄĒthey do not have the power to undo harm from you or transfer it ňĻto someone elseňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  17,57,"ňĻEvenňļ the closest ňĻto Godňļ of those invoked would be seeking a way to their Lord, hoping for His mercy, and fearing His punishment. Indeed, your Lord‚Äôs torment is fearsome"
  17,58,There is not a ňĻwickedňļ society that We will not destroy or punish with a severe torment before the Day of Judgment. That is written in the Record
  17,59,"Nothing keeps Us from sending the ňĻdemandedňļ signs except that they had ňĻalreadyňļ been denied by earlier peoples. And We gave Tham√Ľd the she-camel as a clear sign, but they wrongfully rejected it.¬†We only send the signs as a warning"
  17,60,"And ňĻremember, O Prophetňļ when We told you, ‚ÄúCertainly your Lord encompasses the people.‚ÄĚ And We have made what We brought you to see¬†as well as the cursed tree ňĻmentionedňļ in the Quran¬†only as a test for the people. We keep warning them, but it only increases them greatly in defiance"
  17,61,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We said to the angels, ‚ÄúProstrate before Adam,‚ÄĚ so they all did‚ÄĒbut not Ibl√ģs,¬†who protested, ‚ÄúShould I prostrate to the one You have created from mud?‚ÄĚ"
  17,62,"Adding, ‚ÄúDo you see this one you honoured above me? If you delay my end until the Day of Judgment, I will certainly take hold of his descendants, except for a few.‚ÄĚ"
  17,63,"God responded, ‚ÄúBe gone! Whoever of them follows you, Hell will surely be the reward for all of you‚ÄĒan ample reward"
  17,64,"And incite whoever you can of them with your voice, mobilize against them all your cavalry and infantry, manipulate them in their wealth and children, and make them promises.‚ÄĚ But Satan promises them nothing but delusion"
  17,65,"ňĻGod added,ňļ ‚ÄúYou will truly have no authority over My ňĻfaithfulňļ servants.‚ÄĚ And sufficient is your Lord as a Guardian"
  17,66,"It is your Lord Who steers the ships for you through the sea, so that you may seek His bounty. Surely He is ever Merciful to you"
  17,67,"When you are touched with hardship at sea, you ňĻtotallyňļ forget all ňĻthe godsňļ you ňĻnormallyňļ invoke, except Him. But when He delivers you ňĻsafelyňļ to shore, you turn away. Humankind is ever ungrateful"
  17,68,"Do you feel secure that He will not cause the land to swallow you up, or unleash upon you a storm of stones? Then you will find none to protect you"
  17,69,"Or do you feel secure that He will not send you back to sea once again, and send upon you a violent storm, drowning you for your denial? Then you will find none to avenge you against Us"
  17,70,"Indeed, We have dignified the children of Adam, carried them on land and sea, granted them good and lawful provisions, and privileged them far above many of Our creatures"
  17,71,ňĻBeware ofňļ the Day We will summon every people with their leader.¬†So whoever will be given their record in their right hand will read it ňĻhappilyňļ and will not be wronged ňĻeven by the width ofňļ the thread of a date stone
  17,72,"But whoever is blind ňĻto the truthňļ in this ňĻworldňļ will be blind in the Hereafter, and ňĻevenňļ far more astray from the ňĻRightňļ Way"
  17,73,"They definitely ňĻthought theyňļ were about to lure you away from what We have revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ, hoping that you would attribute something else to Us falsely‚ÄĒand then they would have certainly taken you as a close friend"
  17,74,"Had We not made you steadfast, you probably would have inclined to them a little"
  17,75,"and then We truly would have made you taste double ňĻpunishmentňļ both in this life and after death, and you would have found no helper against Us"
  17,76,"They were about to intimidate you to drive you out of the land ňĻof Meccaňļ, but then they would not have survived after you ňĻhad leftňļ except for a little while"
  17,77,ňĻThis has beenňļ Our way with the messengers We sent before you. And you will never find any change in Our way
  17,78,"Observe the prayer from the decline of the sun until the darkness of the night and the dawn prayer, for certainly the dawn prayer is witnessed ňĻby angelsňļ"
  17,79,"And rise at ňĻthe lastňļ part of the night, offering additional prayers, so your Lord may raise you to a station of praise"
  17,80,"And say, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Grant me an honourable entrance and an honourable exit¬†and give me a supporting authority from Yourself.‚ÄĚ"
  17,81,"And declare, ‚ÄúThe truth has come and falsehood has vanished. Indeed, falsehood is bound to vanish.‚ÄĚ"
  17,82,"We send down the Quran as a healing and mercy for the believers, but it only increases the wrongdoers in loss"
  17,83,"When We grant people Our favours, they turn away, acting arrogantly. But when touched with evil, they lose all hope"
  17,84,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúEveryone acts in their own way. But your Lord knows best whose way is rightly guided.‚ÄĚ"
  17,85,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about the spirit. Say, ‚ÄúIts nature is known only to my Lord, and you ňĻO humanityňļ have been given but little knowledge.‚ÄĚ"
  17,86,"If We willed, We could have certainly taken away what We have revealed to you ňĻO Prophetňļ‚ÄĒthen you would find none to guarantee its return from Us‚ÄĒ"
  17,87,"had it not been for the mercy of your Lord. Indeed, His favour upon you is immense"
  17,88,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIf ňĻallňļ humans and jinn were to come together to produce the equivalent of this Quran, they could not produce its equal, no matter how they supported each other.‚ÄĚ"
  17,89,"And We have truly set forth every ňĻkind ofňļ lesson for humanity in this Quran, yet most people persist in disbelief"
  17,90,"They challenge ňĻthe Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúWe will never believe in you until you cause a spring to gush forth from the earth for us"
  17,91,"or until you have a garden of palm trees and vineyards, and cause rivers to flow abundantly in it"
  17,92,"or cause the sky to fall upon us in pieces, as you have claimed, or bring God and the angels before us, face to face"
  17,93,"or until you have a house of gold, or you ascend into heaven‚ÄĒand even then we will not believe in your ascension until you bring down to us a book that we can read.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúGlory be to my Lord! Am I not only a human messenger?‚ÄĚ"
  17,94,"And nothing has prevented people from believing when guidance comes to them except their protest: ‚ÄúHas God sent a human as a messenger?‚ÄĚ"
  17,95,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúHad there been angels walking the earth, well settled, We would have surely sent down for them an angel from heaven as a messenger.‚ÄĚ"
  17,96,"Say, ‚ÄúSufficient is God as a Witness between me and you. He is certainly All-Knowing, All-Seeing of His servants.‚ÄĚ"
  17,97,"Whoever God guides is truly guided. And whoever He leaves to stray, you will find no guardians for them besides Him. And We will drag them on their faces on the Day of Judgment‚ÄĒdeaf, dumb, and blind. Hell will be their home. Whenever it dies down, We will flare it up for them"
  17,98,"That is their reward for rejecting Our signs and asking ňĻmockinglyňļ, ‚ÄúWhen we are reduced to bones and ashes, will we really be raised as a new creation?‚ÄĚ"
  17,99,"Have they not realized that God, Who created the heavens and the earth, can ňĻeasilyňļ re-create them? He has ňĻalreadyňļ set for them a time, about which there is no doubt. But the wrongdoers persist in denial"
  17,100,"Say ňĻto them, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúEven if you were to possess the ňĻinfiniteňļ treasuries of my Lord‚Äôs mercy, then you would certainly withhold ňĻthemňļ, fearing they would run out‚ÄĒfor humankind is ever stingy!‚ÄĚ"
  17,101,"We surely gave Moses nine clear signs.¬†ňĻYou, O Prophet, canňļ ask the Children of Israel. When Moses came to them, Pharaoh said to him, ‚ÄúI really think that you, O Moses, are bewitched.‚ÄĚ"
  17,102,"Moses replied, ‚ÄúYou know well that none has sent these ňĻsignsňļ down except the Lord of the heavens and the earth as insights. And I really think that you, O Pharaoh, are doomed.‚ÄĚ"
  17,103,"So Pharaoh wanted to scare the Israelites out of the land ňĻof Egyptňļ, but We drowned him and all of those with him"
  17,104,"And We said to the Children of Israel after Pharaoh, ‚ÄúReside in the land, but when the promise of the Hereafter comes to pass,¬†We will bring you all together.‚ÄĚ"
  17,105,"We have sent down the Quran in truth, and with the truth it has come down. We have sent you ňĻO Prophetňļ only as a deliverer of good news and a warner"
  17,106,ňĻIt isňļ a Quran We have revealed in stages so that you may recite it to people at a deliberate pace. And We have sent it down in successive revelations
  17,107,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúBelieve in this ňĻQuranňļ, or do not. Indeed, when it is recited to those who were gifted with knowledge¬†before it ňĻwas revealedňļ, they fall upon their faces in prostration"
  17,108,"and say, ‚ÄėGlory be to our Lord! Surely the promise of our Lord has been fulfilled.‚Äô"
  17,109,"And they fall down upon their faces weeping, and it increases them in humility.‚ÄĚ"
  17,110,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúCall upon God or call upon the Most Compassionate‚ÄĒwhichever you call, He has the Most Beautiful Names.‚ÄĚ Do not recite your prayers too loudly or silently, but seek a way between"
  17,111,"And say, ‚ÄúAll praise is for God, Who has never had ňĻanyňļ offspring;¬†nor does He have a partner in ňĻgoverningňļ the kingdom;¬†nor is He pathetic, needing a protector.¬†And revere Him immensely.‚ÄĚ"
  18,1,"All praise is for God Who has revealed the Book to His servant,¬†allowing no crookedness in it"
  18,2,"ňĻmaking itňļ perfectly upright, to warn ňĻthe disbelieversňļ of a severe torment from Him; to give good news to the believers‚ÄĒwho do good‚ÄĒthat they will have a fine reward"
  18,3,in which they will remain forever
  18,4,"and to warn those who claim, ‚ÄúGod has offspring.‚ÄĚ"
  18,5,"They have no knowledge of this, nor did their forefathers. What a terrible claim that comes out of their mouths! They say nothing but lies"
  18,6,"Now, perhaps you ňĻO Prophetňļ will grieve yourself to death over their denial, if they ňĻcontinue toňļ disbelieve in this message"
  18,7,"We have indeed made whatever is on earth as an adornment for it, in order to test which of them is best in deeds"
  18,8,And We will certainly reduce whatever is on it to barren ground
  18,9,Have you ňĻO Prophetňļ thought that the people of the cave¬†and the plaque¬†were ňĻthe onlyňļ wonders of Our signs
  18,10,"ňĻRememberňļ when those youths took refuge in the cave, and said, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Grant us mercy from Yourself and guide us rightly through our ordeal.‚ÄĚ"
  18,11,So We caused them to fall into a dead sleep¬†in the cave for many years
  18,12,then We raised them so We may show which of the two groups would make a better estimation of the length of their stay
  18,13,"We relate to you ňĻO Prophetňļ their story in truth. They were youths who truly believed in their Lord, and We increased them in guidance"
  18,14,"And We strengthened their hearts when they stood up and declared, ‚ÄúOur Lord is the Lord of the heavens and the earth. We will never call upon any god besides Him, or we would truly be uttering an outrageous lie.‚ÄĚ"
  18,15,"ňĻThen they said to one another,ňļ ‚ÄúThese people of ours have taken gods besides Him. Why do they not produce a clear proof of them? Who then does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against God"
  18,16,"Since you have distanced yourselves from them and what they worship besides God, take refuge in the cave. Your Lord will extend His mercy to you and accommodate you in your ordeal.‚ÄĚ"
  18,17,"And you would have seen the sun, as it rose, inclining away from their cave to the right, and as it set, declining away from them to the left, while they lay in its open space.¬†That is one of the signs of God. Whoever God guides is truly guided. But whoever He leaves to stray, you will never find for them a guiding mentor"
  18,18,"And you would have thought they were awake,¬†though they were asleep. We turned them over, to the right and left, while their dog stretched his forelegs at the entrance. Had you looked at them, you would have certainly fled away from them, filled with horror"
  18,19,"And so We awakened them so that they might question one another. One of them exclaimed, ‚ÄúHow long have you remained ňĻasleepňļ?‚ÄĚ Some replied, ‚ÄúPerhaps a day, or part of a day.‚ÄĚ They said ňĻto one anotherňļ, ‚ÄúYour Lord knows best how long you have remained. So send one of you with these silver coins of yours to the city, and let him find which food is the purest, and then bring you provisions from it. Let him be ňĻexceptionallyňļ cautious, and do not let him give you away"
  18,20,"For, indeed, if they find out about you, they will stone you ňĻto deathňļ, or force you back into their faith, and then you will never succeed.‚ÄĚ"
  18,21,"That is how We caused them to be discovered so that their people might know that God‚Äôs promise ňĻof resurrectionňļ is true and that there is no doubt about the Hour.¬†When the people disputed with each other about the case of the youth ňĻafter their deathňļ,¬†some proposed, ‚ÄúBuild a structure around them. Their Lord knows best about them.‚ÄĚ Those who prevailed in the matter said, ‚ÄúWe will surely build a place of worship over them.‚ÄĚ"
  18,22,"Some will say, ‚ÄúThey were three, their dog was the fourth,‚ÄĚ while others will say, ‚ÄúThey were five, their dog was the sixth,‚ÄĚ ňĻonlyňļ guessing blindly. And others will say, ‚ÄúThey were seven and their dog was the eighth.‚ÄĚ Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúMy Lord knows best their ňĻexactňļ number. Only a few people know as well.‚ÄĚ So do not argue about them except with sure knowledge,¬†nor consult any of those ňĻwho debateňļ about them"
  18,23,"And never say of anything, ‚ÄúI will definitely do this tomorrow,‚ÄĚ"
  18,24,"without adding, ‚Äúif God so wills!‚ÄĚ But if you forget, then remember your Lord, and say, ‚ÄúI trust my Lord will guide me to what is more right than this.‚ÄĚ"
  18,25,"They had remained in their cave for three hundred years, adding nine"
  18,26,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúGod knows best how long they stayed. With Him ňĻaloneňļ is ňĻthe knowledge ofňļ the unseen of the heavens and the earth. How perfectly He hears and sees! They have no guardian besides Him, and He shares His command with none.‚ÄĚ"
  18,27,"Recite what has been revealed to you from the Book of your Lord. None can change His Words, nor can you find any refuge besides Him"
  18,28,"And patiently stick with those who call upon their Lord morning and evening, seeking His pleasure.¬†Do not let your eyes look beyond them, desiring the luxuries of this worldly life. And do not obey those whose hearts We have made heedless of Our remembrance, who follow ňĻonlyňļ their desires and whose state is ňĻtotalňļ loss"
  18,29,"And say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúňĻThis isňļ the truth from your Lord. Whoever wills let them believe, and whoever wills let them disbelieve.‚ÄĚ Surely We have prepared for the wrongdoers a Fire whose walls will ňĻcompletelyňļ surround them. When they cry for aid, they will be aided with water like molten metal, which will burn ňĻtheirňļ faces. What a horrible drink! And what a terrible place to rest"
  18,30,"As for those who believe and do good, We certainly never deny the reward of those who are best in deeds"
  18,31,"It is they who will have the Gardens of Eternity, with rivers flowing under their feet. There they will be adorned with bracelets of gold, and wear green garments of fine silk and rich brocade, reclining there on ňĻcanopiedňļ couches. What a marvellous reward! And what a fabulous place to rest"
  18,32,"Give them ňĻO Prophetňļ an example of two men. To ňĻthe disbelievingňļ one We gave two gardens of grapevines, which We surrounded with palm trees and placed ňĻvariousňļ crops in between"
  18,33,"Each garden yielded ňĻallňļ its produce, never falling short. And We caused a river to flow between them"
  18,34,"And he had other resources¬†ňĻas wellňļ. So he boasted to a ňĻpoorňļ companion of his, while conversing with him, ‚ÄúI am greater than you in wealth and superior in manpower.‚ÄĚ"
  18,35,"And he entered his property, while wronging his soul, saying, ‚ÄúI do not think this will ever perish"
  18,36,"nor do I think the Hour will ňĻeverňļ come. And if in fact I am returned to my Lord, I will definitely get a far better outcome than ňĻallňļ this.‚ÄĚ"
  18,37,"His ňĻbelievingňļ companion replied, while conversing with him, ‚ÄúDo you disbelieve in the One Who created you from dust,¬†then ňĻdeveloped youňļ from a sperm-drop, then formed you into a man"
  18,38,"But as for me: He is God, my Lord, and I will never associate anyone with my Lord ňĻin worshipňļ"
  18,39,"If only you had said, upon entering your property, ‚ÄėThis is what God has willed! There is no power except with God!‚Äô Even though you see me inferior to you in wealth and offspring"
  18,40,"perhaps my Lord will grant me ňĻsomethingňļ better than your garden, and send down upon your garden a thunderbolt from the sky, turning it into a barren waste"
  18,41,"Or its water may sink ňĻinto the earthňļ, and then you will never be able to seek it out.‚ÄĚ"
  18,42,"And so all his produce was ňĻtotallyňļ ruined, so he started to wring his hands for all he had spent on it, while it had collapsed on its trellises. He cried, ‚ÄúAlas! I wish I had never associated anyone with my Lord ňĻin worshipňļ!‚ÄĚ"
  18,43,"And he had no manpower to help him against God, nor could he ňĻevenňļ help himself"
  18,44,"At this time, support comes ňĻonlyňļ from God‚ÄĒthe True ňĻLordňļ. He is best in reward and best in outcome"
  18,45,"And give them a parable of this worldly life. ňĻIt isňļ like the plants of the earth, thriving when sustained by the rain We send down from the sky. Then they ňĻsoonňļ turn into chaff scattered by the wind. And God is fully capable of ňĻdoingňļ all things"
  18,46,"Wealth and children are the adornment of this worldly life, but the everlasting good deeds are far better with your Lord in reward and in hope"
  18,47,"ňĻBeware ofňļ the Day We will blow the mountains away, and you will see the earth laid bare. And We will gather all ňĻhumankindňļ, leaving none behind"
  18,48,"They will be presented before your Lord in rows, ňĻand the deniers will be told,ňļ ‚ÄúYou have surely returned to Us ňĻall aloneňļ as We created you the first time, although you ňĻalwaysňļ claimed that We would never appoint a time for your return.‚ÄĚ"
  18,49,"And the record ňĻof deedsňļ will be laid ňĻopenňļ, and you will see the wicked in fear of what is ňĻwrittenňļ in it. They will cry, ‚ÄúWoe to us! What kind of record is this that does not leave any sin, small or large, unlisted?‚ÄĚ They will find whatever they did present ňĻbefore themňļ. And your Lord will never wrong anyone"
  18,50,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We said to the angels, ‚ÄúProstrate before Adam,‚ÄĚ so they all did‚ÄĒbut not Ibl√ģs,¬†who was one of the jinn, but he rebelled against the command of his Lord. Would you then take him and his descendants as patrons instead of Me, although they are your enemy? What an evil alternative for the wrongdoers ňĻto chooseňļ"
  18,51,"I never called them to witness the creation of the heavens and the earth or ňĻevenňļ their own creation, nor would I take the misleaders as helpers"
  18,52,"And ňĻbeware ofňļ the Day He will say, ‚ÄúCall upon those you claimed were My associate-gods.‚ÄĚ So they will call them, but will receive no response. And We will make them ňĻallňļ share in the same doom"
  18,53,"The wicked will see the Fire and realize that they are bound to fall into it, and will find no way to avoid it"
  18,54,"We have surely set forth in this Quran every ňĻkind ofňļ lesson for people, but humankind is the most argumentative of all beings"
  18,55,And nothing prevents people from believing when guidance comes to them and from seeking their Lord‚Äôs forgiveness except ňĻtheir demandňļ to meet the same fate of earlier deniers or that the torment would confront them face to face
  18,56,"We do not send the messengers except as deliverers of good news and warners. But the disbelievers argue in falsehood, ňĻhopingňļ to discredit the truth with it, and make a mockery of My revelations and warnings"
  18,57,"And who does more wrong than those who, when reminded of their Lord‚Äôs revelations, turn away from them and forget what their own hands have done? We have certainly cast veils over their hearts‚ÄĒleaving them unable to comprehend this ňĻQuranňļ‚ÄĒand deafness in their ears. And if you ňĻO Prophetňļ invite them to ňĻtrueňļ guidance, they will never be ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  18,58,"Your Lord is the All-Forgiving, Full of Mercy. If He were to seize them ňĻimmediatelyňļ for what they commit, He would have certainly hastened their punishment. But they have an appointed time, from which they will find no refuge"
  18,59,"Those ňĻare theňļ societies We destroyed when they persisted in wrong,¬†and We had set a time for their destruction"
  18,60,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Moses said to his young assistant, ‚ÄúI will never give up until I reach the junction of the two seas, even if I travel for ages.‚ÄĚ"
  18,61,"But when they ňĻfinallyňļ reached the point where the seas met, they forgot their ňĻsaltedňļ fish, and it made its way into the sea, slipping away ňĻwondrouslyňļ"
  18,62,"When they had passed further, he said to his assistant, ‚ÄúBring us our meal! We have certainly been exhausted by today‚Äôs journey.‚ÄĚ"
  18,63,"He replied, ‚ÄúDo you remember when we rested by the rock? ňĻThat is whenňļ I forgot the fish. None made me forget to mention this except Satan. And the fish made its way into the sea miraculously.‚ÄĚ"
  18,64,"Moses responded, ‚ÄúThat is ňĻexactlyňļ what we were looking for.‚ÄĚ¬†So they returned, retracing their footsteps"
  18,65,"There they found a servant of Ours, to whom We had granted mercy from Us and enlightened with knowledge of Our Own"
  18,66,"Moses said to him, ‚ÄúMay I follow you, provided that you teach me some of the right guidance you have been taught?‚ÄĚ"
  18,67,"He said, ‚ÄúYou certainly cannot be patient ňĻenoughňļ with me"
  18,68,And how can you be patient with what is beyond your ňĻrealm ofňļ knowledge?‚ÄĚ
  18,69,"Moses assured ňĻhimňļ, ‚ÄúYou will find me patient, God willing, and I will not disobey any of your orders.‚ÄĚ"
  18,70,"He responded, ‚ÄúThen if you follow me, do not question me about anything until I ňĻmyselfňļ clarify it for you.‚ÄĚ"
  18,71,"So they set out, but after they had boarded a ship, the man made a hole in it. Moses protested, ‚ÄúHave you done this to drown its people? You have certainly done a terrible thing!‚ÄĚ"
  18,72,"He replied, ‚ÄúDid I not say that you cannot have patience with me?‚ÄĚ"
  18,73,"Moses pleaded, ‚ÄúExcuse me for forgetting, and do not be hard on me.‚ÄĚ"
  18,74,"So they proceeded until they came across a boy, and the man killed him. Moses protested, ‚ÄúHave you killed an innocent soul, who killed no one? You have certainly done a horrible thing.‚ÄĚ"
  18,75,"He answered, ‚ÄúDid I not tell you that you cannot have patience with me?‚ÄĚ"
  18,76,"Moses replied, ‚ÄúIf I ever question you about anything after this, then do not keep me in your company, for by then I would have given you enough of an excuse.‚ÄĚ"
  18,77,"So they moved on until they came to the people of a town. They asked them for food, but the people refused to give them hospitality. There they found a wall ready to collapse, so the man set it right. Moses protested, ‚ÄúIf you wanted, you could have demanded a fee for this.‚ÄĚ"
  18,78,"He replied, ‚ÄúThis is the parting of our ways. I will explain to you what you could not bear patiently"
  18,79,"‚ÄúAs for the ship, it belonged to some poor people, working at sea. So I intended to damage it, for there was a ňĻtyrantňļ king ahead of them who seizes every ňĻgoodňļ ship by force"
  18,80,"‚ÄúAnd as for the boy, his parents were ňĻtrueňļ believers, and we¬†feared that he would pressure them into defiance and disbelief"
  18,81,"So we hoped that their Lord would give them another, more virtuous and caring in his place"
  18,82,"‚ÄúAnd as for the wall, it belonged to two orphan boys in the city, and under the wall was a treasure that belonged to them, and their father had been a righteous man. So your Lord willed that these children should come of age and retrieve their treasure, as a mercy from your Lord. I did not do it ňĻallňļ on my own. This is the explanation of what you could not bear patiently.‚ÄĚ"
  18,83,"They ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about ‚Īęul-Qarnain. Say, ‚ÄúI will relate to you something of his narrative.‚ÄĚ"
  18,84,"Surely We established him in the land, and gave him the means to all things"
  18,85,So he travelled a course
  18,86,"until he reached the setting ňĻpointňļ of the sun, which appeared to him to be setting in a spring of murky water, where he found some people. We said, ‚ÄúO ‚Īęul-Qarnain! Either punish them or treat them kindly.‚ÄĚ"
  18,87,"He responded, ‚ÄúWhoever does wrong will be punished by us, then will be returned to their Lord, Who will punish them with a horrible torment"
  18,88,"As for those who believe and do good, they will have the finest reward, and we will assign them easy commands.‚ÄĚ"
  18,89,Then he travelled a ňĻdifferentňļ course
  18,90,until he reached the rising ňĻpointňļ of the sun. He found it rising on a people for whom We had provided no shelter from it
  18,91,So it was. And We truly had full knowledge of him
  18,92,Then he travelled a ňĻthirdňļ course
  18,93,until he reached ňĻa passňļ between two mountains. He found in front of them a people who could hardly understand ňĻhisňļ language
  18,94,"They pleaded, ‚ÄúO ‚Īęul-Qarnain! Surely Gog and Magog¬†are spreading corruption throughout the land. Should we pay you tribute, provided that you build a wall between us and them?‚ÄĚ"
  18,95,"He responded, ‚ÄúWhat my Lord has provided for me is far better. But assist me with resources, and I will build a barrier between you and them"
  18,96,"Bring me blocks of iron!‚ÄĚ Then, when he had filled up ňĻthe gapňļ between the two mountains, he ordered, ‚ÄúBlow!‚ÄĚ When the iron became red hot, he said, ‚ÄúBring me molten copper to pour over it.‚ÄĚ"
  18,97,And so the enemies could neither scale nor tunnel through it
  18,98,"He declared, ‚ÄúThis is a mercy from my Lord. But when the promise of my Lord comes to pass, He will level it to the ground. And my Lord‚Äôs promise is ever true.‚ÄĚ"
  18,99,"On that Day, We will let them¬†surge ňĻlike wavesňļ over one another. Later, the Trumpet will be blown,¬†and We will gather all ňĻpeopleňļ together"
  18,100,On that Day We will display Hell clearly for the disbelievers
  18,101,those who turned a blind eye to My Reminder¬†and could not stand listening ňĻto itňļ
  18,102,Do the disbelievers think they can ňĻsimplyňļ take My servants¬†as lords instead of Me? We have surely prepared Hell as an accommodation for the disbelievers
  18,103,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúShall we inform you of who will lose the most deeds"
  18,104,"ňĻThey areňļ those whose efforts are in vain in this worldly life, while they think they are doing good!‚ÄĚ"
  18,105,"It is they who reject the signs of their Lord and their meeting with Him, rendering their deeds void, so We will not give their deeds any weight on Judgment Day"
  18,106,"That is their reward: Hell, for their disbelief and mockery of My signs and messengers"
  18,107,"Indeed, those who believe and do good will have the Gardens of Paradise¬†as an accommodation"
  18,108,"where they will be forever, never desiring anywhere else"
  18,109,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIf the ocean were ink for ňĻwritingňļ the Words of my Lord, it would certainly run out before the Words of my Lord were finished, even if We refilled it with its equal.‚ÄĚ"
  18,110,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúI am only a man like you, ňĻbutňļ it has been revealed to me that your God is only One God. So whoever hopes for the meeting with their Lord, let them do good deeds and associate none in the worship of their Lord.‚ÄĚ"
  19,1,K√£f-Ha-Ya-‚ÄôAń©n- ŠĻĘ√£d
  19,2,ňĻThis isňļ a reminder of your Lord‚Äôs mercy to His servant Zachariah
  19,3,when he cried out to his Lord privately
  19,4,"saying, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Surely my bones have become brittle, and grey hair has spread across my head, but I have never been disappointed in my prayer to You, my Lord"
  19,5,"And I am concerned about ňĻthe faith ofňļ my relatives after me, since my wife is barren. So grant me, by Your grace, an heir"
  19,6,"who will inherit ňĻprophethoodňļ from me and the family of Jacob, and make him, O Lord, pleasing ňĻto Youňļ!‚ÄĚ"
  19,7,"ňĻThe angels announced,ňļ ‚ÄúO Zachariah! Indeed, We give you the good news of ňĻthe birth ofňļ a son, whose name will be John‚ÄĒa name We have not given to anyone before.‚ÄĚ"
  19,8,"He wondered, ‚ÄúMy Lord! How can I have a son when my wife is barren, and I have become extremely old?‚ÄĚ"
  19,9,"An angel replied, ‚ÄúSo will it be! Your Lord says, ‚ÄėIt is easy for Me, just as I created you before, when you were nothing!‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  19,10,"Zachariah said, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Grant me a sign.‚ÄĚ He responded, ‚ÄúYour sign is that you will not ňĻbe able toňļ speak to people for three nights, despite being healthy.‚ÄĚ"
  19,11,"So he came out to his people from the sanctuary, signalling to them to glorify ňĻGodňļ morning and evening"
  19,12,"ňĻIt was later said,ňļ ‚ÄúO John! Hold firmly to the Scriptures.‚ÄĚ And We granted him wisdom while ňĻhe was stillňļ a child"
  19,13,as well as purity and compassion from Us. And he was God-fearing
  19,14,and kind to his parents. He was neither arrogant nor disobedient
  19,15,"Peace be upon him the day he was born, and the day of his death, and the day he will be raised back to life"
  19,16,"And mention in the Book ňĻO Prophet, the story ofňļ Mary when she withdrew from her family to a place in the east"
  19,17,"screening herself off from them. Then We sent to her Our angel, ňĻGabriel,ňļ appearing before her as a man, perfectly formed"
  19,18,"She appealed, ‚ÄúI truly seek refuge in the Most Compassionate from you! ňĻSo leave me aloneňļ if you are God-fearing.‚ÄĚ"
  19,19,"He responded, ‚ÄúI am only a messenger from your Lord, ňĻsentňļ to bless you with a pure son.‚ÄĚ"
  19,20,"She wondered, ‚ÄúHow can I have a son when no man has ever touched me, nor am I unchaste?‚ÄĚ"
  19,21,"He replied, ‚ÄúSo will it be! Your Lord says, ‚ÄėIt is easy for Me. And so will We make him a sign for humanity and a mercy from Us.‚Äô It is a matter ňĻalreadyňļ decreed.‚ÄĚ"
  19,22,So she conceived him and withdrew with him to a remote place
  19,23,"Then the pains of labour drove her to the trunk of a palm tree. She cried, ‚ÄúAlas! I wish I had died before this, and was a thing long forgotten!‚ÄĚ"
  19,24,"So a voice¬†reassured her from below her, ‚ÄúDo not grieve! Your Lord has provided a stream at your feet"
  19,25,"And shake the trunk of this palm tree towards you, it will drop fresh, ripe dates upon you"
  19,26,"So eat and drink, and put your heart at ease. But if you see any of the people, say, ‚ÄėI have vowed silence¬†to the Most Compassionate, so I am not talking to anyone today.‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  19,27,"Then she returned to her people, carrying him. They said ňĻin shockňļ, ‚ÄúO Mary! You have certainly done a horrible thing"
  19,28,"O sister of Aaron!¬†Your father was not an indecent man, nor was your mother unchaste.‚ÄĚ"
  19,29,"So she pointed to the baby. They exclaimed, ‚ÄúHow can we talk to someone who is an infant in the cradle?‚ÄĚ"
  19,30,"ňĻJesusňļ declared, ‚ÄúI am truly a servant of God. He has destined me to be given the Scripture and to be a prophet"
  19,31,"He has made me a blessing wherever I go, and bid me to establish prayer and give alms-tax as long as I live"
  19,32,and to be kind to my mother. He has not made me arrogant or defiant
  19,33,"Peace be upon me the day I was born, the day I die, and the day I will be raised back to life!‚ÄĚ"
  19,34,"That is Jesus, son of Mary. ňĻAnd this isňļ a word of truth, about which they dispute"
  19,35,"It is not for God to take a son! Glory be to Him. When He decrees a matter, He simply tells it, ‚ÄúBe!‚ÄĚ And it is"
  19,36,"ňĻJesus also declared,ňļ ‚ÄúSurely God is my Lord and your Lord, so worship Him ňĻaloneňļ. This is the Straight Path.‚ÄĚ"
  19,37,"Yet their ňĻvariousňļ groups have differed among themselves ňĻabout himňļ, so woe to the disbelievers when they face a tremendous Day"
  19,38,How clearly will they hear and see on the Day they will come to Us! But today the wrongdoers are clearly astray
  19,39,"And warn them ňĻO Prophetňļ of the Day of Regret, when all matters will be settled, while they are ňĻengrossedňļ in heedlessness and disbelief"
  19,40,"Indeed, it is We Who will succeed the earth and whoever is on it. And to Us they will ňĻallňļ be returned"
  19,41,"And mention in the Book ňĻO Prophet, the story ofňļ Abraham. He was surely a man of truth and a prophet"
  19,42,"ňĻRememberňļ when he said to his father, ‚ÄúO dear father! Why do you worship what can neither hear nor see, nor benefit you at all"
  19,43,"O dear father! I have certainly received some knowledge which you have not received, so follow me and I will guide you to the Straight Path"
  19,44,O dear father! Do not worship Satan. Surely Satan is ever rebellious against the Most Compassionate
  19,45,"O dear father! I truly fear that you will be touched by a torment from the Most Compassionate, and become Satan‚Äôs companion ňĻin Hellňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  19,46,"He threatened, ‚ÄúHow dare you reject my idols, O Abraham! If you do not desist, I will certainly stone you ňĻto deathňļ. So be gone from me for a long time!‚ÄĚ"
  19,47,"Abraham responded, ‚ÄúPeace be upon you! I will pray to my Lord for your forgiveness. He has truly been Most Gracious to me"
  19,48,"As I distance myself from ňĻall ofňļ you and from whatever you invoke besides God, I will ňĻcontinue toňļ call upon my Lord ňĻaloneňļ, trusting that I will never be disappointed in invoking my Lord.‚ÄĚ"
  19,49,"So after he had left them and what they worshipped besides God, We granted him Isaac and Jacob, and made each of them a prophet"
  19,50,"We showered them with Our mercy, and blessed them with honourable mention"
  19,51,"And mention in the Book ňĻO Prophet, the story ofňļ Moses. He was truly a chosen man, and was a messenger and a prophet"
  19,52,"We called him from the right side of Mount ŠĻ¨√Ľr, and drew him near, speaking ňĻwith himňļ directly"
  19,53,"And We appointed for him‚ÄĒout of Our grace‚ÄĒhis brother, Aaron, as a prophet"
  19,54,"And mention in the Book ňĻO Prophet, the story ofňļ Ishmael. He was truly a man of his word, and was a messenger and a prophet"
  19,55,He used to urge his people to pray and give alms-tax. And his Lord was well pleased with him
  19,56,"And mention in the Book ňĻO Prophet, the story ofňļ Enoch. He was surely a man of truth and a prophet"
  19,57,And We elevated him to an honourable status
  19,58,"Those were ňĻsome ofňļ the prophets who God has blessed from among the descendants of Adam, and of those We carried with Noah ňĻin the Arkňļ, and of the descendants of Abraham and Israel,¬†and of those We ňĻrightlyňļ guided and chose. Whenever the revelations of the Most Compassionate were recited to them, they fell down, prostrating and weeping"
  19,59,But they were succeeded by generations who neglected prayer and followed their lusts and so will soon face the evil consequences
  19,60,"As for those who repent, believe, and do good, it is they who will be admitted into Paradise, never being denied any reward"
  19,61,"ňĻThey will be inňļ the Gardens of Eternity, promised in trust by the Most Compassionate to His servants. Surely His promise will be fulfilled"
  19,62,There they will never hear any idle talk‚ÄĒonly ňĻgreetings ofňļ peace. And there they will have their provisions morning and evening
  19,63,"That is Paradise, which We will grant to whoever is devout among Our servants"
  19,64,"‚ÄúWe only descend by the command of your Lord. To Him belongs whatever is before us, and whatever is behind us, and everything in between. And your Lord is never forgetful"
  19,65,"ňĻHe is theňļ Lord of the heavens, and the earth, and everything in between. So worship Him ňĻaloneňļ, and be steadfast in His worship. Do you know of anyone equal to Him ňĻin His attributesňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  19,66,"Yet ňĻsomeňļ people ask ňĻmockinglyňļ, ‚ÄúAfter I die, will I really be raised to life again?‚ÄĚ"
  19,67,"Do ňĻsuchňļ people not remember that We created them before, when they were nothing"
  19,68,"By your Lord ňĻO Prophetňļ! We will surely gather them along with the devils, and then set them around Hell on their knees"
  19,69,Then We will certainly begin by dragging out of every group the ones most defiant to the Most Compassionate
  19,70,And We truly know best who is most deserving of burning in it
  19,71,There is none of you who will not pass over it.¬†ňĻThis isňļ a decree your Lord must fulfil
  19,72,"Then We will deliver those who were devout, leaving the wrongdoers there on their knees"
  19,73,"When Our clear revelations are recited to them, the disbelievers ask the believers ňĻmockinglyňļ, ‚ÄúWhich of the two of us is better in status and superior in assembly?‚ÄĚ"
  19,74,"ňĻImagine, O Prophetňļ how many peoples We have destroyed before them, who were far better in luxury and splendour"
  19,75,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWhoever is ňĻentrenchedňļ in misguidance, the Most Compassionate will allow them plenty of time, until‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒthey face what they are threatened with: either the torment or the Hour. Only then will they realize who is worse in position and inferior in manpower.‚ÄĚ"
  19,76,And God increases in guidance those who are ňĻrightlyňļ guided. And the everlasting good deeds are far better with your Lord in reward and in outcome
  19,77,"Have you seen ňĻO Prophetňļ the one¬†who rejects Our revelations yet boasts, ‚ÄúI will definitely be granted ňĻplenty ofňļ wealth and children ňĻif there is an afterlifeňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  19,78,Has he looked into the unseen or taken a pledge from the Most Compassionate
  19,79,Not at all! We certainly record whatever he claims and will increase his punishment extensively
  19,80,"And We will inherit what he boasts of, and he will come before Us all by himself"
  19,81,"They have taken other gods, instead of God, seeking strength ňĻand protectionňļ through them"
  19,82,But no! Those ňĻgodsňļ will deny their worship and turn against them
  19,83,"Do you ňĻO Prophetňļ not see that We have sent the devils against the disbelievers, constantly inciting them"
  19,84,"So do not be in haste against them, for indeed We are ňĻcloselyňļ counting down their days"
  19,85,ňĻWatch forňļ the Day We will gather the righteous before the Most Compassionate as an honoured delegation
  19,86,and drive the wicked to Hell like a thirsty herd
  19,87,"None will have the right to intercede, except those who have taken a covenant from the Most Compassionate"
  19,88,"They¬†say, ‚ÄúThe Most Compassionate has offspring.‚ÄĚ"
  19,89,You have certainly made an outrageous claim
  19,90,"by which the heavens are about to burst, the earth to split apart, and the mountains to crumble to pieces"
  19,91,in protest of attributing children to the Most Compassionate
  19,92,It does not befit ňĻthe majesty ofňļ the Most Compassionate to have children
  19,93,There is none in the heavens or the earth who will not return to the Most Compassionate in full submission
  19,94,"Indeed, He fully knows them and has counted them precisely"
  19,95,And each of them will return to Him on the Day of Judgment all alone
  19,96,"As for those who believe and do good, the Most Compassionate will ňĻcertainlyňļ bless them with ňĻgenuineňļ love"
  19,97,"Indeed, We have made this ňĻQuranňļ easy in your own language ňĻO Prophetňļ so with it you may give good news to the righteous and warn those who are contentious"
  19,98,"ňĻImagineňļ how many peoples We have destroyed before them! Do you ňĻstillňļ see any of them, or ňĻevenňļ hear from them the slightest sound"
  20,1,ŠĻ¨√Ę-H√Ę
  20,2,We have not revealed the Quran to you ňĻO Prophetňļ to cause you distress
  20,3,but as a reminder to those in awe ňĻof Godňļ
  20,4,ňĻIt isňļ a revelation from the One Who created the earth and the high heavens‚ÄĒ
  20,5,"the Most Compassionate, ňĻWho isňļ established on the Throne"
  20,6,To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth and whatever is in between and whatever is underground
  20,7,"Whether you speak openly ňĻor notňļ, He certainly knows what is secret and what is even more hidden"
  20,8,God‚ÄĒthere is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. He has the Most Beautiful Names
  20,9,Has the story of Moses reached you ňĻO Prophetňļ
  20,10,"When he saw a fire, he said to his family, ‚ÄúWait here, ňĻforňļ I have spotted¬†a fire. Perhaps I can bring you a torch from it, or find some guidance at the fire.‚ÄĚ"
  20,11,"But when he approached it, he was called, ‚ÄúO Moses"
  20,12,"It is truly I. I am your Lord! So take off your sandals, for you are in the sacred valley of ŠĻ¨uwa"
  20,13,"I have chosen you, so listen to what is revealed"
  20,14,"‚ÄėIt is truly I. I am God! There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Me. So worship Me ňĻaloneňļ, and establish prayer for My remembrance"
  20,15,"The Hour is sure to come. My Will is to keep it hidden, so that every soul may be rewarded according to their efforts"
  20,16,"So do not let those who disbelieve in it and follow their desires distract you from it, or you will be doomed.‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  20,17,"ňĻGod added,ňļ ‚ÄúAnd what is that in your right hand, O Moses?‚ÄĚ"
  20,18,"He replied, ‚ÄúIt is my staff! I lean on it, and with it I beat down ňĻbranchesňļ for my sheep, and have other uses for it.‚ÄĚ"
  20,19,"God said, ‚ÄúThrow it down, O Moses!‚ÄĚ"
  20,20,"So he did, then‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒit became a serpent, slithering"
  20,21,"God said, ‚ÄúTake it, and have no fear. We will return it to its former state"
  20,22,"And put your hand under your armpit, it will come out ňĻshiningňļ white, unblemished,¬†as another sign"
  20,23,so that We may show you some of Our greatest signs
  20,24,"Go to Pharaoh, for he has truly transgressed ňĻall boundsňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  20,25,"Moses prayed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Uplift my heart for me"
  20,26,and make my task easy
  20,27,and remove the impediment from my tongue
  20,28,so people may understand my speech
  20,29,and grant me a helper from my family
  20,30,"Aaron, my brother"
  20,31,Strengthen me through him
  20,32,and let him share my task
  20,33,so that we may glorify You much
  20,34,and remember You much
  20,35,for truly You have ňĻalwaysňļ been overseeing us.‚ÄĚ
  20,36,"God responded, ‚ÄúAll that you requested has been granted, O Moses"
  20,37,And surely We had shown You favour before
  20,38,when We inspired your mother with this
  20,39,"‚ÄėPut him into a chest, then put it into the river. The river will wash it ashore, and he will be taken by ňĻPharaoh,ňļ an enemy of Mine and his.‚Äô And I blessed you with lovability from Me¬†ňĻO Mosesňļ so that you would be brought up under My ňĻwatchfulňļ Eye"
  20,40,"ňĻRememberňļ when your sister came along and proposed, ‚ÄėShall I direct you to someone who will nurse him?‚Äô¬†So We reunited you with your mother so that her heart would be put at ease, and she would not grieve. ňĻLaterňļ you killed a man ňĻby mistakeňļ, but We saved you from sorrow, as well as other tests We put you through. Then you stayed for a number of years among the people of Midian. Then you came here as pre-destined, O Moses"
  20,41,And I have selected you for My service
  20,42,"Go forth, you and your brother, with My signs and never falter in remembering Me"
  20,43,"Go, both of you, to Pharaoh, for he has truly transgressed ňĻall boundsňļ"
  20,44,"Speak to him gently, so perhaps he may be mindful ňĻof Meňļ or fearful ňĻof My punishmentňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  20,45,"They both pleaded, ‚ÄúOur Lord! We fear that he may be quick to harm us or act tyrannically.‚ÄĚ"
  20,46,"God reassured ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúHave no fear! I am with you, hearing and seeing"
  20,47,"So go to him and say, ‚ÄėIndeed we are both messengers from your Lord, so let the Children of Israel go with us, and do not oppress them. We have come to you with a sign from your Lord. And salvation will be for whoever follows the ňĻrightňļ guidance"
  20,48,It has indeed been revealed to us that the punishment will be upon whoever denies ňĻthe truthňļ and turns away.‚Äô‚ÄĚ
  20,49,"Pharaoh asked, ‚ÄúWho then is the Lord of you two, O Moses?‚ÄĚ"
  20,50,"He answered, ‚ÄúOur Lord is the One Who has given everything its ňĻdistinctiveňļ form, then guided ňĻitňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  20,51,"Pharaoh asked, ‚ÄúAnd what about previous peoples?‚ÄĚ"
  20,52,"He replied, ‚ÄúThat knowledge is with my Lord in a Record. My Lord neither falters¬†nor forgets ňĻanythingňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  20,53,"ňĻHe is the Oneňļ Who has laid out the earth for ňĻall ofňļ you, and set in it pathways for you, and sends down rain from the sky, causing various types of plants to grow"
  20,54,ňĻsoňļ eat and graze your cattle. Surely in this are signs for people of sound judgment
  20,55,"From the earth We created you, and into it We will return you, and from it We will bring you back again"
  20,56,"And We certainly showed Pharaoh all of Our signs,¬†but he denied them and refused ňĻto believeňļ"
  20,57,"He said, ‚ÄúHave you come to drive us out of our land with your magic, O Moses"
  20,58,"We can surely meet you with similar magic. So set for us an appointment that neither of us will fail to keep, in a central place.‚ÄĚ"
  20,59,"Moses said, ‚ÄúYour appointment is on the Day of the Festival, and let the people be gathered mid-morning.‚ÄĚ"
  20,60,"Pharaoh then withdrew, orchestrated his scheme, then returned"
  20,61,"Moses warned the magicians, ‚ÄúWoe to you! Do not fabricate a lie against God,¬†or He will wipe you out with a torment. Whoever fabricates ňĻliesňļ is bound to fail.‚ÄĚ"
  20,62,"So the magicians disputed the matter among themselves, conversing privately"
  20,63,"They concluded, ‚ÄúThese two are only magicians who want to drive you out of your land with their magic, and do away with your most cherished traditions"
  20,64,"So orchestrate your plan, then come forward in ňĻperfectňļ ranks. And whoever prevails today will certainly be successful.‚ÄĚ"
  20,65,"They said, ‚ÄúO Moses! Either you cast, or let us be the first to cast.‚ÄĚ"
  20,66,"Moses responded, ‚ÄúNo, you go first.‚ÄĚ And suddenly their ropes and staffs appeared to him‚ÄĒby their magic‚ÄĒto be slithering"
  20,67,So Moses concealed fear within himself
  20,68,"We reassured ňĻhimňļ, ‚ÄúDo not fear! It is certainly you who will prevail"
  20,69,"Cast what is in your right hand, and it will swallow up what they have made, for what they have made is no more than a magic trick. And magicians can never succeed wherever they go.‚ÄĚ"
  20,70,"So the magicians fell down in prostration, declaring, ‚ÄúWe believe in the Lord of Aaron and Moses.‚ÄĚ"
  20,71,"Pharaoh threatened, ‚ÄúHow dare you believe in him before I give you permission? He must be your master who taught you magic. I will certainly cut off your hands and feet on opposite sides, and crucify you on the trunks of palm trees. You will really see whose punishment is more severe and more lasting.‚ÄĚ"
  20,72,"They responded, ‚ÄúBy the One Who created us! We will never prefer you over the clear proofs that have come to us. So do whatever you want! Your authority only covers the ňĻfleetingňļ life of this world"
  20,73,"Indeed, we have believed in our Lord so He may forgive our sins and that magic you have forced us to practice. And God is far superior ňĻin rewardňļ and more lasting ňĻin punishmentňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  20,74,"Whoever comes to their Lord as an evildoer will certainly have Hell, where they can neither live nor die"
  20,75,"But whoever comes to Him as a believer, having done good, they will have the highest ranks"
  20,76,"the Gardens of Eternity, under which rivers flow, where they will stay forever. That is the reward of those who purify themselves"
  20,77,"And We surely inspired Moses, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúLeave with My servants ňĻat nightňļ and strike a dry passage for them across the sea. Have no fear of being overtaken, nor be concerned ňĻof drowningňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  20,78,Then Pharaoh pursued them with his soldiers‚ÄĒbut how overwhelming were the waters that submerged them
  20,79,"And ňĻsoňļ Pharaoh led his people astray, and did not guide ňĻthem rightlyňļ"
  20,80,"O Children of Israel! We saved you from your enemy, and made an appointment with you¬†on the right side of Mount ŠĻ¨√Ľr, and sent down to you manna and quails"
  20,81,"ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúEat from the good things We have provided for you, but do not transgress in them, or My wrath will befall you. And whoever My wrath befalls is certainly doomed"
  20,82,"But I am truly Most Forgiving to whoever repents, believes, and does good, then persists on ňĻtrueňļ guidance.‚ÄĚ"
  20,83,"ňĻGod asked,ňļ ‚ÄúWhy have you come with such haste ahead of your people, O Moses?‚ÄĚ"
  20,84,"He replied, ‚ÄúThey are close on my tracks. And I have hastened to You, my Lord, so You will be pleased.‚ÄĚ"
  20,85,"God responded, ‚ÄúWe have indeed tested your people in your absence, and the S√Ęmiri¬†has led them astray.‚ÄĚ"
  20,86,"So Moses returned to his people, furious and sorrowful. He said, ‚ÄúO my people! Had your Lord not made you a good promise?¬†Has my absence been too long for you? Or have you wished for wrath from your Lord to befall you, so you broke your promise to me?‚ÄĚ"
  20,87,"They argued, ‚ÄúWe did not break our promise to you of our own free will, but we were made to carry the burden of the people‚Äôs ňĻgoldenňļ jewellery,¬†then we threw it ňĻinto the fireňļ, and so did the S√Ęmiri.‚ÄĚ"
  20,88,"Then he moulded for them an idol of a calf that made a lowing sound. They said, ‚ÄúThis is your god and the god of Moses, but Moses forgot ňĻwhere it wasňļ!‚ÄĚ"
  20,89,"Did they not see that it did not respond to them, nor could it protect or benefit them"
  20,90,"Aaron had already warned them beforehand, ‚ÄúO my people! You are only being tested by this, for indeed your ňĻone trueňļ Lord is the Most Compassionate. So follow me and obey my orders.‚ÄĚ"
  20,91,"They replied, ‚ÄúWe will not cease to worship it until Moses returns to us.‚ÄĚ"
  20,92,"Moses scolded ňĻhis brotherňļ, ‚ÄúO Aaron! What prevented you, when you saw them going astray"
  20,93,from following after me? How could you disobey my orders?‚ÄĚ
  20,94,"Aaron pleaded, ‚ÄúO son of my mother! Do not seize me by my beard or ňĻthe hair ofňļ my head. I really feared that you would say, ‚ÄėYou have caused division among the Children of Israel, and did not observe my word.‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  20,95,"Moses then asked, ‚ÄúWhat did you think you were doing, O S√Ęmiri?‚ÄĚ"
  20,96,"He said, ‚ÄúI saw what they did not see, so I took a handful ňĻof dustňļ from the hoof-prints of ňĻthe horse ofňļ the messenger-angel ňĻGabrielňļ then cast it ňĻon the moulded calfňļ. This is what my lower-self tempted me into.‚ÄĚ"
  20,97,"Moses said, ‚ÄúGo away then! And for ňĻthe rest of yourňļ life you will surely be crying, ‚ÄėDo not touch ňĻmeňļ!‚Äô¬†Then you will certainly have a fate¬†that you cannot escape. Now look at your god to which you have been devoted: we will burn it up, then scatter it in the sea completely.‚ÄĚ"
  20,98,"ňĻThen Moses addressed his people,ňļ ‚ÄúYour only god is God, there is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him. He encompasses everything in ňĻHisňļ knowledge.‚ÄĚ"
  20,99,This is how We relate to you ňĻO Prophetňļ some of the stories of the past. And We have certainly granted you a Reminder¬†from Us
  20,100,Whoever turns away from it will surely bear the burden ňĻof sinňļ on the Day of Judgment
  20,101,suffering its consequences forever. What an evil burden they will carry on Judgment Day
  20,102,"ňĻBeware ofňļ the Day the Trumpet will be blown,¬†and We will gather the wicked on that Day blue-faced ňĻfrom horror and thirstňļ"
  20,103,"They will whisper among themselves, ‚ÄúYou stayed no more than ten days ňĻon the earthňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  20,104,"We know best what they will say‚ÄĒthe most reasonable of them will say, ‚ÄúYou stayed no more than a day.‚ÄĚ"
  20,105,"And ňĻifňļ they ask you ňĻO Prophetňļ about the mountains, ňĻthenňļ say, ‚ÄúMy Lord will wipe them out completely"
  20,106,leaving the earth level and bare
  20,107,with neither depressions nor elevations to be seen.‚ÄĚ
  20,108,"On that Day all will follow the caller ňĻfor assemblyňļ, ňĻandňļ none will dare to deviate. All voices will be hushed before the Most Compassionate. Only whispers¬†will be heard"
  20,109,"On that Day no intercession will be of any benefit, except by those granted permission by the Most Compassionate and whose words are agreeable to Him"
  20,110,"He ňĻfullyňļ knows what is ahead of them and what is behind them,¬†but they cannot encompass Him in ňĻtheirňļ knowledge"
  20,111,"And all faces will be humbled before the Ever-Living, All-Sustaining. And those burdened with wrongdoing will be in loss"
  20,112,But whoever does good and is a believer will have no fear of being wronged or denied ňĻtheir rewardňļ
  20,113,"And so We have sent it down as an Arabic Quran and varied the warnings in it, so perhaps they will shun evil or it may cause them to be mindful"
  20,114,"Exalted is God, the True King! Do not rush to recite ňĻa revelation ofňļ the Quran ňĻO Prophetňļ before it is ňĻproperlyňļ conveyed to you,¬†and pray, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Increase me in knowledge.‚ÄĚ"
  20,115,"And indeed, We once made a covenant with Adam, but he forgot, and ňĻsoňļ We did not find determination in him"
  20,116,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We said to the angels, ‚ÄúProstrate before Adam,‚ÄĚ so they all did‚ÄĒbut not Ibl√ģs,¬†who refused ňĻarrogantlyňļ"
  20,117,"So We cautioned, ‚ÄúO Adam! This is surely an enemy to you and to your wife. So do not let him drive you both out of Paradise, for you ňĻO Adamňļ would then suffer ňĻhardshipňļ"
  20,118,Here it is guaranteed that you will never go hungry or unclothed
  20,119,nor will you ňĻeverňļ suffer from thirst or ňĻthe sun‚Äôsňļ heat.‚ÄĚ
  20,120,"But Satan whispered to him, saying, ‚ÄúO Adam! Shall I show you the Tree of Immortality and a kingdom that does not fade away?‚ÄĚ"
  20,121,"So they both ate from the tree and then their nakedness was exposed to them, prompting them to cover themselves with leaves from Paradise. So Adam disobeyed his Lord, and ňĻsoňļ lost his way"
  20,122,"Then his Lord chose him ňĻfor His graceňļ, accepted his repentance, and guided him ňĻrightlyňļ"
  20,123,"God said, ‚ÄúDescend, both of you, from here together ňĻwith Satanňļ as enemies to each other. Then when guidance comes to you from Me, whoever follows My guidance will neither go astray ňĻin this lifeňļ nor suffer ňĻin the nextňļ"
  20,124,"But whoever turns away from My Reminder will certainly have a miserable life,¬†then We will raise them up blind on the Day of Judgment.‚ÄĚ"
  20,125,"They will cry, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Why have you raised me up blind, although I used to see?‚ÄĚ"
  20,126,"God will respond, ‚ÄúIt is so, just as Our revelations came to you and you neglected them, so Today you are neglected.‚ÄĚ"
  20,127,This is how We reward whoever transgresses and does not believe in the revelations of their Lord. And the punishment of the Hereafter is far more severe and more lasting
  20,128,"Is it not yet clear to them how many peoples We destroyed before them, whose ruins they still pass by? Surely in this are signs for people of sound judgment"
  20,129,"Had it not been for a prior decree from your Lord¬†ňĻO Prophetňļ and a term already set, their ňĻinstantňļ doom would have been inevitable"
  20,130,"So be patient ňĻO Prophetňļ with what they say. And glorify the praises of your Lord before sunrise and before sunset, and glorify Him in the hours of the night and at both ends of the day,¬†so that you may be pleased ňĻwith the rewardňļ"
  20,131,"Do not let your eyes crave what We have allowed some of the disbelievers to enjoy; the ňĻfleetingňļ splendour of this worldly life, which We test them with. But your Lord‚Äôs provision ňĻin the Hereafterňļ is far better and more lasting"
  20,132,"Bid your people to pray, and be diligent in ňĻobservingňļ it. We do not ask you to provide. It is We Who provide for you. And the ultimate outcome is ňĻonlyňļ for ňĻthe people ofňļ righteousness"
  20,133,"They demand, ‚ÄúIf only he could bring us a sign from his Lord!‚ÄĚ¬†Have they not ňĻalreadyňļ received a confirmation of what is in earlier Scriptures"
  20,134,"Had We destroyed them with a torment before this ňĻProphet cameňļ, they would have surely argued, ‚ÄúOur Lord! If only You had sent us a messenger, we would have followed Your revelations before being humiliated and put to shame.‚ÄĚ"
  20,135,"Say ňĻto them, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúEach ňĻof usňļ is waiting, so keep waiting! You will soon know who is on the Straight Path and is ňĻrightlyňļ guided.‚ÄĚ"
  21,1,"ňĻThe time ofňļ people‚Äôs judgment has drawn near, yet they are heedlessly turning away"
  21,2,"Whatever new reminder comes to them from their Lord, they only listen to it jokingly"
  21,3,"with their hearts ňĻtotallyňļ distracted. The evildoers would converse secretly, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúIs this ňĻoneňļ not human like yourselves? Would you fall for ňĻthisňļ witchcraft, even though you can ňĻclearlyňļ see?‚ÄĚ"
  21,4,"The Prophet responded, ‚ÄúMy Lord ňĻfullyňļ knows every word spoken in the heavens and the earth. For He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.‚ÄĚ"
  21,5,"Yet they say, ‚ÄúThis ňĻQuranňļ is a set of confused dreams! No, he has fabricated it! No, he must be a poet! So let him bring us a ňĻtangibleňļ sign like those ňĻprophetsňļ sent before.‚ÄĚ"
  21,6,Not a ňĻsingleňļ society We destroyed before them ever believed ňĻafter receiving the signsňļ. Will these ňĻpagansňļ then believe
  21,7,"We did not send ňĻmessengersňļ before you ňĻO Prophetňļ except mere men inspired by Us. If you ňĻpolytheistsňļ do not know ňĻthis alreadyňļ, then ask those who have knowledge ňĻof the Scripturesňļ"
  21,8,"We did not give those messengers ňĻsupernaturalňļ bodies that did not need food, nor were they immortal"
  21,9,"Then We fulfilled Our promise to them, saving them along with whoever We willed and destroying the transgressors"
  21,10,"We have surely revealed to you a Book, in which there is glory for you. Will you not then understand"
  21,11,"ňĻImagineňļ how many societies of wrongdoers We have destroyed, raising up other people after them"
  21,12,"When the wrongdoers sensed ňĻthe arrival ofňļ Our torment, they started to run away from their cities"
  21,13,"ňĻThey were told,ňļ ‚ÄúDo not run away! Return to your luxuries and your homes, so you may be questioned ňĻabout your fateňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  21,14,"They cried, ‚ÄúWoe to us! We have surely been wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  21,15,"They kept repeating their cry until We mowed them down, ňĻleaving themňļ lifeless"
  21,16,We did not create the heavens and the earth and everything in between for sport
  21,17,"Had We intended to take ňĻsomeňļ amusement, We could have found it in Our presence, if that had been Our Will"
  21,18,"In fact, We hurl the truth against falsehood, leaving it crushed, and it quickly vanishes. And woe be to you for what you claim"
  21,19,"To Him belong all those in the heavens and the earth. And those nearest to Him are not too proud to worship Him, nor do they tire"
  21,20,"They glorify ňĻHimňļ day and night, never wavering"
  21,21,"Or have they taken gods from the earth, who can raise the dead"
  21,22,"Had there been other gods besides God in the heavens or the earth, both ňĻrealmsňļ would have surely been corrupted. So Glorified is God, Lord of the Throne, far above what they claim"
  21,23,"He cannot be questioned about what He does, but they will ňĻallňļ be questioned"
  21,24,"Or have they taken other gods besides Him? Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúShow ňĻmeňļ your proof. Here is ňĻthe Quran,ňļ the Reminder for those with me; along with ňĻearlier Scriptures,ňļ the Reminder for those before me.‚ÄĚ¬†But most of them do not know the truth, so they turn away"
  21,25,"We never sent a messenger before you ňĻO Prophetňļ without revealing to him: ‚ÄúThere is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Me, so worship Me ňĻaloneňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  21,26,"And they say, ‚ÄúThe Most Compassionate has offspring!‚ÄĚ¬†Glory be to Him! In fact, those ňĻangelsňļ are only ňĻHisňļ honoured servants"
  21,27,"who do not speak until He has spoken, ňĻonlyňļ acting at His command"
  21,28,"He ňĻfullyňļ knows what is ahead of them and what is behind them. They do not intercede except for whom He approves, and they tremble in awe of Him"
  21,29,"Whoever of them were to say, ‚ÄúI am a god besides Him,‚ÄĚ they would be rewarded with Hell by Us. This is how We reward the wrongdoers"
  21,30,Do the disbelievers not realize that the heavens and earth were ňĻonceňļ one mass then We split them apart?¬†And We created from water every living thing. Will they not then believe
  21,31,"And We have placed firm mountains upon the earth so it does not shake with them, and made in it broad pathways so they may find their way"
  21,32,"And We have made the sky a well-protected canopy, still they turn away from its signs"
  21,33,"And He is the One Who created the day and the night, the sun and the moon‚ÄĒeach travelling in an orbit"
  21,34,"We have not granted immortality to any human before you ňĻO Prophetňļ: so if you die, will they live forever"
  21,35,"Every soul will taste death. And We test you ňĻO humanityňļ with good and evil as a trial, then to Us you will ňĻallňļ be returned"
  21,36,"When the disbelievers see you ňĻO Prophetňļ, they only make fun of you, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúIs this the one who speaks ňĻillňļ of your gods?‚ÄĚ while they disbelieve at the mention of the Most Compassionate"
  21,37,"Humankind is made of haste. I will soon show you My signs, so do not ask Me to hasten them"
  21,38,"They ask ňĻthe believersňļ, ‚ÄúWhen will this threat come to pass if what you say is true?‚ÄĚ"
  21,39,"If only the disbelievers knew that a time will come when they will not be able to keep the Fire off their faces or backs, nor will they be helped"
  21,40,"In fact, the Hour will take them by surprise, leaving them stunned. So they will not be able to avert it, nor will it be delayed from them"
  21,41,"ňĻOtherňļ messengers had already been ridiculed before you ňĻO Prophetňļ, but those who mocked them were overtaken by what they used to ridicule"
  21,42,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúWho can defend you by day or by night against the Most Compassionate?‚ÄĚ Still they turn away from the remembrance of their Lord"
  21,43,"Or do they have gods‚ÄĒother than Us‚ÄĒthat can protect them? They cannot ňĻevenňļ protect themselves, nor will they be aided against Us"
  21,44,"In fact, We have allowed enjoyment for these ňĻMeccansňļ and their forefathers for such a long time ňĻthat they took it for grantedňļ. Do they not see that We gradually reduce ňĻtheirňļ land from its borders? Is it they who will then prevail"
  21,45,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúI warn you only by revelation.‚ÄĚ But the deaf cannot hear the call when they are warned"
  21,46,"If they were touched by even a breath of your Lord‚Äôs torment, they would certainly cry, ‚ÄúWoe to us! We have really been wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  21,47,"We will set up the scales of justice on the Day of Judgment, so no soul will be wronged in the least. And ňĻevenňļ if a deed is the weight of a mustard seed, We will bring it forth. And sufficient are We as a ňĻvigilantňļ Reckoner"
  21,48,"Indeed, We granted Moses and Aaron the standard ňĻto distinguish between right and wrongňļ‚ÄĒa light and a reminder for the righteous"
  21,49,"who are in awe of their Lord without seeing Him,¬†and are fearful of the Hour"
  21,50,And this ňĻQuranňļ is a blessed reminder which We have revealed. Will you ňĻpagansňļ then deny it
  21,51,"And indeed, We had granted Abraham sound judgment early on, for We knew him well ňĻto be worthy of itňļ"
  21,52,"ňĻRememberňļ when he questioned his father and his people, ‚ÄúWhat are these statues to which you are so devoted?‚ÄĚ"
  21,53,"They replied, ‚ÄúWe found our forefathers worshipping them.‚ÄĚ"
  21,54,"He responded, ‚ÄúIndeed, you and your forefathers have been clearly astray.‚ÄĚ"
  21,55,"They asked, ‚ÄúHave you come to us with the truth, or is this a joke?‚ÄĚ"
  21,56,"He replied, ‚ÄúIn fact, your Lord is the Lord of the heavens and the earth, Who created them ňĻbothňļ. And to that I bear witness.‚ÄĚ"
  21,57,"ňĻThen he said to himself,ňļ ‚ÄúBy God! I will surely plot against your idols after you have turned your backs and gone away.‚ÄĚ"
  21,58,"So he smashed them into pieces, except the biggest of them, so they might turn to it ňĻfor answersňļ"
  21,59,"They protested, ‚ÄúWho dared do this to our gods? It must be an evildoer!‚ÄĚ"
  21,60,"Some said, ‚ÄúWe heard a young man, called Abraham, speaking ňĻillňļ of them.‚ÄĚ"
  21,61,"They demanded, ‚ÄúBring him before the eyes of the people, so that they may witness ňĻhis trialňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  21,62,"They asked, ‚ÄúWas it you who did this to our gods, O Abraham?‚ÄĚ"
  21,63,"He replied ňĻsarcasticallyňļ, ‚ÄúNo, this one‚ÄĒthe biggest of them‚ÄĒdid it! So ask them, if they can talk!‚ÄĚ"
  21,64,"So they came back to their senses, saying ňĻto one anotherňļ, ‚ÄúYou yourselves are truly the wrongdoers!‚ÄĚ"
  21,65,"Then they ňĻquicklyňļ regressed to their ňĻoriginalňļ mind-set, ňĻarguing,ňļ ‚ÄúYou already know that those ňĻidolsňļ cannot talk.‚ÄĚ"
  21,66,"He rebuked ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúDo you then worship‚ÄĒinstead of God‚ÄĒwhat can neither benefit nor harm you in any way"
  21,67,Shame on you and whatever you worship instead of God! Do you not have any sense?‚ÄĚ
  21,68,"They concluded, ‚ÄúBurn him up to avenge your gods, if you must act.‚ÄĚ"
  21,69,"We ordered, ‚ÄúO fire! Be cool and safe for Abraham!‚ÄĚ"
  21,70,"They had sought to harm him, but We made them the worst losers"
  21,71,"Then We delivered him, along with Lot, to the land We had showered with blessings for all people"
  21,72,"And We blessed him with Isaac ňĻas a sonňļ and Jacob ňĻas a grandsonňļ, as an additional favour‚ÄĒmaking all of them righteous"
  21,73,"We ňĻalsoňļ made them leaders, guiding by Our command, and inspired them to do good deeds, establish prayer, and pay alms-tax. And they were devoted to Our worship"
  21,74,"And to Lot We gave wisdom and knowledge, and delivered him from the society engrossed in shameful practices. They were certainly an evil, rebellious people"
  21,75,"And We admitted him into Our mercy, ňĻforňļ he was truly one of the righteous"
  21,76,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Noah had cried out to Us earlier, so We responded to him and delivered him and his family¬†from the great distress"
  21,77,"And We made him prevail over those who had rejected Our signs. They were truly an evil people, so We drowned them all"
  21,78,"And ňĻrememberňļ when David and Solomon passed judgment regarding the crops ruined ňĻat nightňļ by someone‚Äôs sheep, and We were witness to their judgments"
  21,79,"We guided ňĻyoungňļ Solomon to a fairer settlement,¬†and granted each of them wisdom and knowledge. We subjected the mountains as well as the birds to hymn ňĻOur praisesňļ along with David. It is We Who did ňĻit allňļ"
  21,80,We taught him the art of making body armour to protect you in battle. Will you then be grateful
  21,81,"And to Solomon We subjected the raging winds, blowing by his command to the land We had showered with blessings. It is We Who know everything"
  21,82,"And ňĻWe subjectedňļ some jinn¬†that dived for him,¬†and performed other duties. It is We Who kept them in check"
  21,83,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Job cried out to his Lord, ‚ÄúI have been touched with adversity,¬†and You are the Most Merciful of the merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  21,84,"So We answered his prayer and removed his adversity, and gave him back his family, twice as many, as a mercy from Us and a lesson for the ňĻdevotedňļ worshippers"
  21,85,"And ňĻrememberňļ Ishmael, Enoch, and ‚Īęul-Kifl.¬†They were all steadfast"
  21,86,"We admitted them into Our mercy, for they were truly of the righteous"
  21,87,"And ňĻrememberňļ when the Man of the Whale stormed off ňĻfrom his cityňļ in a rage, thinking We would not restrain him.¬†Then in the ňĻveils ofňļ darkness¬†he cried out, ‚ÄúThere is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except You. Glory be to You! I have certainly done wrong.‚ÄĚ"
  21,88,So We answered his prayer and rescued him from anguish. And so do We save the ňĻtrueňļ believers
  21,89,"And ňĻrememberňļ when Zachariah cried out to his Lord, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Do not leave me childless, though You are the Best of Successors.‚ÄĚ"
  21,90,"So We answered his prayer, granted him John, and made his wife fertile. Indeed, they used to race in doing good, and call upon Us with hope and fear, totally humbling themselves before Us"
  21,91,"And ňĻrememberňļ the one who guarded her chastity, so We breathed into her through Our angel, ňĻGabriel,ňļ¬†making her and her son a sign for all peoples"
  21,92,"ňĻO prophets!ňļ Indeed, this religion of yours is ňĻonlyňļ one, and I am your Lord, so worship Me ňĻaloneňļ"
  21,93,Yet the people have divided it into sects. But to Us they will all return
  21,94,"So whoever does good and is a believer will never be denied ňĻthe reward forňļ their striving, for We are recording it all"
  21,95,It is impossible for a society which We have destroyed to ever rise again
  21,96,"until ňĻafterňļ Gog and Magog have broken loose ňĻfrom the barrierňļ,¬†swarming down from every hill"
  21,97,"ushering in the True Promise.¬†Then‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒthe disbelievers will stare ňĻin horror, crying,ňļ ‚ÄúOh, woe to us! We have truly been heedless of this. In fact, we have been wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  21,98,Certainly you ňĻdisbelieversňļ and whatever you worship instead of God will be the fuel of Hell.¬†You are ňĻallňļ bound to enter it
  21,99,"Had those idols been ňĻtrueňļ gods, they would not have entered it. And they will be there forever"
  21,100,"In it they will groan, and will not be able to hear"
  21,101,Surely those for whom We have destined the finest reward will be kept far away from Hell
  21,102,not even hearing the slightest hissing from it. And they will delight forever in what their souls desire
  21,103,"The Supreme Horror ňĻof that Dayňļ will not disturb them, and the angels will greet them, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúThis is your Day, which you have been promised.‚ÄĚ"
  21,104,"On that Day We will roll up the heavens like a scroll of writings. Just as We produced the first creation, ňĻsoňļ shall We reproduce it. That is a promise binding on Us. We truly uphold ňĻOur promisesňļ"
  21,105,"Surely, following the ňĻheavenlyňļ Record, We decreed in the Scriptures: ‚ÄúMy righteous servants shall inherit the land.‚ÄĚ"
  21,106,Surely this ňĻQuranňļ is sufficient ňĻas a reminderňļ for those devoted to worship
  21,107,We have sent you ňĻO Prophetňļ only as a mercy for the whole world
  21,108,"Say, ‚ÄúWhat has been revealed to me is this: ‚ÄėYour God is only One God.‚Äô Will you then submit?‚ÄĚ"
  21,109,"If they turn away, then say, ‚ÄúI have warned you all equally. I do not know if what you are threatened with is near or far"
  21,110,God surely knows what you say openly and whatever you hide
  21,111,I do not know if this ňĻdelayňļ is possibly a test for you and an enjoyment for a while.‚ÄĚ
  21,112,"ňĻIn the end,ňļ the Prophet said, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Judge ňĻbetween usňļ in truth. And our Lord is the Most Compassionate, Whose help is sought against what you claim.‚ÄĚ"
  22,1,"O humanity! Fear your Lord, for the ňĻviolentňļ quaking at the Hour is surely a dreadful thing"
  22,2,"The Day you see it, every nursing mother will abandon what she is nursing, and every pregnant woman will deliver her burden ňĻprematurelyňļ. And you will see people ňĻas if they wereňļ drunk, though they will not be drunk; but the torment of God is ňĻterriblyňļ severe"
  22,3,"ňĻStillňļ there are some who dispute about God without knowledge, and follow every rebellious devil"
  22,4,It has been decreed for such devils that whoever takes them as a guide will be misguided and led by them into the torment of the Blaze
  22,5,"O humanity! If you are in doubt about the Resurrection, then ňĻknow thatňļ We did create you¬†from dust, then from a sperm-drop,¬†then ňĻdeveloped you intoňļ a clinging clot ňĻof bloodňļ,¬†then a lump of flesh‚ÄĒfully formed or unformed‚ÄĒin order to demonstrate ňĻOur powerňļ to you. ňĻThenňļ We settle whatever ňĻembryoňļ We will in the womb for an appointed term, then bring you forth as infants, so that you may reach your prime. Some of you ňĻmayňļ die ňĻyoungňļ, while others are left to reach the most feeble stage of life so that they may know nothing after having known much. And you see the earth lifeless, but as soon as We send down rain upon it, it begins to stir ňĻto lifeňļ and swell, producing every type of pleasant plant"
  22,6,"That is because God ňĻaloneňļ is the Truth, He ňĻaloneňļ gives life to the dead, and He ňĻaloneňļ is Most Capable of everything"
  22,7,"And certainly the Hour is coming, there is no doubt about it. And God will surely resurrect those in the graves"
  22,8,"ňĻStillňļ there are some who dispute about God without knowledge, guidance, or an enlightening scripture"
  22,9,"turning away ňĻin prideňļ to lead ňĻothersňļ astray from God‚Äôs Way. They will suffer disgrace in this world, and on the Day of Judgment We will make them taste the torment of burning"
  22,10,"ňĻThey will be told,ňļ ‚ÄúThis is ňĻthe rewardňļ for what your hands have done. And God is never unjust to ňĻHisňļ creation.‚ÄĚ"
  22,11,"And there are some who worship God on the verge ňĻof faithňļ: if they are blessed with something good, they are content with it; but if they are afflicted with a trial, they relapse ňĻinto disbeliefňļ,¬†losing this world and the Hereafter. That is ňĻtrulyňļ the clearest loss"
  22,12,They call besides God what can neither harm nor benefit them. That is ňĻtrulyňļ the farthest one can stray
  22,13,"They invoke those whose worship leads to harm, not benefit. What an evil patron and what an evil associate"
  22,14,"Indeed, God will admit those who believe and do good into Gardens, under which rivers flow. Surely God does what He wills"
  22,15,"Whoever thinks that God will not help His Prophet in this world and the Hereafter, let them stretch out a rope to the ceiling and strangle themselves, then let them see if this plan will do away with ňĻthe cause ofňļ their rage"
  22,16,And so We revealed this ňĻQuranňļ as clear verses. And God certainly guides whoever He wills
  22,17,"Indeed, the believers, Jews, Sabians,¬†Christians, Magi,¬†and the polytheists‚ÄĒGod will judge between them ňĻallňļ on Judgment Day. Surely God is a Witness over all things"
  22,18,"Do you not see that to God bow down ňĻin submissionňļ¬†all those in the heavens and all those on the earth, as well as the sun, the moon, the stars, the mountains, the trees, and ňĻallňļ living beings, as well as many humans, while many are deserving of punishment. And whoever God disgraces, none can honour. Surely God does what He wills"
  22,19,"These are two opposing groups that disagree about their Lord: as for the disbelievers, garments of Fire will be cut out for them and boiling water will be poured over their heads"
  22,20,"melting whatever is in their bellies, along with their skin"
  22,21,And awaiting them are maces of iron
  22,22,"Whenever they try to escape from Hell‚ÄĒout of anguish‚ÄĒthey will be forced back into it, ňĻand will be told,ňļ ‚ÄúTaste the torment of burning!‚ÄĚ"
  22,23,"ňĻButňļ God will surely admit those who believe and do good into Gardens, under which rivers flow, where they will be adorned with bracelets of gold and pearls, and their clothing will be silk"
  22,24,"for they have been guided to the best of speech, and they have been guided to the Commendable Path"
  22,25,"Indeed, those who persist in disbelief and hinder ňĻothersňļ from the Way of God and from the Sacred Mosque‚ÄĒwhich We have appointed for all people, residents and visitors alike‚ÄĒalong with whoever intends to deviate by doing wrong in it,¬†We will cause them to taste a painful punishment"
  22,26,"And ňĻrememberňļ when We assigned to Abraham the site of the House, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúDo not associate anything with Me ňĻin worshipňļ and purify My House for those who circle ňĻthe Ka‚Äôbahňļ, stand ňĻin prayerňļ, and bow and prostrate themselves"
  22,27,Call ňĻallňļ people to the pilgrimage.¬†They will come to you on foot and on every lean camel from every distant path
  22,28,"so they may obtain the benefits ňĻin storeňļ for them,¬†and pronounce the Name of God on appointed days over the sacrificial animals He has provided for them. So eat from their meat and feed the desperately poor"
  22,29,"Then let them groom themselves,¬†fulfil their vows, and circle the Ancient House.‚ÄĚ"
  22,30,"That is so. And whoever honours the rituals of God, it is best for them in the sight of their Lord. The ňĻmeat ofňļ cattle has been made lawful for you, except what has ňĻalreadyňļ been recited to you.¬†So shun the impurity of idolatry, and shun words of falsehood"
  22,31,"Be upright ňĻin devotionňļ to God, associating none with Him ňĻin worshipňļ. For whoever associates ňĻothersňļ with God is like someone who has fallen from the sky and is either snatched away by birds or swept by the wind to a remote place"
  22,32,"That is so. And whoever honours the symbols of God, it is certainly out of the piety of the heart"
  22,33,"You may benefit from sacrificial animals for an appointed term,¬†then their place of sacrifice is at the Ancient House"
  22,34,"For every community We appointed a rite of sacrifice so that they may pronounce the Name of God over the sacrificial animals He has provided for them. For your God is only One God, so submit yourselves to Him ňĻaloneňļ. And give good news ňĻO Prophetňļ to the humble"
  22,35,"those whose hearts tremble at the remembrance of God, who patiently endure whatever may befall them, and who establish prayer and donate from what We have provided for them"
  22,36,"We have made sacrificial camels ňĻand cattleňļ among the symbols of God, in which there is ňĻmuchňļ good for you. So pronounce the Name of God over them when they are lined up ňĻfor sacrificeňļ. Once they have fallen ňĻlifelessňļ on their sides, you may eat from their meat, and feed the needy‚ÄĒthose who do not beg, and those who do. In this way We have subjected these ňĻanimalsňļ to you so that you may be grateful"
  22,37,"Neither their meat nor blood reaches God. Rather, it is your piety that reaches Him. This is how He has subjected them to you so that you may proclaim the greatness of God for what He has guided you to, and give good news to the good-doers"
  22,38,"Indeed, God defends those who believe. Surely God does not like whoever is deceitful, ungrateful"
  22,39,"Permission ňĻto fight backňļ is ňĻherebyňļ granted to those being fought, for they have been wronged.¬†And God is truly Most Capable of helping them ňĻprevailňļ"
  22,40,"ňĻThey areňļ those who have been expelled from their homes for no reason other than proclaiming: ‚ÄúOur Lord is God.‚ÄĚ Had God not repelled ňĻthe aggression ofňļ some people by means of others, destruction would have surely claimed monasteries, churches, synagogues, and mosques in which God‚Äôs Name is often mentioned. God will certainly help those who stand up for Him. God is truly All-Powerful, Almighty"
  22,41,"ňĻThey areňļ those who, if established in the land by Us, would perform prayer, pay alms-tax, encourage what is good, and forbid what is evil. And with God rests the outcome of all affairs"
  22,42,"If they deny you ňĻO Prophetňļ, so did the people of Noah before them, as well as ňĻthe tribes ofňļ ‚Äô»ād and Tham√Ľd"
  22,43,"the people of Abraham, the people of Lot"
  22,44,and the residents of Midian. And Moses was denied ňĻtooňļ. But I delayed ňĻthe fate ofňļ the disbelievers ňĻuntil their appointed timeňļ then seized them. And how severe was My response
  22,45,"Many are the societies We have destroyed for persisting in wrongdoing, leaving them in total ruin. ňĻMany areňļ also the abandoned wells and lofty palaces"
  22,46,"Have they not travelled throughout the land so their hearts may reason, and their ears may listen? Indeed, it is not the eyes that are blind, but it is the hearts in the chests that grow blind"
  22,47,They challenge you ňĻO Prophetňļ to hasten the torment. And God will never fail in His promise. But a day with your Lord is indeed like a thousand years by your counting
  22,48,"Many are the societies whose end We delayed while they did wrong, then seized them. And to Me is the final return"
  22,49,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúO humanity! I am only sent to you with a clear warning"
  22,50,So those who believe and do good will have forgiveness and an honourable provision
  22,51,"But those who strive to discredit Our revelations, they will be the residents of the Hellfire.‚ÄĚ"
  22,52,"Whenever We sent a messenger or a prophet before you ňĻO Prophetňļ and he recited ňĻOur revelationsňļ, Satan would influence ňĻpeople‚Äôs understanding ofňļ his recitation. But ňĻeventuallyňļ God would eliminate Satan‚Äôs influence. Then God would ňĻfirmlyňļ establish His revelations. And God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  22,53,All that so He may make Satan‚Äôs influence a trial for those ňĻhypocritesňļ whose hearts are sick and those ňĻdisbelieversňļ whose hearts are hardened. Surely the wrongdoers are totally engrossed in opposition
  22,54,"ňĻThis isňļ also so that those gifted with knowledge would know that this ňĻrevelationňļ is the truth from your Lord, so they have faith in it, and so their hearts would submit humbly to it. And God surely guides the believers to the Straight Path"
  22,55,"Yet the disbelievers will persist in doubt about this ňĻrevelationňļ until the Hour takes them by surprise, or the torment of a terminating¬†Day comes to them"
  22,56,All authority on that Day is for God ňĻaloneňļ.¬†He will judge between them. So those who believe and do good will be in the Gardens of Bliss
  22,57,"But those who disbelieve and deny Our revelations, it is they who will suffer a humiliating punishment"
  22,58,"As for those who emigrate in the cause of God and then are martyred or die, God will indeed grant them a good provision. Surely God is the Best Provider"
  22,59,"He will certainly admit them into a place they will be pleased with. For God is truly All-Knowing, Most Forbearing"
  22,60,"That is so. And whoever retaliates in equivalence to the injury they have received, and then are wronged ňĻagainňļ, God will certainly help them. Surely God is Ever-Pardoning, All-Forgiving"
  22,61,"That is because God causes the night to merge into the day, and the day into the night. Indeed, God is All-Hearing, All-Seeing"
  22,62,"That is because God ňĻaloneňļ is the Truth and what they invoke besides Him is falsehood, and God ňĻaloneňļ is truly the Most High, All-Great"
  22,63,"Do you not see that God sends down rain from the sky, then the earth becomes green? Surely God is Most Subtle, All-Aware"
  22,64,"To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth. God ňĻaloneňļ is truly the Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy"
  22,65,Do you not see that God has subjected to you¬†whatever is in the earth as well as the ships ňĻthatňļ sail through the sea by His command? He keeps the sky from falling down on the earth except by His permission. Surely God is Ever Gracious and Most Merciful to humanity
  22,66,"And He is the One Who gave you life, then will cause you to die, and then will bring you back to life. ňĻButňļ surely humankind is ever ungrateful"
  22,67,"For every community We appointed a code¬†of life to follow.¬†So do not let them dispute with you ňĻO Prophetňļ in this matter. And invite ňĻallňļ to your Lord, for you are truly on the Right Guidance"
  22,68,"But if they argue with you, then say, ‚ÄúGod knows best what you do.‚ÄĚ"
  22,69,God will judge between you ňĻallňļ on Judgment Day regarding your differences
  22,70,Do you not know that God ňĻfullyňļ knows whatever is in the heavens and the earth? Surely it is all ňĻwrittenňļ in a Record. That is certainly easy for God
  22,71,"Yet they worship besides God that for which He has sent down no authority, and of which they have no knowledge. The wrongdoers will have no helper"
  22,72,"Whenever Our clear revelations are recited to them, you ňĻO Prophetňļ recognize rage on the faces of the disbelievers, as if they are going to snap at those who recite Our revelations to them. Say, ‚ÄúShall I inform you of something far more enraging than that? ňĻIt isňļ the Fire with which God has threatened those who disbelieve. What an evil destination!‚ÄĚ"
  22,73,"O humanity! A lesson is set forth, so listen to it ňĻcarefullyňļ: those ňĻidolsňļ you invoke besides God can never create ňĻso much asňļ a fly, even if they ňĻallňļ were to come together for that. And if a fly were to snatch anything away from them, they cannot ňĻevenňļ retrieve it from the fly. How powerless are those who invoke and those invoked"
  22,74,"They have not shown God the reverence He deserves. Surely God is All-Powerful, Almighty"
  22,75,"God selects messengers from both angels and people, for God is truly All-Hearing, All-Seeing"
  22,76,He knows what is ahead of them and what is behind them. And to God ňĻallňļ matters will be returned ňĻfor judgmentňļ
  22,77,"O believers! Bow down, prostrate yourselves, worship your Lord, and do ňĻwhat isňļ good so that you may be successful"
  22,78,"Strive for ňĻthe cause ofňļ God in the way He deserves, for ňĻit isňļ He ňĻWhoňļ has chosen you, and laid upon you no hardship in the religion‚ÄĒthe way of your forefather Abraham. ňĻIt is Godňļ Who named you ‚Äėthe ones who submit‚Äô¬†ňĻin theňļ earlier ňĻScripturesňļ and in this ňĻQuranňļ, so that the Messenger may be a witness over you, and that you may be witnesses over humanity. So establish prayer, pay alms-tax, and hold fast to God. He ňĻaloneňļ is your Guardian. What an excellent Guardian, and what an excellent Helper"
  23,1,Successful indeed are the believers
  23,2,those who humble themselves in prayer
  23,3,those who avoid idle talk
  23,4,those who pay alms-tax
  23,5,those who guard their chastity
  23,6,"except with their wives or those ňĻbondwomenňļ in their possession,¬†for then they are free from blame"
  23,7,but whoever seeks beyond that are the transgressors
  23,8,ňĻthe believers are alsoňļ those who are true to their trusts and covenants
  23,9,and those who are ňĻproperlyňļ observant of their prayers
  23,10,These are the ones who will be awarded
  23,11,Paradise as their own.¬†They will be there forever
  23,12,"And indeed, We created humankind¬†from an extract of clay"
  23,13,then placed each ňĻhumanňļ as a sperm-drop¬†in a secure place
  23,14,"then We developed the drop into a clinging clot ňĻof bloodňļ, then developed the clot into a lump ňĻof fleshňļ, then developed the lump into bones, then clothed the bones with flesh, then We brought it into being as a new creation.¬†So Blessed is God, the Best of Creators"
  23,15,After that you will surely die
  23,16,then on the Day of Judgment you will be resurrected
  23,17,"And indeed, We created above you seven levels ňĻof heavenňļ. We are never unmindful of ňĻOurňļ creation"
  23,18,"We send down rain from the sky in perfect measure, causing it to soak into the earth. And We are surely able to take it away"
  23,19,"With it We produce for you gardens of palm trees and grapevines, in which there are abundant fruits, and from which you may eat"
  23,20,"as well as ňĻoliveňļ trees which grow at Mount Sinai, providing oil and a condiment to eat"
  23,21,"And there is certainly a lesson for you in cattle, from whose bellies We give you ňĻmilkňļ to drink, and in them are many other benefits for you, and from them you may eat"
  23,22,And you are carried upon ňĻsome ofňļ them and upon ships
  23,23,"Indeed, We sent Noah to his people. He declared, ‚ÄúO my people! Worship God ňĻaloneňļ. You have no god other than Him. Will you not then fear ňĻHimňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  23,24,"But the disbelieving chiefs of his people said ňĻto the massesňļ, ‚ÄúThis is only a human like you, who wants to be superior to you. Had God willed, He could have easily sent down angels ňĻinsteadňļ. We have never heard of this in ňĻthe history ofňļ our forefathers"
  23,25,"He is simply insane, so bear with him for a while.‚ÄĚ"
  23,26,"Noah prayed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Help me, because they have denied ňĻmeňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  23,27,"So We inspired him: ‚ÄúBuild the Ark under Our ňĻwatchfulňļ Eyes and directions. Then when Our command comes and the oven bursts ňĻwith waterňļ,¬†take on board a pair from every species along with your family‚ÄĒexcept those against whom the decree ňĻto drownňļ has already been passed. And do not plead with Me for those who have done wrong, for they will surely be drowned.‚ÄĚ"
  23,28,"Then when you and those with you have settled in the Ark, say, ‚ÄúAll praise is for God, Who saved us from the wrongdoing people.‚ÄĚ"
  23,29,"And pray, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Allow me a blessed landing, for You are the best accommodator.‚ÄĚ"
  23,30,Surely in this are lessons.¬†And We ňĻalwaysňļ put ňĻpeopleňļ to the test
  23,31,Then We raised another generation after them
  23,32,"and sent to them a messenger from among themselves, ňĻdeclaring,ňļ ‚ÄúWorship God ňĻaloneňļ. You have no god other than Him. Will you not then fear ňĻHimňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  23,33,"But the chiefs of his people‚ÄĒwho disbelieved, denied the meeting ňĻwith Godňļ in the Hereafter, and were spoiled by the worldly luxuries We had provided for them‚ÄĒsaid ňĻto the massesňļ, ‚ÄúThis is only a human like you. He eats what you eat, and drinks what you drink"
  23,34,"And if you ňĻeverňļ obey a human like yourselves, then you would certainly be losers"
  23,35,"Does he promise you that once you are dead and reduced to dust and bones, you will be brought forth ňĻaliveňļ"
  23,36,"Impossible, simply impossible is what you are promised"
  23,37,"There is nothing beyond our worldly life. We die, others are born, and none will be resurrected"
  23,38,"He is no more than a man who has fabricated a lie about God, and we will never believe in him.‚ÄĚ"
  23,39,"The messenger prayed, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Help me, because they have denied ňĻmeňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  23,40,"God responded, ‚ÄúSoon they will be truly regretful.‚ÄĚ"
  23,41,"Then the ňĻmightyňļ blast overtook them with justice, and We reduced them to rubble. So away with the wrongdoing people"
  23,42,Then We raised other generations after them
  23,43,"No people can advance their doom, nor can they delay it"
  23,44,"Then We sent Our messengers in succession: whenever a messenger came to his people, they denied him. So We destroyed them, one after the other, reducing them to ňĻcautionaryňļ tales. So away with the people who refuse to believe"
  23,45,Then We sent Moses and his brother Aaron with Our signs¬†and compelling proof
  23,46,"to Pharaoh and his chiefs, but they behaved arrogantly and were a tyrannical people"
  23,47,"They argued, ‚ÄúWill we believe in two humans, like ourselves, whose people are slaves to us?‚ÄĚ"
  23,48,"So they rejected them both, and ňĻsoňļ were among those destroyed"
  23,49,"And We certainly gave Moses the Scripture, so perhaps his people would be ňĻrightlyňļ guided"
  23,50,"And We made the son of Mary and his mother a sign, and gave them refuge on high ground‚ÄĒa ňĻsuitableňļ place for rest with flowing water"
  23,51,"O messengers! Eat from what is good and lawful, and act righteously. Indeed, I fully know what you do"
  23,52,"Surely this religion of yours is ňĻonlyňļ one, and I am your Lord, so fear Me ňĻaloneňļ"
  23,53,"Yet the people have divided it into different sects, each rejoicing in what they have"
  23,54,So leave them ňĻO Prophetňļ in their heedlessness for a while
  23,55,"Do they think, since We provide them with wealth and children"
  23,56,that We hasten to ňĻhonourňļ them ňĻwithňļ all kinds of good? No! They are not aware
  23,57,Surely those who tremble in awe of their Lord
  23,58,and who believe in the revelations of their Lord
  23,59,and who associate none with their Lord
  23,60,"and who do whatever ňĻgoodňļ they do with their hearts fearful, ňĻknowingňļ that they will return to their Lord‚ÄĒ"
  23,61,"it is they who race to do good deeds, always taking the lead"
  23,62,We never require of any soul more than what it can afford. And with Us is a record which speaks the truth. None will be wronged
  23,63,"But the hearts of those ňĻwho disbelieveňļ are oblivious to ňĻall ofňļ this,¬†and they have other ňĻevilňļ deeds, opposite to this, in which they are engrossed"
  23,64,"But as soon as We seize their elite with torment, they start to cry for help"
  23,65,"ňĻThey will be told,ňļ ‚ÄúDo not cry for help today. Surely you will never be saved from Us"
  23,66,"Indeed, My revelations were recited to you, but you used to back away ňĻin disgustňļ"
  23,67,"boasting of the Sacred House, and babbling ňĻnonsense about the Quranňļ by night.‚ÄĚ"
  23,68,Is it because they have never contemplated the Word ňĻof Godňļ? Or ňĻbecauseňļ there has come to them something that did not come to their forefathers
  23,69,"Or ňĻbecauseňļ they failed to recognize their Messenger, and so they denied him"
  23,70,"Or ňĻbecauseňļ they say, ‚ÄúHe is insane?‚ÄĚ In fact, he has come to them with the truth, but most of them are resentful of the truth"
  23,71,"Had the truth followed their desires,¬†the heavens, the earth, and all those in them would have certainly been corrupted. In fact, We have brought them ňĻthe means toňļ their glory, but they turn away from it"
  23,72,"Or ňĻis it becauseňļ you ňĻO Prophetňļ are asking them for tribute? But the reward of your Lord is best, for He is the Best Provider"
  23,73,And surely you are calling them to the Straight Path
  23,74,but those who disbelieve in the Hereafter are certainly deviating from that Path
  23,75,"ňĻEvenňļ if We had mercy on them and removed their affliction,¬†they would still persist in their transgression, wandering blindly"
  23,76,"And We have already seized them with torment, but they never humbled themselves to their Lord, nor did they ňĻsubmissivelyňļ appeal ňĻto Himňļ"
  23,77,"But as soon as We open for them a gate of severe punishment, they will be utterly desperate"
  23,78,"He is the One Who created for you hearing, sight, and intellect. ňĻYetňļ you hardly give any thanks"
  23,79,"And He is the One Who has dispersed you ňĻallňļ over the earth, and to Him you will ňĻallňļ be gathered"
  23,80,"And He is the One Who gives life and causes death, and to Him belongs the alternation of the day and night. Will you not then understand"
  23,81,But they ňĻjustňļ say what their predecessors said
  23,82,"They said, ‚ÄúOnce we are dead and reduced to dust and bones, will we really be resurrected"
  23,83,"We have already been promised this, as well as our forefathers earlier. This is nothing but ancient fables!‚ÄĚ"
  23,84,"Ask ňĻthem, O Prophetňļ, ‚ÄúTo whom belong the earth and all those on it, if you ňĻreallyňļ know?‚ÄĚ"
  23,85,"They will reply, ‚ÄúTo God!‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúWhy are you not then mindful?‚ÄĚ"
  23,86,"ňĻAndňļ ask ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúWho is the Lord of the seven heavens and the Lord of the Mighty Throne?‚ÄĚ"
  23,87,"They will reply, ‚ÄúGod.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúWill you not then fear ňĻHimňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  23,88,"Ask ňĻthem also,ňļ ‚ÄúIn Whose Hands is the authority over all things, protecting ňĻallňļ while none can protect against Him, if you ňĻreallyňļ know?‚ÄĚ"
  23,89,"They will reply, ‚ÄúGod.‚ÄĚ Say, ‚ÄúHow are you then so deluded?‚ÄĚ"
  23,90,"In fact, We have brought them the truth, and they are certainly liars"
  23,91,"God has never had ňĻanyňļ offspring, nor is there any god besides Him. Otherwise, each god would have taken away what he created, and they would have tried to dominate one another. Glorified is God above what they claim"
  23,92,ňĻHe is theňļ Knower of the seen and unseen. Exalted is He above what they associate ňĻwith Himňļ
  23,93,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúMy Lord! Should You show me what they¬†are threatened with"
  23,94,"then, my Lord, do not count me among the wrongdoing people.‚ÄĚ"
  23,95,We are indeed able to show you what We have threatened them with
  23,96,Respond to evil with what is best. We know well what they claim
  23,97,"And say, ‚ÄúMy Lord! I seek refuge in You from the temptations of the devils"
  23,98,"And I seek refuge in You, my Lord, that they ňĻevenňļ come near me.‚ÄĚ"
  23,99,"When death approaches any of them, they cry, ‚ÄúMy Lord! Let me go back"
  23,100,so I may do good in what I left behind.‚ÄĚ Never! It is only a ňĻuselessňļ appeal they make. And there is a barrier behind them until the Day they are resurrected
  23,101,"Then, when the Trumpet will be blown,¬†there will be no kinship between them on that Day, nor will they ňĻeven care toňļ ask about one another"
  23,102,"As for those whose scale is heavy ňĻwith good deedsňļ, it is they who will be successful"
  23,103,"But those whose scale is light, they will have doomed themselves, staying in Hell forever"
  23,104,"The Fire will burn their faces, leaving them deformed"
  23,105,"ňĻIt will be said,ňļ ‚ÄúWere My revelations not recited to you, but you used to deny them?‚ÄĚ"
  23,106,"They will cry, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Our ill-fate took hold of us, so we became a misguided people"
  23,107,"Our Lord! Take us out of this ňĻFireňļ. Then if we ever return ňĻto denialňļ, we will truly be wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  23,108,"God will respond, ‚ÄúBe despised in there! Do not ňĻeverňļ plead with Me ňĻagainňļ"
  23,109,"Indeed, there was a group of My servants who used to pray, ‚ÄėOur Lord! We have believed, so forgive us and have mercy on us, for You are the best of those who show mercy,‚Äô"
  23,110,but you were ňĻso busyňļ making fun of them that it made you forget My remembrance. And you used to laugh at them
  23,111,"Today I have indeed rewarded them for their perseverance: they are certainly the triumphant.‚ÄĚ"
  23,112,"He will ask ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúHow many years did you remain on earth?‚ÄĚ"
  23,113,"They will reply, ‚ÄúWe remained ňĻonlyňļ a day or part of a day.¬†But ask those who kept count.‚ÄĚ"
  23,114,"He will say, ‚ÄúYou only remained for a little while, if only you knew"
  23,115,"Did you then think that We had created you without purpose, and that you would never be returned to Us?‚ÄĚ"
  23,116,"Exalted is God, the True King! There is no god ňĻworthy of worshipňļ except Him, the Lord of the Honourable Throne"
  23,117,"Whoever invokes, besides God, another god‚ÄĒfor which they can have no proof‚ÄĒthey will surely find their penalty with their Lord. Indeed, the disbelievers will never succeed"
  23,118,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúMy Lord! Forgive and have mercy, for You are the best of those who show mercy.‚ÄĚ"
  24,1,"ňĻThis isňļ a s√Ľrah¬†which We have revealed and made ňĻits rulingsňļ obligatory, and revealed in it clear commandments so that you may be mindful"
  24,2,"As for female and male fornicators, give each of them one hundred lashes,¬†and do not let pity for them make you lenient in ňĻenforcingňļ the law of God, if you ňĻtrulyňļ believe in God and the Last Day. And let a number of believers witness their punishment"
  24,3,A male fornicator would only marry a female fornicator or idolatress. And a female fornicator would only be married to a fornicator or idolater. This is ňĻallňļ forbidden to the believers
  24,4,"Those who accuse chaste women ňĻof adulteryňļ and fail to produce four witnesses, give them eighty lashes ňĻeachňļ. And do not ever accept any testimony from them‚ÄĒfor they are indeed the rebellious‚ÄĒ"
  24,5,"except those who repent afterwards and mend their ways, then surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  24,6,"And those who accuse their wives ňĻof adulteryňļ but have no witness except themselves, the accuser must testify,¬†swearing four times by God that he is telling the truth"
  24,7,and a fifth oath that God may condemn him if he is lying
  24,8,"For her to be spared the punishment, she must swear four times by God that he is telling a lie"
  24,9,and a fifth oath that God may be displeased with her if he is telling the truth
  24,10,"ňĻYou would have suffered,ňļ had it not been for God‚Äôs grace and mercy upon you, and had God not been Accepting of Repentance, All-Wise"
  24,11,"Indeed, those who came up with that ňĻoutrageousňļ slander are a group of you. Do not think this is bad for you. Rather, it is good for you.¬†They will be punished, each according to their share of the sin. As for their mastermind,¬†he will suffer a tremendous punishment"
  24,12,"If only the believing men and women had thought well of one another, when you heard this ňĻrumourňļ, and said, ‚ÄúThis is clearly ňĻan outrageousňļ slander!‚ÄĚ"
  24,13,"Why did they not produce four witnesses? Now, since they have failed to produce witnesses, they are ňĻtrulyňļ liars in the sight of God"
  24,14,"Had it not been for God‚Äôs grace and mercy upon you in this world and the Hereafter, you would have certainly been touched with a tremendous punishment for what you plunged into‚ÄĒ"
  24,15,"when you passed it from one tongue to the other, and said with your mouths what you had no knowledge of, taking it lightly while it is ňĻextremelyňļ serious in the sight of God"
  24,16,"If only you had said upon hearing it, ‚ÄúHow can we speak about such a thing! Glory be to You ňĻO Lordňļ! This is a heinous slander!‚ÄĚ"
  24,17,"God forbids you from ever doing something like this again, if you are ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  24,18,"And God makes ňĻHisňļ commandments clear to you, for God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  24,19,"Indeed, those who love to see indecency spread among the believers will suffer a painful punishment in this life and the Hereafter. God knows and you do not know"
  24,20,"ňĻYou would have suffered,ňļ had it not been for God‚Äôs grace and mercy upon you, and had God not been Ever Gracious, Most Merciful"
  24,21,"O believers! Do not follow the footsteps of Satan. Whoever follows Satan‚Äôs footsteps, then ňĻlet them know thatňļ he surely bids ňĻall toňļ immorality and wickedness. Had it not been for God‚Äôs grace and mercy upon you, none of you would have ever been purified. But God purifies whoever He wills. And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  24,22,"Do not let the people of virtue and affluence among you swear to suspend donations to their relatives, the needy, and the emigrants in the cause of God. Let them pardon and forgive. Do you not love to be forgiven by God? And God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  24,23,"Surely those who accuse chaste, unsuspecting,¬†believing women are cursed in this life and the Hereafter. And they will suffer a tremendous punishment"
  24,24,"on the Day their tongues, hands, and feet will testify against them for what they used to do"
  24,25,"On that Day, God will give them their just penalty in full, and they will ňĻcome toňļ know that God ňĻaloneňļ is the Ultimate Truth"
  24,26,"Wicked women are for wicked men, and wicked men are for wicked women. And virtuous women are for virtuous men, and virtuous men are for virtuous women. The virtuous are innocent of what the wicked say. They will have forgiveness and an honourable provision"
  24,27,"O believers! Do not enter any house other than your own until you have asked for permission and greeted its occupants. This is best for you, so perhaps you will be mindful"
  24,28,"If you find no one at home, do not enter it until you have been given permission. And if you are asked to leave, then leave. That is purer for you. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of what you do"
  24,29,There is no blame on you if you enter public places¬†where there is something of benefit for you. And God knows what you reveal and what you conceal
  24,30,ňĻO Prophet!ňļ Tell the believing men to lower their gaze and guard their chastity. That is purer for them. Surely God is All-Aware of what they do
  24,31,"And tell the believing women to lower their gaze and guard their chastity, and not to reveal their adornments¬†except what normally appears.¬†Let them draw their veils over their chests, and not reveal their ňĻhiddenňļ adornments¬†except to their husbands, their fathers, their fathers-in-law, their sons, their stepsons, their brothers, their brothers‚Äô sons or sisters‚Äô sons, their fellow women, those ňĻbondwomenňļ in their possession, male attendants with no desire, or children who are still unaware of women‚Äôs nakedness. Let them not stomp their feet, drawing attention to their hidden adornments. Turn to God in repentance all together, O believers, so that you may be successful"
  24,32,"Marry off the ňĻfreeňļ singles among you, as well as the righteous of your bondmen and bondwomen. If they are poor, God will enrich them out of His bounty. For God is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing"
  24,33,"And let those who do not have the means to marry keep themselves chaste until God enriches them out of His bounty. And if any of those ňĻbondspeopleňļ in your possession desires a deed of emancipation, make it possible for them, if you find goodness in them. And give them some of God‚Äôs wealth which He has granted you. Do not force your ňĻslaveňļ girls into prostitution for your own worldly gains while they wish to remain chaste. And if someone coerces them, then after such a coercion God is certainly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful ňĻto themňļ"
  24,34,"Indeed, We have sent down to you clear revelations, along with examples of those who had gone before you, and a lesson to the God-fearing"
  24,35,"God is the Light of the heavens and the earth. His light¬†is like a niche in which there is a lamp, the lamp is in a crystal, the crystal is like a shining star, lit from ňĻthe oil ofňļ a blessed olive tree, ňĻlocatedňļ neither to the east nor the west,¬†whose oil would almost glow, even without being touched by fire. Light upon light! God guides whoever He wills to His light. And God sets forth parables for humanity. For God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  24,36,"ňĻThat light shinesňļ through houses ňĻof worshipňļ which God has ordered to be raised, and where His Name is mentioned. He is glorified there morning and evening"
  24,37,"by men¬†who are not distracted‚ÄĒeither by buying or selling‚ÄĒfrom God‚Äôs remembrance, or performing prayer, or paying alms-tax. They fear a Day when hearts and eyes will tremble"
  24,38,"ňĻhopingňļ that God may reward them according to the best of their deeds, and increase them out of His grace. And God provides for whoever He wills without limit"
  24,39,"As for the disbelievers, their deeds are like a mirage in a desert, which the thirsty perceive as water, but when they approach it, they find it to be nothing. Instead, they find God there ňĻin the Hereafter, readyňļ to settle their account. And God is swift in reckoning"
  24,40,"Or ňĻtheir deeds areňļ like the darkness in a deep sea, covered by waves upon waves,¬†topped by ňĻdarkňļ clouds. Darkness upon darkness! If one stretches out their hand, they can hardly see it. And whoever God does not bless with light will have no light"
  24,41,"Do you not see that God is glorified by all those in the heavens and the earth, even the birds as they soar? Each ňĻinstinctivelyňļ knows their manner of prayer and glorification. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all they do"
  24,42,To God ňĻaloneňļ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth. And to God is the final return
  24,43,"Do you not see that God gently drives the clouds, then joins them together, piling them up into masses, from which you see raindrops come forth? And He sends down from the sky mountains ňĻof cloudsňļ loaded with hail, pouring it on whoever He wills and averting it from whoever He wills. The flash of the clouds‚Äô lightning nearly takes away eyesight"
  24,44,God alternates the day and night. Surely in this is a lesson for people of insight
  24,45,"And God has created from water every living creature. Some of them crawl on their bellies, some walk on two legs, and some walk on four. God creates whatever He wills. Surely God is Most Capable of everything"
  24,46,We have indeed sent down revelations clarifying ňĻthe truthňļ. But God ňĻonlyňļ guides whoever He wills to the Straight Path
  24,47,"And the hypocrites say, ‚ÄúWe believe in God and the Messenger, and we obey.‚ÄĚ Then a group of them turns away soon after that. These are not ňĻtrueňļ believers"
  24,48,"And as soon as they are called to God and His Messenger so he may judge between them, a group of them¬†turns away"
  24,49,"But if the truth is in their favour, they come to him, fully submitting"
  24,50,"Is there a sickness in their hearts? Or are they in doubt? Or do they fear that God and His Messenger will be unjust to them? In fact, it is they who are the ňĻtrueňļ wrongdoers"
  24,51,"The only response of the ňĻtrueňļ believers, when they are called to God and His Messenger so he may judge between them, is to say, ‚ÄúWe hear and obey.‚ÄĚ It is they who will ňĻtrulyňļ succeed"
  24,52,"For whoever obeys God and His Messenger, and fears God and is mindful of Him, then it is they who will ňĻtrulyňļ triumph"
  24,53,"They swear by God their most solemn oaths that if you ňĻO Prophetňļ were to command them, they would certainly march forth ňĻin God‚Äôs causeňļ. Say, ‚ÄúňĻYouňļ do not ňĻhave toňļ swear; your obedience is well known!‚ÄĚ¬†Surely God is All-Aware of what you do.‚ÄĚ"
  24,54,"Say, ‚ÄúObey God and obey the Messenger. But if you turn away, then he is only responsible for his duty¬†and you are responsible for yours.¬†And if you obey him, you will be ňĻrightlyňļ guided. The Messenger‚Äôs duty is only to deliver ňĻthe messageňļ clearly.‚ÄĚ"
  24,55,"God has promised those of you who believe and do good that He will certainly make them successors in the land, as He did with those before them; and will surely establish for them their faith which He has chosen for them; and will indeed change their fear into security‚ÄĒňĻprovided thatňļ they worship Me, associating nothing with Me. But whoever disbelieves after this ňĻpromiseňļ, it is they who will be the rebellious"
  24,56,"Moreover, establish prayer, pay alms-tax, and obey the Messenger, so you may be shown mercy"
  24,57,"Do not think ňĻO Prophetňļ that the disbelievers can escape in the land. The Fire will be their home. Indeed, what an evil destination"
  24,58,"O believers! Let those ňĻbondspeopleňļ in your possession and those of you who are still under age ask for your permission ňĻto come inňļ at three times: before dawn prayer, when you take off your ňĻouterňļ clothes at noon, and after the late evening prayer. ňĻThese areňļ three times of privacy for you. Other than these times, there is no blame on you or them to move freely, attending to one another. This is how God makes the revelations clear to you, for God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  24,59,"And when your children reach the age of puberty, let them seek permission ňĻto come inňļ, as their seniors do. This is how God makes His revelations clear to you, for God is All-Knowing, All-Wise"
  24,60,"As for elderly women past the age of marriage, there is no blame on them if they take off their ňĻouterňļ garments, without revealing their adornments. But it is better for them if they avoid this ňĻaltogetherňļ. And God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
  24,61,"There is no restriction on the blind, or the disabled, or the sick.¬†Nor on yourselves if you eat from your homes,¬†or the homes of your fathers, or your mothers, or your brothers, or your sisters, or your paternal uncles, or your paternal aunts, or your maternal uncles, or your maternal aunts, or from the homes in your trust, or ňĻthe homes ofňļ your friends. There is no blame on you eating together or separately. However, when you enter houses, greet one another with a greeting ňĻof peaceňļ from God, blessed and good.¬†This is how God makes His revelations clear to you, so perhaps you will understand"
  24,62,"The ňĻtrueňļ believers are only those who believe in God and His Messenger, and when they are with him on a public matter, they do not leave without his permission. Indeed, those who ask your permission ňĻO Prophetňļ are the ones who ňĻtrulyňļ believe in God and His Messenger. So when they ask your permission for a private matter, grant permission to whoever you wish and ask God‚Äôs forgiveness for them. Surely God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  24,63,"Do not treat the Messenger‚Äôs summons to you ňĻas lightlyňļ as your summons to one another.¬†God certainly knows those of you who slip away, hiding behind others.¬†So let those who disobey his orders beware, for an affliction may befall them, or a painful torment may overtake them"
  24,64,"Surely to God belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth. He knows well what you stand for. And ňĻonňļ the Day all will be returned to Him, He will inform them of what they did. For God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  25,1,"Blessed is the One Who sent down the Standard¬†to His servant,¬†so that he may be a warner to the whole world"
  25,2,"ňĻGod isňļ the One to Whom belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth, Who has never had ňĻanyňļ offspring, nor does He have a partner in ňĻgoverningňļ the kingdom. He has created everything, ordaining it precisely"
  25,3,"Yet they have taken besides Him gods who cannot create anything but are themselves created. Nor can they protect or benefit themselves. Nor can they control life, death, or resurrection"
  25,4,"The disbelievers say, ‚ÄúThis ňĻQuranňļ is nothing but a fabrication which he¬†made up with the help of others.‚ÄĚ Their claim is totally unjustified and untrue"
  25,5,"And they say, ‚ÄúňĻThese revelations are onlyňļ ancient fables which he has had written down, and they are rehearsed to him morning and evening.‚ÄĚ"
  25,6,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúThis ňĻQuranňļ has been revealed by the One Who knows the secrets of the heavens and the earth. Surely He is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.‚ÄĚ"
  25,7,"And they say ňĻmockinglyňļ, ‚ÄúWhat kind of messenger is this who eats food and goes about in market-places ňĻfor a livingňļ? If only an angel had been sent down with him to be his co-warner"
  25,8,"or a treasure had been cast down to him, or he had had a garden from which he may eat!‚ÄĚ And the wrongdoers say ňĻto the believersňļ, ‚ÄúYou are only following a bewitched man.‚ÄĚ"
  25,9,See ňĻO Prophetňļ how they call you names!¬†So they have gone so ňĻfarňļ astray that they cannot find the ňĻRightňļ Way
  25,10,"Blessed is the One Who‚ÄĒif He wills‚ÄĒcan give you far better than ňĻallňļ that: gardens under which rivers flow, and palaces as well"
  25,11,"In fact, they deny the Hour.¬†And for the deniers of the Hour, We have prepared a blazing Fire"
  25,12,"Once it sees them from a distance, they will hear it fuming and growling"
  25,13,"And when they are tossed into a narrow place inside ňĻHellňļ, chained together, then and there they will cry out for ňĻinstantňļ destruction"
  25,14,"ňĻThey will be told,ňļ ‚ÄúDo not cry only once for destruction, but cry many times over!‚ÄĚ"
  25,15,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúIs this better or the Garden of Eternity which the righteous have been promised, as a reward and ňĻan ultimateňļ destination"
  25,16,"There they will have whatever they wish for, forever. That is a promise ňĻto be sought afterňļ, binding on your Lord.‚ÄĚ"
  25,17,"ňĻWatch forňļ the Day He will gather them along with what they used to worship besides God, and ask ňĻthe objects of worshipňļ,¬†‚ÄúWas it you who misled these servants of Mine, or did they stray from the Way ňĻon their ownňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  25,18,"They will say, ‚ÄúGlory be to You! It was not right for ňĻothers likeňļ us to take any lords besides You,¬†but You allowed enjoyment for them and their forefathers ňĻfor so longňļ that they forgot ňĻYourňļ remembrance and became a doomed people.‚ÄĚ"
  25,19,"ňĻThe doomed will be toldňļ, ‚ÄúYour gods have clearly denied your claims. So now you can neither ward off ňĻthe punishmentňļ nor get any help.‚ÄĚ And whoever of you does wrong, We will make them taste a horrible punishment"
  25,20,"We never sent any messenger before you ňĻO Prophetňļ, who did not eat food and go about in market-places. We have made some of you a trial for others. Will you ňĻnot thenňļ be patient? And your Lord is All-Seeing"
  25,21,"Those who do not expect to meet Us say, ‚ÄúIf only the angels were sent down to us, or we could see our Lord!‚ÄĚ They have certainly been carried away by their arrogance and have entirely exceeded all limits"
  25,22,"ňĻButňļ on the Day they will see the angels, there will be no good news for the wicked, who will cry, ‚ÄúKeep away! Away ňĻfrom usňļ!‚ÄĚ"
  25,23,"Then We will turn to whatever ňĻgoodňļ deeds they did, reducing them to scattered dust"
  25,24,ňĻButňļ on that Day the residents of Paradise will have the best settlement and the finest place to rest
  25,25,"ňĻWatch forňļ the Day the heavens will burst with clouds, and the angels will be sent down in successive ranks"
  25,26,True authority on that Day will belong ňĻonlyňļ to the Most Compassionate.¬†And it will be a hard day for the disbelievers
  25,27,"And ňĻbeware ofňļ the Day the wrongdoer will bite his nails ňĻin regretňļ and say, ‚ÄúOh! I wish I had followed the Way along with the Messenger"
  25,28,Woe to me! I wish I had never taken so-and-so as a close friend
  25,29,It was he who truly made me stray from the Reminder after it had reached me.‚ÄĚ And Satan has always betrayed humanity
  25,30,"The Messenger has cried, ‚ÄúO my Lord! My people have indeed received this Quran with neglect.‚ÄĚ"
  25,31,"Similarly, We made enemies for every prophet from among the wicked, but sufficient is your Lord as a Guide and Helper"
  25,32,"The disbelievers say, ‚ÄúIf only the Quran had been sent down to him all at once!‚ÄĚ ňĻWe have sent itňļ as such ňĻin stagesňļ so We may reassure your heart with it. And We have revealed it at a deliberate pace"
  25,33,"Whenever they bring you an argument, We come to you with the right refutation and the best explanation"
  25,34,"Those who will be dragged into Hell on their faces will be in the worst place, and are ňĻnowňļ farthest from the ňĻRightňļ Way"
  25,35,We certainly gave Moses the Book and appointed his brother Aaron as his helper
  25,36,"We had ordered ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúGo to the people who would deny Our signs.‚ÄĚ Then We annihilated the deniers entirely"
  25,37,"And when the people of Noah rejected the messengers,¬†We drowned them, making them an example to humanity. And We have prepared a painful punishment for the wrongdoers"
  25,38,"Also ňĻWe destroyedňļ ‚Äô»ād, Tham√Ľd, and the people of the Water-pit,¬†as well as many peoples in between"
  25,39,"For each We set forth ňĻvariousňļ lessons, and We ultimately destroyed each"
  25,40,"They have certainly passed by the city ňĻof Sodomňļ, which had been showered with a dreadful rain ňĻof stonesňļ. Have they not seen its ruins? But they do not expect to be resurrected"
  25,41,"When they see you ňĻO Prophetňļ, they only make fun of you, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúIs this the one that God has sent as a messenger"
  25,42,"He would have almost tricked us away from our gods, had we not been so devoted to them.‚ÄĚ ňĻButňļ soon they will know, when they face the punishment, who is far astray from the ňĻRightňļ Way"
  25,43,Have you seen ňĻO Prophetňļ the one who has taken their own desires as their god? Will you then be a keeper over them
  25,44,"Or do you think that most of them listen or understand?¬†They are only like cattle‚ÄĒno, more than that, they are astray from the ňĻRightňļ Way"
  25,45,Have you not seen how your Lord extends the shade‚ÄĒHe could have simply made it ňĻremainňļ still if He so willed‚ÄĒthen We make the sun its guide
  25,46,causing the shade to retreat gradually
  25,47,"He is the One Who has made the night for you as a cover, and ňĻmadeňļ sleep for resting, and the day for rising"
  25,48,"And He is the One Who sends the winds ushering in His mercy, and We send down pure rain from the sky"
  25,49,"giving life to a lifeless land, and providing water for countless animals and humans of Our Own creation"
  25,50,"We certainly disperse it among them so they may be mindful, but most people persist in ungratefulness"
  25,51,"Had We willed, We could have easily sent a warner to every society"
  25,52,"So do not yield to the disbelievers, but strive diligently against them with this ňĻQuranňļ"
  25,53,"And He is the One Who merges the two bodies of water: one fresh and palatable and the other salty and bitter, placing between them a barrier they cannot cross"
  25,54,"And He is the One Who creates human beings from a ňĻhumbleňļ liquid,¬†then establishes for them bonds of kinship and marriage. For your Lord is Most Capable"
  25,55,Yet they worship besides God what can neither benefit nor harm them. And the disbeliever always collaborates against their Lord
  25,56,And We have sent you ňĻO Prophetňļ only as a deliverer of good news and a warner
  25,57,"Say, ‚ÄúI do not ask you for any reward for this ňĻmessageňļ, but whoever wishes, let them pursue the Way to their Lord.‚ÄĚ"
  25,58,"Put your trust in the Ever-Living, Who never dies, and glorify His praises. Sufficient is He as All-Aware of the sins of His servants"
  25,59,"ňĻHe isňļ the One Who created the heavens and the earth and everything in between in six Days,¬†then established Himself on the Throne. ňĻHe isňļ the Most Compassionate! Ask ňĻnone other thanňļ the All-Knowledgeable about Himself"
  25,60,"When it is said to them, ‚ÄúProstrate to the Most Compassionate,‚ÄĚ they ask ňĻin disgustňļ, ‚ÄúWhat is ‚Äėthe Most Compassionate‚Äô? Will we prostrate to whatever you order us to?‚ÄĚ And it only drives them farther away"
  25,61,"Blessed is the One Who has placed constellations in the sky, as well as a ňĻradiantňļ lamp¬†and a luminous moon"
  25,62,"And He is the One Who causes the day and the night to alternate, ňĻas a signňļ for whoever desires to be mindful or to be grateful"
  25,63,"The ňĻtrueňļ servants of the Most Compassionate are those who walk on the earth humbly, and when the foolish address them ňĻimproperlyňļ, they only respond with peace"
  25,64,"ňĻThey areňļ those who spend ňĻa good portion ofňļ the night, prostrating themselves and standing before their Lord"
  25,65,"ňĻThey areňļ those who pray, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Keep the punishment of Hell away from us, for its punishment is indeed unrelenting"
  25,66,It is certainly an evil place to settle and reside.‚ÄĚ
  25,67,"ňĻThey areňļ those who spend neither wastefully nor stingily, but moderately in between"
  25,68,"ňĻThey areňļ those who do not invoke any other god besides God, nor take a ňĻhumanňļ life‚ÄĒmade sacred by God‚ÄĒexcept with ňĻlegalňļ right,¬†nor commit fornication. And whoever does ňĻany ofňļ this will face the penalty"
  25,69,"Their punishment will be multiplied on the Day of Judgment, and they will remain in it forever, in disgrace"
  25,70,"As for those who repent, believe, and do good deeds, they are the ones whose evil deeds God will change into good deeds. For God is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful"
  25,71,And whoever repents and does good has truly turned to God properly
  25,72,"ňĻThey areňļ those who do not bear false witness, and when they come across falsehood, they pass ňĻitňļ by with dignity"
  25,73,"ňĻThey areňļ those who, when reminded of the revelation of their Lord, do not turn a blind eye or a deaf ear to it"
  25,74,"ňĻThey areňļ those who pray, ‚ÄúOur Lord! Bless us with ňĻpiousňļ spouses and offspring who will be the joy of our hearts, and make us models for the righteous.‚ÄĚ"
  25,75,"It is they who will be rewarded with ňĻelevatedňļ mansions ňĻin Paradiseňļ for their perseverance, and will be received with salutations and ňĻgreetings ofňļ peace"
  25,76,staying there forever. What an excellent place to settle and reside
  25,77,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúYou ňĻallňļ would not ňĻevenňļ matter to my Lord were it not for your faith ňĻin Himňļ. But now you ňĻdisbelieversňļ have denied ňĻthe truthňļ, so the torment is bound to come.‚ÄĚ"
  26,1,ŠĻ¨√Ę-Sń©n-Mń©m
  26,2,These are the verses of the clear Book
  26,3,Perhaps you ňĻO Prophetňļ will grieve yourself to death over their disbelief
  26,4,"If We willed, We could send down upon them a ňĻcompellingňļ sign from the heavens, leaving their necks bent in ňĻutterňļ submission to it"
  26,5,"Whatever new reminder comes to them from the Most Compassionate, they always turn away from it"
  26,6,"They have certainly denied ňĻthe truthňļ, so they will soon face the consequences of their ridicule"
  26,7,"Have they failed to look at the earth, ňĻto seeňļ how many types of fine plants We have caused to grow in it"
  26,8,Surely in this is a sign. Yet most of them would not believe
  26,9,"And your Lord is certainly the Almighty, Most Merciful"
  26,10,"ňĻRememberňļ when your Lord called out to Moses, ‚ÄúGo to the wrongdoing people‚ÄĒ"
  26,11,the people of Pharaoh. Will they not fear ňĻGodňļ?‚ÄĚ
  26,12,"He replied, ‚ÄúMy Lord! I fear that they will reject me"
  26,13,And ňĻsoňļ my heart will be broken and my tongue will be tied. So send Aaron along ňĻas a messengerňļ
  26,14,"Also, they have a charge against me,¬†so I fear they may kill me.‚ÄĚ"
  26,15,"God responded, ‚ÄúCertainly not! So go, both of you, with Our signs. We will be with you, listening"
  26,16,"Go to Pharaoh and say, ‚ÄėWe are messengers from the Lord of all worlds"
  26,17,"ňĻcommanded to say:ňļ ‚ÄėLet the Children of Israel go with us.‚Äô‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  26,18,"Pharaoh protested, ‚ÄúDid we not raise you among us as a child, and you stayed several years of your life in our care"
  26,19,"Then you did what you did,¬†being ňĻutterlyňļ ungrateful!‚ÄĚ"
  26,20,"Moses replied, ‚ÄúI did it then, lacking guidance"
  26,21,So I fled from you when I feared you. Then my Lord granted me wisdom and made me one of the messengers
  26,22,"How can that be a ‚Äėfavour,‚Äô of which you remind me, when ňĻit was only becauseňļ you ňĻhaveňļ enslaved the Children of Israel?‚ÄĚ"
  26,23,"Pharaoh asked, ‚ÄúAnd what is ‚Äėthe Lord of all worlds‚Äô?‚ÄĚ"
  26,24,"Moses replied, ‚ÄúňĻHe isňļ the Lord of the heavens and the earth and everything in between, if only you had sure faith.‚ÄĚ"
  26,25,"Pharaoh said to those around him, ‚ÄúDid you hear ňĻwhat he saidňļ?‚ÄĚ"
  26,26,"Moses added, ‚ÄúňĻHe isňļ your Lord and the Lord of your forefathers.‚ÄĚ"
  26,27,"Pharaoh said ňĻmockinglyňļ, ‚ÄúYour messenger, who has been sent to you, must be insane.‚ÄĚ"
  26,28,"Moses responded: ‚ÄúňĻHe isňļ the Lord of the east and west, and everything in between, if only you had any sense.‚ÄĚ"
  26,29,"Pharaoh threatened, ‚ÄúIf you take any other god besides me, I will certainly have you imprisoned.‚ÄĚ"
  26,30,"Moses responded, ‚ÄúEven if I bring you a clear proof?‚ÄĚ"
  26,31,"Pharaoh demanded, ‚ÄúBring it then, if what you say is true.‚ÄĚ"
  26,32,So he threw down his staff and‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒit became a real snake
  26,33,Then he drew his hand ňĻout of his collarňļ and it was ňĻshiningňļ white for all to see
  26,34,"Pharaoh said to the chiefs around him, ‚ÄúHe is indeed a skilled magician"
  26,35,who seeks to drive you from your land by his magic. So what do you propose?‚ÄĚ
  26,36,"They replied, ‚ÄúLet him and his brother wait and dispatch mobilizers to all cities"
  26,37,to bring you every skilled magician.‚ÄĚ
  26,38,So the magicians were assembled at the set time on the appointed day
  26,39,"And the people were asked, ‚ÄúWill you join the gathering"
  26,40,so that we may follow the magicians if they prevail?‚ÄĚ
  26,41,"When the magicians came, they asked Pharaoh, ‚ÄúShall we have a ňĻsuitableňļ reward if we prevail?‚ÄĚ"
  26,42,"He replied, ‚ÄúYes, and you will then certainly be among those closest to me.‚ÄĚ"
  26,43,"Moses said to them, ‚ÄúCast whatever you wish to cast.‚ÄĚ"
  26,44,"So they cast down their ropes and staffs, saying, ‚ÄúBy Pharaoh‚Äôs might, it is we who will surely prevail.‚ÄĚ"
  26,45,"Then Moses threw down his staff, and‚ÄĒbehold!‚ÄĒit devoured the objects of their illusion"
  26,46,"So the magicians fell down, prostrating"
  26,47,"They declared, ‚ÄúWe ňĻnowňļ believe in the Lord of all worlds‚ÄĒ"
  26,48,the Lord of Moses and Aaron.‚ÄĚ
  26,49,"Pharaoh threatened, ‚ÄúHow dare you believe in him before I give you permission? He must be your master who taught you magic, but soon you will see. I will certainly cut off your hands and feet on opposite sides, then crucify you all.‚ÄĚ"
  26,50,"They responded, ‚ÄúňĻThat would beňļ no harm! Surely to our Lord we will ňĻallňļ return"
  26,51,"We really hope that our Lord will forgive our sins, as we are the first to believe.‚ÄĚ"
  26,52,"And We inspired Moses, ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúLeave with My servants at night, for you will surely be pursued.‚ÄĚ"
  26,53,Then Pharaoh sent mobilizers to all cities
  26,54,"ňĻand said,ňļ ‚ÄúThese ňĻoutcastsňļ are just a handful of people"
  26,55,who have really enraged us
  26,56,but we are all on the alert.‚ÄĚ
  26,57,"So We lured the tyrants¬†out of ňĻtheirňļ gardens, springs"
  26,58,"treasures, and splendid residences"
  26,59,So it was. And We awarded it ňĻallňļ to the Children of Israel
  26,60,And so they pursued them at sunrise
  26,61,"When the two groups came face to face, the companions of Moses cried out, ‚ÄúWe are overtaken for sure.‚ÄĚ"
  26,62,"Moses reassured ňĻthemňļ, ‚ÄúAbsolutely not! My Lord is certainly with me‚ÄĒHe will guide me.‚ÄĚ"
