  48,21,And ňĻthere areňļ other gains which are beyond your reach that God is keeping in store ňĻfor youňļ. For God is Most Capable of everything
  48,22,"If the disbelievers were to fight you, they would certainly flee.¬†Then they would never find any protector or helper"
  48,23,"ňĻThis isňļ God‚Äôs way, already long established ňĻin the pastňļ. And you will find no change in God‚Äôs way"
  48,24,"He is the One Who held back their hands from you and your hands from them in the valley of ňĻŠł§udaibiyah, nearňļ Mecca, after giving you the upper hand over ňĻa group ofňļ them.¬†And God is All-Seeing of what you do"
  48,25,"They are the ones who persisted in disbelief and hindered you from the Sacred Mosque, preventing the sacrificial animals from reaching their destination.¬†ňĻWe would have let you march through Mecca,ňļ had there not been believing men and women, unknown to you. You might have trampled them underfoot, incurring guilt for ňĻwhat you did toňļ them unknowingly. That was so God may admit into His mercy whoever He wills.¬†Had those ňĻunknownňļ believers stood apart, We would have certainly inflicted a painful punishment on the disbelievers"
  48,26,"ňĻRememberňļ when the disbelievers had filled their hearts with pride‚ÄĒthe pride of ňĻpre-Islamicňļ ignorance‚ÄĒthen God sent down His serenity upon His Messenger and the believers, inspiring them to uphold the declaration of faith,¬†for they were better entitled and more worthy of it. And God has ňĻperfectňļ knowledge of all things"
  48,27,"Indeed, God will fulfil His Messenger‚Äôs vision in all truth: God willing, you will surely enter the Sacred Mosque, in security‚ÄĒňĻsome withňļ heads shaved and ňĻothers withňļ hair shortened‚ÄĒwithout fear.¬†He knew what you did not know, so He first granted you the triumph at hand"
  48,28,"He is the One Who has sent His Messenger with ňĻrightňļ guidance and the religion of truth, making it prevail over all others. And sufficient is God as a Witness"
  48,29,"MuŠł•ammad is the Messenger of God. And those with him are firm with the disbelievers¬†and compassionate with one another. You see them bowing and prostrating¬†ňĻin prayerňļ, seeking God‚Äôs bounty and pleasure. The sign ňĻof brightness can be seenňļ on their faces from the trace of prostrating ňĻin prayerňļ. This is their description in the Torah.¬†And their parable in the Gospel is that of a seed that sprouts its ňĻtinyňļ branches, making it strong. Then it becomes thick, standing firmly on its stem, to the delight of the planters‚ÄĒin this way God makes the believers a source of dismay for the disbelievers.¬†To those of them who believe and do good, God has promised forgiveness and a great reward"
  49,1,"O believers! Do not proceed ňĻin any matterňļ before ňĻa decree fromňļ God and His Messenger. And fear God. Surely God is All-Hearing, All-Knowing"
